{"title_page": "Keith Poole", "text_new": "{{for|the Australian lawn bowler|Keith Poole (bowls)}}\n{{for|the American political scientist|Keith T. Poole}}\n{{Infobox gridiron football person\n| name = \n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|06|18}}\n| birth_place = [[San Jose, California]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| team = \n| number = \n| status = \n| position1 = [[Wide receiver]]\n| height_ft = \n| height_in = \n| weight_lb = \n| college = [[Arizona State University|Arizona State]]\n| NFLDraftedYear = 1997\n| NFLDraftedRound = 4 / Pick 116\n| NFLDraftedPick = \n| NFLDraftedTeam = \n| playing_years1 = 1997\u20132000\n| playing_team1 = [[New Orleans Saints]]\n| playing_years2 = 2001\n| playing_team2 = [[Denver Broncos]]\n| career_highlights = \n| DatabaseFootball = POOLEKEI01\n}}\n'''Keith Robert Strohmaier Poole''' (born June 18, 1974 in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]]) is a former professional [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] in the [[National Football League|NFL]] for the [[New Orleans Saints]] and [[Denver Broncos]] from 1997 to 2001.  Poole was a stand out receiver at [[Clovis High School (Clovis, California)|Clovis High School]] in [[Clovis, California]] and played [[College football|collegiately]] at [[Arizona State University|Arizona State]] alongside [[quarterback]] [[Jake Plummer]]. In 1996, he and Plummer helped lead the [[Arizona State Sun Devils|Sun Devils]] to the [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]] only to lose to [[Ohio State]] 20-17.\n\nPoole was selected by the Saints in the fourth round of the [[1997 NFL Draft]]. In his five-year NFL career, Poole caught 96 receptions for 1,734 yards and 11 touchdowns.\n\nPoole now runs a business developing training programs which are specifically tailored to each individual client. The initial consultation includes a comprehensive fitness assessment that will calculate your fitness level, as well as discussing your personal fitness goals and objectives. http://kptrainingzone.com/\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Saints1997DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poole, Keith}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Clovis, California]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Arizona State Sun Devils football players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n\n\n{{widereceiver-1970s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Australian lawn bowler|Keith Poole (bowls)}}\n{{for|the American political scientist|Keith T. Poole}}\n{{Infobox gridiron football person\n| name = \n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|06|18}}\n| birth_place = [[San Jose, California]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| team = \n| number = \n| status = \n| position1 = [[Wide receiver]]\n| height_ft = \n| height_in = \n| weight_lb = \n| college = [[Arizona State University|Arizona State]]\n| NFLDraftedYear = 1997\n| NFLDraftedRound = 4 / Pick 116\n| NFLDraftedPick = \n| NFLDraftedTeam = \n| playing_years1 = 1997\u20132000\n| playing_team1 = [[New Orleans Saints]]\n| playing_years2 = 2001\n| playing_team2 = [[Denver Broncos]]\n| career_highlights = \n| DatabaseFootball = POOLEKEI01\n}}\n'''Keith Robert Strohmaier Poole''' (born June 18, 1974 in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]]) is a former professional [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] in the [[National Football League|NFL]] for the [[New Orleans Saints]] and [[Denver Broncos]] from 1997 to 2001.  Poole was a stand out receiver at [[Clovis High School (Clovis, California)|Clovis High School]] in [[Clovis, California]] and played [[College football|collegiately]] at [[Arizona State University|Arizona State]] alongside [[quarterback]] [[Jake Plummer]]. In 1996, he and Plummer helped lead the [[Arizona State Sun Devils|Sun Devils]] to the [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]] only to lose to [[Ohio State]] 20-17.\n\nPoole was selected by the Saints in the fourth round of the [[1997 NFL Draft]]. In his five-year NFL career, Poole caught 96 receptions for 1,734 yards and 11 touchdowns.\n\nIn November 1998, he was sentenced to two months of probation for attacking a man with a golf club. He was fined $8,500, team and league officials said.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Freeman |authorlink=Mike Freeman (columnist) |title=PRO FOOTBALL; Stains From the Police Blotter Leave N.F.L. Embarrassed  |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F05E7DB113BF93AA35752C0A9669C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2 |work=New York Times |date=9 January 2000 |accessdate=5 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Saints1997DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poole, Keith}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Clovis, California]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Arizona State Sun Devils football players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n\n\n{{widereceiver-1970s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2600:8800:1500:ce2:154a:5406:e517:54c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keith_Poole"}
{"title_page": "Qatar diplomatic crisis", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Qatar diplomatic crisis\n| partof      = [[Qatar\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]] and [[Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]]\n| date        = 5 June 2017 \u2013 ongoing <br />({{Age in months, weeks and days|year1=2017|month1=6|day1=5}})\n| place       = [[Qatar]]\n| territory   = \n| result      = [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Bahrain]], the [[United Arab Emirates]], and [[Egypt]] cut diplomatic relations with Qatar; others downgrade.\n| status      = Ongoing\n*13-point ultimatum issued and replaced with altered conditions.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40654023|title=Saudi-led Bloc|publisher=BBC|date=19 July 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n*Qatar ends its involvement in the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|war in Yemen]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2017/06/05/Arab-coalition-suspends-Qatar-s-participation-in-Yemen.html|title=Arab coalition suspends Qatar's participation in Yemen|publisher=[[Al Arabiya English]]|date=5 June 2017|accessdate=20 August 2017}}</ref> and peacekeeping in [[Ras Doumeira]].\n| combatants_header = Parties involved in diplomatic dispute\n| combatant1  = {{flag|Saudi Arabia}}<br />{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}<br />{{flag|Bahrain}}<br />{{flag|Egypt}}<br />{{flag|Maldives}}<br />{{flag|Yemen}}{{Ref label|Yemen|a}}<br />{{flag|Mauritania}}<br />{{flag|Djibouti}}<br />{{flag|Comoros}}<br />{{flag|Niger}}<br />{{flag|Gabon}}<br />'''Others:'''<br />{{flag|Somaliland}}{{Ref label|Somaliland|c}}<br />{{flag|Libya|House of Representatives (Libya)|name=Libya (Tobruk)}}{{Ref label|Libya|b}}<br />'''No longer participating:'''<br />{{flag|Senegal}} <small>(until 2017)</small><br />{{flag|Chad}} <small>(until 2018)</small><br />{{flag|Jordan}} <small>(until 2019)</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/jordan-seeks-middle-ground-mideast-rift|title=Jordan Seeks Middle Ground in Mideast Rift|website=Voice of America}}</ref>\n| notes       = {{Note label|Yemen|a}} The [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi#Rebel takeover and civil war|Government stationed in Aden]] has cut ties with Qatar.<br/>{{Note label|Libya|b}} The [[Second Al-Thani Cabinet|Tobruk-based government]] lost international recognition after the formation of the [[Government of National Accord]] in January 2016. The Tobruk-based government claims to have cut ties with Qatar despite not having diplomatic representation in the country.<br/>{{Note label|Somaliland|c}} Somaliland's independence is not recognized by the international community.\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Qatar}}<br />''Supported by:''<br />{{flag|Turkey}} (food aid, diplomatic and military support)<ref name=\"Turkey\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/06/implications-qatar-turkey-alliance-170618110726262.html |title=The implications of the Qatar-Turkey alliance|date=18 June 2017|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref><br />{{flag|Iran}} (food aid, airspace access and diplomatic support)<ref name=\"Iran\">{{cite news|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/gulf-crisis-iran-sends-five-planes-food-qatar-avert-food-shortages-1021805206|title=Iran sends five plane loads of food as Kuwait says Qatar 'ready' to listen|date=11 June 2017|accessdate=18 June 2017}}<br/>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/iran-hassan-rouhani-condemns-siege-qatar-170625174347048.html|title=Iran: Hassan Rouhani condemns 'siege of Qatar'|date=26 June 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''[[Qatar]] diplomatic crisis''' began in June 2017, when [[Foreign relations of Saudi Arabia#Qatar|Saudi Arabia]], the [[Qatar\u2013United Arab Emirates relations|United Arab Emirates]], [[Bahrain\u2013Qatar relations|Bahrain]], [[Egypt\u2013Qatar relations|Egypt]], [[Maldives|the Maldives]], [[Mauritania]], [[Senegal]], [[Djibouti]], [[Comoros|the Comoros]], [[Jordan-Qatar relations|Jordan]], the Tobruk-based [[Libya|Libyan]] government, and the [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi|Hadi]]-led [[Yemen]]<nowiki/>i government severed diplomatic relations with Qatar and banned Qatari airplanes and ships from utilising their [[airspace]] and sea routes along with Saudi Arabia blocking the only land crossing.<ref>{{cite web |title=Qatar-Gulf crisis: Your questions answered |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/06/qatar-gulf-crisis-questions-answered-170606103033599.html |website=aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=It\u2019s a boycott, not a blockade |url=https://gulfnews.com/opinion/editorials/it-s-a-boycott-not-a-blockade-1.2043769 |accessdate=August 31, 2018 |work=Gulf News |date=June 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Saudi-led coalition cited Qatar's alleged [[Qatar and state-sponsored terrorism|support for terrorism]] as the main reason for their actions, insisting that Qatar has violated a 2014 agreement with the members of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC).<ref>{{cite news|title=Doha's Actions May Destabilize the Region: Saudi Minister|url=http://newsweekme.com/dohas-actions-may-destabilize-region-saudi-minister/|accessdate=2 July 2017|work=Newsweek ME |date=14 June 2017}}</ref> Saudi Arabia and other countries have [[Al Jazeera controversies and criticism|criticized Al Jazeera]] and [[Iran\u2013Qatar relations|Qatar's relations with Iran]]. Qatar acknowledges that it has provided assistance to some Islamist groups (such as the [[Muslim Brotherhood]]), but denies aiding militant groups linked to al-Qaeda or the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL).<ref>{{cite news|title=Sheikh Tamim denies Qatar has links to terrorism|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40173757 |newspaper=[[BBC]]|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> Qatar also claims that it has [[Qatar\u2013United States relations|assisted the United States]] in the [[War on Terror]] and the ongoing [[military intervention against ISIL]].<ref name=Tamim>{{cite news|title=Sheikh Tamim denies Qatar has links to terrorism|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/region/qatar/sheikh-tamim-denies-qatar-has-links-to-terrorism|date=25 May 2017|newspaper=[[Khaleej Times]]|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nInitial supply disruptions were mitigated by additional imports from Iran and Turkey, and Qatar did not agree to any of the Saudi-led coalition's demands.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Collins |first1=Gabriel |title=Anti-Qatar Embargo Grinds Toward Strategic Failure |url=https://scholarship.rice.edu/bitstream/handle/1911/99690/bi-brief-012218-ces-qatarembargo.pdf?sequence=1 |publisher=Rice University\u2019s Baker Institute for Public Policy}}</ref>  The demands included reducing diplomatic relations with Iran, stopping military coordination with Turkey, and closing [[Al-Jazeera]].\n\nOn 27 July 2017, Qatari foreign minister [[Mohammed bin Abdulrahman Al Thani]] told reporters that Egypt, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates and Bahrain were showing \"stubbornness\" to Qatar and had not taken any steps to solve the crisis. Al Thani added that the Security Council, the General Assembly and \"all the United Nations mechanisms\" could play a role in resolving the situation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/07/27/qatar-says-un-should-play-role-in-resolving-gulf-crisis.html|title=Qatar says UN should play a role in resolving Gulf crisis|date=27 July 2017|publisher=Fox News Channel|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref> On 24 August 2017, Qatar announced that it would restore full diplomatic relations with Iran.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qatar To Reinstate Ambassador To Iran Amid Gulf Crisis|url=http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/qatar-to-reinstate-ambassador-to-iran-amid-gulf-crisis-1741557|date=24 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Qatar\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict}}\n{{Further|2017 United States\u2013Saudi Arabia arms deal|Riyadh Summit 2017}}\n\nSince he took power in 1995, [[Hamad bin Khalifa al-Thani]] believed Qatar could find security only by transforming itself from a Saudi appendage to a rival of Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/13/world/middleeast/how-the-saudi-qatar-rivalry-now-combusting-reshaped-the-middle-east.html|title=How the Saudi-Qatar Rivalry, Now Combusting, Reshaped the Middle East|first=Max|last=Fisher|date=13 June 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref> Saudi Arabia withdrew its ambassador to Doha from 2002 to 2008 to try to pressure Qatar to curb its individualistic tendencies. This approach broadly failed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40159080|title=Qatar row: What's caused the fall-out between Gulf neighbours?|first=Dr David|last=Roberts|date=5 June 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref> The [[Arab Spring]] left a power vacuum which both Saudi Arabia and Qatar sought to fill, with Qatar being supportive of the [[revolutionary wave]] and Saudi Arabia opposing it; since both states are allies of the United States, they avoid direct conflict with one another.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/05/world/middleeast/qatar-saudi-arabia-egypt-bahrain-united-arab-emirates.html|title=5 Arab Nations Move to Isolate Qatar, Putting the U.S. in a Bind|date=5 June 2017|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Qatar has had differences with other Arab governments on a number of issues: it broadcasts [[Al Jazeera]]; it is accused of maintaining good relations with Iran; and it has supported the Muslim Brotherhood in the past.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/05/world/middleeast/qatar-saudi-arabia-egypt-bahrain-united-arab-emirates.html|title=5 Arab States Break Ties With Qatar, Complicating U.S. Coalition-Building|first1=Anne|last1=Barnard|first2=David|last2=Kirkpatrick|date=5 June 2017|accessdate=5 June 2017|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Qatar has been accused of sponsoring terrorism. Some countries have faulted Qatar for [[Timber Sycamore|funding]] rebel groups in Syria, including [[al-Qaeda]]\u2019s affiliate in Syria, the [[al-Nusra Front]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/News/12392.aspx|title=Gulf allies and \u2018Army of Conquest |newspaper=[[Al-Ahram Weekly]]|date=28 May 2015}}</ref> although the Saudis have done the same.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mazzetti|first1=Mark|last2=Apuzzo|first2=Matt|title=U.S. Relies Heavily on Saudi Money to Support Syrian Rebels|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/24/world/middleeast/us-relies-heavily-on-saudi-money-to-support-syrian-rebels.html?_r=0|work=The New York Times|date=23 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/syria-crisis-turkey-and-saudi-arabia-shock-western-countries-by-supporting-antiassad-jihadists-10242747.html|title=Turkey and Saudi Arabia alarm the West by backing Islamist extremists the Americans had bombed in Syria|author=Kim Sengupta|newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=12 May 2015}}</ref> Qatar has allowed the Afghan [[Taliban]] to set up a political office inside the country.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Robert|title=How Tiny Qatar 'Punches Above Its Weight'|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2013/12/20/255748469/how-tiny-qatar-punches-above-its-weight|publisher=NPR|date=23 December 2013}}</ref> Qatar is [[Qatar\u2013United States relations|a close ally of the United States]], hosting the largest American base in the Middle East, [[Al Udeid Air Base]].<ref name=USbase>{{cite web|last=Lendon|first=Brad |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/05/middleeast/qatar-us-largest-base-in-mideast/index.html |title=Qatar hosts largest US military base in Mideast|agency=CNN|date=5 June 2017|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===March 2014 GCC Crisis===\n\nIn March 2014, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and Egypt withdrew their ambassadors from Qatar. This severing of relations was the first of its kind since the establishment of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC). The disagreement that sparked the ambassadors\u2019 withdrawal was among the most serious in recent years, and threatened to seriously undermine relations between the GCC states. The crisis certainly affected the GCC negatively at first \u2013 raising questions among member states, revealing shifts in their political agendas, and changing the balance of power in the region to some extent.<ref name=\"Islam Hassan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/12696782/GCCs_2014_Crisis_Causes_Issues_and_Solutions|title=GCC's 2014 Crisis: Causes, Issues and Solutions|author=Islam Hassan|date=31 March 2015|publisher=Al Jazeera Research Center|accessdate=4 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904020157/http://www.academia.edu/12696782/GCCs_2014_Crisis_Causes_Issues_and_Solutions|archivedate=4 September 2015}}</ref> It also set the stage for the 2017 GCC crisis.\n\nThe exact reasons for the diplomatic break-offs are unclear, but contemporary news coverage primarily attributes this to several events in April and May 2017.\n\n===April 2017 hostage negotiations===\n[[File:Flag of Hayat Tahrir al-Sham.svg|right|thumb|Flag of [[Tahrir al-Sham]], a Sunni militant group. Qatar is accused of paying the group $140&nbsp;million in a deal that saw the release of hostages.<ref name=\"SolomonFinTimes\" /> According to an Iraqi Shi'ite militia, the deal was linked to delivery of humanitarian aid to Shi'ite and Sunni villages in Syria.<ref name=Hostages />]]\n{{Further|2015 Qatari hunters kidnapping}}\nIn April 2017, Qatar was involved in [[2015 Zabadani cease-fire agreement|a deal]] with both [[Sunni]] and [[Shi'ite]] militants in Iraq and Syria. The deal had two goals. The immediate goal was to secure the return of 26 Qatari hostages (including [[House of Thani|Qatari royals]]) who had been kidnapped by Shi'ite militants while falcon hunting in Southern Iraq and kept in captivity for more than 16 months.<ref name=\"FA\">{{cite journal|last1=Roberts|first1=David |title=A Dustup in the Gulf|journal=Foreign Affairs|date=June 2017 |url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/middle-east/2017-06-13/dustup-gulf}}{{subscription required|work=Foreign Affairs}}</ref><ref name=Hostages>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/21/world/middleeast/big-ransom-and-syria-deals-win-release-of-royal-qatari-hunters.html|title=Big Ransom and Syria Deals Win Release of Royal Qatari Hunters|first=Tim|last=Arango|date=21 April 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The second goal was to get both Sunni and Shi'ite militants in Syria to allow [[humanitarian aid]] to pass through and allow the safe evacuation of civilians.<ref name=Hostages/> According to the ''[[New York Times]]'', this deal allowed the evacuation of at least 2,000 civilians from [[Madaya, Syria|the Syrian village of Madaya]] alone.<ref name=Hostages/> What outraged Saudi Arabia and the UAE is the amount of money Qatar had to pay to secure the deal. According to the ''[[Financial Times]]'' Qatar paid $700&nbsp;million to Iranian-backed [[Shia Islam|Shi'a]] militias in Iraq, $120\u2013140&nbsp;million to [[Tahrir al-Sham]], and $80&nbsp;million to [[Ahrar al-Sham]].<ref name=\"SolomonFinTimes\">Erika Solomon, [https://www.ft.com/content/dd033082-49e9-11e7-a3f4-c742b9791d43 The $1bn hostage deal that enraged Qatar's Gulf rivals: Doha reportedly paid al-Qaeda affiliate and Iran to win release of royal hunting party] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605210800/https://www.ft.com/content/dd033082-49e9-11e7-a3f4-c742b9791d43|date=5 June 2017|title=}}, ''Financial Times'' (5 June 2017).</ref>\n\n===Riyadh Summit 2017===\n[[File:Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, King Salman of Saudi Arabia, Melania Trump, and Donald Trump, May 2017.jpg|thumb|left|US President [[Donald Trump]], King [[Salman of Saudi Arabia]], and Egyptian President [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]] at the 2017 Riyadh Summit. The meeting is cited as one of the catalysts for the crisis.<ref name=nytimes/>]]\nAs part of the [[Riyadh Summit 2017|Riyadh Summit]] in late May 2017, many world leaders, including US President Donald Trump visited the region. Trump gave strong support for Saudi Arabia's efforts in fighting against states and groups allied with Iran and the Muslim Brotherhood, leading to an [[2017 United States-Saudi Arabia arms deal|arms deal]] between the countries. The ''Business Insider'' reported that \"[[Elliott Broidy]] a top fundraiser for President Donald Trump; and [[George Nader (businessman)|George Nader]], Broidy's business partner ... pushed for anti-Qatar policies at the highest levels of government, and expected large consulting contracts from Saudi Arabia and the UAE.\"<ref>\"[http://www.businessinsider.com/george-nader-elliott-broidy-trump-middle-east-uae-qatar-saudi-arabia-mueller-2018-5 How a top Trump fundraiser spent a year cultivating 2 crown princes to nail $1 billion in business]\". ''[[Business Insider]]''. May 21, 2018.</ref> Trump's support may have induced other [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] states to fall in line with Saudi Arabia to take a stance against Qatar.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> Trump's public support for Saudi Arabia, according to ''The New York Times'', emboldened the kingdom and sent a chill through other Gulf states, including Oman and Kuwait, that fear that any country that defies the Saudis or the United Arab Emirates could face ostracism as Qatar has.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/07/world/middleeast/trump-qatar-saudi-arabia-middle-east.html|title=Trump Has Busy Day in Vortex of Middle East Relations|first1=David E. Sanger, Mark|last1=Landler|first2=Eric|last2=Schmitt|date=7 June 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref> The Saudi-led move was at once an opportunity for the GCC partners and Egypt to punish their adversaries in Doha, please their allies in Washington, and remove attention from their own shortcomings and challenges.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inss.org.il/publication/qatar-crisis-causes-implications-risks-need-compromise/|title=The Qatar Crisis: Causes,........... Implications, Risks, and the Need for Compromise|date=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hacking of Qatari websites===\nAccording to Qatar-based Al Jazeera and the American FBI, the [[Qatar News Agency]] website and other government media platforms were [[hack (computing)|hacked]] in May 2017, where hackers posted fake remarks on the official Qatar News Agency attributed to the Emir of Qatar, Sheikh [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]], that expressed support for Iran, Hamas, Hezbollah, and Israel.<ref name=auto>{{Cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/saudi-arabia-uae-egypt-bahrain-cut-ties-qatar-170605031700062.html|title=Saudi Arabia, UAE, Egypt, Bahrain cut ties to Qatar|date=5 June 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref> The emir was quoted as saying: \"Iran represents a regional and Islamic power that cannot be ignored and it is unwise to face up against it. It is a big power in the stabilization of the region.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/05/23/qatar-says-state-news-website-hacked-fake-article-published.html|title=Hack, fake story expose real tensions between Qatar, Gulf|agency=[[Fox News]]|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"stratfor\">\"[https://www.stratfor.com/article/trumps-arab-nato-vision-desert-mirage Trump's 'Arab NATO' Vision is a Desert Mirage]\". [[Stratfor]]. 31 May 2017.</ref> Qatar reported that the statements were false and did not know their origin.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> Despite this, the remarks were widely publicized in the various Arab news media, including UAE-based [[Sky News Arabia]] and Saudi-owned [[Al Arabiya]].<ref name=auto/> On 3 June 2017, the [[Twitter|Twitter account]] of Bahraini foreign minister [[Khalid bin Ahmed Al Khalifa]] was hacked.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://phys.org/news/2017-06-bahrain-minister-briefly-hacked-qatar.html |title=Bahrain minister briefly hacked after Qatar cyber attack|publisher=Phys.org|date=3 June 2017|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nInitially alleged intelligence gathered by the US security agencies indicated that [[Cyberwarfare by Russia|Russian hackers]] were behind the intrusion first reported by the Qataris.<ref name=\"PerezProkupecz\">{{cite news|author=Evan Perez & Shimon Prokupecz|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/06/politics/russian-hackers-planted-fake-news-qatar-crisis/index.html|title=US suspects Russian hackers planted fake news behind Qatar crisis|agency=CNN|date=6 June 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Wintour\">{{cite news|author=[[Patrick Wintour]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/07/russian-hackers-qatar-crisis-fbi-inquiry-saudi-arabia-uae|title=Russian hackers to blame for sparking Qatar crisis, FBI inquiry finds|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> However, a US official briefed on the inquiry told the ''New York Times'' that it \"was unclear whether the hackers were state-sponsored\"<ref name=\"Landler\">{{cite news|author=[[Mark Landler]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/06/world/middleeast/trump-qatar-saudi-arabia.html|title=Trump Takes Credit for Saudi Move Against Qatar, a U.S. Military Partner|work=New York Times|date=6 June 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> and ''The Guardian'' diplomatic editor [[Patrick Wintour]] reported that \"it is believed that the Russian government was not involved in the hacks; instead, freelance hackers were paid to undertake the work on behalf of some other state or individual.\"<ref name=\"Wintour\"/> A US diplomat said that Russia and its ally Iran stood to benefit from sowing discord among US allies in the region, \"particularly if they made it more difficult for the United States to use Qatar as a major base.\"<ref name=\"Landler\"/> The FBI sent a team of investigators to [[Doha]] to help the [[Qatari government]] investigate the hacking incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mofa.gov.qa/en/all-mofa-news/details/2017/06/07/ministry-of-the-interior-statement-on-piracy-crime-on-qatar-news-agency-website |title=Ministry of the Interior Statement on Piracy Crime on Qatar News Agency Website |publisher=mofa.gov.qa |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621122056/https://mofa.gov.qa/en/all-mofa-news/details/2017/06/07/ministry-of-the-interior-statement-on-piracy-crime-on-qatar-news-agency-website |archivedate=21 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Later, the [[The New York Times|''New York Times'']] reported that the hacking incidents may be part of a long-running cyberwar between Qatar and other Gulf countries that was only revealed to the public during the recent incidents, and they noted how Saudi and UAE media picked up the statement made by the hacked media in less than 20 minutes and began interviewing many well-prepared commentators against Qatar.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/08/world/middleeast/qatar-cyberattack-espionage-for-hire.html |title=Hacking in Qatar Highlights a Shift Toward Espionage-for-Hire |last=Kirkpatrick |first=David D. |date=8 June 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=11 June 2017 |last2=Frenkel |first2=Sheera  |issn=0362-4331 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610221221/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/08/world/middleeast/qatar-cyberattack-espionage-for-hire.html |archivedate=10 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nUS intelligence agencies believe that the hacking was done by the United Arab Emirates, according to a ''[[Washington Post]]'' article published on 16 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/uae-hacked-qatari-government-sites-sparking-regional-upheaval-according-to-us-intelligence-officials/2017/07/16/00c46e54-698f-11e7-8eb5-cbccc2e7bfbf_story.html |title=UAE orchestrated hacking of Qatari government sites, sparking regional upheaval, according to U.S. intelligence officials |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=30 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729180340/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/uae-hacked-qatari-government-sites-sparking-regional-upheaval-according-to-us-intelligence-officials/2017/07/16/00c46e54-698f-11e7-8eb5-cbccc2e7bfbf_story.html |archivedate=29 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The intelligence officials stated that the hacking was discussed among Emirati officials on 23 May, one day before the operation took place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/uae-arranged-hacking-qatari-media-washington-post-170717004353563.html |title=UAE arranged hacking of Qatari media: Washington Post |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=16 July 2017 |accessdate=27 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827000653/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/uae-arranged-hacking-qatari-media-washington-post-170717004353563.html |archivedate=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The UAE denied any involvement in the hacking.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/07/17/middleeast/uae-qatar-report/index.html |title=UAE denies Washington Post report it orchestrated Qatar hack |publisher=CNN |author1=Tamara Qiblawi |author2=Angela Dewan |date=27 July 2017 |accessdate=27 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827215835/http://www.cnn.com/2017/07/17/middleeast/uae-qatar-report/index.html |archivedate=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was announced on 26 August 2017, that five individuals allegedly involved in the hacking were arrested in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-cyber-idUSKCN1B608L |title=Qatar says five suspects in news agency hacking detained in Turkey |agency=Reuters |date=26 August 2017 |accessdate=27 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827034414/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-cyber-idUSKCN1B608L |archivedate=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Hacking of UAE ambassador's email===\n[[File:Yousef Al Otaiba 2013.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Yousef Al Otaiba|Yousef Al-Otaiba]]]]\nIn May 2017, the email account of the UAE's ambassador to the US, [[Yousef Al Otaiba|Yousef Al-Otaiba]], was hacked. The emails were reported as \"embarrassing\" by Al Jazeera because they showed links between the UAE and the US-based [[Foundation for Defense of Democracies]].<ref name=embarrass>{{cite news |title=Someone Is Using These Leaked Emails To Embarrass Washington's Most Powerful Ambassador |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/otaiba-ambassador-uae-leaked-emails_us_5932bf04e4b02478cb9bec1c |date=3 June 2017 |first=Akbar Shahid |last=Ahmed |work=HuffPost |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603233228/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/otaiba-ambassador-uae-leaked-emails_us_5932bf04e4b02478cb9bec1c |archivedate=3 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Arab countries saw the media coverage of the alleged email hack as a provocation and a move orchestrated by Qatar,<ref>{{cite web |title=ANALYSIS: UAE envoy\u2019s hacked emails and Qatar\u2019s escalating Gulf rift |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2017/06/04/ANALYSIS-UAE-envoy-s-hacked-emails-and-Qatar-s-escalating-Gulf-rift-.html |date=4 June 2017 |publisher=Al Arabiya |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731203753/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2017/06/04/ANALYSIS-UAE-envoy-s-hacked-emails-and-Qatar-s-escalating-Gulf-rift-.html |archivedate=31 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and deepened the rift between the two sides.<ref name=FT>{{cite news |title=What is behind the extraordinary Gulf dispute with Qatar? |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3c6b7224-49d0-11e7-a3f4-c742b9791d43 |newspaper=Financial Times |date=5 June 2017 |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-access=subscription  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703000219/https://www.ft.com/content/3c6b7224-49d0-11e7-a3f4-c742b9791d43 |archivedate=3 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 9 June, Al Jazeera's media network was the victim of a [[cyber attack]] across all its platforms.<ref name=Metro6695692>{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/08/al-jazeera-hit-by-cyber-attack-on-all-systems-6695692/ |title=Al Jazeera hit by 'cyber attack on all systems' |first=Jen |last=Mills |work=Metro |accessdate=9 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609005503/http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/08/al-jazeera-hit-by-cyber-attack-on-all-systems-6695692/ |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to ''The Intercept'', Yousef al-Otaiba has been reportedly linked to buy influence for UAE-led campaigns in the White House.<ref name=FT2>{{cite news |title=Why UAE ambassador is so much influential in DC |url=https://theintercept.com/2017/07/30/uae-yousef-otaiba-cnas-american-progress-michele-flournoy-drone |newspaper=The Intercept |date=5 June 2017 |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-access=subscription  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730133741/https://theintercept.com/2017/07/30/uae-yousef-otaiba-cnas-american-progress-michele-flournoy-drone/ |archivedate=30 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Severance of diplomatic and economic ties==\nBetween 5 and 6 June 2017, Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Yemen, Egypt, the [[Maldives]], and Bahrain all separately announced that they were cutting diplomatic ties with Qatar; among these Bahrain was the first to announce the severing of ties at 02:50 GMT in the early morning of 5 June.<ref name=\"Qatar-Gulf crisis: Your questions answered\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/06/qatar-gulf-crisis-questions-answered-170606103033599.html |title=Qatar-Gulf crisis: Your questions answered |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=30 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728112951/http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/06/qatar-gulf-crisis-questions-answered-170606103033599.html |archivedate=28 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Why Saudi Arabia and six other countries have cut ties with Qatar |url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/work/leaders/why-saudi-arabia-and-six-other-countries-have-cut-ties-with-qatar/news-story/b758105a63a70df40b73211e0395d550 |work=News.com.au |accessdate=6 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607004931/http://www.news.com.au/finance/work/leaders/why-saudi-arabia-and-six-other-countries-have-cut-ties-with-qatar/news-story/b758105a63a70df40b73211e0395d550 |archivedate=7 June 2017 }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40155829 |title=Qatar row: Five countries cut links with Doha |date=5 June 2017 |work=BBC News |access-date=5 June 2017  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605041425/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40155829 |archivedate=5 June 2017 }}<br/>{{cite news |last1=Kirkpatrick |first1=David D. |last2=Barnard |first2=Anne |url=https://www.academia.edu/33408516/Terrorist_Attacks_Pour_Gas_on_Saudi-_Iranian_Rivalry_and_Gulf_Tensions |title=Terrorist Attacks Pour Gas on Saudi- Iranian Rivalry and Gulf Tensions |work=Eurasia Diary |date=7 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727235532/http://www.academia.edu/33408516/Terrorist_Attacks_Pour_Gas_on_Saudi-_Iranian_Rivalry_and_Gulf_Tensions |archivedate=27 July 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"nbcnews\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/egypt-saudi-arabia-among-gulf-states-cutting-ties-qatar-n768161 |title=Saudi Arabia Accuses Qatar of Backing Terrorism, Cuts Ties |last=Associated Press |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=NBC News|access-date=5 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605044937/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/egypt-saudi-arabia-among-gulf-states-cutting-ties-qatar-n768161|archive-date=5 June 2017|url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/05/saudi-arabia-and-bahrain-break-diplomatic-ties-with-qatar-over-terrorism |title=Gulf plunged into diplomatic crisis as countries cut ties with Qatar |last=Wintour |first=Patrick |date=5 June 2017|access-date=5 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605042514/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/05/saudi-arabia-and-bahrain-break-diplomatic-ties-with-qatar-over-terrorism|archive-date=5 June 2017|url-status=live  |newspaper=The Guardian |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/syria-crisis-turkey-and-saudi-arabia-shock-western-countries-by-supporting-antiassad-jihadists-10242747.html |title=Turkey and Saudi Arabia alarm the West by backing Islamist extremists the Americans had bombed in Syria |first=Kim |last=Sengupta |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=12 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150513214636/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/syria-crisis-turkey-and-saudi-arabia-shock-western-countries-by-supporting-antiassad-jihadists-10242747.html |archivedate=13 May 2015 }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.academia.edu/33408451/Qatar_Pursues_an_Independent_Foreign_Policy_that_Clashes_with_the_Saudis_Strategic_Interests.pdf |title=Qatar Pursues an Independent Foreign Policy that Clashes with the Saudi's Strategic Interests |work=Eurasia Diary |date=8 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727225548/http://www.academia.edu/33408451/Qatar_Pursues_an_Independent_Foreign_Policy_that_Clashes_with_the_Saudis_Strategic_Interests.pdf |archivedate=27 July 2017 }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.academia.edu/33408486/Saudi_Diplomatic_Offensive_on_Qatar_to_Barely_Impact_Anti-Terror_Fight_in_Region |title=Saudi Diplomatic Offensive on Qatar to Barely Impact Anti-Terror Fight in Region |work=Sputnik International |date=8 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727234344/http://www.academia.edu/33408486/Saudi_Diplomatic_Offensive_on_Qatar_to_Barely_Impact_Anti-Terror_Fight_in_Region |archivedate=27 July 2017 }}<br/>{{cite news |last1=Kirkpatrick |first2=David D. |last2=Barnard |first1=Anne |url=https://www.academia.edu/33408516/Terrorist_Attacks_Pour_Gas_on_Saudi-_Iranian_Rivalry_and_Gulf_Tensions |title=Terrorist Attacks Pour Gas on Saudi- Iranian Rivalry and Gulf Tensions |work=Eurasia Diary |date=7 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727235532/http://www.academia.edu/33408516/Terrorist_Attacks_Pour_Gas_on_Saudi-_Iranian_Rivalry_and_Gulf_Tensions |archivedate=27 July 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite news |url=https://www.academia.edu/33408486/Saudi_Diplomatic_Offensive_on_Qatar_to_Barely_Impact_Anti-Terror_Fight_in_Region |title=Saudi Diplomatic Offensive on Qatar to Barely Impact Anti-Terror Fight in Region |work=Sputnik International |date=8 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727234344/http://www.academia.edu/33408486/Saudi_Diplomatic_Offensive_on_Qatar_to_Barely_Impact_Anti-Terror_Fight_in_Region |archivedate=27 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Qatar Flights.png|thumb|upright=2|Maps showing the routes taken by Qatar Airways flights leaving Doha before and after the embargo was imposed. Data taken from [[Flightradar24|FlightRadar24]].]]\nA variety of diplomatic actions were taken. Saudi Arabia and the UAE notified ports and shipping agents not to receive Qatari vessels or ships owned by Qatari companies or individuals.<ref name=\"aljazeera1/6june2017\" /> Saudi Arabia closed the border with Qatar.<ref name=\"aljazeera1/6june2017\" /> Saudi Arabia restricted its airspace to [[Qatar Airways]]. Instead, Qatar was forced to reroute flights to Africa and Europe through Iranian airspace.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |title=Saudi-led Rupture With Qatar Pushes Nation into Iran's Embrace |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-06/saudi-led-rupture-with-qatar-pushes-nation-into-iran-s-embrace |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607085920/https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-06/saudi-led-rupture-with-qatar-pushes-nation-into-iran-s-embrace |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Saudi Arabia's central bank advised banks not to trade with Qatari banks in [[Qatari riyal]]s.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-saudi-banks-idUSKBN18X0S9 \"Saudi central bank tells banks not to trade with Qatar banks in Qatari riyals: sources\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003175217/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-saudi-banks-idUSKBN18X0S9 |date=3 October 2017 }}. Reuters</ref>\n\nQatar verbally criticized the ban. The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Qatar)|Foreign Ministry of Qatar]] criticized the ban, arguing that it undermined Qatar's sovereignty.<ref name=\"dawn/5june2017\"/> The foreign minister of Qatar, [[Mohammed bin Abdulrahman Al-Thani]], said that Saudi statements regarding Qatar were contradictory: on the one hand, Saudi Arabia claimed Qatar was supporting Iran, on the other hand, it claimed Qatar was funding [[Sunni]] extremists fighting against Iran.<ref>{{cite news |title=Qatar: We're 'willing to talk' to resolve diplomatic crisis |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/middleeast/qatar-diplomatic-crisis/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606101325/http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/middleeast/qatar-diplomatic-crisis/ |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia's move was welcomed by United States president Donald Trump despite a large US presence at the Al Udeid Air Base, the primary base of US air operations against the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-07/trump-s-qatar-curveball-makes-tillerson-improvise-policy-again |title=Trump's Qatar Curveball Makes Tillerson Improvise Policy Again |date=7 June 2017 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |accessdate=10 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826025948/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-07/trump-s-qatar-curveball-makes-tillerson-improvise-policy-again |archivedate=26 August 2017 }}<br/>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/06/06/for-qataris-a-u-s-air-base-is-best-defense-against-trump-attacks/ |title=For Qataris, a U.S. air base is best defense against Trump attacks |first1=Greg |last1=Jaffe |first2=Thomas |last2=Gibbons-Neff |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=10 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707090451/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/06/06/for-qataris-a-u-s-air-base-is-best-defense-against-trump-attacks/ |archivedate=7 July 2017 }}</ref> However, Secretary of State [[Rex Tillerson|Rex W. Tillerson]] and Defense Secretary [[James Mattis]] worked on de-escalating the situation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-07/trump-s-qatar-curveball-makes-tillerson-improvise-policy-again |title=Trump's Qatar Curveball Makes Tillerson Improvise Policy Again |date=7 June 2017 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |access-date=5 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826025948/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-07/trump-s-qatar-curveball-makes-tillerson-improvise-policy-again |archivedate=26 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tillerson, as the CEO of [[ExxonMobil]], was acquainted with the current and previous emirs of Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Overdahl |first1=Stian |title=Saudi and UAE Stumble Over Tiny Qatar |url=https://magazine.zenith.me/en/politics/pyrrhic-manoeuvres-among-gulf-states |accessdate=16 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828160937/https://magazine.zenith.me/en/politics/pyrrhic-manoeuvres-among-gulf-states |archivedate=28 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A number of countries in the region, including [[Qatar\u2013Turkey relations|Turkey]], [[Qatar\u2013Russia relations|Russia]] and [[Iran\u2013Qatar relations|Iran]], called for the crisis to be resolved through peaceful negotiations.\n\nAll [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]] countries involved in the announcement ordered their citizens out of Qatar.<ref name=\"associatedpress\">{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/8257ce650e224188a1884e34eabb5e90/4-Arab-nations-cut-diplomatic-ties-to-Qatar-as-rift-deepens |title=Arab nations cut ties with Qatar in new Mideast crisis |last=Gambrell |first=Jon |date=5 June 2017 |access-date=5 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625070305/https://www.apnews.com/8257ce650e224188a1884e34eabb5e90/4-Arab-nations-cut-diplomatic-ties-to-Qatar-as-rift-deepens |archive-date=25 June 2017 |url-status=live |agency=[[Associated Press]]  |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Three Gulf states (Saudi Arabia, UAE, Bahrain) gave Qatari visitors and residents two weeks to leave their countries.<ref name=\"dawn/5june2017\">{{cite news |agency=Reuters/AFP/AP |title=Saudi, Egypt, UAE, Bahrain and Yemen isolate Qatar over 'terrorism' as rift deepens |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1337555/saudi-egypt-uae-bahrain-and-yemen-isolate-qatar-over-terrorism-as-rift-deepens |accessdate=5 June 2017 |newspaper=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |date=5 June 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605090748/https://www.dawn.com/news/1337555/saudi-egypt-uae-bahrain-and-yemen-isolate-qatar-over-terrorism-as-rift-deepens |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The foreign ministries of Bahrain and Egypt gave Qatari diplomats 48 hours to leave their countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Qatar: 'No justification' for cutting diplomatic ties |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/qatar-justification-cutting-diplomatic-ties-170605073154112.html |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605091658/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/qatar-justification-cutting-diplomatic-ties-170605073154112.html |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\"/> Qatar was expelled from the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]] and Yemen's government itself has cut ties.<ref name=\"dawn/5june2017\" /> Kuwait and Oman remained neutral.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kuwait and Oman: As they remain silent on the Qatar-Gulf rift, what does this mean for them? |url=https://www.zawya.com/mena/en/story/Kuwait_and_Oman_As_they_remain_silent_on_the_QatarGulf_rift_what_does_this_mean_for_them-ZAWYA20170606110347/ |date=6 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606143751/https://www.zawya.com/mena/en/story/Kuwait_and_Oman_As_they_remain_silent_on_the_QatarGulf_rift_what_does_this_mean_for_them-ZAWYA20170606110347/ |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nKuwaiti mediators in Riyadh were presented with a list of Saudi demands of Qatar. These included cutting off all links with Iran and expelling resident members of Hamas and the Muslim Brotherhood, shutting down the Al-Jazeera network, to stop \"interfering\" in foreign countries' affairs and to cease any funding or support for terrorist organisations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/qatar-crisis-saudi-arabia-insists-150444797.html |title=Qatar crisis: Saudi Arabia insists Gulf country must meet its demands \u2018soon\u2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003175457/https://uk.news.yahoo.com/qatar-crisis-saudi-arabia-insists-150444797.html |archivedate=3 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Diplomatic activity===\n{{As of|2019|08|10|post=,}} seven sovereign governments have not restored diplomatic ties with Qatar.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-chad/chad-and-qatar-restore-ties-cut-in-wake-of-arab-states-rift-idUSKCN1G515I|title=Chad and Qatar restore ties cut in wake of Arab states rift|work=Reuters|date=21 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://maldivesindependent.com/politics/maldives-to-restore-ties-with-qatar-and-iran-142905|title=Maldives to restore ties with Qatar and Iran|website=Maldivesindependent.com|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Senegal restores its ambassador to Qatar |url=http://aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/senegal-restores-its-ambassador-to-qatar/890618 |publisher=Anadolu Agency |accessdate=22 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822051723/http://aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/senegal-restores-its-ambassador-to-qatar/890618 |archivedate=22 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Gulf Crisis: Saudi-led bloc loses ally Senegal in boycott of Qatar |url=https://me-confidential.com/16844-gulf-crisis-saudi-led-bloc-loses-ally-senegal-in-boycott-of-qatar.html |publisher=Middle East Confidential |accessdate=22 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822191946/http://me-confidential.com/16844-gulf-crisis-saudi-led-bloc-loses-ally-senegal-in-boycott-of-qatar.html |archivedate=22 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{div col}}\n*{{flag|Bahrain}}\n*{{flag|Comoros}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=1638089 |title=Comoros severs diplomatic relations with Qatar The official Saudi Press Agency |publisher=spa.gov.sa |accessdate=8 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015120038/http://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=1638089 |archivedate=15 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Egypt}}\n*{{flag|Mauritania}} \n*{{flag|Saudi Arabia}}\n*{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}\n*{{flag|Yemen}} ([[Cabinet of Yemen]])\n{{divend}}\n\nThe [[Tobruk]]-based [[Second Al-Thani Cabinet|government]] of Libya claimed to have cut diplomatic ties with Qatar despite having no diplomatic representation in that country.<ref name=\"CNNlist\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-libya-idUSKBN18W11M |title=Libya's eastern-based government cuts diplomatic ties with Qatar |date=5 June 2017 |agency=Reute rs |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619142529/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-libya-idUSKBN18W11M |archivedate=19 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2017/06/05/beida-government-cuts-off-diplomatic-relations-with-qatar/ |title=Beida government cuts off diplomatic relations with Qatar |last=Prentis |first=Jamie |date=5 June 2017 |work=Libya Herald |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613002409/https://www.libyaherald.com/2017/06/05/beida-government-cuts-off-diplomatic-relations-with-qatar/ |archive-date=13 June 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe semi-autonomous [[States and regions of Somalia#States|Somali regions]] of [[Puntland]],\n[[Hirshabelle]], and [[Galmudug]] each issued statements cutting ties with Qatar, in opposition to the neutral stance of the federal government of [[Somalia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/09/somalia-rebukes-states-breaking-qatar-170922021127727.html |title=Somalia chides its regions for cutting ties with Qatar |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=22 September 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929184134/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/09/somalia-rebukes-states-breaking-qatar-170922021127727.html |archivedate=29 September 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019|08|10|post=,}} two countries still have downgraded diplomatic ties with Qatar without fully cutting relations.<ref name=\"CNNlist\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/middleeast/qatar-diplomatic-crisis/index.html |title=Qatar: We're 'willing to talk' to resolve diplomatic crisis |publisher=CNN |date=6 June 2017 |accessdate=6 June 2017 |author1=Katie Hunt |author2=Elizabeth Roberts |author3=Victoria Brown |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606113452/http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/middleeast/qatar-diplomatic-crisis/index.html |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n{{div col}}\n*{{flag|Djibouti}}<ref name=\"DjiTieDowngrade\">{{cite web |url=http://www.djibdiplomatie.dj/index.php/8-communique-de-presse/660-urgent-communique-de-presse |title=URGENT/COMMUNIQUE DE PRESSE |last=Djibdiplomatie1 |website=djibdiplomatie.dj |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821003340/http://www.djibdiplomatie.dj/index.php/8-communique-de-presse/660-urgent-communique-de-presse |archivedate=21 August 2017 |df=dmy-all |access-date=7 June 2017 }}</ref>\n*{{flag|Niger}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Niger recalls ambassador to Qatar in solidarity with Arab states |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/gulf-qatar-niger-idUSL8N1J70A1 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611202259/http://www.reuters.com/article/gulf-qatar-niger-idUSL8N1J70A1 |archivedate=11 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{divend}}\n\nOther countries made statements condemning Qatar, including [[Gabon]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Mauritania breaks diplomatic ties with Qatar, Gabon voices condemnation |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-mauritania-idUSKBN18X2ZH |agency=Reuters |accessdate=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607193940/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-mauritania-idUSKBN18X2ZH |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Eritrea]].<ref name=Eritrea>{{cite news |title=Eritrea sides with Gulf nations against Qatar |url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1113951/middle-east |accessdate=13 June 2017 |work=Arab News |agency=Associated Press |date=12 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613075605/http://www.arabnews.com/node/1113951/middle-east |archivedate=13 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan arriving in Tehran's Mehrabad International Airport.jpg|thumb|[[Turkey]] has supported Qatar in its diplomatic confrontation with a Saudi and Emirati-led bloc of countries<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20170625-why-turkey-backing-qatar-diplomatic-crisis|title=Why Turkey is backing Qatar in Gulf diplomatic crisis|publisher=France 24|author=Tom Wheeldon|date=26 June 2017}}</ref> ]] \nMultiple countries, the [[European Union]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.gulfnews.com/news/gulf/qatar/eu-urges-talks-to-resolve-qatar-crisis-1.2063305 |title=EU urges talks to resolve Qatar crisis |work=Gulf News |date=24 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724054719/http://m.gulfnews.com/news/gulf/qatar/eu-urges-talks-to-resolve-qatar-crisis-1.2063305 |archivedate=24 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/eu-mogherini-urges-direct-talks-gulf-crisis-170723162849193.html |title=EU's Mogherini urges direct talks to end Gulf crisis |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=24 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724074239/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/eu-mogherini-urges-direct-talks-gulf-crisis-170723162849193.html |archivedate=24 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the [[United Nations]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.un.org/press/en/2017/sgsm18559.doc.htm |title=Deeply Concerned by Middle East Situation, Secretary-General Encourages Diplomacy to Avoid Escalating Tensions {{!}} Meetings Coverage and Press Releases|publisher=United Nations|language=en|access-date=8 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721023828/http://www.un.org/press/en/2017/sgsm18559.doc.htm|archivedate=21 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> called for resolution of the diplomatic crisis through dialogue:\n\n{{div col}}\n*{{flag|Algeria}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aa.com.tr/en/africa/algeria-calls-for-dialogue-to-resolve-qatar-row/835502 |title=Algeria calls for dialogue to resolve Qatar row |publisher=Anadolu Agency |date=6 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704210933/http://aa.com.tr/en/africa/algeria-calls-for-dialogue-to-resolve-qatar-row/835502 |archivedate=4 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Canada}}<ref name=\"theglobeandmail.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/international-business/amid-qatar-boycott-canadian-firms-urged-to-consider-alternative-plans/article35240109/|title=Amid Qatar boycott, Canadian firms urged to consider alternative plans|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n*{{flag|China}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://af.reuters.com/article/energyOilNews/idAFL3N1J221D |title=Amid Qatar crisis, China tells Iran that Gulf stability is best |agency=Reuters |accessdate=9 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609002054/http://af.reuters.com/article/energyOilNews/idAFL3N1J221D |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Ethiopia}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Ethiopia Vows to Extend More Support for Sustainable Peace Between Qatar and the Gulf Region Countries |url=http://www.awrambatimes.com/?p=16412 |date=19 June 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017 |work=Awramba Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619215539/http://www.awrambatimes.com/?p=16412 |archivedate=19 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|France}}<ref>{{cite web |title=French Foreign Minister Heads to Gulf States to Help Resolve Qatar Crisis |url=https://sputniknews.com/politics/201707151055568500-french-minister-qatar-mediation/ |publisher=Sputnik International |accessdate=15 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715073016/https://sputniknews.com/politics/201707151055568500-french-minister-qatar-mediation/ |archivedate=15 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=France wades into Qatar row, urges end to punitive measures |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/uae-diplomat-warns-of-long-estrangement-in-qatar-crisis/2017/07/15/b9c97cca-6942-11e7-94ab-5b1f0ff459df_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=15 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715130534/https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/uae-diplomat-warns-of-long-estrangement-in-qatar-crisis/2017/07/15/b9c97cca-6942-11e7-94ab-5b1f0ff459df_story.html |archivedate=15 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Germany}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Germany urges diplomatic solution to Qatar crisis |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-germany-idUSKBN19010W?il=0 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=9 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720050929/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-germany-idUSKBN19010W?il=0 |archivedate=20 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Guinea}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasdaq.com/article/guineas-president-offers-to-mediate-in-gulf-crisis-20170611-00057 |title=Guinea's president offers to mediate in Gulf crisis |date=11 June 2017 |publisher=NASDAQ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612072111/http://www.nasdaq.com/article/guineas-president-offers-to-mediate-in-gulf-crisis-20170611-00057 |archivedate=12 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|India}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Qatar crisis: India favours constructive dialogue |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/qatar-crisis-india-favours-constructive-dialogue/articleshow/59084917.cms |accessdate=12 June 2017 |work=The Times of India |date=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611001105/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/qatar-crisis-india-favours-constructive-dialogue/articleshow/59084917.cms |archivedate=11 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Indonesia}}<ref name=\"antaranews\">{{cite news |title=Indonesia calls for dialogue over Qatar rift with Arab states |url=http://www.antaranews.com/en/news/111240/indonesia-calls-for-dialogue-over-qatar-rift-with-arab-states |accessdate=15 June 2017 |work=Antara News |date=5 June 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605191828/http://www.antaranews.com/en/news/111240/indonesia-calls-for-dialogue-over-qatar-rift-with-arab-states |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Iran}}<ref name=\"yahoo1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/saudi-arabia-egypt-uae-sever-ties-qatar-over-040718986.html|title=Arab powers sever Qatar ties, widening rift among US allies |last=Browning |first=Noah |date=5 June 2017 |access-date=5 June 2017 |agency=Reuters  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605045835/https://www.yahoo.com/news/saudi-arabia-egypt-uae-sever-ties-qatar-over-040718986.html |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/04/saudi-arabia-bahrain-and-egypt-cut-diplomatic-ties-with-qatar.html |title=Saudi Arabia, Egypt lead Arab states cutting Qatar ties, Iran blames Trump |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=CNBC |access-date=5 June 2017 |agency=Reuters with AP |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605052416/http://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/04/saudi-arabia-bahrain-and-egypt-cut-diplomatic-ties-with-qatar.html |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n*{{flag|Italy}}<ref name=\"aljazeeraenglish\">{{cite news |title=Qatar to buy seven navy vessels from Italy for \u20ac5bn |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/08/qatar-buy-7-navy-vessels-italy-5bn-170802135937765.html |accessdate=3 August 2017 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=2 August 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802233020/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/08/qatar-buy-7-navy-vessels-