 |date=8 June 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608105816/https://www.dawn.com/news/1338258/middle-east-diplomatic-crisis-lawmakers-pass-resolution-in-na-urging-restraint |archivedate=8 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Russia}}<ref name=RussianStance>{{cite news |title=Russia Hopes Anti-Terror Efforts Unaffected by Qatar Diplomatic Row |url=https://sputniknews.com/world/201706051054319483-russia-kremlin-qatar-diplomacy/ |accessdate=5 June 2017 |work=Sputnik News |date=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605122627/https://sputniknews.com/world/201706051054319483-russia-kremlin-qatar-diplomacy/ |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Somalia}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201706080163.html |title=Somalia: Govt Breaks Silence Over the Qatar Crisis |publisher=allAfrica |date=7 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610101236/http://allafrica.com/stories/201706080163.html |archivedate=10 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Sudan}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://m.news24.com/news24/Africa/News/sudan-urges-reconciliation-to-end-gulf-row-with-qatar-20170606 |title=Sudan urges 'reconciliation' to end Gulf row with Qatar |date=6 June 2017 |work=News24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606123705/http://m.news24.com/news24/africa/news/sudan-urges-reconciliation-to-end-gulf-row-with-qatar-20170606 |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20170606-sudan-appeals-for-calm-between-qatar-and-gulf/ |title=Sudan appeals for calm between Qatar and Gulf |publisher=Middle East Monitor |date=6 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606140934/https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20170606-sudan-appeals-for-calm-between-qatar-and-gulf/ |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Switzerland}}<ref>[https://www.thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/31/03/2018/Switzerland-backs-Kuwaiti-efforts-to-resolve-Gulf-crisis Switzerland backs Kuwaiti efforts to resolve Gulf crisis] ''The Peninsula''. Qatar's Daily Newspaper. Retrieved 6 May 2018.</ref>\n*{{flag|Tunisia}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Tunisia follows with concern diplomatic crisis in Gulf countries |publisher=Xinhua Net |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-06/06/c_136342155.htm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605201953/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-06/06/c_136342155.htm |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Turkey}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-turkey-idUSKBN18W19Z |title=Turkey calls for dialogue over Qatar rift with Arab states |date=5 June 2017 |agency=Reuters |access-date=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605121746/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-turkey-idUSKBN18W19Z |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|United Kingdom}}<ref name=\"SolomonFinTimes\"/>\n*{{flag|Venezuela}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gulf-times.com/story/622922/Venezuela-rejects-unjust-blockade-against-Qatar|title=Venezuela rejects unjust blockade against Qatar|last=|first=|date=21 February 2019|work=Gulf Times|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n{{divend}}\n\nHassan al-Thawadi, secretary general of the Qatar World Cup supreme committee, has stated that projects are progressing as scheduled for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]. Qatar's only land border and air and sea routes have been cut off by Bahrain, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE). As the blockade came into play, World Cup organizers were asked to investigate a \"Plan B\", [[FIFA]] however has confidence in not exploring a \"Plan B\" for an alternate 2022 host. According to Thawadi, all these logistical obstacles are being overcome and building progress is continuing with only minimal cost increases, in preparation for the first World Cup in the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/10/gulf-blockade-poses-risk-qatar-world-cup-171006210428080.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=8 October 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008154735/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/10/gulf-blockade-poses-risk-qatar-world-cup-171006210428080.html |archivedate=8 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Global Reactions ==\n===United States===\n[[File:Donald Trump meets with the Emir of Qatar (Sheikh Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani), May 2017.jpg|thumb|[[United States President]] Donald Trump with the [[Emir of Qatar]] [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]], May 2017.]]\n[[File:Secretary Tillerson is Escorted to his Meeting With the Emir of Qatar (35088035863).jpg|thumb|UAE and Saudi Arabia lobbied President Trump to fire [[Rex Tillerson]] for not supporting the blockade of Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alex |last=Emmons |title=Saudi Arabia Planned to Invade Qatar Last Summer. Rex Tillerson\u2019s Efforts to Stop It May Have Cost Him His Job. |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/08/01/rex-tillerson-qatar-saudi-uae/ |work=The Intercept |date=August 1, 2018}}</ref>]]\n[[United States]] President [[Donald Trump]] claimed credit for engineering the diplomatic crisis in a [[Donald Trump on social media|series of tweets]].<ref name=credit>{{cite news |publisher=BBC |title=Qatar row: Trump claims credit for isolation |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40175935 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607013027/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40175935 |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 6 June, Trump began by tweeting: \"During my recent trip to the Middle East I stated that there can no longer be funding of Radical Ideology. Leaders pointed to Qatar \u2013 look!\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=realDonaldTrump |last=Trump |first=Donald J. |number=872062159789985792 |date=6 June 2017 |title=During my recent trip to the Middle East I stated that there can no longer be funding of Radical Ideology. Leaders pointed to Qatar \u2013 look! |link=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872062159789985792 |access-date=7 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606120637/https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872062159789985792 |archive-date=6 June 2017 |url-status= live}}</ref><ref name= credit /> An hour and a half later, he remarked on Twitter that it was \"good to see the Saudi Arabia visit with the King and 50 countries already paying off. They said they would take a hard line on funding extremism, and all reference{{sic}} was pointing to Qatar. Perhaps this will be the beginning of the end to the horror of terrorism!\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=realDonaldTrump |last=Trump |first=Donald J.  |number=872084870620520448 |date=6 June 2017 |title=So good to see the Saudi Arabia visit with the King and 50 countries already paying off. They said they would take a hard line on funding... |link=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872084870620520448 |access-date=7 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606133708/https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872084870620520448 |archive-date= 6 June 2017 |url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=realDonaldTrump |last=Trump |first=Donald J.  |number=872086906804240384 |date=6 June 2017 |title=...extremism, and all reference was pointing to Qatar. Perhaps this will be the beginning of the end to the horror of terrorism! |link=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872086906804240384 |access-date= 7 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606134456/https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872086906804240384 |archive-date= 6 June 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name= \"WaPo 6 June\"/> This was in contrast to attempts by [[the Pentagon]] and the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]] to remain neutral. The Pentagon praised Qatar for hosting the Al Udeid Air Base and for its \"enduring commitment to regional security.\" [[United States Ambassador to Qatar|US Ambassador to Qatar]], [[Dana Shell Smith]], sent a similar message.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. military praises Qatar, despite Trump tweet |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-usa-pentagon-idUSKBN18X2G2 |accessdate=8 June 2017 |agency=Reuters |date=6 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607190432/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-usa-pentagon-idUSKBN18X2G2 |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump appears to take credit for Gulf nations' move against Qatar |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/politics/trump-qatar-ideology/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607002540/http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/politics/trump-qatar-ideology/ |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Earlier, the US [[U.S. Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] had taken a neutral stance and called for dialogue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/05/tillerson-says-break-with-qatar-by-saudi-arabia-others-wont-affect-counter-terrorism.html |title=Tillerson says break with Qatar by Saudi Arabia, others won't affect counter-terrorism |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=CNBC |access-date=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605081330/http://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/05/tillerson-says-break-with-qatar-by-saudi-arabia-others-wont-affect-counter-terrorism.html |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nOn 8 June, President Donald Trump, during a phone call with the [[Emir of Qatar]] [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]], offered to act as a mediator in the conflict with a White House meeting between the parties if necessary.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gaouette |first1=Nicole |last2=Browne |first2=Ryan |title=Trump reverses course in Qatar call |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/07/politics/trump-qatar-call/index.html |accessdate=8 June 2017 |publisher=CNN |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608070721/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/07/politics/trump-qatar-call/index.html |archivedate=8 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The offer was declined, and a Qatari official stated, \"The emir has no plans to leave Qatar while the country is under a blockade.\"<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-idUSKBN18Z1C9 |title=Qatar vows no surrender in Gulf crisis as U.S., Kuwait seek solution |date=8 June 2017 |agency=Reuters |access-date=8 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608113447/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-idUSKBN18Z1C9 |archivedate=8 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 9 June, Trump once again put the blame on Qatar, calling the blockade \"hard but necessary\" while claiming that Qatar had been funding terrorism at a \"very high level\" and described the country as having an \"extremist ideology in terms of funding.\"<ref name=\"Mindock\">{{cite news |last1=Mindock |first1=Clark |title=Donald Trump accuses Qatar of funding terrorism 'at very high level' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-qatar-terrorism-funding-saudi-arabia-gulf-accusation-very-high-level-a7782896.html |accessdate=10 June 2017 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609204835/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-qatar-terrorism-funding-saudi-arabia-gulf-accusation-very-high-level-a7782896.html |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> This statement was in conflict with Secretary of State Tillerson's comments on the same day, which called on Gulf states to ease the blockade.<ref name=contradict>{{cite news |title=President Trump Just Directly Contradicted His Secretary of State |url=http://time.com/4813247/donald-trump-contradict-rex-tillerson-qatar/ |work=Time |accessdate=9 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609213250/http://time.com/4813247/donald-trump-contradict-rex-tillerson-qatar/ |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Mindock\"/> In 13 June 2017 after meeting with Tillerson in Washington, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Saudi Foreign Minister]] [[Adel al-Jubeir]] stated that there was \"no blockade\" and \"what we have done is we have denied them use of our airspace, and this is our sovereign right,\" and that the King Salman Centre for Humanitarian Aid and Relief would send food or medical aid to Qatar if needed.<ref name=\"TurkeyBBC\"/> The following day, Trump authorized the sale of $12 billion of U.S. weapons to Qatar.<ref>Brennan, Margaret and Kylie Atwood.  [https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-sells-qatar-12-billion-arms-days-after-accusing-it-of-funding-terrorism/ \"Trump sells Qatar $12 billion of U.S. weapons days after accusing it of funding terrorism.\"] ''CBS News''.  15 June 2017.  21 January 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 2017, Trump told a crowd in [[Iowa]] that \"We cannot let these incredibly rich nations fund radical Islamic terror or terrorism of any kind\", noting that after his visit to Riyadh in May 2017 to meet with Saudi [[King Salman]] and urge an end to terror funding, \"He has taken it to heart. And now they're fighting with other countries that have been funding terrorism. And I think we had a huge impact.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/transcript/2017/06/21/conway-special-elections-reaffirmation-trumps-agenda-sekulow-investigation-should-include-comeys-leak.html |title=Conway: Special elections a reaffirmation of Trump's agenda; Sekulow: Investigation should include Comey's leak |date=21 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630215456/http://www.foxnews.com/transcript/2017/06/21/conway-special-elections-reaffirmation-trumps-agenda-sekulow-investigation-should-include-comeys-leak.html |archivedate=30 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-qatar-list-20170623-story.html |title=Will Qatar agree to Arab countries' new list of demands? Unlikely |first=Molly |last=Hennessy-Fiske |date=23 June 2017 |work=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630180620/http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-qatar-list-20170623-story.html |archivedate=30 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n===Other countries===\nIsrael's former defense minister, [[Avigdor Lieberman]], described the situation as an \"opportunity\" for Israel, stating, \"Some [Arab countries'] interests overlap with Israeli interests, including the issue with al-Jazeera.\" He went on to describe al-Jazeera as an \"incitement machine\" and \"pure propaganda.\" Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] has demanded al-Jazeera shut down its offices in Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-demands-al-jazeera-offices-in-israel-be-shut-down/ |title=Netanyahu demands al-Jazeera offices in Israel be shut down |website=The Times of Israel |accessdate=30 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727013412/http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-demands-al-jazeera-offices-in-israel-be-shut-down/ |archivedate=27 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nReports that Mauritius had cut ties with Qatar were refuted by the Mauritian government.<ref name=\"IONNews\">{{cite news |url=http://ionnews.mu/maurice-maintient-ses-relations-diplomatiques-avec-le-qatar-060617/ |title=Maurice maintient ses relations diplomatiques avec le Qatar |trans-title=Mauritius maintains its diplomatic relations with Qatar |agency=Indian Ocean News Network |date=6 June 2017 |accessdate=7 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703201410/http://ionnews.mu/maurice-maintient-ses-relations-diplomatiques-avec-le-qatar-060617/ |archivedate=3 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"DefiMedia\">{{cite news |url=http://defimedia.info/diplomatie-maurice-maintient-ses-liens-avec-le-qatar |title=Diplomatie : Maurice maintient ses liens avec le Qatar |trans-title=Diplomacy: Mauritius maintains its links with Qatar |agency=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]] |date=7 June 2017 |accessdate=7 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717090106/http://defimedia.info/diplomatie-maurice-maintient-ses-liens-avec-le-qatar |archivedate=17 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A report in the ''[[Saudi Gazette]]'' incorrectly stated that Mauritius had broken off ties with Qatar and that [[Vice Prime Minister of Mauritius|Mauritius' Vice Prime-Minister]] had issued a communiqu\u00e9 pledging his country's support for Saudi Arabia. This prompted further erroneous reports by other outlets. However, Mauritian [[Vice Prime Minister of Mauritius|Vice Prime Minister]] Showkutally Soodhun in an interview with [[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]] of Mauritius refuted claims that he had issued any such communiqu\u00e9, and [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Mauritius)|Mauritius' Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] issued a statement that Mauritius continued to maintain diplomatic relations with Qatar.<ref name=\"IONNews\"/><ref name=\"DefiMedia\"/>\n\nPakistan stated that it had no plans to cut diplomatic relations with Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan has no plans to cut diplomatic ties with Qatar: FO |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1427775/pakistan-no-plans-cut-diplomatic-ties-qatar-fo/ |accessdate=5 June 2017 |work=The Express Tribune |date=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605095833/https://tribune.com.pk/story/1427775/pakistan-no-plans-cut-diplomatic-ties-qatar-fo/ |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Members of the Parliament passed a resolution in [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] urging all countries to \"show restraint and resolve their differences through dialogue.\"<ref name=\"auto2\"/> The Pakistani Federal minister for Petroleum and Natural Resources said that \"Pakistan will continue to import liquefied natural gas (LNG) from Qatar.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan to continue import of LNG from Qatar |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1338261/pakistan-to-continue-import-of-lng-from-qatar |accessdate=8 June 2017 |work=Dawn|location=Pakistan |date=8 June 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609040058/https://www.dawn.com/news/1338261/pakistan-to-continue-import-of-lng-from-qatar |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A six-member Qatari delegation headed by a special envoy of the Qatari Emir visited Pakistan and asked Pakistan to play a positive role in resolving the diplomatic crisis former, and the Prime Minister of Pakistan, [[Nawaz Sharif]], was quoted as saying that \"Pakistan would do 'all it can' to help resolve the crisis,\" as well as calling on the Muslim world to play a role in ending hostilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Siddiqui |first1=Dawn.com |title=Delegation headed by special envoy of Qatari Emir makes short visit to Pakistan |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1338268/delegation-headed-by-special-envoy-of-qatari-emir-makes-short-visit-to-pakistan |accessdate=8 June 2017 |work=Dawn|location=Pakistan |date=8 June 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003180039/https://www.dawn.com/news/1338268/delegation-headed-by-special-envoy-of-qatari-emir-makes-short-visit-to-pakistan |archivedate=3 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation|TRT]] report stated that Pakistan would deploy 20,000 troops in Qatar, which the Pakistani foreign ministry denied.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2017/06/11/Pakistan-denies-media-reports-of-troop-deployment-to-Qatar.html |title=Pakistan denies media reports of troop deployment to Qatar |accessdate=11 June 2017 |publisher=Al Arabiya Network |date=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003174927/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2017/06/11/Pakistan-denies-media-reports-of-troop-deployment-to-Qatar.html |archivedate=3 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Philippines suspended the deployment of migrant workers to Qatar on 6 June 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Philippines bans deployment of workers to Qatar |url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/manila/local-news/2017/06/06/philippines-bans-deployment-workers-qatar-545962 |accessdate=6 June 2017 |work=Sun Star Manila |agency=HDT, SunStar Philippines |date=6 June 2017}}</ref> However, the next day, they allowed the deployment of returning workers and those with an Overseas Employment Certificate, but still maintained the suspension of the deployment of new workers.<ref>{{cite news |title=PHL partially lifts suspension of OFW deployment to Qatar |publisher=GMA network |url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/pinoyabroad/613610/phl-partially-lifts-ban-on-ofw-deployment-to-qatar/story/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717145919/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/pinoyabroad/613610/phl-partially-lifts-ban-on-ofw-deployment-to-qatar/story/ |archivedate=17 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The suspension was later fully lifted on 15 June.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jaymalin |first1=Mayen |title=DOLE lifts suspension of OFW deployment in Qatar |url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2017/06/16/1710495/dole-lifts-suspension-ofw-deployment-qatar |accessdate=16 June 2017 |work=The Philippine Star |date=16 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615191514/http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2017/06/16/1710495/dole-lifts-suspension-ofw-deployment-qatar |archivedate=15 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 June 2017, Egypt's deputy [[United Nations|UN]] Ambassador Ihab Moustafa called for the [[United Nations Security Council]] to launch an investigation into accusations that Qatar \"paid up to $1 billion to a terrorist group active in Iraq\" to free 26 Qatari hostages, including members of its royal family, which payment would violate UN resolutions. The Qataris were kidnapped on 16 December 2015 from a desert camp for falcon hunters in [[southern Iraq]]. The hostages were released eighteen months later in April 2017. Qatari diplomats responded to the Egyptian calls for an investigation by reaffirming their commitment to the UN resolutions towards eliminating the financing of terrorism.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-un-idUSKBN18Z26W |title=Egypt calls for U.N. inquiry into accusation of Qatar ransom payment |date=8 June 2017 |agency=Reuters |access-date=8 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608222124/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-un-idUSKBN18Z26W |archivedate=8 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/latest-qatar-releases-initial-report-alleged-hack-47904088 |title=The Latest: Egypt seeks UN probe of alleged Qatar ransom |last=News |first=ABC |publisher=ABC News |access-date=8 June 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608042824/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/latest-qatar-releases-initial-report-alleged-hack-47904088 |archivedate=8 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, the government of Qatar hired American attorney and politician [[John Ashcroft]] to lobby on its behalf and help the state deny international allegations of supporting terror.<ref>{{cite web |title=Qatar, accused of supporting terrorism, hires ex-U.S. attorney general \u2013 Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-ashcroft-idUSKBN1910T6 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610181957/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-ashcroft-idUSKBN1910T6 |archivedate=10 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Singled Out by Trump, Qatar Hires Former Top U.S. Law Man \u2013 Bloomberg |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-10/singled-out-by-trump-qatar-hires-former-top-law-man-to-lobby |website=BloombergPolitics |accessdate=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610041552/https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-10/singled-out-by-trump-qatar-hires-former-top-law-man-to-lobby |archivedate=10 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Qatar blockade: Iran sends five planeloads of food \u2013 BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40237721 |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612040431/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40237721 |archivedate=12 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Qatar Hires Former U.S. Attorney General To Rebut Terrorism Allegations |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/qatar-hires-lawyer-boycott-terrorism-allegations-saudis-trump/28539933.html |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |accessdate=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610205539/https://www.rferl.org/a/qatar-hires-lawyer-boycott-terrorism-allegations-saudis-trump/28539933.html |archivedate=10 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 November 2017, deputy chief of Dubai Police Lieutenant General Dhahi Khalfan, blamed the [[2017 Sinai attack]] on Al-Jazeera's reporting and called for the bombing of Al-Jazeera's headquarters by the Saudi-led coalition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/11/dubai-security-chief-calls-bombing-al-jazeera-171125143439231.html|title=Dubai security chief calls for bombing of Al Jazeera|website=aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn=13960905000275|title=Farsnews|website=en.farsnews.com}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n\n===Logistical implications===\n\nOn 6 June 2017, [[Emirates Post]] of UAE halted postal services to Qatar.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/emirates-post-group-halts-services-qatar-677207.html |title=Emirates Post Group halts services to Qatar |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609072905/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/emirates-post-group-halts-services-qatar-677207.html |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nNearly 80 percent of Qatar's food requirements come from Persian Gulf Arab neighbors, with only 1 percent being produced domestically and even imports from outside the Gulf states usually crossing the now closed land border with Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Adam |title=Analysis {{!}} Qatar could face a food crisis in spat with Arab neighbors|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/06/05/qatar-could-face-a-food-crisis-in-spat-with-arab-neighbors/|accessdate=7 June 2017|work=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606222639/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/06/05/qatar-could-face-a-food-crisis-in-spat-with-arab-neighbors/|archivedate=6 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Immediately after the cutting of relations, local reports indicated residents [[Panic buying|swarmed]] grocery stores in hopes of stockpiling food. Many food delivery trucks were idled along the Saudi-Qatari border. On 8 June 2017, Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh [[Mohammed bin Abdulrahman al-Thani]] said, \"We're not worried about a food shortage, we're fine. We can live forever like this, we are well prepared.\" {{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Qatar has been in talks with both Turkey and Iran to secure supply of food. On 11 June 2017, Iran sent four cargo planes with fruit and vegetables and promised to continue the supply.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-iran-idUSKBN1920EG?il=0 |title=Iran flies food to Qatar amid concerns of shortages |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=11 June 2017 |access-date=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003174716/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-iran-idUSKBN1920EG?il=0 |archivedate=3 October 2017 }}</ref> Turkey has pledged food and water supplies to go along with their troop deployment at their [[Turkish military]] base in Qatar.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nAs part of the Qatari government's response to lost food imports, it provided support to domestic agricultural company [[Baladna (company)|Baladna]], which built a new dairy farm with imported cattle that was planned to produce enough milk to fulfill domestic demand for dairy products by June 2018.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-cows/qatar-builds-dairy-industry-in-desert-as-it-defies-arab-boycott-idUSKBN1DT2E9 | title=Qatar builds dairy industry in desert as it defies Arab boycott | work=Reuters | date=29 November 2017 | accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>{{update inline|date=September 2018}}\n\n===Air travel===\nAll [[airlines]] based in these countries, including [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]], suspended flights to and from Qatar.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-05/saudi-led-alliance-cuts-qatar-ties-as-gulf-crisis-escalates |title=Flights Grounded as Gulf Split on Iran Leaves Qatar Isolated |last=Carey |first=Glen |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |access-date=5 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605041617/https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-05/saudi-led-alliance-cuts-qatar-ties-as-gulf-crisis-escalates |archive-date=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |last2=Fattah |first2=Zainab |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.emirates.com/ae/english/about/operational_updates/operational_updates.aspx#/#4258319 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606220356/https://www.emirates.com/ae/english/about/operational_updates/operational_updates.aspx |archivedate=6 June 2017 |title=Suspension of flights between Dubai and Doha with effect from 6 June 2017 |publisher=[[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] |date=5 June 2017}}</ref> [[Gulf Air]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Emirates, Etihad, Flydubai, Gulf Air and Air Arabia to suspend Qatar flights |url=http://gulfbusiness.com/abu-dhabis-etihad-suspend-flights-qatar-tuesday/ |first=Aarti |last=Nagraj |date=5 June 2017 |work=Gulf Business |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606032326/http://gulfbusiness.com/abu-dhabis-etihad-suspend-flights-qatar-tuesday/ |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[EgyptAir]],<ref>{{cite news |title=EgyptAir Suspends Flights to Qatar Until Special Notice |url=https://sputniknews.com/middleeast/201706051054314335-egyptair-suspends-flights-to-qatar/ |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=[[Sputniknews.com]] |language=en |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702081250/https://sputniknews.com/middleeast/201706051054314335-egyptair-suspends-flights-to-qatar/ |archivedate=2 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[FlyDubai]], [[Air Arabia]], [[Saudi Arabian Airlines]] and [[Etihad Airways]] suspended their flights to and from Qatar.<ref name=\"aljazeera/5june2017\">{{cite news |title=Qatar diplomatic crisis: How it affects air travel|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/qatar-diplomatic-crisis-affects-air-travel-170605093547258.html|date=5 June 2017|agency=Al Jazeera|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref> Bahrain,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blog.flightradar24.com/blog/flight-ban-for-qatar-flights-in-uae-saudi-arabia-bahrain-and-egypt/|title=Flight Ban for Qatar Flights in UAE, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, and Egypt|date=5 June 2017|accessdate=5 June 2017|work=[[Flightradar24]]}}</ref> Egypt, Saudi Arabia, and the United Arab Emirates are also banning overflights by aircraft registered in Qatar (A7). Instead Qatar has rerouted flights to Africa and Europe via Iran,<ref name=auto1/> paying a \u201chefty\u201d overflight fee for each such flight.<ref name=veconomist>{{cite news|title=The boycott of Qatar is hurting its enforcers|url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21730426-if-saudis-and-emiratis-will-not-trade-doha-iranians-will-boycott|work=[[The Economist]]|date=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nQatar Airways in response also suspended its flight operations to Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Egypt, and Bahrain.<ref name=\"aljazeera/5june2017\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatarairways.com/us/en/travel-alerts.page|title=Travel Alerts {{!}} Qatar Airways|date=5 June 2017|website=Qatar Airways|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Pakistan International Airlines]] sent special flights to bring back over 200 Pakistani pilgrims stuck at [[Hamad International Airport|Doha airport]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Qatar row: Over 200 Pakistani pilgrims stuck at Doha airport \u2013 Pakistan \u2013 Dunya News|url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/391625-Qatar-row-Over-200-Pakistani-pilgrims-stuck-at-Do|accessdate=6 June 2017|work=dunyanews.tv}}</ref> Over 550 Pakistani pilgrims in Doha were subsequently flown to [[Muscat, Oman|Muscat]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Siddiqui|first=Naveed|title=550 Pakistani pilgrims stranded in Qatar flown to Muscat |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1337785/550-pakistani-pilgrims-stranded-in-qatar-flown-to-muscat |accessdate=6 June 2017 |work=Dawn|location=Pakistan|date=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrivate jet travel is also being impacted by the crisis. Business aviation officials said private flights between Qatar and the countries that cut diplomatic ties now need to make a technical stop in a third country. Aircraft registered in Qatar cannot fly to the countries that cut diplomatic ties and vice versa. While business jet operators can request a nonstop routing, two officials said requests so far have been turned down necessitating a stop in a third country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://privatejetcardcomparisons.com/2017/06/06/qatars-diplomatic-crisis-is-impacting-private-jets-too/|title=Private Jet Card Comparisons \u2013 Know Before You Buy Qatar's Diplomatic Crisis Is Impacting Private Jets Too|date=6 June 2017 |publisher=privatejetcardcomparisons.com|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nDue to the blockade of [[Qatar Airways]] from the airspace of Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Bahrain and Egypt, [[Oman Air]] has taken up a significant role transporting travelers from and to [[Doha]], mostly through Iranian airspace, while still allowing [[Qatari passport]] holders to book flights. The travel embargo has had a significant impact on foreign nationals living and working in Qatar, with about 100,000 Egyptians and citizens from other countries stranded there, unable to book direct flights or obtain travel documents for their return.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=D. Dudley|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dominicdudley/2017/06/08/oman-air-takes-advantage-of-qatar-crisis/|title=\"A Winner Emerges From The Qatar Crisis: Oman's National Airline\"|magazine=Forbes|date=14 June 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> Per request from Qatar, the blockade was under review by the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] (ICAO), a UN-agency seeking \"consensus-based solutions\" for the resolution of the crisis.\n\nOn 31 July 2017, the agency asserted its neutrality in the conflict and announced that Qatar Airways will have access to three contingency routes over international waters in early August based on a preliminary agreement reached with the Saudi aviation authority (GACA) early that month. The ICAO, based in [[Montreal]], also reminded all member countries to comply with the [[Chicago Convention on International Civil Aviation|1944 Chicago Convention on International Civil Aviation]] and its agenda.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/08/qatar-airways-expected-access-air-corridors-170801020434530.html|title=Qatar Airways expected to access new flight routes|agency=Al Jazeera News|date=31 July 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Shipping===\nThe United Arab Emirates banned Qatar-flagged ships from calling at [[Fujairah]]. It also banned vessels from Qatar from the port and vessels at the port from sailing directly to Qatar.<ref name=WMN221956>{{cite news|url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/221956/report-port-of-fujairah-bans-qatari-flagged-ships/|title=Report: Port of Fujairah Bans Qatari-Flagged Ships|publisher=World Maritime News|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Similar restrictions were put in place at [[Jebel Ali]], which pre-boycott used to handle over 85% of shipborne cargo for Qatar.<ref name=veconomist/> Bahrain, Egypt and Saudi Arabia also banned Qatar-flagged ships from their ports.<ref name=WMN222007>{{cite web|url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/222007/more-arab-ports-deny-calls-to-qatari-ships/|title=More Arab Ports Deny Calls to Qatari Ships|publisher=World Maritime News|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 June 2017 shipping giant [[Maersk Line|Maersk]] was unable to transport in or out of Qatar entirely. Due to Qatar's shallow ports, large cargo ships are required to dock at Jebel Ali or other nearby ports where a [[Feeder ship|feeder]] service transports the goods into Qatar.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saul|first=Jonathan|title=Maersk says unable to ship Qatar bound cargo from UAE, seeks alternatives|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-shipping-idUSKBN18X1YS|accessdate=8 June 2017|agency=Reuters|year=2017}}</ref> In response, Maersk and Swiss-based [[Mediterranean Shipping Company|MSC]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/hundreds-containers-qatar-oman-170612163855982.html|title=Hundreds of containers on their way to Qatar from Oman|agency=Al Jazeera News|date=12 June 2017|access-date=2 December 2017}}</ref> vessels for Qatar were rerouted to [[Salalah]] and [[Sohar]] in Oman.<ref name=BBC40248145>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-40248145|title=Qatar ships cargo via Oman to bypass Gulf restrictions|work=BBC News|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref> Particularly smaller shipments of perishable and frozen foods have taken that route.\n\nOn 12 June 2017, Chinese shipping company [[COSCO]] announced suspension of services to and from Qatar. Taiwan's [[Evergreen Marine]] and Hong Kong's [[Orient Overseas Container Line]] have already suspended services.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/region/qatar-crisis/chinese-shipping-firm-suspends-services-to-qatar |title=Chinese shipping firm suspends services to Qatar|agency=IANS|publisher=khaleejtimes.com|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Media ban===\nHamad Saif al-Shamsi, the Attorney-General of the [[United Arab Emirates]] announced on 7 June that publishing expressions of sympathy towards Qatar through [[social media]], or any type of written, visual or verbal form is [[Human rights in the United Arab Emirates#Freedom of speech|considered illegal]] under UAE's Federal Penal Code and the Federal law on Combating Information Technology Crimes. Violators of this offense face between 3 and 15 years imprisonment, a fine of up to 500,000 [[emirati dirham]]s ([[USD|$]]136,000) or both.<ref>{{cite news|title=UAE bans expressions of sympathy toward Qatar: media|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-idUSKBN18Y0DH|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref> Bahrain also issued a similar statement with a [[Human rights in Bahrain#Freedom of speech|penalty]] up to 5 years imprisonment and a fine.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/bahrain-and-uae-criminalize-sympathy-for-qatar/2017/06/08/ce74a666-4c70-11e7-9669-250d0b15f83b_story.html|title=Bahrain and UAE criminalize 'sympathy' for Qatar|first=Karen|last=DeYoung|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=8 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia, Egypt, Bahrain, and the UAE all blocked access to Qatari news agencies, including the controversial Qatar-based Al Jazeera.<ref>{{cite news|last=Youssef|first=Neveen|title=Qatar hacking row fuels Gulf tensions|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40046782|accessdate=7 June 2017|work=BBC News|date=25 May 2017}}</ref> Saudi Arabia shut down the local office of Al Jazeera Media Network.<ref name=\"aljazeera1/6june2017\">{{cite news |title=Qatar diplomatic crisis: All the latest updates|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/qatar-diplomatic-crisis-latest-updates-170605105550769.html|accessdate=6 June 2017|agency=Al Jazeera}}</ref> The [[BBC]] speculated that changes to Al-Jazeera would be a necessary part of any peaceful resolution.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40187414|title=Qatar crisis: Can Al Jazeera survive?|first=Kevin|last=Ponniah|date=7 June 2017|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe Qatar-based [[BeIN Sports (Middle East TV network)|beIN Sports]] channels (a spin-off of Al Jazeera) were also initially banned in June in the UAE.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/06/08/media/uae-qatar-media-blocked/index.html|title=Blocked in Dubai: Qatar cartoon and soccer channels|first=Zahraa|last=Alkhalisi|date=8 June 2017|agency=CNN|accessdate=13 August 2017}}</ref> The following month, the UAE restored normal access to beIN Sports channels via its local telecom providers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/uae-restores-qatar-bein-sports-network-air-170722144955060.html|title=UAE restores Qatar's BeIN sports network on air|date=23 July 2017|agency=[[Al Jazeera]]|accessdate=13 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/bein-sports-back-on-tv-in-the-uae-1.613012|title=BeIN Sports back on TV in the UAE|first1=Steven|last1=McCombe|first2=Roberta|last2=Pennington|date=22 July 2017|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|accessdate=13 August 2017}}</ref> In Saudi Arabia, the channels remain banned, while a large-scale [[pirate decryption]] operation known as \"[[beoutQ]]\" has made the channels' content available.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/analysis/world-cup-broadcasting-pirates-saudi-arabias-bein-sport-qatar|title=World Cup pirates: Saudi Arabia\u2019s BeIN action threatens future of international sports broadcasting|work=SportsPro|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/21/premier-league-games-screened-illegally-via-saudi-satellite-firm|title=Premier League games 'screened illegally via Saudi satellite firm'|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=2018-08-21|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/premier-league-piracy-beoutq-bein-saudi-arabia-qatar-ligue-1|title=BeoutQ illegally shows opening Premier League and Ligue 1 games|work=SportsPro|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/09/sports/bein-sports-qatar-beoutq.html |title=The Brazen Bootlegging of a Multibillion-Dollar Sports Network |first=Tariq |last=Panja |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 May 2018}}</ref> In 2018, in parallel with the diplomatic crisis and piracy issues, Saudi officials also began to accuse beIN Sports of having a [[monopoly]] position in sports broadcasting in the region, including revoking its broadcast licenses based on accusations of anti-competitive behaviour, and pulling its rights to the [[Asian Football Confederation]] in the Kingdom in 2019. beIN Sports has considered the moves to be politically-motivated,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://advanced-television.com/2018/08/23/saudis-ban-bein-sports/|title=Saudis ban beIN Sports|website=Advanced Television|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/afc-cancels-bein-sports-rights-saudi-arabia|title=AFC cancels BeIN Sports rights in Saudi Arabia|website=SportsPro Media|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/bein-sports-saudi-arabia-afc-legal-battle|title=BeIN Sports to launch AFC legal action|website=SportsPro Media|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref> and has accused beoutQ of operating from Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/beoutq-riyadh-al-jazeera-documentary-piracy|title=BeoutQ\u2019s Riyadh HQ revealed in Al Jazeera doc, says report|website=SportsPro Media|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref>\n\n===Finances===\n{{See also|Economy of Qatar}}\nThe [[International Monetary Fund]] said it was too soon to judge the economic impact of the diplomatic crisis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/gulf-qatar-imf-idUSL1N1J50UM|title=IMF says too soon to judge impact from Qatar, Gulf diplomatic dispute|date=8 June 2017|agency=Reuters|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref> [[Standard & Poor's]] downgraded Qatar's debt by one notch from AA to AA-.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/news/world/standard-and-poors-downgrades-qatar-debt-rating-20170607-gwmuyz|title=Standard and Poor's downgrades Qatar debt rating|date=8 June 2017|work=Financial Review|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref> Qatar's stock market dropped 7.3% on the first day of the crisis, and reached a 9.7% drop by 8 June 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/06/05/investing/qatar-stocks-plunge-gulf-diplomacy/index.html|title=Qatari stocks plunge 7% after Arab states cut ties|date=5 June 2017|agency=CNN|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref> Additionally, in the first months following the crisis the government of Qatar injected $38.5 billion, which was equivalent to 23% of the country's GDP, to support the country's economy and its banking sector.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Martin|first1=Geoffrey|title=Everyone loses|journal=zenith|date=17 January 2019|url=https://magazine.zenith.me/en/business/other-lessons-qatar-crisis|}}</ref>\n\nAs per [[S&P Global]] Ratings, banks in Qatar are strong enough to survive a withdrawal of all Gulf country deposits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/qatar-banks-can-survive-gulf-foreign-funds-withdrawal-s-p-says--677427.html|title=Qatar banks can survive Gulf, foreign funds withdrawal, S&P says|work=Arabian Business|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nDespite the ongoing diplomatic blockade led by Saudi Arabia, international banks like [[HSBC]], [[Goldman Sachs]] and others are trying to repair their ties with Qatar by building stronger financial and business relations. Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates informally warned the bankers not to have close relations with Doha or else there would be consequences.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-17/bankers-are-sick-of-choosing-sides-between-qatar-and-saudi-arabia|title=Bankers Are Sick of Choosing Sides Between Qatar and Saudi Arabia|accessdate=17 February 2019|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2019, Sheikh [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]] attended the opening session of the [[Economic and Social Council (Arab League)#2019 summit|Arab Economic Summit]] in Beirut, Lebanon. This helped Qatar increase its influence and soft power in the region. Sheikh Tamim Bin Hamad Al Thani and Mauritanian President [[Mohamed Ould Abdel Aziz]] were the only two Arab leaders to attend the summit. Since Sheikh Tamim was the only [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]] leader to attend, he received praise from the President of Lebanon himself, [[Michel Aoun]]. Hilal Khashan, a professor of political science at the [[American University of Beirut]], said \u201cHe became the star of the summit.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rose |first1=Sunniva |title=Lebanon fails to attract high-level turnout for Arab economic summit |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/lebanon-fails-to-attract-high-level-turnout-for-arab-economic-summit-1.815757 |website=The National}}</ref>\n\n===Energy===\nQatar is a global [[List of countries by natural gas production|leader]] in [[liquefied natural gas]] production. Despite the severing of ties, Qatari natural gas continues to flow to the [[United Arab Emirates|UAE]] and [[Oman]] through [[Abu Dhabi]] based [[Dolphin Energy]]'s [[Dolphin Gas Project|pipeline]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Law|first=Bill|date=14 November 2017|title=Qatar Rides Out the Blockade|url=http://www.indrastra.com/2017/11/Qatar-Rides-Out-Blockade-003-11-2017-0006.html|journal=IndraStra Global|publication-place=New York, USA|publication-date=9 November 2017|volume=003|issue=11|pages=0006|issn=2381-3652}}</ref> The pipeline meets about 30\u201340 percent of UAE's energy needs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/06/07/news/qatar-uae-gas-pipeline/index.html |title=Qatar keeps gas flowing to UAE despite blockade|last=Alkhalisi|first=Zahraa|date=7 June 2017|website=CNNMoney|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref> Shipping constraints from the crisis have also rerouted multiple shipments of oil and gas to and from the Gulf, which has caused reverberations in many local energy markets. \nOn 8 June 2017, gas futures spiked nearly 4 percent in the United Kingdom, which had nearly a third of all its imported gas arriving from Qatar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/08/qatar-fight-finally-spills-into-global-energy-market.html|title=Qatar fight finally spills into global energy market|last=Domm|first=Patti|date=8 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref> A secondary effect of the dispute has been on worldwide supplies of [[helium]], which is often extracted from natural gas. Qatar is the world's second largest supplier of helium (the US ranks first).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2017/06/26/middle-east-turmoil-is-disrupting-a-vital-resource-for-nuclear-energy-space-flight-and-birthday-balloons|title=Middle East turmoil is disrupting a vital resource for nuclear energy, space flight and birthday balloons|date=26 June 2017|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Qatar lodged a complaint to [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] regarding the United Arab Emirates [[Barakah nuclear power plant]], stating that it poses a serious threat to regional stability and the environment. The UAE denied that there are safety issues with the plant, which is being built by [[Korea Electric Power Corporation]] (KEPCO) with operation by French utility [[\u00c9lectricit\u00e9 de France]], and stated \u201cThe United Arab Emirates ... adheres to its commitment to the highest standards of nuclear safety, security and non-proliferation.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL8N2175GH|title=Qatar says UAE nuclear plant is threat to regional stability|work=Reuters|last1=De Clercq|first1=Geert|date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===23rd Gulf Cup===\nThe [[23rd Arabian Gulf Cup]] was scheduled to be hosted in Qatar.  In November 2017, [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]], [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]], and [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] pulled out of the Gulf Cup due to the Qatar boycott.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Editorial|first1=Reuters|title=Saudi, UAE, Bahrain to miss Qatar's Gulf Cup amid rift|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-gulf-qatar-football/saudi-uae-bahrain-to-miss-qatars-gulf-cup-amid-rift-idUKKBN1DH267|website=U.K.}}</ref> On 7 December 2017, it was announced that [[Kuwait]] will host the football tournament after [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]], United Arab Emirates, and [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] all withdrew because of the diplomatic crisis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1205581/sports|title=Gulf Cup to return to Kuwait following lifting of FIFA ban|date=2017-12-08|work=Arab News|access-date=2018-06-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Qatari military relations===\n[[File:Refueling the fight against terrorism 170103-F-XF291-0016.jpg|thumb|[[Al Udeid Air Base]] in Qatar]]\nOn 7 June 2017, the Turkish parliament passed, with 240 votes in favour and 98 against, a legislative act first drafted in May allowing Turkish troops to be deployed to a Turkish military base in Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/turkey-fast-track-troops-deployment-qatar-170607151127104.html |title=Turkish parliament approves troop deployment to Qatar |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=8 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611231348/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/turkey-fast-track-troops-deployment-qatar-170607151127104.html |archivedate=11 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2017/06/09/turk-j09.html |title=Turkey prepares to send troops to Qatar in conflict with Saudi Arabia |publisher=World Socialist Web Site |date=9 June 2017 |author=Halil Celik and Alex Lantier |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609064129/https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2017/06/09/turk-j09.html |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>  During a speech on 13 June 2017, the [[President of Turkey]], [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], condemned the boycott of Qatar as \"inhumane and against Islamic values\" and stated that \"victimising Qatar through smear campaigns serves no purpose\".<ref name=\"TurkeyBBC\">{{cite news |title=Turkey's Erdogan decries Qatar's 'inhumane' isolation |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40261479 |accessdate=14 June 2017 |publisher=BBC |date=13 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613185712/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40261479 |archivedate=13 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 23 June 2017, Turkey rejected demands to shut down its military base in Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schreck |first1=Adam |last2=Lederman |first2=Josh |title=Turkey rejects Gulf Arab states' demands over its Qatar base |url=https://apnews.com/9a12e8024ac245f3b31bdb67c68a9b67/Turkey-rejects-Gulf-Arab-states'-demands-over-its-Qatar-base |accessdate=23 June 2017 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=23 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nQatar hosts about 10,000 US troops at Al Udeid Air Base, which houses the forward operating base of [[United States Central Command]] that plays a commanding role in US [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|airstrikes in Syria]], Iraq, and Afghanistan.<ref name=ABC>{{cite news |publisher=ABC News |title=Trump sides with Saudis, other Arab nations against Qatar |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/trump-arab-leaders-complained-qatar-47861002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612005732/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/trump-arab-leaders-complained-qatar-47861002 |archivedate=12 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"WaPo 6 June\">{{cite news |title=The Latest: Trump says Qatar dispute could end terror |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/the-latest-trump-says-qatar-dispute-could-end-terror/2017/06/06/4ccabb7c-4ac8-11e7-987c-42ab5745db2e_story.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606200453/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/the-latest-trump-says-qatar-dispute-could-end-terror/2017/06/06/4ccabb7c-4ac8-11e7-987c-42ab5745db2e_story.html |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/world/1475326-trump-sides-with-saudis-other-arab-nations-against-qatar |title=Siding against ally Qatar, Trump injects US into Arab crisis |date=6 June 2017 |accessdate=6 June 2017 |website=[[The Chronicle Herald]]|agency=[[The Canadian Press]] }}</ref> A Pentagon spokesperson claimed the diplomatic crisis would not affect the US military posture in Qatar.<ref name=\"WaPo 6 June\" /><ref name=credit />\n\nOn 10 and 11 November 2018, the [[Italian Air Force]] along with the [[Qatar Air Force|Qatari Display Team]], perform an airshow at the corniche that confirms the bonds of friendship between [[Italy]] and [[Qatar]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Doha Airshow 2018: Italian Air Force and Qatar Display Team |url=https://ambdoha.esteri.it/ambasciata_doha/en/ambasciata/news/dall_ambasciata/2018/11/doha-airshow-2018-frecce-tricolori.html |website=Ambasciata d'Italia Doha |publisher=Ambasciata d'Italia Doha}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January 2018 an inaugural United States-Qatar Strategic Dialogue meeting was held, co-chaired by U.S. Secretary of State Rex Tillerson, U.S. Secretary of Defense [[Jim Mattis]], Qatari Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of State for Defence Affairs<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gco.gov.qa/en/ministries/minister-of-state-for-defence-affairs/|title=Minister of State for Defence Affairs|website=Government Communications Office|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref> [[Khalid al-Attiyah]] and Qatari Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister [[Mohammed bin Abdulrahman Al Thani]]. The meeting expressed the need for an immediate resolution of the crisis which respects Qatar's sovereignty. In a Joint Declaration on Security Cooperation, the United States expressed its readiness to deter and confront any external threat to Qatar's territorial integrity. Qatar offered to help fund the expansion of facilities at US bases in Qatar.<ref name=atlantic-20180131>{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/01/qatar-us/551873/ |title=America Wins the Gulf Crisis |last=Calamur |first=Krishnadev |newspaper=The Atlantic |date=31 January 2018 |accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=state-20180130>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2018/01/277776.htm |title=Joint Statement of the Inaugural United States-Qatar Strategic Dialogue |publisher=U.S. Department of State |date=30 January 2018 |accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March 2018, the [[United States Central Command]] (CENTCOM) officially denied rumours that the [[Incirlik Air Base]] in Turkey and the Al Udeid Air Base in Qatar will be closed due to the ongoing regional conflict.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/03/denies-leaving-air-bases-turkey-qatar-180326073201309.html \"US denies leaving air bases in Turkey and Qatar\"]. ''Aljazeera News/Turkey''. Retrieved 26 March 2018.</ref>\n\n[[File:Combined Air and Space Operations Center 151007-F-MS415-015.jpg|thumb|Combined [[Air and Space Operations Center]] (CAOC) in Qatar provides command and control of air power throughout [[Iraq]], [[Syria]], [[Afghanistan]], and 17 other nations.]]\nOn January 2018, Qatar's ambassador was in talks with Russia with the intent to purchase [[S-400 missile system|S-400 surface-to-air missile]]s. Both countries signed an agreement on military and technical cooperation in 2017. In May 2018, the French daily newspaper ''Le Monde'' reported that King [[Salman of Saudi Arabia]] would take military action if Qatar installed the Russian air defence system. However, a senior Russian official remarked the system would still be delivered even against the will of Saudi Arabia.<ref>[https://in.reuters.com/article/saudi-qatar-france/saudi-arabia-threatens-military-action-if-qatar-deploys-anti-aircraft-missiles-report-idINKCN1IY0IJ \"Saudi Arabia threatens military action if Qatar deploys anti-aircraft missiles \u2013 report]\". ''Reuters''. Retrieved 2 June 2018.</ref> The Saudis were themselves approaching Russia to improve economic and military ties in 2017, but talks relating to the arms deal were hindered by concerns the United States and Saudi Arabia had with regard to the Russian position towards Iran's military and strategic involvement in the Middle East.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/06/russia-supply-400-system-qatar-saudi-position-180602195629315.html Russia 'to supply S-400 system to Qatar' despite Saudi position]. ''Al Jazeera News''. Retrieved 2 June 2018.</ref>\n\nOn June 2018, Qatar expressed its wish to join [[NATO]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/05/06/2018/Qatar-eyes-full-NATO-membership-Defense-minister|title=Qatar eyes full NATO membership: Defense minister|work=The Peninsula|date=5 June 2018}}</ref> However, NATO declined membership, stating that only additional European countries could join according to [[Enlargement of NATO#Article 10|Article 10 of NATO's founding treaty]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/world/2018/06/06/qatar-says-it-wants-to-join-nato|title=Nato rejects Qatar membership ambition|newspaper=Dhaka Tribune|date=6 June 2018}}</ref> Qatar and NATO have previously signed a security agreement together in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_150794.htm|title=Qatar signs security agreement with NATO|publisher=NATO|date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 September 2018, Qatar finalised a deal to purchase [[Eurofighter Typhoon]] and [[BAE Hawk]] aircraft in a deal reported as being worth \u00a35Bn.<ref>[https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-bae-systems-qatar/bae-systems-finalises-deal-to-sell-typhoon-jets-to-qatar-idUKKCN1LY261 BAE Systems finalises deal to sell Typhoon jets to Qatar]. ''Reuters''. Retrieved 18 September 2018.</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, as Qatar completed two years under the diplomatic embargo, the country received its first five of the 36 purchased [[Dassault Rafale|Rafale]] fighter jets from [[France]]. The first aircraft was formally handed to Qatar in February 2019, but was kept in France itself before being delivered on 5 June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190605-under-embargo-qatar-takes-delivery-first-rafale-jets|title=Under embargo Qatar takes delivery of first Rafale jets|work=France 24|accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Arab League Council 2017===\nDuring the 148th Session of the Arab League Council at the level of Foreign Ministers which was held in Cairo, Qatar\u2019s State Minister for Foreign Affairs, Sultan Al Muraikhi, got into a heated argument with Saudi delegate Ahmad Al Qattan. Al Muraikhi said: \"Ahmad Al Qattan's tone was very threatening and I don't think he is capable of being responsible for his words.\" Ahmad Al Qattan interrupted Al Muraikhi, and said \u201cNo I am capable.\u201d Things escalated when Al Muraikhi said \u201cWhen I speak, you stay quiet.\u201d Al Qattan replied, \u201cNo you stay quiet.\u201d The Iraqi delegate tried to be the mediator in this back and forth argument. The ministers of the three blockading countries of the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain and Egypt had their say by backing Ahmad Al Qattan. This was all caused after Al Muraikhi gave a short speech about how Qatar had to go back to supporting Iran after it cut its ties to support Saudi Arabia. He adds that Saudi Arabia brought in a person from the Qatari royal family and made him look like he was the future ruler of Qatar. The argument continued for around forty minutes.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thrar |first1=Abdulrahim |title=\u0641\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0648.. \u0645\u0646\u062f\u0648\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u064a\u0647\u062f\u062f.. \u0648\u0645\u0646\u062f\u0648\u0628 \u0642\u0637\u0631 \u064a\u0631\u062f: \"\u0645\u0646\u062a \u0628\u0642\u062f\u0647\u0627\" |url=https://www.al-sharq.com/article/12/09/2017/%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%88-%D9%85%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%8A%D9%87%D8%AF%D8%AF-%D9%88%D9%85%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%A8-%D9%82%D8%B7%D8%B1-%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%AF-%D9%85%D9%86%D8%AA-%D8%A8%D9%82%D8%AF%D9%87%D8%A7 |website=Al Sharq}}</ref>\n\n===2019 Asian Cup===\nDuring the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage#Qatar vs United Arab Emirates|semi-final match]] between the [[Qatar national football team]] and the tournament hosts the United Arab Emirates, the UAE supporters [[Shoe tossing#Insult|threw shoes]] and bottles onto the pitch. This conduct was preceded by booing the [[As-Salam al-Amiri|Qatari national anthem]]. Qatar won 4\u20130, paving the way to their first Asian Cup final and eventual title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Qatar 4\u20130 United Arab Emirates|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47049246|accessdate=1 February 2019 |publisher=BBC |date=29 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Watch: Fans throw shoes at the Qatar players after Almoez Ali scores their second goal against the UAE in the AFC Asian Cup 2019|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/asian-football/afc-asian-cup/1031989/watch-fans-throw-shoes-at-the-qatar-players-after-almoez-ali-scores-their-second-goal-against-the-uae-in-the-afc-asian-cup-2019/ |author=Aditya |work=Fox Sports Asia |date=29 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Shoes and Insults Flying, Qatar Beats U.A.E. and Advances to Asian Cup Final |date=29 January 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/29/sports/qatar-uae-boycott-asian-cup.html|agency=Associated Press |accessdate=1 February 2019 |newspaper= The New York Times }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Asian Cup: Qatar pelted with shoes by hostile UAE fans as they thrash hosts 4\u20130 to reach final |accessdate=1 February 2019 |url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/football/article/2184193/asian-cup-uae-fans-pelt-qatar-players-shoes-hosts-are-thrashed-4-0|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=30 January 2019|agency= Agence France-Presse}}</ref>\n\nA British-Sudanese football fan was allegedly beaten by fans for wearing a Qatar football shirt to a match in which Qatar was playing and then, after investigation by the UAE police, arrested for [[wasting police time]] and making [[False statement#In Law|false statements]] of being assaulted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47135629|title=Briton held in UAE in football shirt row|website=Bbc.com|date=2019-02-06|access-date=2019-02-06|language=en-GB}}</ref> According to ''The Guardian'', the fan was arrested for wearing a Qatar football shirt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/05/british-man-detained-in-uae-after-wearing-qatar-football-t-shirt-to-match|title=British man detained in UAE after wearing Qatar football shirt to match|first=Diane|last=Taylor|date=5 February 2019|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2019|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=\"indy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/uae-football-fan-qatar-shirt-arrest-detained-ali-issa-ahmad-police-a8764366.html|title=UK football fan held in United Arab Emirates 'for wearing Qatar shirt to match'|date=5 February 2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gu-friends\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/06/friends-of-uk-football-fan-detained-in-uae-call-for-his-release-qatar|title=UAE officials suggest detained UK football fan beat himself up|first=Diane|last=Taylor|date=6 February 2019|accessdate=6 February 2019|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> The claim was denied by UAE authorities who stated the fan was arrested for wasting police time and making false assault claims to the police. The UAE police said that the fan had admitted to making false statements. A UAE official in London stated \u201cHe was categorically not arrested for wearing a Qatar football shirt. This is instead an instance of a person seeking media attention and wasting police time.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-emirates-britain-arrests/uae-denies-british-man-detained-for-showing-qatar-support-idUSKCN1PV0F5|title=UAE denies British man detained for showing Qatar support|date=5 February 2019|work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11629525/uae-denies-arresting-british-national-for-wearing-qatar-shirt|title=UAE denies arresting British national for wearing Qatar shirt|publisher=Sky Sports|date=6 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"indy\"/><ref name=\"gu-friends\"/> According to photos shown by ''The National'', fans were seen waving the Qatari flag and wearing Qatari football shirts without any instances of arrests in the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup Final|final]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/british-football-fan-arrested-for-misleading-uae-police-1.822499#2|title=British football fan arrested for misleading UAE police|work=The National|date=6 February 2019}}</ref> According to ''[[The New York Times]]'', the UAE accuses Qatar of fielding ineligible players due to them being not originally Qatari. The players accused were the competitions' top scorer [[Almoez Ali]], a Sudan born striker, as well as [[Bassam Al-Rawi]], an Iraq born defender.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Panja |first1=Tariq |title=U.A.E. Accuses Qatar of Fielding Ineligible Players at Asian Cup |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/31/sports/soccer/qatar-uae-asian-cup.html |work=The New York Times |date=31 January 2019 |accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Demands on Qatar and responses==\nOn 22 June 2017, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Egypt and Bahrain issued Qatar a list of 13 demands through Kuwait, which is acting as a mediator, that Qatar should agree in full within 10 days, which expired on 2 July 2017. According to reports on 23 June, these demands included:<ref name=\"reuters.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-demands-idUSKBN19E0BB|title=Arab states issue ultimatum to Qatar: close Jazeera, curb ties with Iran|date=23 June 2017|agency=Reuters|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|title=Qatar given 10 days to meet 13 sweeping demands by Saudi Arabia|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/23/close-al-jazeera-saudi-arabia-issues-qatar-with-13-demands-to-end-blockade|accessdate=24 June 2017|work=The Guardian|date=23 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=auto8/>\n\n*Closing [[Al-Jazeera]] and its affiliate stations.\n*Closing other news outlets that Qatar funds, directly and indirectly, including Arabi21, [[Rassd News Network (RNN)|Rassd]], [[Al-Araby Al-Jadeed]] and [[Middle East Eye]].\n*Closing the Turkish military base in Qatar, and terminate the Turkish military presence and any joint military cooperation with Turkey inside Qatar.\n*Reducing diplomatic relations with Iran. Only trade and commerce with Iran that complies with US and international sanctions will be permitted.<ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/qatar/qatar-crisis/what-are-the-13-demands-given-to-qatar-1.2048118|title=What are the 13 demands given to Qatar?|last=AP|date=23 June 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> \n*Expelling any members of the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC) and cutting off military and intelligence cooperation with Iran.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/arab-states-issue-list-demands-qatar-crisis-170623022133024.html|title=Arab states issue list of demands to end Qatar crisis|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=11 July 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n*\"Qatar must announce it is severing ties with terrorist, ideological and sectarian organizations including the Muslim Brotherhood, [[Hamas]], the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL), [[Al-Qaeda]], [[Hezbollah]], and [[al-Nusra Front|Jabhat Fateh al Sham]], formerly al Qaeda's branch in Syria\" according to one Arab official.\n*Surrendering all designated terrorists in Qatar, and stopping all means of funding for individuals, groups or organisations that have been designated as terrorists.\n*Ending interference in the four countries' domestic and foreign affairs and having contact with their political oppositions.\n*Stopping granting citizenship to wanted nationals from Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Egypt and Bahrain.\n*Revoking Qatari citizenship for existing nationals where such citizenship violates those countries' laws.<ref name=\"auto9\" />\n*The payment of reparations for years of alleged wrongs.\n*Monitoring for 10 years.<ref name=\"reuters.com\"/>\n*Aligning itself with the other Gulf and Arab countries militarily, politically, socially and economically, as well as on economic matters, in line with an agreement reached with Saudi Arabia in 2014.<ref name=auto9/>\n\nAccording to a report by the Qatar-owned Al-Jazeera, \"Qatari officials immediately dismissed the document as neither reasonable or actionable.\" Iran denounced the blockade. US Secretary of State Rex Tillerson said that some of the demands would be very hard to meet but encouraged further dialogue.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2017/06/iran-hassan-rouhani-condemns-siege-qatar-170625174347048.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=30 June 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629232954/http://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2017/06/iran-hassan-rouhani-condemns-siege-qatar-170625174347048.html|archivedate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July, Saudi Arabia accepted a Kuwaiti request for the deadline to be extended by 48 hours.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi-bloc gives Qatar 48 more hours to accept demands|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/qatar-formally-respond-saudi-led-list-monday-170702202036876.html|accessdate=2 December 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=3 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 July, foreign ministers from Egypt, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates and Bahrain met in Cairo after receiving a response from Qatar to their list of demands. The meeting aimed to resolve the dispute ended in a stalemate when Saudi foreign minister Adel al-Jubeir said that the political and economic boycott of Qatar will remain until it changes its policies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/saudi-led-group-qatar-demands-170705144209453.html|title=Saudi-led group: Qatar not serious about demands|agency=Al Jazeera|date=6 July 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> Also on the same day, the Saudi-led bloc said it no longer insisting it to comply with its 13 specific demands they tabled last month. Instead, it asked Qatar to accept six broad principles, which includes commitments to combat terrorism, extremism, to end acts of provocation, and incitement.<ref name=\"auto6\"/>\n\nHowever, by 30 July 2017, the 13 demands had been reinstated.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Feteha|first1=Ahmed|last2=MacDonald|first2=Fiona|last3=El-Tablawy|first3=Tarek|title=Qatar Crisis Is Back to Square One as Economy Shows the Strain |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-30/saudi-bloc-ministers-meet-to-discuss-next-step-in-qatar-crisis|accessdate=8 September 2017|agency=Bloomberg|date=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[International propagation of Salafism and Wahhabism]]\n*{{section link|State-sponsored terrorism|Saudi Arabia}}\n*[[OPEC]]\n*[[Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of Qatar}}\n{{Portal bar|Saudi Arabia|United Arab Emirates|Bahrain|Egypt}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2017-18 Qatar diplomatic crisis}}\n[[Category:2017 in international relations|Qatar diplomatic crisis]]\n[[Category:2017 in Qatar|Diplomatic crisis]]\n[[Category:2018 in international relations|Qatar diplomatic crisis]]\n[[Category:2018 in Qatar|Diplomatic crisis]]\n[[Category:Arab Winter by country]]\n[[Category:Bahrain\u2013Qatar relations]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic incidents]]\n[[Category:Egypt\u2013Qatar relations]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Qatar]]\n[[Category:June 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:July 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:August 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:September 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:October 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:November 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:December 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:January 2018 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Politics of Qatar]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Arab world]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Qatar\u2013Saudi Arabia relations]]\n[[Category:Qatar\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n[[Category:Censorship in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Bahrain]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]]\n[[Category:Ongoing conflicts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Qatar diplomatic crisis\n| partof      = [[Qatar\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]] and [[Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]]\n| date        = 5 June 2017 \u2013 ongoing <br />({{Age in months, weeks and days|year1=2017|month1=6|day1=5}})\n| place       = [[Qatar]]\n| territory   = \n| result      = [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Bahrain]], the [[United Arab Emirates]], and [[Egypt]] cut diplomatic relations with Qatar; others downgrade.\n| status      = Ongoing\n*13-point ultimatum issued and replaced with altered conditions.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40654023|title=Saudi-led Bloc|publisher=BBC|date=19 July 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n*Qatar ends its involvement in the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|war in Yemen]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2017/06/05/Arab-coalition-suspends-Qatar-s-participation-in-Yemen.html|title=Arab coalition suspends Qatar's participation in Yemen|publisher=[[Al Arabiya English]]|date=5 June 2017|accessdate=20 August 2017}}</ref> and peacekeeping in [[Ras Doumeira]].\n| combatants_header = Parties involved in diplomatic dispute\n| combatant1  = {{flag|Saudi Arabia}}<br />{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}<br />{{flag|Bahrain}}<br />{{flag|Egypt}}<br />{{flag|Maldives}}<br />{{flag|Yemen}}{{Ref label|Yemen|a}}<br />{{flag|Mauritania}}<br />{{flag|Djibouti}}<br />{{flag|Comoros}}<br />{{flag|Niger}}<br />{{flag|Gabon}}<br />'''Others:'''<br />{{flag|Somaliland}}{{Ref label|Somaliland|c}}<br />{{flag|Libya|House of Representatives (Libya)|name=Libya (Tobruk)}}{{Ref label|Libya|b}}<br />'''No longer participating:'''<br />{{flag|Senegal}} <small>(until 2017)</small><br />{{flag|Chad}} <small>(until 2018)</small><br />{{flag|Jordan}} <small>(until 2019)</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/jordan-seeks-middle-ground-mideast-rift|title=Jordan Seeks Middle Ground in Mideast Rift|website=Voice of America}}</ref>\n| notes       = {{Note label|Yemen|a}} The [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi#Rebel takeover and civil war|Government stationed in Aden]] has cut ties with Qatar.<br/>{{Note label|Libya|b}} The [[Second Al-Thani Cabinet|Tobruk-based government]] lost international recognition after the formation of the [[Government of National Accord]] in January 2016. The Tobruk-based government claims to have cut ties with Qatar despite not having diplomatic representation in the country.<br/>{{Note label|Somaliland|c}} Somaliland's independence is not recognized by the international community.\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Qatar}}<br />''Supported by:''<br />{{flag|Turkey}} (food aid, diplomatic and military support)<ref name=\"Turkey\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/06/implications-qatar-turkey-alliance-170618110726262.html |title=The implications of the Qatar-Turkey alliance|date=18 June 2017|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref><br />{{flag|Iran}} (food aid, airspace access and diplomatic support)<ref name=\"Iran\">{{cite news|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/gulf-crisis-iran-sends-five-planes-food-qatar-avert-food-shortages-1021805206|title=Iran sends five plane loads of food as Kuwait says Qatar 'ready' to listen|date=11 June 2017|accessdate=18 June 2017}}<br/>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/iran-hassan-rouhani-condemns-siege-qatar-170625174347048.html|title=Iran: Hassan Rouhani condemns 'siege of Qatar'|date=26 June 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''[[Qatar]] diplomatic crisis''' began in June 2017, when [[Foreign relations of Saudi Arabia#Qatar|Saudi Arabia]], the [[Qatar\u2013United Arab Emirates relations|United Arab Emirates]], [[Bahrain\u2013Qatar relations|Bahrain]], [[Egypt\u2013Qatar relations|Egypt]], [[Maldives|the Maldives]], [[Mauritania]], [[Senegal]], [[Djibouti]], [[Comoros|the Comoros]], [[Jordan-Qatar relations|Jordan]], the Tobruk-based [[Libya|Libyan]] government, and the [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi|Hadi]]-led [[Yemen]]<nowiki/>i government severed diplomatic relations with Qatar and banned Qatari airplanes and ships from utilising their [[airspace]] and sea routes along with Saudi Arabia blocking the only land crossing.<ref>{{cite web |title=Qatar-Gulf crisis: Your questions answered |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/06/qatar-gulf-crisis-questions-answered-170606103033599.html |website=aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=It\u2019s a boycott, not a blockade |url=https://gulfnews.com/opinion/editorials/it-s-a-boycott-not-a-blockade-1.2043769 |accessdate=August 31, 2018 |work=Gulf News |date=June 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Saudi-led coalition cited Qatar's alleged [[Qatar and state-sponsored terrorism|support for terrorism]] as the main reason for their actions, insisting that Qatar has violated a 2014 agreement with the members of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC).<ref>{{cite news|title=Doha's Actions May Destabilize the Region: Saudi Minister|url=http://newsweekme.com/dohas-actions-may-destabilize-region-saudi-minister/|accessdate=2 July 2017|work=Newsweek ME |date=14 June 2017}}</ref> Saudi Arabia and other countries have [[Al Jazeera controversies and criticism|criticized Al Jazeera]] and [[Iran\u2013Qatar relations|Qatar's relations with Iran]]. Qatar acknowledges that it has provided assistance to some Islamist groups (such as the [[Muslim Brotherhood]]), but denies aiding militant groups linked to al-Qaeda or the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL).<ref>{{cite news|title=Sheikh Tamim denies Qatar has links to terrorism|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40173757 |newspaper=[[BBC]]|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> Qatar also claims that it has [[Qatar\u2013United States relations|assisted the United States]] in the [[War on Terror]] and the ongoing [[military intervention against ISIL]].<ref name=Tamim>{{cite news|title=Sheikh Tamim denies Qatar has links to terrorism|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/region/qatar/sheikh-tamim-denies-qatar-has-links-to-terrorism|date=25 May 2017|newspaper=[[Khaleej Times]]|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nInitial supply disruptions were mitigated by additional imports from Iran and Turkey, and Qatar did not agree to any of the Saudi-led coalition's demands.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Collins |first1=Gabriel |title=Anti-Qatar Embargo Grinds Toward Strategic Failure |url=https://scholarship.rice.edu/bitstream/handle/1911/99690/bi-brief-012218-ces-qatarembargo.pdf?sequence=1 |publisher=Rice University\u2019s Baker Institute for Public Policy}}</ref>  The demands included reducing diplomatic relations with Iran, stopping military coordination with Turkey, and closing [[Al-Jazeera]].\n\nOn 27 July 2017, Qatari foreign minister [[Mohammed bin Abdulrahman Al Thani]] told reporters that Egypt, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates and Bahrain were showing \"stubbornness\" to Qatar and had not taken any steps to solve the crisis. Al Thani added that the Security Council, the General Assembly and \"all the United Nations mechanisms\" could play a role in resolving the situation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/07/27/qatar-says-un-should-play-role-in-resolving-gulf-crisis.html|title=Qatar says UN should play a role in resolving Gulf crisis|date=27 July 2017|publisher=Fox News Channel|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref> On 24 August 2017, Qatar announced that it would restore full diplomatic relations with Iran.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qatar To Reinstate Ambassador To Iran Amid Gulf Crisis|url=http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/qatar-to-reinstate-ambassador-to-iran-amid-gulf-crisis-1741557|date=24 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Qatar\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict}}\n{{Further|2017 United States\u2013Saudi Arabia arms deal|Riyadh Summit 2017}}\n\nSince he took power in 1995, [[Hamad bin Khalifa al-Thani]] believed Qatar could find security only by transforming itself from a Saudi appendage to a rival of Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/13/world/middleeast/how-the-saudi-qatar-rivalry-now-combusting-reshaped-the-middle-east.html|title=How the Saudi-Qatar Rivalry, Now Combusting, Reshaped the Middle East|first=Max|last=Fisher|date=13 June 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref> Saudi Arabia withdrew its ambassador to Doha from 2002 to 2008 to try to pressure Qatar to curb its individualistic tendencies. This approach broadly failed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40159080|title=Qatar row: What's caused the fall-out between Gulf neighbours?|first=Dr David|last=Roberts|date=5 June 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref> The [[Arab Spring]] left a power vacuum which both Saudi Arabia and Qatar sought to fill, with Qatar being supportive of the [[revolutionary wave]] and Saudi Arabia opposing it; since both states are allies of the United States, they avoid direct conflict with one another.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/05/world/middleeast/qatar-saudi-arabia-egypt-bahrain-united-arab-emirates.html|title=5 Arab Nations Move to Isolate Qatar, Putting the U.S. in a Bind|date=5 June 2017|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Qatar has had differences with other Arab governments on a number of issues: it broadcasts [[Al Jazeera]]; it is accused of maintaining good relations with Iran; and it has supported the Muslim Brotherhood in the past.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/05/world/middleeast/qatar-saudi-arabia-egypt-bahrain-united-arab-emirates.html|title=5 Arab States Break Ties With Qatar, Complicating U.S. Coalition-Building|first1=Anne|last1=Barnard|first2=David|last2=Kirkpatrick|date=5 June 2017|accessdate=5 June 2017|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Qatar has been accused of sponsoring terrorism. Some countries have faulted Qatar for [[Timber Sycamore|funding]] rebel groups in Syria, including [[al-Qaeda]]\u2019s affiliate in Syria, the [[al-Nusra Front]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/News/12392.aspx|title=Gulf allies and \u2018Army of Conquest |newspaper=[[Al-Ahram Weekly]]|date=28 May 2015}}</ref> although the Saudis have done the same.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mazzetti|first1=Mark|last2=Apuzzo|first2=Matt|title=U.S. Relies Heavily on Saudi Money to Support Syrian Rebels|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/24/world/middleeast/us-relies-heavily-on-saudi-money-to-support-syrian-rebels.html?_r=0|work=The New York Times|date=23 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/syria-crisis-turkey-and-saudi-arabia-shock-western-countries-by-supporting-antiassad-jihadists-10242747.html|title=Turkey and Saudi Arabia alarm the West by backing Islamist extremists the Americans had bombed in Syria|author=Kim Sengupta|newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=12 May 2015}}</ref> Qatar has allowed the Afghan [[Taliban]] to set up a political office inside the country.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Robert|title=How Tiny Qatar 'Punches Above Its Weight'|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2013/12/20/255748469/how-tiny-qatar-punches-above-its-weight|publisher=NPR|date=23 December 2013}}</ref> Qatar is [[Qatar\u2013United States relations|a close ally of the United States]], hosting the largest American base in the Middle East, [[Al Udeid Air Base]].<ref name=USbase>{{cite web|last=Lendon|first=Brad |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/05/middleeast/qatar-us-largest-base-in-mideast/index.html |title=Qatar hosts largest US military base in Mideast|agency=CNN|date=5 June 2017|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===March 2014 GCC Crisis===\n\nIn March 2014, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and Egypt withdrew their ambassadors from Qatar. This severing of relations was the first of its kind since the establishment of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC). The disagreement that sparked the ambassadors\u2019 withdrawal was among the most serious in recent years, and threatened to seriously undermine relations between the GCC states. The crisis certainly affected the GCC negatively at first \u2013 raising questions among member states, revealing shifts in their political agendas, and changing the balance of power in the region to some extent.<ref name=\"Islam Hassan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/12696782/GCCs_2014_Crisis_Causes_Issues_and_Solutions|title=GCC's 2014 Crisis: Causes, Issues and Solutions|author=Islam Hassan|date=31 March 2015|publisher=Al Jazeera Research Center|accessdate=4 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904020157/http://www.academia.edu/12696782/GCCs_2014_Crisis_Causes_Issues_and_Solutions|archivedate=4 September 2015}}</ref> It also set the stage for the 2017 GCC crisis.\n\nThe exact reasons for the diplomatic break-offs are unclear, but contemporary news coverage primarily attributes this to several events in April and May 2017.\n\n===April 2017 hostage negotiations===\n[[File:Flag of Hayat Tahrir al-Sham.svg|right|thumb|Flag of [[Tahrir al-Sham]], a Sunni militant group. Qatar is accused of paying the group $140&nbsp;million in a deal that saw the release of hostages.<ref name=\"SolomonFinTimes\" /> According to an Iraqi Shi'ite militia, the deal was linked to delivery of humanitarian aid to Shi'ite and Sunni villages in Syria.<ref name=Hostages />]]\n{{Further|2015 Qatari hunters kidnapping}}\nIn April 2017, Qatar was involved in [[2015 Zabadani cease-fire agreement|a deal]] with both [[Sunni]] and [[Shi'ite]] militants in Iraq and Syria. The deal had two goals. The immediate goal was to secure the return of 26 Qatari hostages (including [[House of Thani|Qatari royals]]) who had been kidnapped by Shi'ite militants while falcon hunting in Southern Iraq and kept in captivity for more than 16 months.<ref name=\"FA\">{{cite journal|last1=Roberts|first1=David |title=A Dustup in the Gulf|journal=Foreign Affairs|date=June 2017 |url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/middle-east/2017-06-13/dustup-gulf}}{{subscription required|work=Foreign Affairs}}</ref><ref name=Hostages>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/21/world/middleeast/big-ransom-and-syria-deals-win-release-of-royal-qatari-hunters.html|title=Big Ransom and Syria Deals Win Release of Royal Qatari Hunters|first=Tim|last=Arango|date=21 April 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The second goal was to get both Sunni and Shi'ite militants in Syria to allow [[humanitarian aid]] to pass through and allow the safe evacuation of civilians.<ref name=Hostages/> According to the ''[[New York Times]]'', this deal allowed the evacuation of at least 2,000 civilians from [[Madaya, Syria|the Syrian village of Madaya]] alone.<ref name=Hostages/> What outraged Saudi Arabia and the UAE is the amount of money Qatar had to pay to secure the deal. According to the ''[[Financial Times]]'' Qatar paid $700&nbsp;million to Iranian-backed [[Shia Islam|Shi'a]] militias in Iraq, $120\u2013140&nbsp;million to [[Tahrir al-Sham]], and $80&nbsp;million to [[Ahrar al-Sham]].<ref name=\"SolomonFinTimes\">Erika Solomon, [https://www.ft.com/content/dd033082-49e9-11e7-a3f4-c742b9791d43 The $1bn hostage deal that enraged Qatar's Gulf rivals: Doha reportedly paid al-Qaeda affiliate and Iran to win release of royal hunting party] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605210800/https://www.ft.com/content/dd033082-49e9-11e7-a3f4-c742b9791d43|date=5 June 2017|title=}}, ''Financial Times'' (5 June 2017).</ref>\n\n===Riyadh Summit 2017===\n[[File:Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, King Salman of Saudi Arabia, Melania Trump, and Donald Trump, May 2017.jpg|thumb|left|US President [[Donald Trump]], King [[Salman of Saudi Arabia]], and Egyptian President [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]] at the 2017 Riyadh Summit. The meeting is cited as one of the catalysts for the crisis.<ref name=nytimes/>]]\nAs part of the [[Riyadh Summit 2017|Riyadh Summit]] in late May 2017, many world leaders, including US President Donald Trump visited the region. Trump gave strong support for Saudi Arabia's efforts in fighting against states and groups allied with Iran and the Muslim Brotherhood, leading to an [[2017 United States-Saudi Arabia arms deal|arms deal]] between the countries. The ''Business Insider'' reported that \"[[Elliott Broidy]] a top fundraiser for President Donald Trump; and [[George Nader (businessman)|George Nader]], Broidy's business partner ... pushed for anti-Qatar policies at the highest levels of government, and expected large consulting contracts from Saudi Arabia and the UAE.\"<ref>\"[http://www.businessinsider.com/george-nader-elliott-broidy-trump-middle-east-uae-qatar-saudi-arabia-mueller-2018-5 How a top Trump fundraiser spent a year cultivating 2 crown princes to nail $1 billion in business]\". ''[[Business Insider]]''. May 21, 2018.</ref> Trump's support may have induced other [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] states to fall in line with Saudi Arabia to take a stance against Qatar.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> Trump's public support for Saudi Arabia, according to ''The New York Times'', emboldened the kingdom and sent a chill through other Gulf states, including Oman and Kuwait, that fear that any country that defies the Saudis or the United Arab Emirates could face ostracism as Qatar has.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/07/world/middleeast/trump-qatar-saudi-arabia-middle-east.html|title=Trump Has Busy Day in Vortex of Middle East Relations|first1=David E. Sanger, Mark|last1=Landler|first2=Eric|last2=Schmitt|date=7 June 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref> The Saudi-led move was at once an opportunity for the GCC partners and Egypt to punish their adversaries in Doha, please their allies in Washington, and remove attention from their own shortcomings and challenges.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inss.org.il/publication/qatar-crisis-causes-implications-risks-need-compromise/|title=The Qatar Crisis: Causes,........... Implications, Risks, and the Need for Compromise|date=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hacking of Qatari websites===\nAccording to Qatar-based Al Jazeera and the American FBI, the [[Qatar News Agency]] website and other government media platforms were [[hack (computing)|hacked]] in May 2017, where hackers posted fake remarks on the official Qatar News Agency attributed to the Emir of Qatar, Sheikh [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]], that expressed support for Iran, Hamas, Hezbollah, and Israel.<ref name=auto>{{Cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/saudi-arabia-uae-egypt-bahrain-cut-ties-qatar-170605031700062.html|title=Saudi Arabia, UAE, Egypt, Bahrain cut ties to Qatar|date=5 June 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref> The emir was quoted as saying: \"Iran represents a regional and Islamic power that cannot be ignored and it is unwise to face up against it. It is a big power in the stabilization of the region.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/05/23/qatar-says-state-news-website-hacked-fake-article-published.html|title=Hack, fake story expose real tensions between Qatar, Gulf|agency=[[Fox News]]|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"stratfor\">\"[https://www.stratfor.com/article/trumps-arab-nato-vision-desert-mirage Trump's 'Arab NATO' Vision is a Desert Mirage]\". [[Stratfor]]. 31 May 2017.</ref> Qatar reported that the statements were false and did not know their origin.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> Despite this, the remarks were widely publicized in the various Arab news media, including UAE-based [[Sky News Arabia]] and Saudi-owned [[Al Arabiya]].<ref name=auto/> On 3 June 2017, the [[Twitter|Twitter account]] of Bahraini foreign minister [[Khalid bin Ahmed Al Khalifa]] was hacked.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://phys.org/news/2017-06-bahrain-minister-briefly-hacked-qatar.html |title=Bahrain minister briefly hacked after Qatar cyber attack|publisher=Phys.org|date=3 June 2017|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nInitially alleged intelligence gathered by the US security agencies indicated that [[Cyberwarfare by Russia|Russian hackers]] were behind the intrusion first reported by the Qataris.<ref name=\"PerezProkupecz\">{{cite news|author=Evan Perez & Shimon Prokupecz|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/06/politics/russian-hackers-planted-fake-news-qatar-crisis/index.html|title=US suspects Russian hackers planted fake news behind Qatar crisis|agency=CNN|date=6 June 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Wintour\">{{cite news|author=[[Patrick Wintour]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/07/russian-hackers-qatar-crisis-fbi-inquiry-saudi-arabia-uae|title=Russian hackers to blame for sparking Qatar crisis, FBI inquiry finds|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> However, a US official briefed on the inquiry told the ''New York Times'' that it \"was unclear whether the hackers were state-sponsored\"<ref name=\"Landler\">{{cite news|author=[[Mark Landler]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/06/world/middleeast/trump-qatar-saudi-arabia.html|title=Trump Takes Credit for Saudi Move Against Qatar, a U.S. Military Partner|work=New York Times|date=6 June 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> and ''The Guardian'' diplomatic editor [[Patrick Wintour]] reported that \"it is believed that the Russian government was not involved in the hacks; instead, freelance hackers were paid to undertake the work on behalf of some other state or individual.\"<ref name=\"Wintour\"/> A US diplomat said that Russia and its ally Iran stood to benefit from sowing discord among US allies in the region, \"particularly if they made it more difficult for the United States to use Qatar as a major base.\"<ref name=\"Landler\"/> The FBI sent a team of investigators to [[Doha]] to help the [[Qatari government]] investigate the hacking incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mofa.gov.qa/en/all-mofa-news/details/2017/06/07/ministry-of-the-interior-statement-on-piracy-crime-on-qatar-news-agency-website |title=Ministry of the Interior Statement on Piracy Crime on Qatar News Agency Website |publisher=mofa.gov.qa |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621122056/https://mofa.gov.qa/en/all-mofa-news/details/2017/06/07/ministry-of-the-interior-statement-on-piracy-crime-on-qatar-news-agency-website |archivedate=21 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Later, the [[The New York Times|''New York Times'']] reported that the hacking incidents may be part of a long-running cyberwar between Qatar and other Gulf countries that was only revealed to the public during the recent incidents, and they noted how Saudi and UAE media picked up the statement made by the hacked media in less than 20 minutes and began interviewing many well-prepared commentators against Qatar.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/08/world/middleeast/qatar-cyberattack-espionage-for-hire.html |title=Hacking in Qatar Highlights a Shift Toward Espionage-for-Hire |last=Kirkpatrick |first=David D. |date=8 June 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=11 June 2017 |last2=Frenkel |first2=Sheera  |issn=0362-4331 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610221221/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/08/world/middleeast/qatar-cyberattack-espionage-for-hire.html |archivedate=10 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nUS intelligence agencies believe that the hacking was done by the United Arab Emirates, according to a ''[[Washington Post]]'' article published on 16 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/uae-hacked-qatari-government-sites-sparking-regional-upheaval-according-to-us-intelligence-officials/2017/07/16/00c46e54-698f-11e7-8eb5-cbccc2e7bfbf_story.html |title=UAE orchestrated hacking of Qatari government sites, sparking regional upheaval, according to U.S. intelligence officials |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=30 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729180340/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/uae-hacked-qatari-government-sites-sparking-regional-upheaval-according-to-us-intelligence-officials/2017/07/16/00c46e54-698f-11e7-8eb5-cbccc2e7bfbf_story.html |archivedate=29 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The intelligence officials stated that the hacking was discussed among Emirati officials on 23 May, one day before the operation took place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/uae-arranged-hacking-qatari-media-washington-post-170717004353563.html |title=UAE arranged hacking of Qatari media: Washington Post |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=16 July 2017 |accessdate=27 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827000653/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/uae-arranged-hacking-qatari-media-washington-post-170717004353563.html |archivedate=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The UAE denied any involvement in the hacking.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/07/17/middleeast/uae-qatar-report/index.html |title=UAE denies Washington Post report it orchestrated Qatar hack |publisher=CNN |author1=Tamara Qiblawi |author2=Angela Dewan |date=27 July 2017 |accessdate=27 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827215835/http://www.cnn.com/2017/07/17/middleeast/uae-qatar-report/index.html |archivedate=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was announced on 26 August 2017, that five individuals allegedly involved in the hacking were arrested in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-cyber-idUSKCN1B608L |title=Qatar says five suspects in news agency hacking detained in Turkey |agency=Reuters |date=26 August 2017 |accessdate=27 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827034414/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-cyber-idUSKCN1B608L |archivedate=27 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Hacking of UAE ambassador's email===\n[[File:Yousef Al Otaiba 2013.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Yousef Al Otaiba|Yousef Al-Otaiba]]]]\nIn May 2017, the email account of the UAE's ambassador to the US, [[Yousef Al Otaiba|Yousef Al-Otaiba]], was hacked. The emails were reported as \"embarrassing\" by Al Jazeera because they showed links between the UAE and the US-based [[Foundation for Defense of Democracies]].<ref name=embarrass>{{cite news |title=Someone Is Using These Leaked Emails To Embarrass Washington's Most Powerful Ambassador |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/otaiba-ambassador-uae-leaked-emails_us_5932bf04e4b02478cb9bec1c |date=3 June 2017 |first=Akbar Shahid |last=Ahmed |work=HuffPost |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603233228/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/otaiba-ambassador-uae-leaked-emails_us_5932bf04e4b02478cb9bec1c |archivedate=3 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Arab countries saw the media coverage of the alleged email hack as a provocation and a move orchestrated by Qatar,<ref>{{cite web |title=ANALYSIS: UAE envoy\u2019s hacked emails and Qatar\u2019s escalating Gulf rift |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2017/06/04/ANALYSIS-UAE-envoy-s-hacked-emails-and-Qatar-s-escalating-Gulf-rift-.html |date=4 June 2017 |publisher=Al Arabiya |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731203753/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/features/2017/06/04/ANALYSIS-UAE-envoy-s-hacked-emails-and-Qatar-s-escalating-Gulf-rift-.html |archivedate=31 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and deepened the rift between the two sides.<ref name=FT>{{cite news |title=What is behind the extraordinary Gulf dispute with Qatar? |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3c6b7224-49d0-11e7-a3f4-c742b9791d43 |newspaper=Financial Times |date=5 June 2017 |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-access=subscription  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703000219/https://www.ft.com/content/3c6b7224-49d0-11e7-a3f4-c742b9791d43 |archivedate=3 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 9 June, Al Jazeera's media network was the victim of a [[cyber attack]] across all its platforms.<ref name=Metro6695692>{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/08/al-jazeera-hit-by-cyber-attack-on-all-systems-6695692/ |title=Al Jazeera hit by 'cyber attack on all systems' |first=Jen |last=Mills |work=Metro |accessdate=9 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609005503/http://metro.co.uk/2017/06/08/al-jazeera-hit-by-cyber-attack-on-all-systems-6695692/ |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to ''The Intercept'', Yousef al-Otaiba has been reportedly linked to buy influence for UAE-led campaigns in the White House.<ref name=FT2>{{cite news |title=Why UAE ambassador is so much influential in DC |url=https://theintercept.com/2017/07/30/uae-yousef-otaiba-cnas-american-progress-michele-flournoy-drone |newspaper=The Intercept |date=5 June 2017 |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-access=subscription  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730133741/https://theintercept.com/2017/07/30/uae-yousef-otaiba-cnas-american-progress-michele-flournoy-drone/ |archivedate=30 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Severance of diplomatic and economic ties==\nBetween 5 and 6 June 2017, Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Yemen, Egypt, the [[Maldives]], and Bahrain all separately announced that they were cutting diplomatic ties with Qatar; among these Bahrain was the first to announce the severing of ties at 02:50 GMT in the early morning of 5 June.<ref name=\"Qatar-Gulf crisis: Your questions answered\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/06/qatar-gulf-crisis-questions-answered-170606103033599.html |title=Qatar-Gulf crisis: Your questions answered |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=30 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728112951/http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/06/qatar-gulf-crisis-questions-answered-170606103033599.html |archivedate=28 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Why Saudi Arabia and six other countries have cut ties with Qatar |url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/work/leaders/why-saudi-arabia-and-six-other-countries-have-cut-ties-with-qatar/news-story/b758105a63a70df40b73211e0395d550 |work=News.com.au |accessdate=6 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607004931/http://www.news.com.au/finance/work/leaders/why-saudi-arabia-and-six-other-countries-have-cut-ties-with-qatar/news-story/b758105a63a70df40b73211e0395d550 |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40155829 |title=Qatar row: Five countries cut links with Doha |date=5 June 2017 |work=BBC News |access-date=5 June 2017  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605041425/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40155829 |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}<br/>{{cite news |last1=Kirkpatrick |first1=David D. |last2=Barnard |first2=Anne |url=https://www.academia.edu/33408516/Terrorist_Attacks_Pour_Gas_on_Saudi-_Iranian_Rivalry_and_Gulf_Tensions |title=Terrorist Attacks Pour Gas on Saudi- Iranian Rivalry and Gulf Tensions |work=Eurasia Diary |date=7 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727235532/http://www.academia.edu/33408516/Terrorist_Attacks_Pour_Gas_on_Saudi-_Iranian_Rivalry_and_Gulf_Tensions |archivedate=27 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"nbcnews\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/egypt-saudi-arabia-among-gulf-states-cutting-ties-qatar-n768161 |title=Saudi Arabia Accuses Qatar of Backing Terrorism, Cuts Ties |last=Associated Press |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=NBC News|access-date=5 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605044937/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/egypt-saudi-arabia-among-gulf-states-cutting-ties-qatar-n768161|archive-date=5 June 2017|url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/05/saudi-arabia-and-bahrain-break-diplomatic-ties-with-qatar-over-terrorism |title=Gulf plunged into diplomatic crisis as countries cut ties with Qatar |last=Wintour |first=Patrick |date=5 June 2017|access-date=5 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605042514/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/05/saudi-arabia-and-bahrain-break-diplomatic-ties-with-qatar-over-terrorism|archive-date=5 June 2017|url-status=live  |newspaper=The Guardian |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/syria-crisis-turkey-and-saudi-arabia-shock-western-countries-by-supporting-antiassad-jihadists-10242747.html |title=Turkey and Saudi Arabia alarm the West by backing Islamist extremists the Americans had bombed in Syria |first=Kim |last=Sengupta |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=12 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150513214636/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/syria-crisis-turkey-and-saudi-arabia-shock-western-countries-by-supporting-antiassad-jihadists-10242747.html |archivedate=13 May 2015 |df=dmy-all}}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.academia.edu/33408451/Qatar_Pursues_an_Independent_Foreign_Policy_that_Clashes_with_the_Saudis_Strategic_Interests.pdf |title=Qatar Pursues an Independent Foreign Policy that Clashes with the Saudi's Strategic Interests |work=Eurasia Diary |date=8 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727225548/http://www.academia.edu/33408451/Qatar_Pursues_an_Independent_Foreign_Policy_that_Clashes_with_the_Saudis_Strategic_Interests.pdf |archivedate=27 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.academia.edu/33408486/Saudi_Diplomatic_Offensive_on_Qatar_to_Barely_Impact_Anti-Terror_Fight_in_Region |title=Saudi Diplomatic Offensive on Qatar to Barely Impact Anti-Terror Fight in Region |work=Sputnik International |date=8 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727234344/http://www.academia.edu/33408486/Saudi_Diplomatic_Offensive_on_Qatar_to_Barely_Impact_Anti-Terror_Fight_in_Region |archivedate=27 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}<br/>{{cite news |last1=Kirkpatrick |first2=David D. |last2=Barnard |first1=Anne |url=https://www.academia.edu/33408516/Terrorist_Attacks_Pour_Gas_on_Saudi-_Iranian_Rivalry_and_Gulf_Tensions |title=Terrorist Attacks Pour Gas on Saudi- Iranian Rivalry and Gulf Tensions |work=Eurasia Diary |date=7 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727235532/http://www.academia.edu/33408516/Terrorist_Attacks_Pour_Gas_on_Saudi-_Iranian_Rivalry_and_Gulf_Tensions |archivedate=27 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite news |url=https://www.academia.edu/33408486/Saudi_Diplomatic_Offensive_on_Qatar_to_Barely_Impact_Anti-Terror_Fight_in_Region |title=Saudi Diplomatic Offensive on Qatar to Barely Impact Anti-Terror Fight in Region |work=Sputnik International |date=8 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727234344/http://www.academia.edu/33408486/Saudi_Diplomatic_Offensive_on_Qatar_to_Barely_Impact_Anti-Terror_Fight_in_Region |archivedate=27 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Qatar Flights.png|thumb|upright=2|Maps showing the routes taken by Qatar Airways flights leaving Doha before and after the embargo was imposed. Data taken from [[Flightradar24|FlightRadar24]].]]\nA variety of diplomatic actions were taken. Saudi Arabia and the UAE notified ports and shipping agents not to receive Qatari vessels or ships owned by Qatari companies or individuals.<ref name=\"aljazeera1/6june2017\" /> Saudi Arabia closed the border with Qatar.<ref name=\"aljazeera1/6june2017\" /> Saudi Arabia restricted its airspace to [[Qatar Airways]]. Instead, Qatar was forced to reroute flights to Africa and Europe through Iranian airspace.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |title=Saudi-led Rupture With Qatar Pushes Nation into Iran's Embrace |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-06/saudi-led-rupture-with-qatar-pushes-nation-into-iran-s-embrace |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607085920/https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-06/saudi-led-rupture-with-qatar-pushes-nation-into-iran-s-embrace |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Saudi Arabia's central bank advised banks not to trade with Qatari banks in [[Qatari riyal]]s.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-saudi-banks-idUSKBN18X0S9 \"Saudi central bank tells banks not to trade with Qatar banks in Qatari riyals: sources\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003175217/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-saudi-banks-idUSKBN18X0S9 |date=3 October 2017 }}. Reuters</ref>\n\nQatar verbally criticized the ban. The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Qatar)|Foreign Ministry of Qatar]] criticized the ban, arguing that it undermined Qatar's sovereignty.<ref name=\"dawn/5june2017\"/> The foreign minister of Qatar, [[Mohammed bin Abdulrahman Al-Thani]], said that Saudi statements regarding Qatar were contradictory: on the one hand, Saudi Arabia claimed Qatar was supporting Iran, on the other hand, it claimed Qatar was funding [[Sunni]] extremists fighting against Iran.<ref>{{cite news |title=Qatar: We're 'willing to talk' to resolve diplomatic crisis |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/middleeast/qatar-diplomatic-crisis/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606101325/http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/middleeast/qatar-diplomatic-crisis/ |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia's move was welcomed by United States president Donald Trump despite a large US presence at the Al Udeid Air Base, the primary base of US air operations against the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-07/trump-s-qatar-curveball-makes-tillerson-improvise-policy-again |title=Trump's Qatar Curveball Makes Tillerson Improvise Policy Again |date=7 June 2017 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |accessdate=10 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826025948/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-07/trump-s-qatar-curveball-makes-tillerson-improvise-policy-again |archivedate=26 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}<br/>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/06/06/for-qataris-a-u-s-air-base-is-best-defense-against-trump-attacks/ |title=For Qataris, a U.S. air base is best defense against Trump attacks |first1=Greg |last1=Jaffe |first2=Thomas |last2=Gibbons-Neff |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=10 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707090451/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/06/06/for-qataris-a-u-s-air-base-is-best-defense-against-trump-attacks/ |archivedate=7 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, Secretary of State [[Rex Tillerson|Rex W. Tillerson]] and Defense Secretary [[James Mattis]] worked on de-escalating the situation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-07/trump-s-qatar-curveball-makes-tillerson-improvise-policy-again |title=Trump's Qatar Curveball Makes Tillerson Improvise Policy Again |date=7 June 2017 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |access-date=5 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826025948/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-06-07/trump-s-qatar-curveball-makes-tillerson-improvise-policy-again |archivedate=26 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tillerson, as the CEO of [[ExxonMobil]], was acquainted with the current and previous emirs of Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Overdahl |first1=Stian |title=Saudi and UAE Stumble Over Tiny Qatar |url=https://magazine.zenith.me/en/politics/pyrrhic-manoeuvres-among-gulf-states |accessdate=16 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828160937/https://magazine.zenith.me/en/politics/pyrrhic-manoeuvres-among-gulf-states |archivedate=28 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A number of countries in the region, including [[Qatar\u2013Turkey relations|Turkey]], [[Qatar\u2013Russia relations|Russia]] and [[Iran\u2013Qatar relations|Iran]], called for the crisis to be resolved through peaceful negotiations.\n\nAll [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]] countries involved in the announcement ordered their citizens out of Qatar.<ref name=\"associatedpress\">{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/8257ce650e224188a1884e34eabb5e90/4-Arab-nations-cut-diplomatic-ties-to-Qatar-as-rift-deepens |title=Arab nations cut ties with Qatar in new Mideast crisis |last=Gambrell |first=Jon |date=5 June 2017 |access-date=5 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625070305/https://www.apnews.com/8257ce650e224188a1884e34eabb5e90/4-Arab-nations-cut-diplomatic-ties-to-Qatar-as-rift-deepens |archive-date=25 June 2017 |url-status=live |agency=[[Associated Press]]  |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Three Gulf states (Saudi Arabia, UAE, Bahrain) gave Qatari visitors and residents two weeks to leave their countries.<ref name=\"dawn/5june2017\">{{cite news |agency=Reuters/AFP/AP |title=Saudi, Egypt, UAE, Bahrain and Yemen isolate Qatar over 'terrorism' as rift deepens |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1337555/saudi-egypt-uae-bahrain-and-yemen-isolate-qatar-over-terrorism-as-rift-deepens |accessdate=5 June 2017 |newspaper=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |date=5 June 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605090748/https://www.dawn.com/news/1337555/saudi-egypt-uae-bahrain-and-yemen-isolate-qatar-over-terrorism-as-rift-deepens |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The foreign ministries of Bahrain and Egypt gave Qatari diplomats 48 hours to leave their countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Qatar: 'No justification' for cutting diplomatic ties |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/qatar-justification-cutting-diplomatic-ties-170605073154112.html |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605091658/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/qatar-justification-cutting-diplomatic-ties-170605073154112.html |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\"/> Qatar was expelled from the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]] and Yemen's government itself has cut ties.<ref name=\"dawn/5june2017\" /> Kuwait and Oman remained neutral.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kuwait and Oman: As they remain silent on the Qatar-Gulf rift, what does this mean for them? |url=https://www.zawya.com/mena/en/story/Kuwait_and_Oman_As_they_remain_silent_on_the_QatarGulf_rift_what_does_this_mean_for_them-ZAWYA20170606110347/ |date=6 June 2017 |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606143751/https://www.zawya.com/mena/en/story/Kuwait_and_Oman_As_they_remain_silent_on_the_QatarGulf_rift_what_does_this_mean_for_them-ZAWYA20170606110347/ |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nKuwaiti mediators in Riyadh were presented with a list of Saudi demands of Qatar. These included cutting off all links with Iran and expelling resident members of Hamas and the Muslim Brotherhood, shutting down the Al-Jazeera network, to stop \"interfering\" in foreign countries' affairs and to cease any funding or support for terrorist organisations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/qatar-crisis-saudi-arabia-insists-150444797.html |title=Qatar crisis: Saudi Arabia insists Gulf country must meet its demands \u2018soon\u2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003175457/https://uk.news.yahoo.com/qatar-crisis-saudi-arabia-insists-150444797.html |archivedate=3 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Diplomatic activity===\n{{As of|2019|08|10|post=,}} seven sovereign governments have not restored diplomatic ties with Qatar.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-chad/chad-and-qatar-restore-ties-cut-in-wake-of-arab-states-rift-idUSKCN1G515I|title=Chad and Qatar restore ties cut in wake of Arab states rift|work=Reuters|date=21 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://maldivesindependent.com/politics/maldives-to-restore-ties-with-qatar-and-iran-142905|title=Maldives to restore ties with Qatar and Iran|website=Maldivesindependent.com|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Senegal restores its ambassador to Qatar |url=http://aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/senegal-restores-its-ambassador-to-qatar/890618 |publisher=Anadolu Agency |accessdate=22 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822051723/http://aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/senegal-restores-its-ambassador-to-qatar/890618 |archivedate=22 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Gulf Crisis: Saudi-led bloc loses ally Senegal in boycott of Qatar |url=https://me-confidential.com/16844-gulf-crisis-saudi-led-bloc-loses-ally-senegal-in-boycott-of-qatar.html |publisher=Middle East Confidential |accessdate=22 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822191946/http://me-confidential.com/16844-gulf-crisis-saudi-led-bloc-loses-ally-senegal-in-boycott-of-qatar.html |archivedate=22 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{div col}}\n*{{flag|Bahrain}}\n*{{flag|Comoros}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=1638089 |title=Comoros severs diplomatic relations with Qatar The official Saudi Press Agency |publisher=spa.gov.sa |accessdate=8 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015120038/http://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=1638089 |archivedate=15 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Egypt}}\n*{{flag|Mauritania}} \n*{{flag|Saudi Arabia}}\n*{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}\n*{{flag|Yemen}} ([[Cabinet of Yemen]])\n{{divend}}\n\nThe [[Tobruk]]-based [[Second Al-Thani Cabinet|government]] of Libya claimed to have cut diplomatic ties with Qatar despite having no diplomatic representation in that country.<ref name=\"CNNlist\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-libya-idUSKBN18W11M |title=Libya's eastern-based government cuts diplomatic ties with Qatar |date=5 June 2017 |agency=Reute rs |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619142529/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-libya-idUSKBN18W11M |archivedate=19 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.libyaherald.com/2017/06/05/beida-government-cuts-off-diplomatic-relations-with-qatar/ |title=Beida government cuts off diplomatic relations with Qatar |last=Prentis |first=Jamie |date=5 June 2017 |work=Libya Herald |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613002409/https://www.libyaherald.com/2017/06/05/beida-government-cuts-off-diplomatic-relations-with-qatar/ |archive-date=13 June 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe semi-autonomous [[States and regions of Somalia#States|Somali regions]] of [[Puntland]],\n[[Hirshabelle]], and [[Galmudug]] each issued statements cutting ties with Qatar, in opposition to the neutral stance of the federal government of [[Somalia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/09/somalia-rebukes-states-breaking-qatar-170922021127727.html |title=Somalia chides its regions for cutting ties with Qatar |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=22 September 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929184134/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/09/somalia-rebukes-states-breaking-qatar-170922021127727.html |archivedate=29 September 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019|08|10|post=,}} two countries still have downgraded diplomatic ties with Qatar without fully cutting relations.<ref name=\"CNNlist\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/middleeast/qatar-diplomatic-crisis/index.html |title=Qatar: We're 'willing to talk' to resolve diplomatic crisis |publisher=CNN |date=6 June 2017 |accessdate=6 June 2017 |author1=Katie Hunt |author2=Elizabeth Roberts |author3=Victoria Brown |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606113452/http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/middleeast/qatar-diplomatic-crisis/index.html |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n{{div col}}\n*{{flag|Djibouti}}<ref name=\"DjiTieDowngrade\">{{cite web |url=http://www.djibdiplomatie.dj/index.php/8-communique-de-presse/660-urgent-communique-de-presse |title=URGENT/COMMUNIQUE DE PRESSE |last=Djibdiplomatie1 |website=djibdiplomatie.dj |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821003340/http://www.djibdiplomatie.dj/index.php/8-communique-de-presse/660-urgent-communique-de-presse |archivedate=21 August 2017 |df=dmy-all |access-date=7 June 2017 }}</ref>\n*{{flag|Niger}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Niger recalls ambassador to Qatar in solidarity with Arab states |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/gulf-qatar-niger-idUSL8N1J70A1 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611202259/http://www.reuters.com/article/gulf-qatar-niger-idUSL8N1J70A1 |archivedate=11 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{divend}}\n\nOther countries made statements condemning Qatar, including [[Gabon]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Mauritania breaks diplomatic ties with Qatar, Gabon voices condemnation |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-mauritania-idUSKBN18X2ZH |agency=Reuters |accessdate=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607193940/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-mauritania-idUSKBN18X2ZH |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and 