 a \"Plan B\" for an alternate 2022 host. According to Thawadi, all these logistical obstacles are being overcome and building progress is continuing with only minimal cost increases, in preparation for the first World Cup in the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/10/gulf-blockade-poses-risk-qatar-world-cup-171006210428080.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=8 October 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008154735/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/10/gulf-blockade-poses-risk-qatar-world-cup-171006210428080.html |archivedate=8 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Global Reactions ==\n===United States===\n[[File:Donald Trump meets with the Emir of Qatar (Sheikh Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani), May 2017.jpg|thumb|[[United States President]] Donald Trump with the [[Emir of Qatar]] [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]], May 2017.]]\n[[File:Secretary Tillerson is Escorted to his Meeting With the Emir of Qatar (35088035863).jpg|thumb|UAE and Saudi Arabia lobbied President Trump to fire [[Rex Tillerson]] for not supporting the blockade of Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alex |last=Emmons |title=Saudi Arabia Planned to Invade Qatar Last Summer. Rex Tillerson\u2019s Efforts to Stop It May Have Cost Him His Job. |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/08/01/rex-tillerson-qatar-saudi-uae/ |work=The Intercept |date=August 1, 2018}}</ref>]]\n[[United States]] President [[Donald Trump]] claimed credit for engineering the diplomatic crisis in a [[Donald Trump on social media|series of tweets]].<ref name=credit>{{cite news |publisher=BBC |title=Qatar row: Trump claims credit for isolation |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40175935 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607013027/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40175935 |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 6 June, Trump began by tweeting: \"During my recent trip to the Middle East I stated that there can no longer be funding of Radical Ideology. Leaders pointed to Qatar \u2013 look!\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=realDonaldTrump |last=Trump |first=Donald J. |number=872062159789985792 |date=6 June 2017 |title=During my recent trip to the Middle East I stated that there can no longer be funding of Radical Ideology. Leaders pointed to Qatar \u2013 look! |link=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872062159789985792 |access-date=7 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606120637/https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872062159789985792 |archive-date=6 June 2017 |url-status= live}}</ref><ref name= credit /> An hour and a half later, he remarked on Twitter that it was \"good to see the Saudi Arabia visit with the King and 50 countries already paying off. They said they would take a hard line on funding extremism, and all reference{{sic}} was pointing to Qatar. Perhaps this will be the beginning of the end to the horror of terrorism!\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=realDonaldTrump |last=Trump |first=Donald J.  |number=872084870620520448 |date=6 June 2017 |title=So good to see the Saudi Arabia visit with the King and 50 countries already paying off. They said they would take a hard line on funding... |link=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872084870620520448 |access-date=7 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606133708/https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872084870620520448 |archive-date= 6 June 2017 |url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=realDonaldTrump |last=Trump |first=Donald J.  |number=872086906804240384 |date=6 June 2017 |title=...extremism, and all reference was pointing to Qatar. Perhaps this will be the beginning of the end to the horror of terrorism! |link=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872086906804240384 |access-date= 7 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606134456/https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/872086906804240384 |archive-date= 6 June 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name= \"WaPo 6 June\"/> This was in contrast to attempts by [[the Pentagon]] and the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]] to remain neutral. The Pentagon praised Qatar for hosting the Al Udeid Air Base and for its \"enduring commitment to regional security.\" [[United States Ambassador to Qatar|US Ambassador to Qatar]], [[Dana Shell Smith]], sent a similar message.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. military praises Qatar, despite Trump tweet |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-usa-pentagon-idUSKBN18X2G2 |accessdate=8 June 2017 |agency=Reuters |date=6 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607190432/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-usa-pentagon-idUSKBN18X2G2 |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump appears to take credit for Gulf nations' move against Qatar |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/politics/trump-qatar-ideology/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607002540/http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/politics/trump-qatar-ideology/ |archivedate=7 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Earlier, the US [[U.S. Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] had taken a neutral stance and called for dialogue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/05/tillerson-says-break-with-qatar-by-saudi-arabia-others-wont-affect-counter-terrorism.html |title=Tillerson says break with Qatar by Saudi Arabia, others won't affect counter-terrorism |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=CNBC |access-date=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605081330/http://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/05/tillerson-says-break-with-qatar-by-saudi-arabia-others-wont-affect-counter-terrorism.html |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nOn 8 June, President Donald Trump, during a phone call with the [[Emir of Qatar]] [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]], offered to act as a mediator in the conflict with a White House meeting between the parties if necessary.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gaouette |first1=Nicole |last2=Browne |first2=Ryan |title=Trump reverses course in Qatar call |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/07/politics/trump-qatar-call/index.html |accessdate=8 June 2017 |publisher=CNN |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608070721/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/07/politics/trump-qatar-call/index.html |archivedate=8 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The offer was declined, and a Qatari official stated, \"The emir has no plans to leave Qatar while the country is under a blockade.\"<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-idUSKBN18Z1C9 |title=Qatar vows no surrender in Gulf crisis as U.S., Kuwait seek solution |date=8 June 2017 |agency=Reuters |access-date=8 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608113447/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-idUSKBN18Z1C9 |archivedate=8 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 9 June, Trump once again put the blame on Qatar, calling the blockade \"hard but necessary\" while claiming that Qatar had been funding terrorism at a \"very high level\" and described the country as having an \"extremist ideology in terms of funding.\"<ref name=\"Mindock\">{{cite news |last1=Mindock |first1=Clark |title=Donald Trump accuses Qatar of funding terrorism 'at very high level' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-qatar-terrorism-funding-saudi-arabia-gulf-accusation-very-high-level-a7782896.html |accessdate=10 June 2017 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609204835/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-qatar-terrorism-funding-saudi-arabia-gulf-accusation-very-high-level-a7782896.html |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> This statement was in conflict with Secretary of State Tillerson's comments on the same day, which called on Gulf states to ease the blockade.<ref name=contradict>{{cite news |title=President Trump Just Directly Contradicted His Secretary of State |url=http://time.com/4813247/donald-trump-contradict-rex-tillerson-qatar/ |work=Time |accessdate=9 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609213250/http://time.com/4813247/donald-trump-contradict-rex-tillerson-qatar/ |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Mindock\"/> In 13 June 2017 after meeting with Tillerson in Washington, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Saudi Arabia)|Saudi Foreign Minister]] [[Adel al-Jubeir]] stated that there was \"no blockade\" and \"what we have done is we have denied them use of our airspace, and this is our sovereign right,\" and that the King Salman Centre for Humanitarian Aid and Relief would send food or medical aid to Qatar if needed.<ref name=\"TurkeyBBC\"/> The following day, Trump authorized the sale of $12 billion of U.S. weapons to Qatar.<ref>Brennan, Margaret and Kylie Atwood.  [https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-sells-qatar-12-billion-arms-days-after-accusing-it-of-funding-terrorism/ \"Trump sells Qatar $12 billion of U.S. weapons days after accusing it of funding terrorism.\"] ''CBS News''.  15 June 2017.  21 January 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 2017, Trump told a crowd in [[Iowa]] that \"We cannot let these incredibly rich nations fund radical Islamic terror or terrorism of any kind\", noting that after his visit to Riyadh in May 2017 to meet with Saudi [[King Salman]] and urge an end to terror funding, \"He has taken it to heart. And now they're fighting with other countries that have been funding terrorism. And I think we had a huge impact.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/transcript/2017/06/21/conway-special-elections-reaffirmation-trumps-agenda-sekulow-investigation-should-include-comeys-leak.html |title=Conway: Special elections a reaffirmation of Trump's agenda; Sekulow: Investigation should include Comey's leak |date=21 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630215456/http://www.foxnews.com/transcript/2017/06/21/conway-special-elections-reaffirmation-trumps-agenda-sekulow-investigation-should-include-comeys-leak.html |archivedate=30 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-qatar-list-20170623-story.html |title=Will Qatar agree to Arab countries' new list of demands? Unlikely |first=Molly |last=Hennessy-Fiske |date=23 June 2017 |work=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630180620/http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-qatar-list-20170623-story.html |archivedate=30 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n===Other countries===\nIsrael's former defense minister, [[Avigdor Lieberman]], described the situation as an \"opportunity\" for Israel, stating, \"Some [Arab countries'] interests overlap with Israeli interests, including the issue with al-Jazeera.\" He went on to describe al-Jazeera as an \"incitement machine\" and \"pure propaganda.\" Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] has demanded al-Jazeera shut down its offices in Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-demands-al-jazeera-offices-in-israel-be-shut-down/ |title=Netanyahu demands al-Jazeera offices in Israel be shut down |website=The Times of Israel |accessdate=30 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727013412/http://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-demands-al-jazeera-offices-in-israel-be-shut-down/ |archivedate=27 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nReports that Mauritius had cut ties with Qatar were refuted by the Mauritian government.<ref name=\"IONNews\">{{cite news |url=http://ionnews.mu/maurice-maintient-ses-relations-diplomatiques-avec-le-qatar-060617/ |title=Maurice maintient ses relations diplomatiques avec le Qatar |trans-title=Mauritius maintains its diplomatic relations with Qatar |agency=Indian Ocean News Network |date=6 June 2017 |accessdate=7 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703201410/http://ionnews.mu/maurice-maintient-ses-relations-diplomatiques-avec-le-qatar-060617/ |archivedate=3 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"DefiMedia\">{{cite news |url=http://defimedia.info/diplomatie-maurice-maintient-ses-liens-avec-le-qatar |title=Diplomatie : Maurice maintient ses liens avec le Qatar |trans-title=Diplomacy: Mauritius maintains its links with Qatar |agency=[[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]] |date=7 June 2017 |accessdate=7 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717090106/http://defimedia.info/diplomatie-maurice-maintient-ses-liens-avec-le-qatar |archivedate=17 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A report in the ''[[Saudi Gazette]]'' incorrectly stated that Mauritius had broken off ties with Qatar and that [[Vice Prime Minister of Mauritius|Mauritius' Vice Prime-Minister]] had issued a communiqu\u00e9 pledging his country's support for Saudi Arabia. This prompted further erroneous reports by other outlets. However, Mauritian [[Vice Prime Minister of Mauritius|Vice Prime Minister]] Showkutally Soodhun in an interview with [[Le D\u00e9fi Media Group]] of Mauritius refuted claims that he had issued any such communiqu\u00e9, and [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Mauritius)|Mauritius' Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] issued a statement that Mauritius continued to maintain diplomatic relations with Qatar.<ref name=\"IONNews\"/><ref name=\"DefiMedia\"/>\n\nPakistan stated that it had no plans to cut diplomatic relations with Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan has no plans to cut diplomatic ties with Qatar: FO |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1427775/pakistan-no-plans-cut-diplomatic-ties-qatar-fo/ |accessdate=5 June 2017 |work=The Express Tribune |date=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605095833/https://tribune.com.pk/story/1427775/pakistan-no-plans-cut-diplomatic-ties-qatar-fo/ |archivedate=5 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Members of the Parliament passed a resolution in [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] urging all countries to \"show restraint and resolve their differences through dialogue.\"<ref name=\"auto2\"/> The Pakistani Federal minister for Petroleum and Natural Resources said that \"Pakistan will continue to import liquefied natural gas (LNG) from Qatar.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Pakistan to continue import of LNG from Qatar |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1338261/pakistan-to-continue-import-of-lng-from-qatar |accessdate=8 June 2017 |work=Dawn|location=Pakistan |date=8 June 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609040058/https://www.dawn.com/news/1338261/pakistan-to-continue-import-of-lng-from-qatar |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A six-member Qatari delegation headed by a special envoy of the Qatari Emir visited Pakistan and asked Pakistan to play a positive role in resolving the diplomatic crisis former, and the Prime Minister of Pakistan, [[Nawaz Sharif]], was quoted as saying that \"Pakistan would do 'all it can' to help resolve the crisis,\" as well as calling on the Muslim world to play a role in ending hostilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Siddiqui |first1=Dawn.com |title=Delegation headed by special envoy of Qatari Emir makes short visit to Pakistan |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1338268/delegation-headed-by-special-envoy-of-qatari-emir-makes-short-visit-to-pakistan |accessdate=8 June 2017 |work=Dawn|location=Pakistan |date=8 June 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003180039/https://www.dawn.com/news/1338268/delegation-headed-by-special-envoy-of-qatari-emir-makes-short-visit-to-pakistan |archivedate=3 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A [[Turkish Radio and Television Corporation|TRT]] report stated that Pakistan would deploy 20,000 troops in Qatar, which the Pakistani foreign ministry denied.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2017/06/11/Pakistan-denies-media-reports-of-troop-deployment-to-Qatar.html |title=Pakistan denies media reports of troop deployment to Qatar |accessdate=11 June 2017 |publisher=Al Arabiya Network |date=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003174927/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2017/06/11/Pakistan-denies-media-reports-of-troop-deployment-to-Qatar.html |archivedate=3 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Philippines suspended the deployment of migrant workers to Qatar on 6 June 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Philippines bans deployment of workers to Qatar |url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/manila/local-news/2017/06/06/philippines-bans-deployment-workers-qatar-545962 |accessdate=6 June 2017 |work=Sun Star Manila |agency=HDT, SunStar Philippines |date=6 June 2017}}</ref> However, the next day, they allowed the deployment of returning workers and those with an Overseas Employment Certificate, but still maintained the suspension of the deployment of new workers.<ref>{{cite news |title=PHL partially lifts suspension of OFW deployment to Qatar |publisher=GMA network |url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/pinoyabroad/613610/phl-partially-lifts-ban-on-ofw-deployment-to-qatar/story/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717145919/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/pinoyabroad/613610/phl-partially-lifts-ban-on-ofw-deployment-to-qatar/story/ |archivedate=17 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The suspension was later fully lifted on 15 June.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jaymalin |first1=Mayen |title=DOLE lifts suspension of OFW deployment in Qatar |url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2017/06/16/1710495/dole-lifts-suspension-ofw-deployment-qatar |accessdate=16 June 2017 |work=The Philippine Star |date=16 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615191514/http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2017/06/16/1710495/dole-lifts-suspension-ofw-deployment-qatar |archivedate=15 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 June 2017, Egypt's deputy [[United Nations|UN]] Ambassador Ihab Moustafa called for the [[United Nations Security Council]] to launch an investigation into accusations that Qatar \"paid up to $1 billion to a terrorist group active in Iraq\" to free 26 Qatari hostages, including members of its royal family, which payment would violate UN resolutions. The Qataris were kidnapped on 16 December 2015 from a desert camp for falcon hunters in [[southern Iraq]]. The hostages were released eighteen months later in April 2017. Qatari diplomats responded to the Egyptian calls for an investigation by reaffirming their commitment to the UN resolutions towards eliminating the financing of terrorism.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-un-idUSKBN18Z26W |title=Egypt calls for U.N. inquiry into accusation of Qatar ransom payment |date=8 June 2017 |agency=Reuters |access-date=8 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608222124/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-un-idUSKBN18Z26W |archivedate=8 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/latest-qatar-releases-initial-report-alleged-hack-47904088 |title=The Latest: Egypt seeks UN probe of alleged Qatar ransom |last=News |first=ABC |publisher=ABC News |access-date=8 June 2017 |language=en |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608042824/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/latest-qatar-releases-initial-report-alleged-hack-47904088 |archivedate=8 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, the government of Qatar hired American attorney and politician [[John Ashcroft]] to lobby on its behalf and help the state deny international allegations of supporting terror.<ref>{{cite web |title=Qatar, accused of supporting terrorism, hires ex-U.S. attorney general \u2013 Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-ashcroft-idUSKBN1910T6 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610181957/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-ashcroft-idUSKBN1910T6 |archivedate=10 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Singled Out by Trump, Qatar Hires Former Top U.S. Law Man \u2013 Bloomberg |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-10/singled-out-by-trump-qatar-hires-former-top-law-man-to-lobby |website=BloombergPolitics |accessdate=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610041552/https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-10/singled-out-by-trump-qatar-hires-former-top-law-man-to-lobby |archivedate=10 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Qatar blockade: Iran sends five planeloads of food \u2013 BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40237721 |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612040431/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40237721 |archivedate=12 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Qatar Hires Former U.S. Attorney General To Rebut Terrorism Allegations |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/qatar-hires-lawyer-boycott-terrorism-allegations-saudis-trump/28539933.html |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |accessdate=10 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610205539/https://www.rferl.org/a/qatar-hires-lawyer-boycott-terrorism-allegations-saudis-trump/28539933.html |archivedate=10 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 November 2017, deputy chief of Dubai Police Lieutenant General Dhahi Khalfan, blamed the [[2017 Sinai attack]] on Al-Jazeera's reporting and called for the bombing of Al-Jazeera's headquarters by the Saudi-led coalition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/11/dubai-security-chief-calls-bombing-al-jazeera-171125143439231.html|title=Dubai security chief calls for bombing of Al Jazeera|website=aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.farsnews.com/newstext.aspx?nn=13960905000275|title=Farsnews|website=en.farsnews.com}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n\n===Logistical implications===\n\nOn 6 June 2017, [[Emirates Post]] of UAE halted postal services to Qatar.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/emirates-post-group-halts-services-qatar-677207.html |title=Emirates Post Group halts services to Qatar |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609072905/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/emirates-post-group-halts-services-qatar-677207.html |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nNearly 80 percent of Qatar's food requirements come from Persian Gulf Arab neighbors, with only 1 percent being produced domestically and even imports from outside the Gulf states usually crossing the now closed land border with Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Adam |title=Analysis {{!}} Qatar could face a food crisis in spat with Arab neighbors|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/06/05/qatar-could-face-a-food-crisis-in-spat-with-arab-neighbors/|accessdate=7 June 2017|work=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606222639/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/06/05/qatar-could-face-a-food-crisis-in-spat-with-arab-neighbors/|archivedate=6 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Immediately after the cutting of relations, local reports indicated residents [[Panic buying|swarmed]] grocery stores in hopes of stockpiling food. Many food delivery trucks were idled along the Saudi-Qatari border. On 8 June 2017, Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh [[Mohammed bin Abdulrahman al-Thani]] said, \"We're not worried about a food shortage, we're fine. We can live forever like this, we are well prepared.\" {{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Qatar has been in talks with both Turkey and Iran to secure supply of food. On 11 June 2017, Iran sent four cargo planes with fruit and vegetables and promised to continue the supply.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-iran-idUSKBN1920EG?il=0 |title=Iran flies food to Qatar amid concerns of shortages |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=11 June 2017 |access-date=11 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003174716/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-iran-idUSKBN1920EG?il=0 |archivedate=3 October 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Turkey has pledged food and water supplies to go along with their troop deployment at their [[Turkish military]] base in Qatar.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nAs part of the Qatari government's response to lost food imports, it provided support to domestic agricultural company [[Baladna (company)|Baladna]], which built a new dairy farm with imported cattle that was planned to produce enough milk to fulfill domestic demand for dairy products by June 2018.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-cows/qatar-builds-dairy-industry-in-desert-as-it-defies-arab-boycott-idUSKBN1DT2E9 | title=Qatar builds dairy industry in desert as it defies Arab boycott | work=Reuters | date=29 November 2017 | accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>{{update inline|date=September 2018}}\n\n===Air travel===\nAll [[airlines]] based in these countries, including [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]], suspended flights to and from Qatar.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-05/saudi-led-alliance-cuts-qatar-ties-as-gulf-crisis-escalates |title=Flights Grounded as Gulf Split on Iran Leaves Qatar Isolated |last=Carey |first=Glen |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |access-date=5 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605041617/https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-06-05/saudi-led-alliance-cuts-qatar-ties-as-gulf-crisis-escalates |archive-date=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |last2=Fattah |first2=Zainab |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.emirates.com/ae/english/about/operational_updates/operational_updates.aspx#/#4258319 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606220356/https://www.emirates.com/ae/english/about/operational_updates/operational_updates.aspx |archivedate=6 June 2017 |title=Suspension of flights between Dubai and Doha with effect from 6 June 2017 |publisher=[[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] |date=5 June 2017}}</ref> [[Gulf Air]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Emirates, Etihad, Flydubai, Gulf Air and Air Arabia to suspend Qatar flights |url=http://gulfbusiness.com/abu-dhabis-etihad-suspend-flights-qatar-tuesday/ |first=Aarti |last=Nagraj |date=5 June 2017 |work=Gulf Business |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606032326/http://gulfbusiness.com/abu-dhabis-etihad-suspend-flights-qatar-tuesday/ |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[EgyptAir]],<ref>{{cite news |title=EgyptAir Suspends Flights to Qatar Until Special Notice |url=https://sputniknews.com/middleeast/201706051054314335-egyptair-suspends-flights-to-qatar/ |date=5 June 2017 |publisher=[[Sputniknews.com]] |language=en |accessdate=5 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702081250/https://sputniknews.com/middleeast/201706051054314335-egyptair-suspends-flights-to-qatar/ |archivedate=2 July 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[FlyDubai]], [[Air Arabia]], [[Saudi Arabian Airlines]] and [[Etihad Airways]] suspended their flights to and from Qatar.<ref name=\"aljazeera/5june2017\">{{cite news |title=Qatar diplomatic crisis: How it affects air travel|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/qatar-diplomatic-crisis-affects-air-travel-170605093547258.html|date=5 June 2017|agency=Al Jazeera|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref> Bahrain,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blog.flightradar24.com/blog/flight-ban-for-qatar-flights-in-uae-saudi-arabia-bahrain-and-egypt/|title=Flight Ban for Qatar Flights in UAE, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, and Egypt|date=5 June 2017|accessdate=5 June 2017|work=[[Flightradar24]]}}</ref> Egypt, Saudi Arabia, and the United Arab Emirates are also banning overflights by aircraft registered in Qatar (A7). Instead Qatar has rerouted flights to Africa and Europe via Iran,<ref name=auto1/> paying a \u201chefty\u201d overflight fee for each such flight.<ref name=veconomist>{{cite news|title=The boycott of Qatar is hurting its enforcers|url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21730426-if-saudis-and-emiratis-will-not-trade-doha-iranians-will-boycott|work=[[The Economist]]|date=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nQatar Airways in response also suspended its flight operations to Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Egypt, and Bahrain.<ref name=\"aljazeera/5june2017\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatarairways.com/us/en/travel-alerts.page|title=Travel Alerts {{!}} Qatar Airways|date=5 June 2017|website=Qatar Airways|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Pakistan International Airlines]] sent special flights to bring back over 200 Pakistani pilgrims stuck at [[Hamad International Airport|Doha airport]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Qatar row: Over 200 Pakistani pilgrims stuck at Doha airport \u2013 Pakistan \u2013 Dunya News|url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/391625-Qatar-row-Over-200-Pakistani-pilgrims-stuck-at-Do|accessdate=6 June 2017|work=dunyanews.tv}}</ref> Over 550 Pakistani pilgrims in Doha were subsequently flown to [[Muscat, Oman|Muscat]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Siddiqui|first=Naveed|title=550 Pakistani pilgrims stranded in Qatar flown to Muscat |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1337785/550-pakistani-pilgrims-stranded-in-qatar-flown-to-muscat |accessdate=6 June 2017 |work=Dawn|location=Pakistan|date=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrivate jet travel is also being impacted by the crisis. Business aviation officials said private flights between Qatar and the countries that cut diplomatic ties now need to make a technical stop in a third country. Aircraft registered in Qatar cannot fly to the countries that cut diplomatic ties and vice versa. While business jet operators can request a nonstop routing, two officials said requests so far have been turned down necessitating a stop in a third country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://privatejetcardcomparisons.com/2017/06/06/qatars-diplomatic-crisis-is-impacting-private-jets-too/|title=Private Jet Card Comparisons \u2013 Know Before You Buy Qatar's Diplomatic Crisis Is Impacting Private Jets Too|date=6 June 2017 |publisher=privatejetcardcomparisons.com|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nDue to the blockade of [[Qatar Airways]] from the airspace of Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Bahrain and Egypt, [[Oman Air]] has taken up a significant role transporting travelers from and to [[Doha]], mostly through Iranian airspace, while still allowing [[Qatari passport]] holders to book flights. The travel embargo has had a significant impact on foreign nationals living and working in Qatar, with about 100,000 Egyptians and citizens from other countries stranded there, unable to book direct flights or obtain travel documents for their return.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=D. Dudley|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dominicdudley/2017/06/08/oman-air-takes-advantage-of-qatar-crisis/|title=\"A Winner Emerges From The Qatar Crisis: Oman's National Airline\"|magazine=Forbes|date=14 June 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> Per request from Qatar, the blockade was under review by the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] (ICAO), a UN-agency seeking \"consensus-based solutions\" for the resolution of the crisis.\n\nOn 31 July 2017, the agency asserted its neutrality in the conflict and announced that Qatar Airways will have access to three contingency routes over international waters in early August based on a preliminary agreement reached with the Saudi aviation authority (GACA) early that month. The ICAO, based in [[Montreal]], also reminded all member countries to comply with the [[Chicago Convention on International Civil Aviation|1944 Chicago Convention on International Civil Aviation]] and its agenda.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/08/qatar-airways-expected-access-air-corridors-170801020434530.html|title=Qatar Airways expected to access new flight routes|agency=Al Jazeera News|date=31 July 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Shipping===\nThe United Arab Emirates banned Qatar-flagged ships from calling at [[Fujairah]]. It also banned vessels from Qatar from the port and vessels at the port from sailing directly to Qatar.<ref name=WMN221956>{{cite news|url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/221956/report-port-of-fujairah-bans-qatari-flagged-ships/|title=Report: Port of Fujairah Bans Qatari-Flagged Ships|publisher=World Maritime News|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Similar restrictions were put in place at [[Jebel Ali]], which pre-boycott used to handle over 85% of shipborne cargo for Qatar.<ref name=veconomist/> Bahrain, Egypt and Saudi Arabia also banned Qatar-flagged ships from their ports.<ref name=WMN222007>{{cite web|url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/222007/more-arab-ports-deny-calls-to-qatari-ships/|title=More Arab Ports Deny Calls to Qatari Ships|publisher=World Maritime News|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 June 2017 shipping giant [[Maersk Line|Maersk]] was unable to transport in or out of Qatar entirely. Due to Qatar's shallow ports, large cargo ships are required to dock at Jebel Ali or other nearby ports where a [[Feeder ship|feeder]] service transports the goods into Qatar.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saul|first=Jonathan|title=Maersk says unable to ship Qatar bound cargo from UAE, seeks alternatives|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-shipping-idUSKBN18X1YS|accessdate=8 June 2017|agency=Reuters|year=2017}}</ref> In response, Maersk and Swiss-based [[Mediterranean Shipping Company|MSC]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/hundreds-containers-qatar-oman-170612163855982.html|title=Hundreds of containers on their way to Qatar from Oman|agency=Al Jazeera News|date=12 June 2017|access-date=2 December 2017}}</ref> vessels for Qatar were rerouted to [[Salalah]] and [[Sohar]] in Oman.<ref name=BBC40248145>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-40248145|title=Qatar ships cargo via Oman to bypass Gulf restrictions|work=BBC News|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref> Particularly smaller shipments of perishable and frozen foods have taken that route.\n\nOn 12 June 2017, Chinese shipping company [[COSCO]] announced suspension of services to and from Qatar. Taiwan's [[Evergreen Marine]] and Hong Kong's [[Orient Overseas Container Line]] have already suspended services.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/region/qatar-crisis/chinese-shipping-firm-suspends-services-to-qatar |title=Chinese shipping firm suspends services to Qatar|agency=IANS|publisher=khaleejtimes.com|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Media ban===\nHamad Saif al-Shamsi, the Attorney-General of the [[United Arab Emirates]] announced on 7 June that publishing expressions of sympathy towards Qatar through [[social media]], or any type of written, visual or verbal form is [[Human rights in the United Arab Emirates#Freedom of speech|considered illegal]] under UAE's Federal Penal Code and the Federal law on Combating Information Technology Crimes. Violators of this offense face between 3 and 15 years imprisonment, a fine of up to 500,000 [[emirati dirham]]s ([[USD|$]]136,000) or both.<ref>{{cite news|title=UAE bans expressions of sympathy toward Qatar: media|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-idUSKBN18Y0DH|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref> Bahrain also issued a similar statement with a [[Human rights in Bahrain#Freedom of speech|penalty]] up to 5 years imprisonment and a fine.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/bahrain-and-uae-criminalize-sympathy-for-qatar/2017/06/08/ce74a666-4c70-11e7-9669-250d0b15f83b_story.html|title=Bahrain and UAE criminalize 'sympathy' for Qatar|first=Karen|last=DeYoung|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=8 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia, Egypt, Bahrain, and the UAE all blocked access to Qatari news agencies, including the controversial Qatar-based Al Jazeera.<ref>{{cite news|last=Youssef|first=Neveen|title=Qatar hacking row fuels Gulf tensions|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40046782|accessdate=7 June 2017|work=BBC News|date=25 May 2017}}</ref> Saudi Arabia shut down the local office of Al Jazeera Media Network.<ref name=\"aljazeera1/6june2017\">{{cite news |title=Qatar diplomatic crisis: All the latest updates|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/qatar-diplomatic-crisis-latest-updates-170605105550769.html|accessdate=6 June 2017|agency=Al Jazeera}}</ref> The [[BBC]] speculated that changes to Al-Jazeera would be a necessary part of any peaceful resolution.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40187414|title=Qatar crisis: Can Al Jazeera survive?|first=Kevin|last=Ponniah|date=7 June 2017|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe Qatar-based [[BeIN Sports (Middle East TV network)|beIN Sports]] channels (a spin-off of Al Jazeera) were also initially banned in June in the UAE.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/06/08/media/uae-qatar-media-blocked/index.html|title=Blocked in Dubai: Qatar cartoon and soccer channels|first=Zahraa|last=Alkhalisi|date=8 June 2017|agency=CNN|accessdate=13 August 2017}}</ref> The following month, the UAE restored normal access to beIN Sports channels via its local telecom providers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/uae-restores-qatar-bein-sports-network-air-170722144955060.html|title=UAE restores Qatar's BeIN sports network on air|date=23 July 2017|agency=[[Al Jazeera]]|accessdate=13 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/bein-sports-back-on-tv-in-the-uae-1.613012|title=BeIN Sports back on TV in the UAE|first1=Steven|last1=McCombe|first2=Roberta|last2=Pennington|date=22 July 2017|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|accessdate=13 August 2017}}</ref> In Saudi Arabia, the channels remain banned, while a large-scale [[pirate decryption]] operation known as \"[[beoutQ]]\" has made the channels' content available.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/analysis/world-cup-broadcasting-pirates-saudi-arabias-bein-sport-qatar|title=World Cup pirates: Saudi Arabia\u2019s BeIN action threatens future of international sports broadcasting|work=SportsPro|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/21/premier-league-games-screened-illegally-via-saudi-satellite-firm|title=Premier League games 'screened illegally via Saudi satellite firm'|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=2018-08-21|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/premier-league-piracy-beoutq-bein-saudi-arabia-qatar-ligue-1|title=BeoutQ illegally shows opening Premier League and Ligue 1 games|work=SportsPro|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/09/sports/bein-sports-qatar-beoutq.html |title=The Brazen Bootlegging of a Multibillion-Dollar Sports Network |first=Tariq |last=Panja |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 May 2018}}</ref> In 2018, in parallel with the diplomatic crisis and piracy issues, Saudi officials also began to accuse beIN Sports of having a [[monopoly]] position in sports broadcasting in the region, including revoking its broadcast licenses based on accusations of anti-competitive behaviour, and pulling its rights to the [[Asian Football Confederation]] in the Kingdom in 2019. beIN Sports has considered the moves to be politically-motivated,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://advanced-television.com/2018/08/23/saudis-ban-bein-sports/|title=Saudis ban beIN Sports|website=Advanced Television|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/afc-cancels-bein-sports-rights-saudi-arabia|title=AFC cancels BeIN Sports rights in Saudi Arabia|website=SportsPro Media|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/bein-sports-saudi-arabia-afc-legal-battle|title=BeIN Sports to launch AFC legal action|website=SportsPro Media|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref> and has accused beoutQ of operating from Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/beoutq-riyadh-al-jazeera-documentary-piracy|title=BeoutQ\u2019s Riyadh HQ revealed in Al Jazeera doc, says report|website=SportsPro Media|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref>\n\n===Finances===\n{{See also|Economy of Qatar}}\nThe [[International Monetary Fund]] said it was too soon to judge the economic impact of the diplomatic crisis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/gulf-qatar-imf-idUSL1N1J50UM|title=IMF says too soon to judge impact from Qatar, Gulf diplomatic dispute|date=8 June 2017|agency=Reuters|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref> [[Standard & Poor's]] downgraded Qatar's debt by one notch from AA to AA-.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/news/world/standard-and-poors-downgrades-qatar-debt-rating-20170607-gwmuyz|title=Standard and Poor's downgrades Qatar debt rating|date=8 June 2017|work=Financial Review|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref> Qatar's stock market dropped 7.3% on the first day of the crisis, and reached a 9.7% drop by 8 June 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/06/05/investing/qatar-stocks-plunge-gulf-diplomacy/index.html|title=Qatari stocks plunge 7% after Arab states cut ties|date=5 June 2017|agency=CNN|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref> Additionally, in the first months following the crisis the government of Qatar injected $38.5 billion, which was equivalent to 23% of the country's GDP, to support the country's economy and its banking sector.<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Martin|first1=Geoffrey|title=Everyone loses|journal=zenith|date=17 January 2019|url=https://magazine.zenith.me/en/business/other-lessons-qatar-crisis|}}</ref>\n\nAs per [[S&P Global]] Ratings, banks in Qatar are strong enough to survive a withdrawal of all Gulf country deposits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/qatar-banks-can-survive-gulf-foreign-funds-withdrawal-s-p-says--677427.html|title=Qatar banks can survive Gulf, foreign funds withdrawal, S&P says|work=Arabian Business|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nDespite the ongoing diplomatic blockade led by Saudi Arabia, international banks like [[HSBC]], [[Goldman Sachs]] and others are trying to repair their ties with Qatar by building stronger financial and business relations. Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates informally warned the bankers not to have close relations with Doha or else there would be consequences.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-17/bankers-are-sick-of-choosing-sides-between-qatar-and-saudi-arabia|title=Bankers Are Sick of Choosing Sides Between Qatar and Saudi Arabia|accessdate=17 February 2019|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2019, Sheikh [[Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani]] attended the opening session of the [[Economic and Social Council (Arab League)#2019 summit|Arab Economic Summit]] in Beirut, Lebanon. This helped Qatar increase its influence and soft power in the region. Sheikh Tamim Bin Hamad Al Thani and Mauritanian President [[Mohamed Ould Abdel Aziz]] were the only two Arab leaders to attend the summit. Since Sheikh Tamim was the only [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]] leader to attend, he received praise from the President of Lebanon himself, [[Michel Aoun]]. Hilal Khashan, a professor of political science at the [[American University of Beirut]], said \u201cHe became the star of the summit.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rose |first1=Sunniva |title=Lebanon fails to attract high-level turnout for Arab economic summit |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/lebanon-fails-to-attract-high-level-turnout-for-arab-economic-summit-1.815757 |website=The National}}</ref>\n\n===Energy===\nQatar is a global [[List of countries by natural gas production|leader]] in [[liquefied natural gas]] production. Despite the severing of ties, Qatari natural gas continues to flow to the [[United Arab Emirates|UAE]] and [[Oman]] through [[Abu Dhabi]] based [[Dolphin Energy]]'s [[Dolphin Gas Project|pipeline]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Law|first=Bill|date=14 November 2017|title=Qatar Rides Out the Blockade|url=http://www.indrastra.com/2017/11/Qatar-Rides-Out-Blockade-003-11-2017-0006.html|journal=IndraStra Global|publication-place=New York, USA|publication-date=9 November 2017|volume=003|issue=11|pages=0006|issn=2381-3652}}</ref> The pipeline meets about 30\u201340 percent of UAE's energy needs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/06/07/news/qatar-uae-gas-pipeline/index.html |title=Qatar keeps gas flowing to UAE despite blockade|last=Alkhalisi|first=Zahraa|date=7 June 2017|website=CNNMoney|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref> Shipping constraints from the crisis have also rerouted multiple shipments of oil and gas to and from the Gulf, which has caused reverberations in many local energy markets. \nOn 8 June 2017, gas futures spiked nearly 4 percent in the United Kingdom, which had nearly a third of all its imported gas arriving from Qatar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/08/qatar-fight-finally-spills-into-global-energy-market.html|title=Qatar fight finally spills into global energy market|last=Domm|first=Patti|date=8 June 2017|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref> A secondary effect of the dispute has been on worldwide supplies of [[helium]], which is often extracted from natural gas. Qatar is the world's second largest supplier of helium (the US ranks first).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2017/06/26/middle-east-turmoil-is-disrupting-a-vital-resource-for-nuclear-energy-space-flight-and-birthday-balloons|title=Middle East turmoil is disrupting a vital resource for nuclear energy, space flight and birthday balloons|date=26 June 2017|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Qatar lodged a complaint to [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] regarding the United Arab Emirates [[Barakah nuclear power plant]], stating that it poses a serious threat to regional stability and the environment. The UAE denied that there are safety issues with the plant, which is being built by [[Korea Electric Power Corporation]] (KEPCO) with operation by French utility [[\u00c9lectricit\u00e9 de France]], and stated \u201cThe United Arab Emirates ... adheres to its commitment to the highest standards of nuclear safety, security and non-proliferation.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL8N2175GH|title=Qatar says UAE nuclear plant is threat to regional stability|work=Reuters|last1=De Clercq|first1=Geert|date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===23rd Gulf Cup===\nThe [[23rd Arabian Gulf Cup]] was scheduled to be hosted in Qatar.  In November 2017, [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]], [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]], and [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] pulled out of the Gulf Cup due to the Qatar boycott.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Editorial|first1=Reuters|title=Saudi, UAE, Bahrain to miss Qatar's Gulf Cup amid rift|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-gulf-qatar-football/saudi-uae-bahrain-to-miss-qatars-gulf-cup-amid-rift-idUKKBN1DH267|website=U.K.}}</ref> On 7 December 2017, it was announced that [[Kuwait]] will host the football tournament after [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]], United Arab Emirates, and [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] all withdrew because of the diplomatic crisis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1205581/sports|title=Gulf Cup to return to Kuwait following lifting of FIFA ban|date=2017-12-08|work=Arab News|access-date=2018-06-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Qatari military relations===\n[[File:Refueling the fight against terrorism 170103-F-XF291-0016.jpg|thumb|[[Al Udeid Air Base]] in Qatar]]\nOn 7 June 2017, the Turkish parliament passed, with 240 votes in favour and 98 against, a legislative act first drafted in May allowing Turkish troops to be deployed to a Turkish military base in Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/turkey-fast-track-troops-deployment-qatar-170607151127104.html |title=Turkish parliament approves troop deployment to Qatar |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=8 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611231348/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/turkey-fast-track-troops-deployment-qatar-170607151127104.html |archivedate=11 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2017/06/09/turk-j09.html |title=Turkey prepares to send troops to Qatar in conflict with Saudi Arabia |publisher=World Socialist Web Site |date=9 June 2017 |author=Halil Celik and Alex Lantier |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609064129/https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2017/06/09/turk-j09.html |archivedate=9 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>  During a speech on 13 June 2017, the [[President of Turkey]], [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], condemned the boycott of Qatar as \"inhumane and against Islamic values\" and stated that \"victimising Qatar through smear campaigns serves no purpose\".<ref name=\"TurkeyBBC\">{{cite news |title=Turkey's Erdogan decries Qatar's 'inhumane' isolation |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40261479 |accessdate=14 June 2017 |publisher=BBC |date=13 June 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613185712/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-40261479 |archivedate=13 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 23 June 2017, Turkey rejected demands to shut down its military base in Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schreck |first1=Adam |last2=Lederman |first2=Josh |title=Turkey rejects Gulf Arab states' demands over its Qatar base |url=https://apnews.com/9a12e8024ac245f3b31bdb67c68a9b67/Turkey-rejects-Gulf-Arab-states'-demands-over-its-Qatar-base |accessdate=23 June 2017 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=23 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nQatar hosts about 10,000 US troops at Al Udeid Air Base, which houses the forward operating base of [[United States Central Command]] that plays a commanding role in US [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|airstrikes in Syria]], Iraq, and Afghanistan.<ref name=ABC>{{cite news |publisher=ABC News |title=Trump sides with Saudis, other Arab nations against Qatar |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/trump-arab-leaders-complained-qatar-47861002 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612005732/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/trump-arab-leaders-complained-qatar-47861002 |archivedate=12 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"WaPo 6 June\">{{cite news |title=The Latest: Trump says Qatar dispute could end terror |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/the-latest-trump-says-qatar-dispute-could-end-terror/2017/06/06/4ccabb7c-4ac8-11e7-987c-42ab5745db2e_story.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606200453/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/the-latest-trump-says-qatar-dispute-could-end-terror/2017/06/06/4ccabb7c-4ac8-11e7-987c-42ab5745db2e_story.html |archivedate=6 June 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/world/1475326-trump-sides-with-saudis-other-arab-nations-against-qatar |title=Siding against ally Qatar, Trump injects US into Arab crisis |date=6 June 2017 |accessdate=6 June 2017 |website=[[The Chronicle Herald]]|agency=[[The Canadian Press]] }}</ref> A Pentagon spokesperson claimed the diplomatic crisis would not affect the US military posture in Qatar.<ref name=\"WaPo 6 June\" /><ref name=credit />\n\nOn the 10th and 11 November 2018, the [[Italian Air Force]] along with the [[Qatar Air Force|Qatari Display Team]], perform an airshow at the corniche that confirms the bonds of friendship between [[Italy]] and [[Qatar]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Doha Airshow 2018: Italian Air Force and Qatar Display Team |url=https://ambdoha.esteri.it/ambasciata_doha/en/ambasciata/news/dall_ambasciata/2018/11/doha-airshow-2018-frecce-tricolori.html |website=Ambasciata d'Italia Doha |publisher=Ambasciata d'Italia Doha}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January 2018 an inaugural United States-Qatar Strategic Dialogue meeting was held, co-chaired by U.S. Secretary of State Rex Tillerson, U.S. Secretary of Defense [[Jim Mattis]], Qatari Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of State for Defence Affairs<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gco.gov.qa/en/ministries/minister-of-state-for-defence-affairs/|title=Minister of State for Defence Affairs|website=Government Communications Office|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref> [[Khalid al-Attiyah]] and Qatari Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister [[Mohammed bin Abdulrahman Al Thani]]. The meeting expressed the need for an immediate resolution of the crisis which respects Qatar's sovereignty. In a Joint Declaration on Security Cooperation, the United States expressed its readiness to deter and confront any external threat to Qatar's territorial integrity. Qatar offered to help fund the expansion of facilities at US bases in Qatar.<ref name=atlantic-20180131>{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/01/qatar-us/551873/ |title=America Wins the Gulf Crisis |last=Calamur |first=Krishnadev |newspaper=The Atlantic |date=31 January 2018 |accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=state-20180130>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2018/01/277776.htm |title=Joint Statement of the Inaugural United States-Qatar Strategic Dialogue |publisher=U.S. Department of State |date=30 January 2018 |accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March 2018, the [[United States Central Command]] (CENTCOM) officially denied rumours that the [[Incirlik Air Base]] in Turkey and the Al Udeid Air Base in Qatar will be closed due to the ongoing regional conflict.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/03/denies-leaving-air-bases-turkey-qatar-180326073201309.html \"US denies leaving air bases in Turkey and Qatar\"]. ''Aljazeera News/Turkey''. Retrieved 26 March 2018.</ref>\n\n[[File:Combined Air and Space Operations Center 151007-F-MS415-015.jpg|thumb|Combined [[Air and Space Operations Center]] (CAOC) in Qatar provides command and control of air power throughout [[Iraq]], [[Syria]], [[Afghanistan]], and 17 other nations.]]\nOn January 2018, Qatar's ambassador was in talks with Russia with the intent to purchase [[S-400 missile system|S-400 surface-to-air missile]]s. Both countries signed an agreement on military and technical cooperation in 2017. In May 2018, the French daily newspaper ''Le Monde'' reported that King [[Salman of Saudi Arabia]] would take military action if Qatar installed the Russian air defence system. However, a senior Russian official remarked the system would still be delivered even against the will of Saudi Arabia.<ref>[https://in.reuters.com/article/saudi-qatar-france/saudi-arabia-threatens-military-action-if-qatar-deploys-anti-aircraft-missiles-report-idINKCN1IY0IJ \"Saudi Arabia threatens military action if Qatar deploys anti-aircraft missiles - report]\". ''Reuters''. Retrieved 2 June 2018.</ref> The Saudis were themselves approaching Russia to improve economic and military ties in 2017, but talks relating to the arms deal were hindered by concerns the United States and Saudi Arabia had with regard to the Russian position towards Iran's military and strategic involvement in the Middle East.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/06/russia-supply-400-system-qatar-saudi-position-180602195629315.html Russia 'to supply S-400 system to Qatar' despite Saudi position]. ''Al Jazeera News''. Retrieved 2 June 2018.</ref>\n\nOn June 2018, Qatar expressed its wish to join [[NATO]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/05/06/2018/Qatar-eyes-full-NATO-membership-Defense-minister|title=Qatar eyes full NATO membership: Defense minister|work=The Peninsula|date=5 June 2018}}</ref> However, NATO declined membership, stating that only additional European countries could join according to [[Enlargement of NATO#Article 10|Article 10 of NATO's founding treaty]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/world/2018/06/06/qatar-says-it-wants-to-join-nato|title=Nato rejects Qatar membership ambition|newspaper=Dhaka Tribune|date=6 June 2018}}</ref> Qatar and NATO have previously signed a security agreement together in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_150794.htm|title=Qatar signs security agreement with NATO|publisher=NATO|date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 September 2018, Qatar finalised a deal to purchase [[Eurofighter Typhoon]] and [[BAE Hawk]] aircraft in a deal reported as being worth \u00a35Bn.<ref>[https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-bae-systems-qatar/bae-systems-finalises-deal-to-sell-typhoon-jets-to-qatar-idUKKCN1LY261 BAE Systems finalises deal to sell Typhoon jets to Qatar]. ''Reuters''. Retrieved 18 September 2018.</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, as Qatar completed two years under the diplomatic embargo, the country received its first five of the 36 purchased [[Dassault Rafale|Rafale]] fighter jets from [[France]]. The first aircraft was formally handed to Qatar in February 2019, but was kept in France itself before being delivered on 5 June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190605-under-embargo-qatar-takes-delivery-first-rafale-jets|title=Under embargo Qatar takes delivery of first Rafale jets|work=France 24|accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Arab League Council 2017===\nDuring the 148th Session of the Arab League Council at the level of Foreign Ministers which was held in Cairo, Qatar\u2019s State Minister for Foreign Affairs, Sultan Al Muraikhi, got into a heated argument with Saudi delegate Ahmad Al Qattan. Al Muraikhi said: \"Ahmad Al Qattan's tone was very threatening and I don't think he is capable of being responsible for his words.\" Ahmad Al Qattan interrupted Al Muraikhi, and said \u201cNo I am capable.\u201d Things escalated when Al Muraikhi said \u201cWhen I speak, you stay quiet.\u201d Al Qattan replied, \u201cNo you stay quiet.\u201d The Iraqi delegate tried to be the mediator in this back and forth argument. The ministers of the three blockading countries of the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain and Egypt had their say by backing Ahmad Al Qattan. This was all caused after Al Muraikhi gave a short speech about how Qatar had to go back to supporting Iran after it cut its ties to support Saudi Arabia. He adds that Saudi Arabia brought in a person from the Qatari royal family and made him look like he was the future ruler of Qatar. The argument continued for around forty minutes.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thrar |first1=Abdulrahim |title=\u0641\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0648.. \u0645\u0646\u062f\u0648\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u064a\u0647\u062f\u062f.. \u0648\u0645\u0646\u062f\u0648\u0628 \u0642\u0637\u0631 \u064a\u0631\u062f: \"\u0645\u0646\u062a \u0628\u0642\u062f\u0647\u0627\" |url=https://www.al-sharq.com/article/12/09/2017/%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%88-%D9%85%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%B9%D9%88%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D9%8A%D9%87%D8%AF%D8%AF-%D9%88%D9%85%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%A8-%D9%82%D8%B7%D8%B1-%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%AF-%D9%85%D9%86%D8%AA-%D8%A8%D9%82%D8%AF%D9%87%D8%A7 |website=Al Sharq}}</ref>\n\n===2019 Asian Cup===\nDuring the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage#Qatar vs United Arab Emirates|semi-final match]] between the [[Qatar national football team]] and the tournament hosts the United Arab Emirates, the UAE supporters [[Shoe tossing#Insult|threw shoes]] and bottles onto the pitch. This conduct was preceded by booing the [[As-Salam al-Amiri|Qatari national anthem]]. Qatar won 4\u20130, paving the way to their first Asian Cup final and eventual title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Qatar 4-0 United Arab Emirates|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/47049246|accessdate=1 February 2019 |publisher=BBC |date=29 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Watch: Fans throw shoes at the Qatar players after Almoez Ali scores their second goal against the UAE in the AFC Asian Cup 2019|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/asian-football/afc-asian-cup/1031989/watch-fans-throw-shoes-at-the-qatar-players-after-almoez-ali-scores-their-second-goal-against-the-uae-in-the-afc-asian-cup-2019/ |author=Aditya |work=Fox Sports Asia |date=29 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Shoes and Insults Flying, Qatar Beats U.A.E. and Advances to Asian Cup Final |date=29 January 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/29/sports/qatar-uae-boycott-asian-cup.html|agency=Associated Press |accessdate=1 February 2019 |newspaper= The New York Times }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Asian Cup: Qatar pelted with shoes by hostile UAE fans as they thrash hosts 4-0 to reach final |accessdate=1 February 2019 |url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/football/article/2184193/asian-cup-uae-fans-pelt-qatar-players-shoes-hosts-are-thrashed-4-0|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=30 January 2019|agency= Agence France-Presse}}</ref>\n\nA British-Sudanese football fan was allegedly beaten by fans for wearing a Qatar football shirt to a match in which Qatar was playing and then, after investigation by the UAE police, arrested for [[wasting police time]] and making [[False statement#In Law|false statements]] of being assaulted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47135629|title=Briton held in UAE in football shirt row|website=Bbc.com|date=2019-02-06|access-date=2019-02-06|language=en-GB}}</ref> According to ''The Guardian'', the fan was arrested for wearing a Qatar football shirt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/05/british-man-detained-in-uae-after-wearing-qatar-football-t-shirt-to-match|title=British man detained in UAE after wearing Qatar football shirt to match|first=Diane|last=Taylor|date=5 February 2019|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2019|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=\"indy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/uae-football-fan-qatar-shirt-arrest-detained-ali-issa-ahmad-police-a8764366.html|title=UK football fan held in United Arab Emirates 'for wearing Qatar shirt to match'|date=5 February 2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gu-friends\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/06/friends-of-uk-football-fan-detained-in-uae-call-for-his-release-qatar|title=UAE officials suggest detained UK football fan beat himself up|first=Diane|last=Taylor|date=6 February 2019|accessdate=6 February 2019|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> The claim was denied by UAE authorities who stated the fan was arrested for wasting police time and making false assault claims to the police. The UAE police said that the fan had admitted to making false statements. A UAE official in London stated \u201cHe was categorically not arrested for wearing a Qatar football shirt. This is instead an instance of a person seeking media attention and wasting police time.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-emirates-britain-arrests/uae-denies-british-man-detained-for-showing-qatar-support-idUSKCN1PV0F5|title=UAE denies British man detained for showing Qatar support|date=5 February 2019|work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11629525/uae-denies-arresting-british-national-for-wearing-qatar-shirt|title=UAE denies arresting British national for wearing Qatar shirt|publisher=Sky Sports|date=6 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"indy\"/><ref name=\"gu-friends\"/> According to photos shown by ''The National'', fans were seen waving the Qatari flag and wearing Qatari football shirts without any instances of arrests in the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup Final|final]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/british-football-fan-arrested-for-misleading-uae-police-1.822499#2|title=British football fan arrested for misleading UAE police|work=The National|date=6 February 2019}}</ref> According to ''[[The New York Times]]'', the UAE accuses Qatar of fielding ineligible players due to them being not originally Qatari. The players accused were the competitions' top scorer [[Almoez Ali]], a Sudan born striker, as well as [[Bassam Al-Rawi]], an Iraq born defender.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Panja |first1=Tariq |title=U.A.E. Accuses Qatar of Fielding Ineligible Players at Asian Cup |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/31/sports/soccer/qatar-uae-asian-cup.html |work=The New York Times |date=31 January 2019 |accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Demands on Qatar and responses==\nOn 22 June 2017, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Egypt and Bahrain issued Qatar a list of 13 demands through Kuwait, which is acting as a mediator, that Qatar should agree in full within 10 days, which expired on 2 July 2017. According to reports on 23 June, these demands included:<ref name=\"reuters.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-gulf-qatar-demands-idUSKBN19E0BB|title=Arab states issue ultimatum to Qatar: close Jazeera, curb ties with Iran|date=23 June 2017|agency=Reuters|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|title=Qatar given 10 days to meet 13 sweeping demands by Saudi Arabia|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/23/close-al-jazeera-saudi-arabia-issues-qatar-with-13-demands-to-end-blockade|accessdate=24 June 2017|work=The Guardian|date=23 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=auto8/>\n\n*Closing [[Al-Jazeera]] and its affiliate stations.\n*Closing other news outlets that Qatar funds, directly and indirectly, including Arabi21, [[Rassd News Network (RNN)|Rassd]], [[Al-Araby Al-Jadeed]] and [[Middle East Eye]].\n*Closing the Turkish military base in Qatar, and terminate the Turkish military presence and any joint military cooperation with Turkey inside Qatar.\n*Reducing diplomatic relations with Iran. Only trade and commerce with Iran that complies with US and international sanctions will be permitted.<ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/qatar/qatar-crisis/what-are-the-13-demands-given-to-qatar-1.2048118|title=What are the 13 demands given to Qatar?|last=AP|date=23 June 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> \n*Expelling any members of the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC) and cutting off military and intelligence cooperation with Iran.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/06/arab-states-issue-list-demands-qatar-crisis-170623022133024.html|title=Arab states issue list of demands to end Qatar crisis|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=11 July 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n*\"Qatar must announce it is severing ties with terrorist, ideological and sectarian organizations including the Muslim Brotherhood, [[Hamas]], the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL), [[Al-Qaeda]], [[Hezbollah]], and [[al-Nusra Front|Jabhat Fateh al Sham]], formerly al Qaeda's branch in Syria\" according to one Arab official.\n*Surrendering all designated terrorists in Qatar, and stopping all means of funding for individuals, groups or organisations that have been designated as terrorists.\n*Ending interference in the four countries' domestic and foreign affairs and having contact with their political oppositions.\n*Stopping granting citizenship to wanted nationals from Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Egypt and Bahrain.\n*Revoking Qatari citizenship for existing nationals where such citizenship violates those countries' laws.<ref name=\"auto9\" />\n*The payment of reparations for years of alleged wrongs.\n*Monitoring for 10 years.<ref name=\"reuters.com\"/>\n*Aligning itself with the other Gulf and Arab countries militarily, politically, socially and economically, as well as on economic matters, in line with an agreement reached with Saudi Arabia in 2014.<ref name=auto9/>\n\nAccording to a report by the Qatar-owned Al-Jazeera, \"Qatari officials immediately dismissed the document as neither reasonable or actionable.\" Iran denounced the blockade. US Secretary of State Rex Tillerson said that some of the demands would be very hard to meet but encouraged further dialogue.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2017/06/iran-hassan-rouhani-condemns-siege-qatar-170625174347048.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=30 June 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629232954/http://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2017/06/iran-hassan-rouhani-condemns-siege-qatar-170625174347048.html|archivedate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July, Saudi Arabia accepted a Kuwaiti request for the deadline to be extended by 48 hours.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi-bloc gives Qatar 48 more hours to accept demands|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/qatar-formally-respond-saudi-led-list-monday-170702202036876.html|accessdate=2 December 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=3 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 July, foreign ministers from Egypt, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates and Bahrain met in Cairo after receiving a response from Qatar to their list of demands. The meeting aimed to resolve the dispute ended in a stalemate when Saudi foreign minister Adel al-Jubeir said that the political and economic boycott of Qatar will remain until it changes its policies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/07/saudi-led-group-qatar-demands-170705144209453.html|title=Saudi-led group: Qatar not serious about demands|agency=Al Jazeera|date=6 July 2017|accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> Also on the same day, the Saudi-led bloc said it no longer insisting it to comply with its 13 specific demands they tabled last month. Instead, it asked Qatar to accept six broad principles, which includes commitments to combat terrorism, extremism, to end acts of provocation, and incitement.<ref name=\"auto6\"/>\n\nHowever, by 30 July 2017, the 13 demands had been reinstated.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Feteha|first1=Ahmed|last2=MacDonald|first2=Fiona|last3=El-Tablawy|first3=Tarek|title=Qatar Crisis Is Back to Square One as Economy Shows the Strain |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-30/saudi-bloc-ministers-meet-to-discuss-next-step-in-qatar-crisis|accessdate=8 September 2017|agency=Bloomberg|date=31 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[International propagation of Salafism and Wahhabism]]\n*{{section link|State-sponsored terrorism|Saudi Arabia}}\n*[[OPEC]]\n*[[Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of Qatar}}\n{{Portal bar|Saudi Arabia|United Arab Emirates|Bahrain|Egypt}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2017-18 Qatar diplomatic crisis}}\n[[Category:2017 in international relations|Qatar diplomatic crisis]]\n[[Category:2017 in Qatar|Diplomatic crisis]]\n[[Category:2018 in international relations|Qatar diplomatic crisis]]\n[[Category:2018 in Qatar|Diplomatic crisis]]\n[[Category:Arab Winter by country]]\n[[Category:Bahrain\u2013Qatar relations]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic incidents]]\n[[Category:Egypt\u2013Qatar relations]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Qatar]]\n[[Category:June 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:July 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:August 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:September 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:October 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:November 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:December 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:January 2018 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Politics of Qatar]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Arab world]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Qatar\u2013Saudi Arabia relations]]\n[[Category:Qatar\u2013United Arab Emirates relations]]\n[[Category:Censorship in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Bahrain]]\n[[Category:Censorship in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]]\n[[Category:Ongoing conflicts]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "date format audit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qatar_diplomatic_crisis"}
{"title_page": "Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n[[File:Kutupalong Refugee Camp (John Owens-VOA).jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Kutupalong Refugee Camp]] in Bangladesh.]]\n\n'''Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh''' mostly refer to Forcibly Displaced Myanmar Nationals (FDMNs) from Myanmar who are living in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rohingya exodus to Bangladesh nears 300,000|url=http://www.muslimglobal.com/2017/09/rohingya-exodus-to-bangladesh-nears.html|accessdate=9 September 2017|publisher=Muslim Global}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-38799586|title=Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh face relocation to island|date=30 January 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> The Rohingya people have experienced ethnic and religious persecution in Myanmar for decades. Hundreds of thousands have fled to other countries in Southeast Asia, including Malaysia, Indonesia, and Philippines.<ref name=\":14\">[http://www.foxnews.com/world/2018/09/27/bangladesh-point-finger-at-myanmar-for-rohingya-genocide.html Bangladesh point finger at Myanmar for Rohingya 'genocide']</ref> The majority have escaped to Bangladesh, where there are two official, registered refugee camps. Recently violence in Myanmar has escalated, so the number of refugees in Bangladesh has increased rapidly. According to the UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR), more than 723,000 Rohingya have fled to Bangladesh since 25 August 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/uae-press-we-must-resolve-to-aid-all-refugees-2017-12-27-1.663327|title=UAE Press: We must resolve to aid all refugees|last=WAM|date=27 December 2017|work=Emirates 24{{!}}7|access-date=28 December 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/rohingya-crisis-myanmar-court-extends-detention-of-two-journalists201712280538520001/|title=Rohingya crisis: Myanmar Court extends detention of two journalists|website=www.aninews.in|language=en|access-date=28 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/bangladesh/bangladesh-humanitarian-situation-report-no16-rohingya-influx-24-december-2017|title=Bangladesh: Humanitarian Situation report No.16 (Rohingya influx) 24 December 2017|work=ReliefWeb|access-date=28 December 2017|language=en}}</ref> \n\nOn 28 September 2018, at the 73rd United Nations General Assembly, Bangladeshi Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasina]] said there are 1.1 million Rohingya refugees now in Bangladesh.<ref name=\":14\" /> Overcrowding from the recent population boom at Bangladesh's Rohingya refugee camps has placed a strain on its infrastructure. The refugees lack access to services, education, food, clean water, and proper sanitation; they are also vulnerable to natural disasters and infectious disease transmission.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":8\" /> As of June 2018 [[World Bank]] announced nearly half a billion dollars in monetary support to help Bangladesh address Rohingya refugees' needs in areas including health, education, water and sanitation, disaster risk management, and social protection.<ref>{{cite web|author=\u5f20\u9510 |url=http://www.china.org.cn/world/2018-06/29/content_53991750.htm |title=World Bank announces nearly half-a-bln USD support for Bangladesh to help Rohingya |publisher=China.org.cn |date=29 June 2018 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> On 1 March 2019 Bangladesh announced that it would no longer accept Rohingya refugees.<ref name=\"urlRohingya crisis: Bangladesh will no longer take in Myanmar refugees - BBC News\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-47412704 |title=Rohingya crisis: Bangladesh will no longer take in Myanmar refugees - BBC News |format= |work= BBC News|accessdate=|date=March 2019 }}</ref> An August 2018 study estimated that more than 24,000 Rohingya were killed by the Myanmar military and local Buddhists militia since the \"clearance operations\" started on 25 August 2017. It also estimated that at least 18,000 Rohingya Muslim women and girls were raped, 116,000 Rohingya were beaten, and 36,000 Rohingya were thrown into fires set alight in an act of deliberate arson.<ref name=\"oida\">{{Cite web|url=https://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/7857480|title=Forced migration of Rohingya: the untold experience|first1=Mohshin|last1=Habib|first2=Christine|last2=Jubb|first3=Salahuddin|last3=Ahmad|first4=Masudur|last4=Rahman|first5=Henri|last5=Pallard|date=July 18, 2018|publisher=Ontario International Development Agency, Canada|via=National Library of Australia (new catalog)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/07/chief-bangladesh-continue-hosting-rohingya-190710191318011.html|title=Former UN chief says Bangladesh cannot continue hosting Rohingya|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/rohingya-crisis/news/dutch-house-representatives-adopts-motion-probe-rohingya-genocide-1767124|title=Dutch House of Representatives adopts motion for probe on Rohingya genocide|date=July 5, 2019|website=The Daily Star}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefrontierpost.com/bangladeshi-pm-calls-for-safe-repatriation-of-rohingya/|title=Bangladeshi PM calls for safe repatriation of Rohingya|date=April 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.transcend.org/tms/2019/02/un-official-cites-horrific-crimes-against-rohingya/|title=UN Official Cites Horrific Crimes against Rohingya|website=TRANSCEND Media Service}}</ref><ref>https://www.researchgate.net/publication/333118905_Prevalence_of_violence_against_children_Evidence_from_2017_Rohingya_Refugee_crises</ref>\n\n== History ==\nRohingyas are a [[Muslim]] minority in Myanmar regarded by many [[Buddhism in Myanmar|Myanmar Buddhist]]s as illegal migrants from Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/burma-rohingya-muslim-refugees-bangladesh-aung-san-suu-kyi-a7554756.html|title=Bangladesh wants to move Muslim refugees to an island to stop them 'mingling' with citizens|date=31 January 2017|work=The Independent|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> The Rohingyas have lived in Myanmar for generations and the Bangladesh government has called for Myanmar to take back the refugees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/bangladesh-pm-asks-myanmar-to-take-back-rohingya-refugees/3431864.html|title=Bangladesh PM asks Myanmar to take back Rohingya refugees|work=Channel NewsAsia|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> They are denied citizenship in Myanmar and have been described as the world's most persecuted minority.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/world/2017/01/31/rohingya-refugees-bangladesh-relocated-remote-inhospitable-island/Blxwtb4cSK6L7sKX2ilfHL/story.html|title=Rohingya Refugees in Bangladesh to Be Relocated to Remote, Inhospitable Island - The Boston Globe|work=BostonGlobe.com|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/bangladesh/2017-02-23/trouble-thengar-char|title=The Trouble With Thengar Char|last=Kullab|first=Samya|date=23 February 2017|work=Foreign Affairs|accessdate=20 March 2017|issn=0015-7120}}</ref> Myanmar has denied persecuting the Rohingyas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.whig.com/article/20170228/AP/302289886|title=Myanmar army: Charges of abuse of Rohingya unsubstantiated|work=Herald-Whig|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rohingya displaced Muslims 010.jpg|thumb|Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh in October 2017]]\nSince the 1970s Rohingya refugees have been coming to Bangladesh from Myanmar . In the 1990s, more than 250,000 resided in refugees camps in Bangladesh. In the early 2000s, all but 20,000 of them were repatriated to Myanmar, some against their will.<ref>Thompson, Larry (2005), \"Bangladesh: Burmese Rohingya refugees virtual hostages,\" https://reliefweb.int/report/myanmar/bangladesh-burmese-rohingya-refugees-virtual-hostages, accessed 6 October 2017</ref> This respite ended in 2015 and by 2017, an estimated 300,000 to 500,000 Rohingya refugees were in Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/rohingya-crisis-security-tightened-along-india-myanmar-border/articleshow/60526163.cms|title=Rohingya crisis: Security tightened along India-Myanmar border|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915082041/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/rohingya-crisis-security-tightened-along-india-myanmar-border/articleshow/60526163.cms|archivedate=15 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Most of the refugees are located along the [[Teknaf-Cox's Bazar highway]] that is parallel to the [[Naf River]], which is the border between Bangladesh and Myanmar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/03/fight-survive-rohingya-refugees-bangladesh-170313091106782.html|title=A fight to survive for Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh|last=|first=|date=|website=aljazeera.com|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref> Most of the refugees are located in or near [[Cox's Bazar]], a coastal area dependent upon tourism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-rohingya-bangladesh-idUSKBN15F0NS|title=Bangladesh resurrects plan to move Rohingya refugees to flooded island|date=31 January 2017|work=Reuters|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh blamed the refugees for crime and [[2012 Ramu violence]] in Cox's Bazar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/10/refugees-and-neighbors-rohingya-in-bangladesh/|title=Refugees and Neighbors: Rohingya in Bangladesh|last=Diplomat|first=Sumit Ganguly and Brandon Miliate , The|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Bangladesh also follows a policy of making the country unwelcome for Rohingya refugees.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21659769-oppressed-myanmar-muslim-rohingyas-are-unwelcome-bangladesh-too-exile-island|title=Exile island|website=The Economist|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref> The majority of the refugees are unregistered, with only 32 thousand refugees registering themselves with UNHCR and the Bangladeshi government. An estimated 200,000+ refugees are living unregistered in Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/28/bangladesh-plans-to-move-rohingya-refugees-to-island-in-the-south|title=Bangladesh plans to move Rohingya refugees to island in the south|last=France-Presse|first=Agence|date=27 May 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Amnesty International reports have stated that the Myanmar security forces are committing rape, extrajudicial killing, and burning homes belonging to the Rohingya in a December 2016 report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.voanews.com/a/rohingya-refugees-in-bangladesh-vow-never-return-to-myanmar/3658693.html|title=Rohingya Refugees in Bangladesh Vow Never to Return to Myanmar|last=Hussain|first=Maaz|work=VOA|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> Refugees have been displacing the indigenous people of the [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/rights-group-accuses-bangladesh-of-ethnic-cleansing-pushing-buddhists-out-with-rohingya-refugees-from-myanmar/story-VyqvLP2rE5AzM0KG7ibgzJ.html|title=Rights group accuses Bangladesh of ethnic cleansing, pushing Buddhists out with Rohingya refugees from Myanmar|last=|first=|date=20 February 2017|work=hindustantimes.com/|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> They have also been blamed for importing the narcotic drug [[Ya ba|Ya Ba]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2017/03/03/bangladesh-ban-cold-pill-chemical-fight-meth-surge/|title=Bangladesh to ban cold pill chemical to fight meth surge |date=3 March 2017|work=Dhaka Tribune|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/02/28/myanmar-rohingya-refugees-sucked-into-booming-bangladesh-drug-trade|title=Myanmar Rohingya refugees sucked into booming Bangladesh drug trade|work=bdnews24.com|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/crime/2017/03/19/myanmar-citizen-among-8-held-600000-yaba-tablets/|title=Myanmar nationals among 8 held with yaba pills worth Tk24cr |date=19 March 2017|work=Dhaka Tribune|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Relocation ==\nIn 2015 the [[government of Bangladesh]] proposed a relocation plan for the Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh to the remote island of [[Bhasan Char]] in the [[Bay of Bengal]]. The plan was pushed back following criticism by human rights activists and the [[UNHCR]].\n\nBetween October and November 2016, about 65,000 Rohingya refugees arrived from Myanmar. The government of Bangladesh decided to revive the relocation plan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/31/world/asia/rohingya-refugees-bangladesh.html|title=Rohingya Refugees in Bangladesh to Be Relocated to Remote Island|last=Sattar|first=Maher|date=31 January 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=20 March 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Bhasan Char submerges during high tide and was formed in the 2000s by sediments from the [[Meghna River]]. It is eight kilometers from [[Hatiya Island]].\n\nThe Bangladesh Army has been tasked with making the island habitable for the refugees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2017/feb/02/bangladesh-government-plan-move-rohingya-remote-island-human-catastrophe|title=Plan to move Rohingya to remote island prompts fears of human catastrophe|last=Rahman|first=Shaikh Azizur|date=2 February 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 March 2017|last2=agencies|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2019 the government announced an expansion of the [[Ashrayan Project]] (Ashrayan-3) to build 100,000 homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khokon |first1=Sahidul Hasan |title=Bangladesh: Govt takes up Ashrayan-3 project to shelter Rohingya refugees |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/rohingya-bangladesh-myanmar-sheikh-hasina-ashrayan-3-1096442-2017-11-29 |accessdate=1 August 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> In January 2020 the project was moving forward despite opposition from Rohingya leaders and human rights groups. Bangladesh\u2019s minister for refugee affairs has said the island is \u201cready for habitation,\u201d though he gave no timetable for the relocation. The government has not permitted foreign journalists or Rohingya leaders to travel to Bhasan Char. The island is less than 20 years old, and some think there is no guarantee that it will not disappear in the next monsoon.<ref> \n{{cite news \n| title = Will thousands of Rohingya refugees be sent to a remote island? \n| url = https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-01-23/will-thousands-of-refugees-soon-be-sent-to-a-remote-island\n| date = January 23, 2020\n| work = [[LA Times]] \n| accessdate = February 5, 2020}}\n</ref>\n\n== Repatriation ==\n[[File:Rohingyas protesting repatriation (Jafor Islam-VOA).jpg|thumb|right|225px|Rohingya refugees in Cox's Bazar, Bangladesh, protesting against what they view as a dangerous repatriation to Myanmar.]]\n\nAfter the [[Northern Rakhine State clashes#25 August ARSA attacks|ARSA attacks on 25 August 2017]] and subsequent [[humanitarian crisis]], [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Bangladesh)|Bangladeshi Foreign Minister]] [[Abul Hassan Mahmud Ali]] met with Myanmar officials on 2 October 2017, later stating after their meeting that both countries had agreed on a \"joint working group\" for the [[repatriation]] of Rohingya refugees who had fled to Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-rohingya-bangladesh/bangladesh-myanmar-agree-on-working-group-for-refugee-plan-minister-idUSKCN1C70XA|title= Bangladesh, Myanmar agree on 'working group' for refugee plan: minister|agency=Reuters|date=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe governments of Myanmar and Bangladesh signed a [[memorandum of understanding]] on 23 November 2017 regarding the repatriation of Rohingya refugees to Rakhine State.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/breaking-news/myanmar-bangladesh-sign-rohingya-deal/news-story/b0989c37a2348826393b42c7521522c5|title=Myanmar, Bangladesh 'sign Rohingya deal'|work=News.com.au|access-date=24 November 2017}}</ref> Bangladesh's Foreign Minister stated that a joint working group composed of UNHCR and members of both nations was to be established within three weeks to fix the final terms for the beginning of the process. He also stated that those returning would be kept in temporary camps near their abandoned homes. Under the deal, Myanmar would ensure that they are not kept in the camps for long and are issued identity cards.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/rohingya-repatriation-will-start-in-two-months-says-bangladesh-11142654|title=Rohingya repatriation will start in two months, says Bangladesh|publisher=Sky News|access-date=24 November 2017}}</ref> The foreign secretaries of both nations met on 19 December to finalise the agreement. Bangladesh's foreign ministry issued a statement saying that the group would \"ensure commencement of repatriation within two months\" by developing a timetable for verification of identities and logistics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2017-12-19-rohingya-refugees-to-start-returning-from-january|title=Rohingya refugees to start returning from January|work=Mail & guardian|access-date=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Bangladesh]]'s [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Bangladesh)|foreign ministry]] announced on 15 January 2018 that their government and Myanmar's had bilaterally agreed on a [[repatriation]] deal for Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh, which would aim to complete the process of repatriation within two years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh 'to return 300 Rohingya a day'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-42699602|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=BBC News|date=2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh, Myanmar aim to return Rohingya within 2 years|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/rohingya-bangladesh-myanmar-return-1.4489847|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=CBC News|language=en}}</ref> [[Win Myat Aye]], Myanmar's [[Ministry of Social Welfare, Relief and Resettlement|Minister for Social Welfare, Relief and Resettlement]], also announced that his country would begin repatriating Rohingya refugees beginning on 23 January 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh, Myanmar aim to finish Rohingya return in 2 years|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/myanmar-says-1st-camp-for-rohingya-will-be-ready-next-week/2018/01/15/7415cea2-fa58-11e7-9b5d-bbf0da31214d_story.html|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=Washington Post|date=16 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Myanmar says camps for Rohingya will be ready next week|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/myanmar-camps-rohingya-ready-week-52350604|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=ABC News|language=en}}</ref> Originally, the government of Myanmar agreed to [[Repatriation|repatriate]] only 374 Rohingya refugees out of a list of over 8,000 submitted by their Bangladeshi counterparts on 14 March 2018, citing incomplete paperwork as the reason for the slow process,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ellis-Petersen|first1=Hannah|title=Myanmar willing to take back fewer than 400 Rohingya refugees|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/15/myanmar-willing-to-take-back-fewer-than-400-rohingya-refugees-bangladesh|accessdate=19 March 2018|work=the Guardian|date=15 March 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Aung|first1=Thu Thu|last2=Naing|first2=Shoon|title=Myanmar says it has verified fewer than 400 Rohingya for repatriation|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-rohingya-repatriation/myanmar-says-it-has-verified-fewer-than-400-rohingya-for-repatriation-idUSKCN1GQ1RX|accessdate=19 March 2018|work=Reuters|date=14 March 2018}}</ref> but on 18 May 2018, they announced they would repatriate a total of 1,100 \"verified\" Rohingyas from the list.<ref>{{cite news|title=Myanmar wants repatriation of 1,101 verified Rohingyas|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/rohingya-crisis/bangladesh-myanmar-wants-repatriation-only-1101-verified-rohingyas-1578172|accessdate=19 May 2018|work=The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|date=18 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2018, the [[United Nations]] and the government of Myanmar signed a memorandum of understanding regarding the repatriation of Rohingya refugees,<ref>{{cite news |title=UN signs Myanmar access deal amid Rohingya repatriation fears - World - Dunya News |url=https://dunyanews.tv/en/World/442758-UN-signs-Myanmar-access-deal-amid-Rohingya-repatriation-fears |accessdate=6 July 2018 |work=Dunya News |date=6 June 2018}}</ref> the details of which were kept secret until they were leaked online on 29 June 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McPherson |first1=Poppy |last2=Siddiqui |first2=Zeba |title=Secret U.N.-Myanmar deal on Rohingya offers no guarantees on... |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-rohingya/secret-u-n-myanmar-deal-on-rohingya-offers-no-guarantees-on-citizenship-idUSKBN1JP2PF |accessdate=6 July 2018 |work=Reuters |date=29 June 2018}}</ref> The agreement was immediately criticised and rejected by Rohingya leaders, who say it does not address the concerns of their community.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Slow |first1=Oliver |title=Refugees Criticize UN-Myanmar Repatriation Deal |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/refugees-criticize-un-myanmar-repatriation-deal/4469094.html |accessdate=6 July 2018 |work=Voice of America |date=5 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rahman |first1=Shaikh Azizur |title=Rohingya refugees reject UN-Myanmar repatriation agreement |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jul/06/rohingya-refugees-reject-un-myanmar-repatriation-agreement |accessdate=6 July 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=5 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Health issues ==\nSince the rapid influx of Rohingya refugees into Bangladesh began in 2017, public health officials have been concerned that a myriad of health issues among the refugees would arise. As predicted, mental health has deteriorated,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Tay|first=A.K.|last2=Islam|first2=R.|last3=Riley|first3=A.|last4=Welton-Mitchell|first4=C.|last5=Duchesne|first5=B.|last6=Waters|first6=V.|last7=Varner|first7=A.|last8=Silove|first8=D.|last9=Ventevogel|first9=P.|date=2018|title=Culture, Context and Mental Health of Rohingya Refugees: A review for staff in mental health and psychosocial support programmes for Rohingya refugees|url=https://www.unhcr.org/5bbc6f014.pdf|journal=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)|location=Geneva, Switzerland|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> food- and water-borne diseases are spreading,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Mahmood|first=Syed S.|last2=Wroe|first2=Emily|last3=Fuller|first3=Arlan|last4=Leaning|first4=Jennifer|date=2017-05-06|title=The Rohingya people of Myanmar: health, human rights, and identity|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(16)00646-2/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=389|issue=10081|pages=1841\u20131850|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)00646-2|issn=0140-6736|pmid=27916235|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Chan|first=Emily Y. Y.|last2=Chiu|first2=Cheuk Pong|last3=Chan|first3=Gloria K. W.|date=2018-03-01|title=Medical and health risks associated with communicable diseases of Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh 2017|url=https://www.ijidonline.com/article/S1201-9712(18)30001-8/abstract|journal=International Journal of Infectious Diseases|language=English|volume=68|pages=39\u201343|doi=10.1016/j.ijid.2018.01.001|issn=1201-9712|pmid=29329951|via=}}</ref> infectious diseases are emerging,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=White|first=Kate|date=2017-10-28|title=Rohingya in Bangladesh: an unfolding public health emergency|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(17)32677-6/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=390|issue=10106|pages=1947|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(17)32677-6|issn=0140-6736|pmid=29050644}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Hossain|first=Md Mahbub|last2=Sultana|first2=Abida|last3=Mazumder|first3=Hoimonty|last4=Munzur-E-Murshid|date=2018-07-01|title=Sexually transmitted infections among Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanhiv/article/PIIS2352-3018(18)30140-1/abstract|journal=The Lancet HIV|language=English|volume=5|issue=7|pages=e342|doi=10.1016/S2352-3018(18)30140-1|issn=2352-3018|pmid=30052506|via=}}</ref> malnutrition is prevalent,<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/rohingya-refugees-facing-malnutrition/4377429.html|title=Rohingya Refugees Face Malnutrition|last=Patinkin|first=Jason|date=4 May 2018|website=VOA|language=en}}</ref> and reproductive health for women and girls must be addressed.\n\n=== Mental health ===\nIn humanitarian crises, mental health responses typically follow the IASC pyramid of Mental Health and Psychosocial Services (MHPSS). Ideally, different levels of care are to be provided to best serve communities, as well as individuals. The philosophy behind this model maintains that individual psychological treatment and broad social interventions are both essential to overall mental wellbeing and resilience. It also acknowledges that most of a population require minimal psychosocial interventions in order to improve or prevent adverse mental health outcomes, which can be facilitated by mental health workers. However, those who experience impaired functioning due to severe emotional distress, or who require pharmaceutical treatment for an existing or developing condition would require more specialized services facilitated my more highly trained professionals, such as psychiatrists and psychologists.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Rohingya refugees settled in the Cox's Bazar region of Bangladesh are at risk for mental health issues due to a wide variety of factors, including prior history of systematic dehumanization, persecution, having witnessed or experienced traumatic events, and daily stressors of remaining in a refugee settlement. The history of the Rohingya located in the Rakhine State of Myanmar includes protracted social and economic exclusion, which ultimately escalated to extreme violence resulting in a mass exodus of up to an estimated 900,000 refugees to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.searo.who.int/mediacentre/releases/2018/1680/en/|title=World Health Organization, Urgent need to scale up health services in Cox's Bazar: WHO|website=SEARO|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref> The traumatic events that have occurred in Rakhine State included burning of villages, arrests, torture, sexual assault, and loss of family and livelihoods.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Riley|first=Andrew|last2=Varner|first2=Andrea|last3=Ventevogel|first3=Peter|last4=Taimur Hasan|first4=M. M.|last5=Welton-Mitchell|first5=Courtney|date=June 2017|title=Daily stressors, trauma exposure, and mental health among stateless Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh|journal=Transcultural Psychiatry|language=en|volume=54|issue=3|pages=304\u2013331|doi=10.1177/1363461517705571|pmid=28540768|issn=1363-4615}}</ref>\n\nMajor agencies involved with mental health response for the Rohingya in Bangladesh include: The Bangladesh government (Ministry of Health and Ministry of Women and Children), UN agencies (IOM, [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]], [[UNICEF]]), International NGOs (ACF, Danish Refugee Council, Handicap International, International Rescue Committee, MSF, Relief International, Save the Children, World Concern), National NGOs (BRAC, Gonoshasthaya Kendra, Mukiti), and Red Cross Societies (Danish Red Cross, International Federation of the Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies).<ref name=\":0\" /> Mental health workers and some specialists have been deployed, but mental health service delivery continues to be problematic and there is a recognized gap in services. Efforts since the beginning of the crisis have focused on providing basic psychosocial training and non-specialized community interventions, including training in Psychological First Aid. Integrating MHPSS interventions and awareness in primary healthcare services have also been problematic, as providing adequate access to basic health services itself has been a challenge in the refugee camps due to a shortage in supplies, space, and staff.<ref name=\":0\" /> This integration continues to be a goal and efforts towards program implementation and training of healthcare professionals in the field have been an area of focus. However, the increases in the camp population, especially during the rapid population influx of an estimated 700,000 in 2017, only exacerbated these challenges. Furthermore, the resource-poor humanitarian efforts are suggested to increase negative psychological impacts by perpetuating anxiety, stress and depression and decreasing capacity for resilience.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAccording to a report published by the United Nations Higher Commissioner for Refugees ([[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]]), there have been few studies published on mental health concerns of the Rohingya refugee populations. Nonetheless, there are a concerning number of cases reported involving \u201cexplosive anger, psychotic-like symptoms, somatic or medically unexplained symptoms, impaired function and suicidal ideation,\u201d along with a documented history of reported high anxiety, hypervigilance, depression, and appetite loss within the population.<ref name=\":0\" /> The factors suggested to cause such prominent mental health concerns involve not only daily stressors of refugee living situations and the immediate trauma endured prior to arrival, but also due to protracted traumatic or stressful experience being persecuted in Rakhine State before fleeing.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe combination of the protracted refugee crisis with a history of stress, persecution and trauma is a cause for concern with the Rohingya and further investigation into the effects and treatments has been recommended. Furthermore, there have been obstacles with reporting mental health measurement results, including not having validated such measurements with the Rohingyas prior to research, as well as a substandard understanding of cultural idioms of distress. This allows for possible misinterpretation of mental health concerns if viewed and diagnosed by Western standards and definitions alone. Further evaluation into cultural idioms of distress, validity of results and continued research has been recommended by multiple involved agencies.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Food- and water-borne diseases ===\n[[File:Rohingya displaced Muslims 011.jpg|thumb|255x255px|Clean water and sanitation are scarce for many Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh, especially in unregistered camps.<ref name=\":15\" />]]\nPoor infrastructure and sanitation in refugee camps place the Rohingya at increased risk for food- and water-borne diseases. The recommended number of residents per latrine to reduce risk for waterborne disease is 20, according to the Minimum Standards in Humanitarian response. In the Rohingya refugee camps in Bangladesh, the actual prevalence of latrines is one latrine for 37 individuals.<ref name=\":1\" /> Clean water is also in demand for the Rohingya refugees. Many people draw from nearby rivers for drinking water, however, these rivers are also sources of bathing and open defecation, especially in unofficial Rohingya camps.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Contamination of these rivers and latrines by harmful pathogens becomes an even greater risk during monsoon seasons for Rohingya camps in both Myanmar and Bangladesh. Poor infrastructure in the refugee camps will not protect against flooding events that can easily spread food- and water-borne pathogens.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Ahmed|first=Bayes|last2=Orcutt|first2=Miriam|last3=Sammonds|first3=Peter|last4=Burns|first4=Rachel|last5=Issa|first5=Rita|last6=Abubakar|first6=Ibrahim|last7=Devakumar|first7=Delan|date=May 2018|title=Humanitarian disaster for Rohingya refugees: impending natural hazards and worsening public health crises|journal=The Lancet Global Health|language=en|volume=6|issue=5|pages=e487\u2013e488|doi=10.1016/S2214-109X(18)30125-6|pmid=29653616}}</ref>\n\nThe inadequate sanitation and hygiene conditions in the Rohingya camps have resulted in increased risk for transmission of diarrheal infections. ''[[Escherichia coli]]'', for example, has been detected in 92% of water samples taken from a Rohingya refugee camp.<ref name=\":2\" /> Other water- and food-borne diseases that pose a threat to the Rohingya refugees are [[cholera]], [[hepatitis A]], [[hepatitis E]], and [[Typhoid fever|typhoid]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Currently, diarrheal diseases contribute significantly to health morbidity in the Rohingya camps. Approximately 8% of morbidity among Rohingya refugees is attributable to acute watery diarrhea (AWD), and the prevalence of AWD among individuals who seek clinical care is 22%.<ref name=\":2\" /> According to the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]], 63,750 Rohingya refugees suffering from AWD visited a registered camp's clinic between August 25 and December 2, 2017. There were also 15 reported deaths due to AWD during that time.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://unhcr.maps.arcgis.com/apps/Cascade/index.html?appid=5fdca0f47f1a46498002f39894fcd26f|title=Rohingya Refugee Emergency at a Glance|date=21 March 2018|editor-last=Gaynor|editor-first=Tim|website=UNHCR.maps.arcgis.com|publisher=UNHCR Mapping Unit}}</ref>\n\nThe threat of food- and water-borne diseases is especially concerning among vulnerable populations, including children and pregnant women. In official camps, 40% of children less than 5-years-old, have been infected with a diarrheal disease. The prevalence of diarrheal symptoms within the past 30 days among children living in unofficial camps, where adequate latrines are rare, is greater than 50%.<ref name=\":1\" /> Pregnancy often complicates a woman's ability to combat infection. Mortality rates for hepatitis E, for example are as low as 1% among the general population but can increase drastically to 20-25% for pregnant women.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Infectious diseases among Rohingya refugees ===\n[[File:4-year-old Anowar pictured with his mum and brother after being treated for diphtheria by the UK's Emergency Medical Team in Kutupalong, Bangladesh (28040394749).jpg|thumb|4-year-old Anowar pictured with his mum and brother after being treated for diphtheria by the UK's Emergency Medical Team in Kutupalong, Bangladesh]]\nDue to poor sanitation, low water quality, close living quarters, and high levels of drug trafficking and sexual violence, infectious disease outbreaks in Rohingya refugee camps are of concern to public health officials.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> High rates of respiratory infections and diarrheal illnesses have already been documented<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Summers|first=Aimee|last2=Humphreys|first2=Alexa|last3=Leidman|first3=Eva|last4=Van Mil|first4=Leonie Toroitich|last5=Wilkinson|first5=Caroline|last6=Narayan|first6=Anuradhha|last7=MALD|last8=Miah|first8=Mohammad Lalan|last9=Cramer|first9=Blanche Greene|date=2018-05-11|title=Notes from the Field: Diarrhea and Acute Respiratory Infection, Oral Cholera Vaccination Coverage, and Care-Seeking Behaviors of Rohingya Refugees \u2014 Cox's Bazar, Bangladesh, October\u2013November 2017|journal=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report|volume=67|issue=18|pages=533\u2013535|doi=10.15585/mmwr.mm6718a6|issn=0149-2195|pmc=5944978|pmid=29746454}}</ref> and children seem to recover more poorly from infectious diseases than adults due to malnutrition, but all ages are struggling to recover from respiratory infections and diarrheal diseases.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCurrently, [[diphtheria]] resurgence is a large concern. As of February 2018, there have been 5,710 reported cases and 35 reported deaths due to diphtheria.<ref name=\":7\" /> Mass vaccination efforts to stop the spread of diphtheria have been difficult due to cultural barriers and hesitation of the Rohingya. However, steps are being taken by public health officials to understand these barriers and to better the Rohingya's understanding of vaccination in hopes of increasing the vaccination rate and preventing new cases of diphtheria.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jalloh|first=Mohamed F.|last2=Bennett|first2=Sarah D.|last3=Alam|first3=Didarul|last4=Kouta|first4=Paryss|last5=Louren\u00e7o|first5=Dalia|last6=Alamgir|first6=Mohammad|last7=Feldstein|first7=Leora R.|last8=Ehlman|first8=Daniel C.|last9=Abad|first9=Neetu|date=11 January 2019|title=Rapid behavioral assessment of barriers and opportunities to improve vaccination coverage among displaced Rohingyas in Bangladesh, January 2018|journal=Vaccine|volume=37|issue=6|pages=833\u2013838|doi=10.1016/j.vaccine.2018.12.042|pmid=30642728|issn=0264-410X}}</ref>\n\nAnother concern of public health officials is the potential increase of sexually transmitted infections. Drug trafficking and sexual violence are high among the Rohingya refugees residing in the Cox's Bazar district in Bangladesh and there are 83 known cases of [[HIV]] among refugees, with many more unknown cases likely.<ref name=\":5\" /> \u00a0\n\nWhile not yet seen in the refugee camps, [[hepatitis E]] is a concern, particularly for pregnant women as the death rate increases from 1% to as much as 25% when infection occurs in the third trimester.<ref name=\":2\" /> There have been, however, cases of acute jaundice syndrome,<ref name=\":2\" /> which is associated with hepatitis E infection.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gerbi|first=Gemechu B.|last2=Williams|first2=Roxanne|last3=Bakamutumaho|first3=Barnabas|last4=Liu|first4=Stephen|last5=Downing|first5=Robert|last6=Drobeniuc|first6=Jan|last7=Kamili|first7=Saleem|last8=Xu|first8=Fujie|last9=Holmberg|first9=Scott D.|last10=Teshale|first10=Eyasu H.|date=2015-02-04|title=Hepatitis E as a Cause of Acute Jaundice Syndrome in Northern Uganda, 2010\u20132012|journal=Am J Trop Med Hyg|language=en|volume=92|issue=2|pages=411\u2013414|doi=10.4269/ajtmh.14-0196|issn=0002-9637|pmc=4347349|pmid=25448237}}</ref>\n\n=== Vaccination status and disease prevention ===\nStarting in October 2017, Rohingya refugees migrated in droves into Bangladesh and since, massive spread of communicable diseases has occurred among them. Rohingya refugees are often not vaccinated and there is worry that outbreaks of vaccine-preventable diseases, such as polio, measles, and tetanus, will occur if living conditions are not improved.<ref name=\":7\" /> But the UN and the WHO, along with Bangladesh Government, were quick to begin mass vaccination of the population. Measles outbreak is a dangerous threat and in 2017, the WHO announced that 136,000 children under 15 years of age were vaccinated against measles and rubella. An oral [[polio vaccine]] was also given to 72,000 children. Permanent vaccination centers are in place to assist in the vaccination effort of children under the age of 2 years. In October 2017, a mass vaccination effort spearheaded by the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare and partners provided 900,000 doses of oral [[cholera vaccine]] in two phases. More than 700,000 people over 1 year of age received a single dose during the first phase; in the second, an additional dose of the oral cholera vaccine was administered to 199,472 children ages 1 to 5 years. In addition, 236,696 children under 5 years of age were also vaccinated against polio.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.searo.who.int/mediacentre/releases/2017/1671/en/ |title = World Health Organization, Bangladesh steps up vaccination for new Rohingya arrivals as measles cases rise}}</ref> No new cases of cholera were detected in the 3 months following mass vaccination. However, Rohingya refugees arriving after the mass vaccination remain unprotected. As a result, a new cholera vaccination campaign began in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Qadri|first=Firdausi|last2=Azad|first2=Abul Kalam|last3=Flora|first3=Meerjady Sabrina|last4=Khan|first4=Ashraful Islam|last5=Islam|first5=Md Taufiqul|last6=Nair|first6=G Balakrish|last7=Singh|first7=Poonam Khetrapal|last8=Clemens|first8=John D|date=12 May 2018|title=Emergency deployment of oral cholera vaccine for the Rohingya in Bangladesh|journal=The Lancet|language=en|volume=391|issue=10133|pages=1877\u20131879|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(18)30993-0|pmid=29781432}}</ref> Also in Cox's Bazar, Rohingya children up to age 6 were immunized in December 2017 against [[Streptococcus pneumoniae|pneumococcal disease]], [[Whooping cough|pertussis]], [[tetanus]], [[Influenza B virus|influenza B]], and [[diphtheria]] in an effort to prevent future outbreaks and to control the spread of diphtheria.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Malnutrition ===\n[[File:Malnourished child.jpg|thumb|173x173px|Malnutrition is a serious public health concern for Rohingya refugee children.]]\n[[Malnutrition]] is a serious public health concern for Rohingya refugee children. According to the World Health Organization (WHO) malnutrition refers to deficiencies and excesses or imbalances in a person's intake of energy and/or nutrients and is a strong predictor of mortality in children that are 5 years and younger. In the refugee camps in Bangladesh, over 25% of Rohingya children are malnourished and over 12% are suffering from severe [[Stunted growth|stunting]], a condition resulting from starvation and malnutrition. Infants under 6 months are among the most vulnerable and have malnutrition rates near 50%.<ref name=\":6\" /> This is in part due to mothers lack of ability to provide breast milk due to their own lack of nutrition. Refugees are dependent on humanitarian aid and while efforts to combat malnutrition are underway, there is still an alarming rate of malnutrition. Efforts in Bangladesh and other surrounding countries by UNICEF, Action Against Hunger and other aid relief are helping to provide food and water.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/04/13/quarter-rohingya-refugee-children-malnourished/|title=Rohingya refugee crisis: A quarter of children are malnourished|last=Gulland|first=Anne|date=13 April 2018|work=The Telegraph|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Rohingya refugee children are facing a high risk of death considering the WHO refers to malnutrition as critical issue when rates reach 15%. \u00a0Acute malnutrition in the refugees exceeds levels between 24.5%-26.5%.<ref name=\":1\" /> Malnutrition is well above emergency levels. Of the thousands of  children that have fled to Bangladesh, chronic malnutrition is prevalent in around 60% of Rohingya children in Bangladesh.\n\nThere are many factors that play a role in the alarming rates of malnutrition among Rohingya refugee children including food security, infectious disease, poor sanitary conditions and contaminated water. Food security is a specific concern since only 6% of refugees report having acceptable food consumption scores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unicef.org/press-releases/malnutrition-rates-among-rohingya-refugee-children-bangladesh-appear-be-least-double|title=Malnutrition rates among Rohingya refugee children in Bangladesh appear to be at least double earlier estimates|last=LeMoyne|date=3 November 2017|website=www.unicef.org|language=en}}</ref> There are still refugees arriving at Cox's Bazar from Myanmar, creating an even greater lack of already very limited resources. A major upcoming concern for the refugees is the potential threat of the rainy season. This has the potential to cause flooding, leading to contaminated water and infectious disease, thus resulting in higher rates of malnutrition.<ref name=\":9\" /> They are in need of huge amounts of nutrient rich foods to reduce the risk of malnutrition rates increasing.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Reproductive health ===\nThe Rohingya refugee crisis has made Rohingya women more vulnerable. Currently, Rohingya women make up approximately 67% of the refugee population and are victims of sexual violence and exploitation.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Hutchinson|first=Susan|date=2018-01-02|title=Gendered insecurity in the Rohingya crisis|journal=Australian Journal of International Affairs|language=en|volume=72|issue=1|pages=1\u20139|doi=10.1080/10357718.2017.1402291|issn=1035-7718}}</ref> Of the 335,670 female refugees in the population, 70,000 (20%) are estimated to be pregnant or new mothers. This pregnancy rate is much higher than that of their native Myanmar where only 4.7% of women are pregnant or new mothers.<ref name=\":10\" /> Many experts believe that the increase in pregnancy rate is a result of sexual violence against displaced Rohingya women. The Bangladesh home ministry states that a staggering 90% of female refugees have been victims of rape.<ref name=\":10\" /> Many victims of rape at the hands of soldiers are killed because of their race. Gender inequalities and marginalization of women are additional reasons for the high rates of violence against women.\n\n[[Child marriage]] is a common practice among the Rohingya.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Ainul|first=Sigma|last2=Ehsan|first2=Iqbal|last3=Haque|first3=Eashita F.|last4=Amin|first4=Sajeda|last5=Rob|first5=Ubaidur|last6=Melnikas|first6=Andrea J.|last7=Falcone|first7=Joseph|date=2018|title=Marriage and Sexual and Reproductive Health of Rohingya Adolescents and Youth in Bangladesh: A Qualitative Study|url=|journal=Population Council|publisher=UNFPA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> There is also a lack of legal procedures for marriage in the Camps that refugees are placed in. Very often marriages are based on dowries and arranged marriages tend to happen early for girls within the camps, due to fear of sexual violence. When women are married, they are told that they should have a large family as it is a sin for a woman to limit the number of children she bears.<ref name=\":11\" /> Contraception methods are very limited and may believe it may lead to infertility or death; family planning is also seen as immoral.<ref name=\":11\" /> Although there are reproductive health services within the camps, not many people seek reproductive care due to a lack of trust in medical personnel and practices, as well as barriers to transportation. Women also tend to be less independently mobile within their communities compared to men. Women and girls usually receive information on sexual and reproductive health through elderly women within the population and although this can be helpful, very often false information is given to people about reproductive health.<ref name=\":11\" /> Having limited participation with the clinics has to lead to increases in unsafe pregnancies and sexually transmitted infections.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nMost of the Rohingya refugees deliver infants with the help of midwives.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unfpa.org/news/sexual-and-reproductive-health-needs-immense-among-rohingya-refugees|title=Sexual and reproductive health needs immense among Rohingya refugees|date=2018|website=www.unfpa.org|publisher=United Nations Population Fund|language=en}}</ref> The United Nations Population Fund ([[United Nations Population Fund|UNFPA]]) has been responsible for ensuring that the midwifery diploma program is in the refugee camps.<ref name=\":12\" /> An increase in violence among refugees has been documented and as a result, the midwives are sometimes unable to provide the proper access to healthcare and resources. Many of the midwives in the region also can not give the best sexual health resources because of language barriers and cultural differences.<ref name=\":12\" /> Due to the Rohingya's conservative values, sexual and reproductive health information and care is limited and midwives are limited in the information they can provide. The majority of expectant women tend to be between the ages of 15 to 18 years old. Currently, there are approximately 19 facilities within the refugee camps that help give access to reproductive healthcare, however, there is a growing need for services and support for reproductive health issues.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nAnother factor contributing to the health of Rohingya women is the ability to breastfeed infants and availability of spaces to do so. As of 2017, about 8.3% of the Rohingya population was breastfeeding.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvi.org/myanmar-%E2%80%93-bangladesh-refugee-crisis/article/breastfeeding-boosts-baby-shamsidas-health-camp|title=Breastfeeding boosts baby Shamsida's health in the camp|last=Homer|first=K.|date=2018|website=WVI.org|publisher=World Vision International|language=en}}</ref> On average the Rohingya women will give birth to 3.8 children in their lifespan and will breastfeed for a total of 6.9 years.<ref name=\":13\" /> A large increase in childbearing has been seen and breastfeeding-safe regions are have become very limited and overcrowded for women as a result. As well as having limited space to participate in breastfeeding, many mothers are not given accurate information on proper feeding practices.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n==Education==\nAs of 2020, approximately one-third of refugee Rohingya children were able to access [[primary education]], primarily through temporary centers run by international organizations. UNICEF runs approximately 1,600 learning centers across the country, educating around 145,000 children.<ref name=\"AJE\">{{cite news |title='Great news': Bangladesh allows education for Rohingya children |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/news-bangladesh-education-rohingya-children-200130061617667.html |publisher=[[Al Jazeera English]] |first=Saba |last=Aziz |first2=Faisal |last2=Mahmud |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> Beginning in April 2020, [[UNICEF]] and the Government of Bangladesh will enroll 10,000 Rohingya children in schools where they will be taught the Myanmar school curriculum.<ref name=\"AJE\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Immigration to Bangladesh}}\n{{Asia topic|Refugees in }}\n\n[[Category:Rohingya diaspora|Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Refugees in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:2000s in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:2010s in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Cox's Bazar District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n[[File:Kutupalong Refugee Camp (John Owens-VOA).jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Kutupalong Refugee Camp]] in Bangladesh.]]\n\n'''Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh''' mostly refer to Forcibly Displaced Myanmar Nationals (FDMNs) from Myanmar who are living in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rohingya exodus to Bangladesh nears 300,000|url=http://www.muslimglobal.com/2017/09/rohingya-exodus-to-bangladesh-nears.html|accessdate=9 September 2017|publisher=Muslim Global}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-38799586|title=Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh face relocation to island|date=30 January 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> The Rohingya people have experienced ethnic and religious persecution in Myanmar for decades. Hundreds of thousands have fled to other countries in Southeast Asia, including Malaysia, Indonesia, and Philippines.<ref name=\":14\">[http://www.foxnews.com/world/2018/09/27/bangladesh-point-finger-at-myanmar-for-rohingya-genocide.html Bangladesh point finger at Myanmar for Rohingya 'genocide']</ref> The majority have escaped to Bangladesh, where there are two official, registered refugee camps. Recently violence in Myanmar has escalated, so the number of refugees in Bangladesh has increased rapidly. According to the UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR), more than 723,000 Rohingya have fled to Bangladesh since 25 August 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/uae-press-we-must-resolve-to-aid-all-refugees-2017-12-27-1.663327|title=UAE Press: We must resolve to aid all refugees|last=WAM|date=27 December 2017|work=Emirates 24{{!}}7|access-date=28 December 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/rohingya-crisis-myanmar-court-extends-detention-of-two-journalists201712280538520001/|title=Rohingya crisis: Myanmar Court extends detention of two journalists|website=www.aninews.in|language=en|access-date=28 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/bangladesh/bangladesh-humanitarian-situation-report-no16-rohingya-influx-24-december-2017|title=Bangladesh: Humanitarian Situation report No.16 (Rohingya influx) 24 December 2017|work=ReliefWeb|access-date=28 December 2017|language=en}}</ref> \n\nOn 28 September 2018, at the 73rd United Nations General Assembly, Bangladeshi Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasina]] said there are 1.1 million Rohingya refugees now in Bangladesh.<ref name=\":14\" /> Overcrowding from the recent population boom at Bangladesh's Rohingya refugee camps has placed a strain on its infrastructure. The refugees lack access to services, education, food, clean water, and proper sanitation; they are also vulnerable to natural disasters and infectious disease transmission.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":8\" /> As of June 2018 [[World Bank]] announced nearly half a billion dollars in monetary support to help Bangladesh address Rohingya refugees' needs in areas including health, education, water and sanitation, disaster risk management, and social protection.<ref>{{cite web|author=\u5f20\u9510 |url=http://www.china.org.cn/world/2018-06/29/content_53991750.htm |title=World Bank announces nearly half-a-bln USD support for Bangladesh to help Rohingya |publisher=China.org.cn |date=29 June 2018 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> On 1 March 2019 Bangladesh announced that it would no longer accept Rohingya refugees.<ref name=\"urlRohingya crisis: Bangladesh will no longer take in Myanmar refugees - BBC News\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-47412704 |title=Rohingya crisis: Bangladesh will no longer take in Myanmar refugees - BBC News |format= |work= BBC News|accessdate=|date=March 2019 }}</ref> An August 2018 study estimated that more than 24,000 Rohingya were killed by the Myanmar military and local Buddhists militia since the \"clearance operations\" started on 25 August 2017. It also estimated that at least 18,000 Rohingya Muslim women and girls were raped, 116,000 Rohingya were beaten, and 36,000 Rohingya were thrown into fires set alight in an act of deliberate arson.<ref name=\"oida\">{{Cite web|url=https://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/7857480|title=Forced migration of Rohingya: the untold experience|first1=Mohshin|last1=Habib|first2=Christine|last2=Jubb|first3=Salahuddin|last3=Ahmad|first4=Masudur|last4=Rahman|first5=Henri|last5=Pallard|date=July 18, 2018|publisher=Ontario International Development Agency, Canada|via=National Library of Australia (new catalog)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/07/chief-bangladesh-continue-hosting-rohingya-190710191318011.html|title=Former UN chief says Bangladesh cannot continue hosting Rohingya|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/rohingya-crisis/news/dutch-house-representatives-adopts-motion-probe-rohingya-genocide-1767124|title=Dutch House of Representatives adopts motion for probe on Rohingya genocide|date=July 5, 2019|website=The Daily Star}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefrontierpost.com/bangladeshi-pm-calls-for-safe-repatriation-of-rohingya/|title=Bangladeshi PM calls for safe repatriation of Rohingya|date=April 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.transcend.org/tms/2019/02/un-official-cites-horrific-crimes-against-rohingya/|title=UN Official Cites Horrific Crimes against Rohingya|website=TRANSCEND Media Service}}</ref><ref>https://www.researchgate.net/publication/333118905_Prevalence_of_violence_against_children_Evidence_from_2017_Rohingya_Refugee_crises</ref>\n\n== History ==\nRohingyas are a [[Muslim]] minority in Myanmar regarded by many [[Buddhism in Myanmar|Myanmar Buddhist]]s as illegal migrants from Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/burma-rohingya-muslim-refugees-bangladesh-aung-san-suu-kyi-a7554756.html|title=Bangladesh wants to move Muslim refugees to an island to stop them 'mingling' with citizens|date=31 January 2017|work=The Independent|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> The Rohingyas have lived in Myanmar for generations and the Bangladesh government has called for Myanmar to take back the refugees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/bangladesh-pm-asks-myanmar-to-take-back-rohingya-refugees/3431864.html|title=Bangladesh PM asks Myanmar to take back Rohingya refugees|work=Channel NewsAsia|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> They are denied citizenship in Myanmar and have been described as the world's most persecuted minority.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/world/2017/01/31/rohingya-refugees-bangladesh-relocated-remote-inhospitable-island/Blxwtb4cSK6L7sKX2ilfHL/story.html|title=Rohingya Refugees in Bangladesh to Be Relocated to Remote, Inhospitable Island - The Boston Globe|work=BostonGlobe.com|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/bangladesh/2017-02-23/trouble-thengar-char|title=The Trouble With Thengar Char|last=Kullab|first=Samya|date=23 February 2017|work=Foreign Affairs|accessdate=20 March 2017|issn=0015-7120}}</ref> Myanmar has denied persecuting the Rohingyas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.whig.com/article/20170228/AP/302289886|title=Myanmar army: Charges of abuse of Rohingya unsubstantiated|work=Herald-Whig|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rohingya displaced Muslims 010.jpg|thumb|Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh in October 2017]]\nSince the 1970s Rohingya refugees have been coming to Bangladesh from Myanmar . In the 1990s, more than 250,000 resided in refugees camps in Bangladesh. In the early 2000s, all but 20,000 of them were repatriated to Myanmar, some against their will.<ref>Thompson, Larry (2005), \"Bangladesh: Burmese Rohingya refugees virtual hostages,\" https://reliefweb.int/report/myanmar/bangladesh-burmese-rohingya-refugees-virtual-hostages, accessed 6 October 2017</ref> This respite ended in 2015 and by 2017, an estimated 300,000 to 500,000 Rohingya refugees were in Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/rohingya-crisis-security-tightened-along-india-myanmar-border/articleshow/60526163.cms|title=Rohingya crisis: Security tightened along India-Myanmar border|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915082041/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/rohingya-crisis-security-tightened-along-india-myanmar-border/articleshow/60526163.cms|archivedate=15 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Most of the refugees are located along the [[Teknaf-Cox's Bazar highway]] that is parallel to the [[Naf River]], which is the border between Bangladesh and Myanmar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/03/fight-survive-rohingya-refugees-bangladesh-170313091106782.html|title=A fight to survive for Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh|last=|first=|date=|website=aljazeera.com|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref> Most of the refugees are located in or near [[Cox's Bazar]], a coastal area dependent upon tourism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-rohingya-bangladesh-idUSKBN15F0NS|title=Bangladesh resurrects plan to move Rohingya refugees to flooded island|date=31 January 2017|work=Reuters|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh blamed the refugees for crime and [[2012 Ramu violence]] in Cox's Bazar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/10/refugees-and-neighbors-rohingya-in-bangladesh/|title=Refugees and Neighbors: Rohingya in Bangladesh|last=Diplomat|first=Sumit Ganguly and Brandon Miliate , The|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Bangladesh also follows a policy of making the country unwelcome for Rohingya refugees.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21659769-oppressed-myanmar-muslim-rohingyas-are-unwelcome-bangladesh-too-exile-island|title=Exile island|website=The Economist|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref> The majority of the refugees are unregistered, with only 32 thousand refugees registering themselves with UNHCR and the Bangladeshi government. An estimated 200,000+ refugees are living unregistered in Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/28/bangladesh-plans-to-move-rohingya-refugees-to-island-in-the-south|title=Bangladesh plans to move Rohingya refugees to island in the south|last=France-Presse|first=Agence|date=27 May 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Amnesty International reports have stated that the Myanmar security forces are committing rape, extrajudicial killing, and burning homes belonging to the Rohingya in a December 2016 report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.voanews.com/a/rohingya-refugees-in-bangladesh-vow-never-return-to-myanmar/3658693.html|title=Rohingya Refugees in Bangladesh Vow Never to Return to Myanmar|last=Hussain|first=Maaz|work=VOA|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> Refugees have been displacing the indigenous people of the [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/rights-group-accuses-bangladesh-of-ethnic-cleansing-pushing-buddhists-out-with-rohingya-refugees-from-myanmar/story-VyqvLP2rE5AzM0KG7ibgzJ.html|title=Rights group accuses Bangladesh of ethnic cleansing, pushing Buddhists out with Rohingya refugees from Myanmar|last=|first=|date=20 February 2017|work=hindustantimes.com/|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> They have also been blamed for importing the narcotic drug [[Ya ba|Ya Ba]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2017/03/03/bangladesh-ban-cold-pill-chemical-fight-meth-surge/|title=Bangladesh to ban cold pill chemical to fight meth surge |date=3 March 2017|work=Dhaka Tribune|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2017/02/28/myanmar-rohingya-refugees-sucked-into-booming-bangladesh-drug-trade|title=Myanmar Rohingya refugees sucked into booming Bangladesh drug trade|work=bdnews24.com|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/crime/2017/03/19/myanmar-citizen-among-8-held-600000-yaba-tablets/|title=Myanmar nationals among 8 held with yaba pills worth Tk24cr |date=19 March 2017|work=Dhaka Tribune|accessdate=20 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Relocation ==\nIn 2015 the [[government of Bangladesh]] proposed a relocation plan for the Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh to the remote island of [[Bhasan Char]] in the [[Bay of Bengal]]. The plan was pushed back following criticism by human rights activists and the [[UNHCR]].\n\nBetween October and November 2016, about 65,000 Rohingya refugees arrived from Myanmar. The government of Bangladesh decided to revive the relocation plan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/31/world/asia/rohingya-refugees-bangladesh.html|title=Rohingya Refugees in Bangladesh to Be Relocated to Remote Island|last=Sattar|first=Maher|date=31 January 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=20 March 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Bhasan Char submerges during high tide and was formed in the 2000s by sediments from the [[Meghna River]]. It is located 8 kilometers away from [[Hatiya Island]].\n\nThe Bangladesh Army has been tasked with making the island habitable for the refugees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2017/feb/02/bangladesh-government-plan-move-rohingya-remote-island-human-catastrophe|title=Plan to move Rohingya to remote island prompts fears of human catastrophe|last=Rahman|first=Shaikh Azizur|date=2 February 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 March 2017|last2=agencies|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2019 the government announced an expansion of the [[Ashrayan Project]] (Ashrayan-3) to build 100,000 homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khokon |first1=Sahidul Hasan |title=Bangladesh: Govt takes up Ashrayan-3 project to shelter Rohingya refugees |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/rohingya-bangladesh-myanmar-sheikh-hasina-ashrayan-3-1096442-2017-11-29 |accessdate=1 August 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> In January 2020 the project was moving forward despite opposition from Rohingya leaders and human rights groups. Bangladesh\u2019s minister for refugee affairs has said the island is \u201cready for habitation,\u201d though he gave no timetable for the relocation. The government has not permitted foreign journalists or Rohingya leaders to travel to Bhasan Char. The island is less than 20 years old, and some think there is no guarantee that it will not disappear in the next monsoon.<ref> \n{{cite news \n| title = Will thousands of Rohingya refugees be sent to a remote island? \n| url = https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-01-23/will-thousands-of-refugees-soon-be-sent-to-a-remote-island\n| date = January 23, 2020\n| work = [[LA Times]] \n| accessdate = February 5, 2020}}\n</ref>\n\n== Repatriation ==\n[[File:Rohingyas protesting repatriation (Jafor Islam-VOA).jpg|thumb|right|225px|Rohingya refugees in Cox's Bazar, Bangladesh, protesting against what they view as a dangerous repatriation to Myanmar.]]\n\nAfter the [[Northern Rakhine State clashes#25 August ARSA attacks|ARSA attacks on 25 August 2017]] and subsequent [[humanitarian crisis]], [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Bangladesh)|Bangladeshi Foreign Minister]] [[Abul Hassan Mahmud Ali]] met with Myanmar officials on 2 October 2017, later stating after their meeting that both countries had agreed on a \"joint working group\" for the [[repatriation]] of Rohingya refugees who had fled to Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-rohingya-bangladesh/bangladesh-myanmar-agree-on-working-group-for-refugee-plan-minister-idUSKCN1C70XA|title= Bangladesh, Myanmar agree on 'working group' for refugee plan: minister|agency=Reuters|date=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe governments of Myanmar and Bangladesh signed a [[memorandum of understanding]] on 23 November 2017 regarding the repatriation of Rohingya refugees to Rakhine State.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/breaking-news/myanmar-bangladesh-sign-rohingya-deal/news-story/b0989c37a2348826393b42c7521522c5|title=Myanmar, Bangladesh 'sign Rohingya deal'|work=News.com.au|access-date=24 November 2017}}</ref> Bangladesh's Foreign Minister stated that a joint working group composed of UNHCR and members of both nations was to be established within three weeks to fix the final terms for the beginning of the process. He also stated that those returning would be kept in temporary camps near their abandoned homes. Under the deal, Myanmar would ensure that they are not kept in the camps for long and are issued identity cards.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/rohingya-repatriation-will-start-in-two-months-says-bangladesh-11142654|title=Rohingya repatriation will start in two months, says Bangladesh|publisher=Sky News|access-date=24 November 2017}}</ref> The foreign secretaries of both nations met on 19 December to finalise the agreement. Bangladesh's foreign ministry issued a statement saying that the group would \"ensure commencement of repatriation within two months\" by developing a timetable for verification of identities and logistics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2017-12-19-rohingya-refugees-to-start-returning-from-january|title=Rohingya refugees to start returning from January|work=Mail & guardian|access-date=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Bangladesh]]'s [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Bangladesh)|foreign ministry]] announced on 15 January 2018 that their government and Myanmar's had bilaterally agreed on a [[repatriation]] deal for Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh, which would aim to complete the process of repatriation within two years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh 'to return 300 Rohingya a day'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-42699602|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=BBC News|date=2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh, Myanmar aim to return Rohingya within 2 years|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/rohingya-bangladesh-myanmar-return-1.4489847|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=CBC News|language=en}}</ref> [[Win Myat Aye]], Myanmar's [[Ministry of Social Welfare, Relief and Resettlement|Minister for Social Welfare, Relief and Resettlement]], also announced that his country would begin repatriating Rohingya refugees beginning on 23 January 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bangladesh, Myanmar aim to finish Rohingya return in 2 years|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/myanmar-says-1st-camp-for-rohingya-will-be-ready-next-week/2018/01/15/7415cea2-fa58-11e7-9b5d-bbf0da31214d_story.html|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=Washington Post|date=16 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Myanmar says camps for Rohingya will be ready next week|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/myanmar-camps-rohingya-ready-week-52350604|accessdate=17 January 2018|work=ABC News|language=en}}</ref> Originally, the government of Myanmar agreed to [[Repatriation|repatriate]] only 374 Rohingya refugees out of a list of over 8,000 submitted by their Bangladeshi counterparts on 14 March 2018, citing incomplete paperwork as the reason for the slow process,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ellis-Petersen|first1=Hannah|title=Myanmar willing to take back fewer than 400 Rohingya refugees|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/15/myanmar-willing-to-take-back-fewer-than-400-rohingya-refugees-bangladesh|accessdate=19 March 2018|work=the Guardian|date=15 March 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Aung|first1=Thu Thu|last2=Naing|first2=Shoon|title=Myanmar says it has verified fewer than 400 Rohingya for repatriation|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-rohingya-repatriation/myanmar-says-it-has-verified-fewer-than-400-rohingya-for-repatriation-idUSKCN1GQ1RX|accessdate=19 March 2018|work=Reuters|date=14 March 2018}}</ref> but on 18 May 2018, they announced they would repatriate a total of 1,100 \"verified\" Rohingyas from the list.<ref>{{cite news|title=Myanmar wants repatriation of 1,101 verified Rohingyas|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/rohingya-crisis/bangladesh-myanmar-wants-repatriation-only-1101-verified-rohingyas-1578172|accessdate=19 May 2018|work=The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|date=18 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2018, the [[United Nations]] and the government of Myanmar signed a memorandum of understanding regarding the repatriation of Rohingya refugees,<ref>{{cite news |title=UN signs Myanmar access deal amid Rohingya repatriation fears - World - Dunya News |url=https://dunyanews.tv/en/World/442758-UN-signs-Myanmar-access-deal-amid-Rohingya-repatriation-fears |accessdate=6 July 2018 |work=Dunya News |date=6 June 2018}}</ref> the details of which were kept secret until they were leaked online on 29 June 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McPherson |first1=Poppy |last2=Siddiqui |first2=Zeba |title=Secret U.N.-Myanmar deal on Rohingya offers no guarantees on... |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-myanmar-rohingya/secret-u-n-myanmar-deal-on-rohingya-offers-no-guarantees-on-citizenship-idUSKBN1JP2PF |accessdate=6 July 2018 |work=Reuters |date=29 June 2018}}</ref> The agreement was immediately criticised and rejected by Rohingya leaders, who say it does not address the concerns of their community.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Slow |first1=Oliver |title=Refugees Criticize UN-Myanmar Repatriation Deal |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/refugees-criticize-un-myanmar-repatriation-deal/4469094.html |accessdate=6 July 2018 |work=Voice of America |date=5 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rahman |first1=Shaikh Azizur |title=Rohingya refugees reject UN-Myanmar repatriation agreement |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jul/06/rohingya-refugees-reject-un-myanmar-repatriation-agreement |accessdate=6 July 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=5 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Health issues ==\nSince the rapid influx of Rohingya refugees into Bangladesh began in 2017, public health officials have been concerned that a myriad of health issues among the refugees would arise. As predicted, mental health has deteriorated,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Tay|first=A.K.|last2=Islam|first2=R.|last3=Riley|first3=A.|last4=Welton-Mitchell|first4=C.|last5=Duchesne|first5=B.|last6=Waters|first6=V.|last7=Varner|first7=A.|last8=Silove|first8=D.|last9=Ventevogel|first9=P.|date=2018|title=Culture, Context and Mental Health of Rohingya Refugees: A review for staff in mental health and psychosocial support programmes for Rohingya refugees|url=https://www.unhcr.org/5bbc6f014.pdf|journal=United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)|location=Geneva, Switzerland|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> food- and water-borne diseases are spreading,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Mahmood|first=Syed S.|last2=Wroe|first2=Emily|last3=Fuller|first3=Arlan|last4=Leaning|first4=Jennifer|date=2017-05-06|title=The Rohingya people of Myanmar: health, human rights, and identity|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(16)00646-2/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=389|issue=10081|pages=1841\u20131850|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)00646-2|issn=0140-6736|pmid=27916235|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Chan|first=Emily Y. Y.|last2=Chiu|first2=Cheuk Pong|last3=Chan|first3=Gloria K. W.|date=2018-03-01|title=Medical and health risks associated with communicable diseases of Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh 2017|url=https://www.ijidonline.com/article/S1201-9712(18)30001-8/abstract|journal=International Journal of Infectious Diseases|language=English|volume=68|pages=39\u201343|doi=10.1016/j.ijid.2018.01.001|issn=1201-9712|pmid=29329951|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref> infectious diseases are emerging,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=White|first=Kate|date=2017-10-28|title=Rohingya in Bangladesh: an unfolding public health emergency|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(17)32677-6/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=390|issue=10106|pages=1947|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(17)32677-6|issn=0140-6736|pmid=29050644}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Hossain|first=Md Mahbub|last2=Sultana|first2=Abida|last3=Mazumder|first3=Hoimonty|last4=Munzur-E-Murshid|date=2018-07-01|title=Sexually transmitted infections among Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanhiv/article/PIIS2352-3018(18)30140-1/abstract|journal=The Lancet HIV|language=English|volume=5|issue=7|pages=e342|doi=10.1016/S2352-3018(18)30140-1|issn=2352-3018|pmid=30052506|via=}}</ref> malnutrition is prevalent,<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/rohingya-refugees-facing-malnutrition/4377429.html|title=Rohingya Refugees Face Malnutrition|last=Patinkin|first=Jason|date=4 May 2018|website=VOA|language=en}}</ref> and reproductive health for women and girls must be addressed.\n\n=== Mental health ===\nIn humanitarian crises, mental health responses typically follow the IASC pyramid of Mental Health and Psychosocial Services (MHPSS). Ideally, different levels of care are to be provided to best serve communities, as well as individuals. The philosophy behind this model maintains that individual psychological treatment and broad social interventions are both essential to overall mental wellbeing and resilience. It also acknowledges that most of a population require minimal psychosocial interventions in order to improve or prevent adverse mental health outcomes, which can be facilitated by mental health workers. However, those who experience impaired functioning due to severe emotional distress, or who require pharmaceutical treatment for an existing or developing condition would require more specialized services facilitated my more highly trained professionals, such as psychiatrists and psychologists.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Rohingya refugees settled in the Cox's Bazar region of Bangladesh are at risk for mental health issues due to a wide variety of factors, including prior history of systematic dehumanization, persecution, having witnessed or experienced traumatic events, and daily stressors of remaining in a refugee settlement. The history of the Rohingya located in the Rakhine State of Myanmar includes protracted social and economic exclusion, which ultimately escalated to extreme violence resulting in a mass exodus of up to an estimated 900,000 refugees to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.searo.who.int/mediacentre/releases/2018/1680/en/|title=World Health Organization, Urgent need to scale up health services in Cox's Bazar: WHO|website=SEARO|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref> The traumatic events that have occurred in Rakhine State included burning of villages, arrests, torture, sexual assault, and loss of family and livelihoods.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Riley|first=Andrew|last2=Varner|first2=Andrea|last3=Ventevogel|first3=Peter|last4=Taimur Hasan|first4=M. M.|last5=Welton-Mitchell|first5=Courtney|date=June 2017|title=Daily stressors, trauma exposure, and mental health among stateless Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh|journal=Transcultural Psychiatry|language=en|volume=54|issue=3|pages=304\u2013331|doi=10.1177/1363461517705571|pmid=28540768|issn=1363-4615}}</ref>\n\nMajor agencies involved with mental health response for the Rohingya in Bangladesh include: The Bangladesh government (Ministry of Health and Ministry of Women and Children), UN agencies (IOM, [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]], [[UNICEF]]), International NGOs (ACF, Danish Refugee Council, Handicap International, International Rescue Committee, MSF, Relief International, Save the Children, World Concern), National NGOs (BRAC, Gonoshasthaya Kendra, Mukiti), and Red Cross Societies (Danish Red Cross, International Federation of the Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies).<ref name=\":0\" /> Mental health workers and some specialists have been deployed, but mental health service delivery continues to be problematic and there is a recognized gap in services. Efforts since the beginning of the crisis have focused on providing basic psychosocial training and non-specialized community interventions, including training in Psychological First Aid. Integrating MHPSS interventions and awareness in primary healthcare services have also been problematic, as providing adequate access to basic health services itself has been a challenge in the refugee camps due to a shortage in supplies, space, and staff.<ref name=\":0\" /> This integration continues to be a goal and efforts towards program implementation and training of healthcare professionals in the field have been an area of focus. However, the increases in the camp population, especially during the rapid population influx of an estimated 700,000 in 2017, only exacerbated these challenges. Furthermore, the resource-poor humanitarian efforts are suggested to increase negative psychological impacts by perpetuating anxiety, stress and depression and decreasing capacity for resilience.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAccording to a report published by the United Nations Higher Commissioner for Refugees ([[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]]), there have been few studies published on mental health concerns of the Rohingya refugee populations. Nonetheless, there are a concerning number of cases reported involving \u201cexplosive anger, psychotic-like symptoms, somatic or medically unexplained symptoms, impaired function and suicidal ideation,\u201d along with a documented history of reported high anxiety, hypervigilance, depression, and appetite loss within the population.<ref name=\":0\" /> The factors suggested to cause such prominent mental health concerns involve not only daily stressors of refugee living situations and the immediate trauma endured prior to arrival, but also due to protracted traumatic or stressful experience being persecuted in Rakhine State before fleeing.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe combination of the protracted refugee crisis with a history of stress, persecution and trauma is a cause for concern with the Rohingya and further investigation into the effects and treatments has been recommended. Furthermore, there have been obstacles with reporting mental health measurement results, including not having validated such measurements with the Rohingyas prior to research, as well as a substandard understanding of cultural idioms of distress. This allows for possible misinterpretation of mental health concerns if viewed and diagnosed by Western standards and definitions alone. Further evaluation into cultural idioms of distress, validity of results and continued research has been recommended by multiple involved agencies.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Food- and water-borne diseases ===\n[[File:Rohingya displaced Muslims 011.jpg|thumb|255x255px|Clean water and sanitation are scarce for many Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh, especially in unregistered camps.<ref name=\":15\" />]]\nPoor infrastructure and sanitation in refugee camps place the Rohingya at increased risk for food- and water-borne diseases. The recommended number of residents per latrine to reduce risk for waterborne disease is 20, according to the Minimum Standards in Humanitarian response. In the Rohingya refugee camps in Bangladesh, the actual prevalence of latrines is one latrine for 37 individuals.<ref name=\":1\" /> Clean water is also in demand for the Rohingya refugees. Many people draw from nearby rivers for drinking water, however, these rivers are also sources of bathing and open defecation, especially in unofficial Rohingya camps.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Contamination of these rivers and latrines by harmful pathogens becomes an even greater risk during monsoon seasons for Rohingya camps in both Myanmar and Bangladesh. Poor infrastructure in the refugee camps will not protect against flooding events that can easily spread food- and water-borne pathogens.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Ahmed|first=Bayes|last2=Orcutt|first2=Miriam|last3=Sammonds|first3=Peter|last4=Burns|first4=Rachel|last5=Issa|first5=Rita|last6=Abubakar|first6=Ibrahim|last7=Devakumar|first7=Delan|date=May 2018|title=Humanitarian disaster for Rohingya refugees: impending natural hazards and worsening public health crises|journal=The Lancet Global Health|language=en|volume=6|issue=5|pages=e487\u2013e488|doi=10.1016/S2214-109X(18)30125-6|pmid=29653616|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nThe inadequate sanitation and hygiene conditions in the Rohingya camps have resulted in increased risk for transmission of diarrheal infections. ''[[Escherichia coli]]'', for example, has been detected in 92% of water samples taken from a Rohingya refugee camp.<ref name=\":2\" /> Other water- and food-borne diseases that pose a threat to the Rohingya refugees are [[cholera]], [[hepatitis A]], [[hepatitis E]], and [[Typhoid fever|typhoid]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Currently, diarrheal diseases contribute significantly to health morbidity in the Rohingya camps. Approximately 8% of morbidity among Rohingya refugees is attributable to acute watery diarrhea (AWD), and the prevalence of AWD among individuals who seek clinical care is 22%.<ref name=\":2\" /> According to the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]], 63,750 Rohingya refugees suffering from AWD visited a registered camp's clinic between August 25 and December 2, 2017. There were also 15 reported deaths due to AWD during that time.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://unhcr.maps.arcgis.com/apps/Cascade/index.html?appid=5fdca0f47f1a46498002f39894fcd26f|title=Rohingya Refugee Emergency at a Glance|date=21 March 2018|editor-last=Gaynor|editor-first=Tim|website=UNHCR.maps.arcgis.com|publisher=UNHCR Mapping Unit}}</ref>\n\nThe threat of food- and water-borne diseases is especially concerning among vulnerable populations, including children and pregnant women. In official camps, 40% of children less than 5-years-old, have been infected with a diarrheal disease. The prevalence of diarrheal symptoms within the past 30 days among children living in unofficial camps, where adequate latrines are rare, is greater than 50%.<ref name=\":1\" /> Pregnancy often complicates a woman's ability to combat infection. Mortality rates for hepatitis E, for example are as low as 1% among the general population but can increase drastically to 20-25% for pregnant women.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Infectious diseases among Rohingya refugees ===\n[[File:4-year-old Anowar pictured with his mum and brother after being treated for diphtheria by the UK's Emergency Medical Team in Kutupalong, Bangladesh (28040394749).jpg|thumb|4-year-old Anowar pictured with his mum and brother after being treated for diphtheria by the UK's Emergency Medical Team in Kutupalong, Bangladesh]]\nDue to poor sanitation, low water quality, close living quarters, and high levels of drug trafficking and sexual violence, infectious disease outbreaks in Rohingya refugee camps are of concern to public health officials.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> High rates of respiratory infections and diarrheal illnesses have already been documented<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Summers|first=Aimee|last2=Humphreys|first2=Alexa|last3=Leidman|first3=Eva|last4=Van Mil|first4=Leonie Toroitich|last5=Wilkinson|first5=Caroline|last6=Narayan|first6=Anuradhha|last7=MALD|last8=Miah|first8=Mohammad Lalan|last9=Cramer|first9=Blanche Greene|date=2018-05-11|title=Notes from the Field: Diarrhea and Acute Respiratory Infection, Oral Cholera Vaccination Coverage, and Care-Seeking Behaviors of Rohingya Refugees \u2014 Cox's Bazar, Bangladesh, October\u2013November 2017|journal=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report|volume=67|issue=18|pages=533\u2013535|doi=10.15585/mmwr.mm6718a6|issn=0149-2195|pmc=5944978|pmid=29746454}}</ref> and children seem to recover more poorly from infectious diseases than adults due to malnutrition, but all ages are struggling to recover from respiratory infections and diarrheal diseases.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCurrently, [[diphtheria]] resurgence is a large concern. As of February 2018, there have been 5,710 reported cases and 35 reported deaths due to diphtheria.<ref name=\":7\" /> Mass vaccination efforts to stop the spread of diphtheria have been difficult due to cultural barriers and hesitation of the Rohingya. However, steps are being taken by public health officials to understand these barriers and to better the Rohingya's understanding of vaccination in hopes of increasing the vaccination rate and preventing new cases of diphtheria.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jalloh|first=Mohamed F.|last2=Bennett|first2=Sarah D.|last3=Alam|first3=Didarul|last4=Kouta|first4=Paryss|last5=Louren\u00e7o|first5=Dalia|last6=Alamgir|first6=Mohammad|last7=Feldstein|first7=Leora R.|last8=Ehlman|first8=Daniel C.|last9=Abad|first9=Neetu|date=11 January 2019|title=Rapid behavioral assessment of barriers and opportunities to improve vaccination coverage among displaced Rohingyas in Bangladesh, January 2018|journal=Vaccine|volume=37|issue=6|pages=833\u2013838|doi=10.1016/j.vaccine.2018.12.042|pmid=30642728|issn=0264-410X}}</ref>\n\nAnother concern of public health officials is the potential increase of sexually transmitted infections. Drug trafficking and sexual violence are high among the Rohingya refugees residing in the Cox's Bazar district in Bangladesh and there are 83 known cases of [[HIV]] among refugees, with many more unknown cases likely.<ref name=\":5\" /> \u00a0\n\nWhile not yet seen in the refugee camps, [[hepatitis E]] is a concern, particularly for pregnant women as the death rate increases from 1% to as much as 25% when infection occurs in the third trimester.<ref name=\":2\" /> There have been, however, cases of acute jaundice syndrome,<ref name=\":2\" /> which is associated with hepatitis E infection.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gerbi|first=Gemechu B.|last2=Williams|first2=Roxanne|last3=Bakamutumaho|first3=Barnabas|last4=Liu|first4=Stephen|last5=Downing|first5=Robert|last6=Drobeniuc|first6=Jan|last7=Kamili|first7=Saleem|last8=Xu|first8=Fujie|last9=Holmberg|first9=Scott D.|last10=Teshale|first10=Eyasu H.|date=2015-02-04|title=Hepatitis E as a Cause of Acute Jaundice Syndrome in Northern Uganda, 2010\u20132012|journal=Am J Trop Med Hyg|language=en|volume=92|issue=2|pages=411\u2013414|doi=10.4269/ajtmh.14-0196|issn=0002-9637|pmc=4347349|pmid=25448237}}</ref>\n\n=== Vaccination status and disease prevention ===\nStarting in October 2017, Rohingya refugees migrated in droves into Bangladesh and since, massive spread of communicable diseases has occurred among them. Rohingya refugees are often not vaccinated and there is worry that outbreaks of vaccine-preventable diseases, such as polio, measles, and tetanus, will occur if living conditions are not improved.<ref name=\":7\" /> But the UN and the WHO, along with Bangladesh Government, were quick to begin mass vaccination of the population. Measles outbreak is a dangerous threat and in 2017, the WHO announced that 136,000 children under 15 years of age were vaccinated against measles and rubella. An oral [[polio vaccine]] was also given to 72,000 children. Permanent vaccination centers are in place to assist in the vaccination effort of children under the age of 2 years. In October 2017, a mass vaccination effort spearheaded by the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare and partners provided 900,000 doses of oral [[cholera vaccine]] in two phases. More than 700,000 people over 1 year of age received a single dose during the first phase; in the second, an additional dose of the oral cholera vaccine was administered to 199,472 children ages 1 to 5 years. In addition, 236,696 children under 5 years of age were also vaccinated against polio.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.searo.who.int/mediacentre/releases/2017/1671/en/ |title = World Health Organization, Bangladesh steps up vaccination for new Rohingya arrivals as measles cases rise}}</ref> No new cases of cholera were detected in the 3 months following mass vaccination. However, Rohingya refugees arriving after the mass vaccination remain unprotected. As a result, a new cholera vaccination campaign began in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Qadri|first=Firdausi|last2=Azad|first2=Abul Kalam|last3=Flora|first3=Meerjady Sabrina|last4=Khan|first4=Ashraful Islam|last5=Islam|first5=Md Taufiqul|last6=Nair|first6=G Balakrish|last7=Singh|first7=Poonam Khetrapal|last8=Clemens|first8=John D|date=12 May 2018|title=Emergency deployment of oral cholera vaccine for the Rohingya in Bangladesh|journal=The Lancet|language=en|volume=391|issue=10133|pages=1877\u20131879|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(18)30993-0|pmid=29781432}}</ref> Also in Cox's Bazar, Rohingya children up to age 6 were immunized in December 2017 against [[Streptococcus pneumoniae|pneumococcal disease]], [[Whooping cough|pertussis]], [[tetanus]], [[Influenza B virus|influenza B]], and [[diphtheria]] in an effort to prevent future outbreaks and to control the spread of diphtheria.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Malnutrition ===\n[[File:Malnourished child.jpg|thumb|173x173px|Malnutrition is a serious public health concern for Rohingya refugee children.]]\n[[Malnutrition]] is a serious public health concern for Rohingya refugee children. According to the World Health Organization (WHO) malnutrition refers to deficiencies and excesses or imbalances in a person's intake of energy and/or nutrients and is a strong predictor of mortality in children that are 5 years and younger. In the refugee camps in Bangladesh, over 25% of Rohingya children are malnourished and over 12% are suffering from severe [[Stunted growth|stunting]], a condition resulting from starvation and malnutrition. Infants under 6 months are among the most vulnerable and have malnutrition rates near 50%.<ref name=\":6\" /> This is in part due to mothers lack of ability to provide breast milk due to their own lack of nutrition. Refugees are dependent on humanitarian aid and while efforts to combat malnutrition are underway, there is still an alarming rate of malnutrition. Efforts in Bangladesh and other surrounding countries by UNICEF, Action Against Hunger and other aid relief are helping to provide food and water.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/04/13/quarter-rohingya-refugee-children-malnourished/|title=Rohingya refugee crisis: A quarter of children are malnourished|last=Gulland|first=Anne|date=13 April 2018|work=The Telegraph|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Rohingya refugee children are facing a high risk of death considering the WHO refers to malnutrition as critical issue when rates reach 15%. \u00a0Acute malnutrition in the refugees exceeds levels between 24.5%-26.5%.<ref name=\":1\" /> Malnutrition is well above emergency levels. Of the thousands of  children that have fled to Bangladesh, chronic malnutrition is prevalent in around 60% of Rohingya children in Bangladesh.\n\nThere are many factors that play a role in the alarming rates of malnutrition among Rohingya refugee children including food security, infectious disease, poor sanitary conditions and contaminated water. Food security is a specific concern since only 6% of refugees report having acceptable food consumption scores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unicef.org/press-releases/malnutrition-rates-among-rohingya-refugee-children-bangladesh-appear-be-least-double|title=Malnutrition rates among Rohingya refugee children in Bangladesh appear to be at least double earlier estimates|last=LeMoyne|date=3 November 2017|website=www.unicef.org|language=en}}</ref> There are still refugees arriving at Cox's Bazar from Myanmar, creating an even greater lack of already very limited resources. A major upcoming concern for the refugees is the potential threat of the rainy season. This has the potential to cause flooding, leading to contaminated water and infectious disease, thus resulting in higher rates of malnutrition.<ref name=\":9\" /> They are in need of huge amounts of nutrient rich foods to reduce the risk of malnutrition rates increasing.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Reproductive health ===\nThe Rohingya refugee crisis has made Rohingya women more vulnerable. Currently, Rohingya women make up approximately 67% of the refugee population and are victims of sexual violence and exploitation.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Hutchinson|first=Susan|date=2018-01-02|title=Gendered insecurity in the Rohingya crisis|journal=Australian Journal of International Affairs|language=en|volume=72|issue=1|pages=1\u20139|doi=10.1080/10357718.2017.1402291|issn=1035-7718}}</ref> Of the 335,670 female refugees in the population, 70,000 (20%) are estimated to be pregnant or new mothers. This pregnancy rate is much higher than that of their native Myanmar where only 4.7% of women are pregnant or new mothers.<ref name=\":10\" /> Many experts believe that the increase in pregnancy rate is a result of sexual violence against displaced Rohingya women. The Bangladesh home ministry states that a staggering 90% of female refugees have been victims of rape.<ref name=\":10\" /> Many victims of rape at the hands of soldiers are killed because of their race. Gender inequalities and marginalization of women are additional reasons for the high rates of violence against women.\n\n[[Child marriage]] is a common practice among the Rohingya.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Ainul|first=Sigma|last2=Ehsan|first2=Iqbal|last3=Haque|first3=Eashita F.|last4=Amin|first4=Sajeda|last5=Rob|first5=Ubaidur|last6=Melnikas|first6=Andrea J.|last7=Falcone|first7=Joseph|date=2018|title=Marriage and Sexual and Reproductive Health of Rohingya Adolescents and Youth in Bangladesh: A Qualitative Study|url=|journal=Population Council|publisher=UNFPA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> There is also a lack of legal procedures for marriage in the Camps that refugees are placed in. Very often marriages are based on dowries and arranged marriages tend to happen early for girls within the camps, due to fear of sexual violence. When women are married, they are told that they should have a large family as it is a sin for a woman to limit the number of children she bears.<ref name=\":11\" /> Contraception methods are very limited and may believe it may lead to infertility or death; family planning is also seen as immoral.<ref name=\":11\" /> Although there are reproductive health services within the camps, not many people seek reproductive care due to a lack of trust in medical personnel and practices, as well as barriers to transportation. Women also tend to be less independently mobile within their communities compared to men. Women and girls usually receive information on sexual and reproductive health through elderly women within the population and although this can be helpful, very often false information is given to people about reproductive health.<ref name=\":11\" /> Having limited participation with the clinics has to lead to increases in unsafe pregnancies and sexually transmitted infections.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nMost of the Rohingya refugees deliver infants with the help of midwives.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unfpa.org/news/sexual-and-reproductive-health-needs-immense-among-rohingya-refugees|title=Sexual and reproductive health needs immense among Rohingya refugees|date=2018|website=www.unfpa.org|publisher=United Nations Population Fund|language=en}}</ref> The United Nations Population Fund ([[United Nations Population Fund|UNFPA]]) has been responsible for ensuring that the midwifery diploma program is in the refugee camps.<ref name=\":12\" /> An increase in violence among refugees has been documented and as a result, the midwives are sometimes unable to provide the proper access to healthcare and resources. Many of the midwives in the region also can not give the best sexual health resources because of language barriers and cultural differences.<ref name=\":12\" /> Due to the Rohingya's conservative values, sexual and reproductive health information and care is limited and midwives are limited in the information they can provide. The majority of expectant women tend to be between the ages of 15 to 18 years old. Currently, there are approximately 19 facilities within the refugee camps that help give access to reproductive healthcare, however, there is a growing need for services and support for reproductive health issues.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nAnother factor contributing to the health of Rohingya women is the ability to breastfeed infants and availability of spaces to do so. As of 2017, about 8.3% of the Rohingya population was breastfeeding.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvi.org/myanmar-%E2%80%93-bangladesh-refugee-crisis/article/breastfeeding-boosts-baby-shamsidas-health-camp|title=Breastfeeding boosts baby Shamsida's health in the camp|last=Homer|first=K.|date=2018|website=WVI.org|publisher=World Vision International|language=en}}</ref> On average the Rohingya women will give birth to 3.8 children in their lifespan and will breastfeed for a total of 6.9 years.<ref name=\":13\" /> A large increase in childbearing has been seen and breastfeeding-safe regions are have become very limited and overcrowded for women as a result. As well as having limited space to participate in breastfeeding, many mothers are not given accurate information on proper feeding practices.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n==Education==\nAs of 2020, approximately one-third of refugee Rohingya children were able to access [[primary education]], primarily through temporary centers run by international organizations. UNICEF runs approximately 1,600 learning centers across the country, educating around 145,000 children.<ref name=\"AJE\">{{cite news |title='Great news': Bangladesh allows education for Rohingya children |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/news-bangladesh-education-rohingya-children-200130061617667.html |publisher=[[Al Jazeera English]] |first=Saba |last=Aziz |first2=Faisal |last2=Mahmud |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> Beginning in April 2020, [[UNICEF]] and the Government of Bangladesh will enroll 10,000 Rohingya children in schools where they will be taught the Myanmar school curriculum.<ref name=\"AJE\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Immigration to Bangladesh}}\n{{Asia topic|Refugees in }}\n\n[[Category:Rohingya diaspora|Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Refugees in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:2000s in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:2010s in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Cox's Bazar District]]\n", "name_user": "AlsoWukai", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rohingya_refugees_in_Bangladesh"}
{"title_page": "Virtual private network", "text_new": "{{Redirect|VPN}}\n{{short description|Allows a private network to go through a public network}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n\n[[File:VPN overview-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|VPN connectivity overview]]\n\nA '''virtual private network''' ('''VPN''') extends a [[private network]] across a public network and enables users to send and receive data across shared or public networks as if their computing devices were directly connected to the private network. Applications running on an [[end system]] (PC, smartphone etc.) across a VPN may therefore benefit from the functionality, security, and management of the private network. [[Encryption]] is a common, though not an inherent, part of a VPN connection.<ref>{{cite book |author= Mason, Andrew G. |title=Cisco Secure Virtual Private Network |url= https://archive.org/details/ciscosecurevirtu00andr |url-access= registration |publisher= Cisco Press |date= 2002 |page= [https://archive.org/details/ciscosecurevirtu00andr/page/7 7]}}</ref>\n\nVPN technology was developed to allow remote users and branch offices to access corporate applications and resources. To ensure security, the private network connection is established using an encrypted layered [[tunneling protocol]], and VPN users use authentication methods, including passwords or certificates, to gain access to the VPN. In other applications, Internet users may secure their connections with a VPN to circumvent [[Geo-blocking|geo-restrictions]] and [[censorship]] or to connect to [[proxy server]]s to protect personal identity and location to stay anonymous on the Internet. Some websites, however, block access to known VPN technology to prevent the circumvention of their geo-restrictions, and many VPN providers have been developing strategies to get around these roadblocks.\n\nA VPN is created by establishing a virtual [[point-to-point (network topology)|point-to-point]] connection through the use of dedicated circuits or with tunneling protocols over existing networks. A VPN available from the public Internet can provide some of the benefits of a [[wide area network]] (WAN). From a user perspective, the resources available within the private network can be accessed remotely.<ref>{{cite web |publisher= [[Microsoft Technet]] |title= Virtual Private Networking: An Overview |url= https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb742566.aspx |date=September 4, 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Types==\n[[File:VPN classification-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|VPN classification based on the topology first, then on the technology used.]]\n[[File:Site-to-site VPN-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|A typical site-to-site VPN.]]\nEarly data networks allowed VPN-style connections to remote sites through [[dial-up modem]] or through [[leased line]] connections utilizing [[X.25]], [[Frame Relay]] and [[Asynchronous Transfer Mode]] (ATM) virtual circuits provided through networks owned and operated by [[Telephone company|telecommunication carriers]]. These networks are not considered true VPNs because they passively secure the data being transmitted by the creation of logical data streams.<ref>Cisco Systems, et al. ''Internet working Technologies Handbook, Third Edition''. Cisco Press, 2000, p. 232.</ref> They have been replaced by VPNs based on IP and IP/[[Multiprotocol Label Switching|Multi-protocol Label Switching]] (MPLS) Networks, due to significant cost-reductions and increased bandwidth<ref>Lewis, Mark. ''Comparing, Designing. And Deploying VPNs''. Cisco Press, 2006, p. 5</ref> provided by new technologies such as digital subscriber line (DSL)<ref>International Engineering Consortium. ''Digital Subscriber Line 2001''. Intl. Engineering Consortium, 2001, p. 40.</ref> and fiber-optic networks.\n\nVPNs can be characterized as ''host-to-network'' or ''remote access'' by connecting a single computer to a network or as ''site-to-site'' for connecting two networks. In a corporate setting, remote-access VPNs allow employees to access the company's [[intranet]] from outside the office. Site-to-site VPNs allow collaborators in geographically disparate offices to share the same virtual network. A VPN can also be used to interconnect two similar networks over a dissimilar intermediate network, such as two [[IPv6]] networks connected over an [[IPv4]] network.<ref>{{cite web|last=Technet Lab |title=IPv6 traffic over VPN connections |url=http://lab.technet.microsoft.com/en-us/magazine/cc138002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615203602/http://lab.technet.microsoft.com/en-us/magazine/cc138002 |archivedate=15 June 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nVPN systems may be classified by:\n* the tunneling protocol used to [[IP tunnel|tunnel]] the traffic\n* the tunnel's termination point location, e.g., on the customer [[Edge device|edge]] or network-provider edge\n* the type of topology of connections, such as site-to-site or network-to-network\n* the levels of security provided\n* the [[OSI model|OSI layer]] they present to the connecting network, such as Layer 2 circuits or Layer 3 network connectivity\n* the number of simultaneous connections\n\n==Security mechanisms==\nVPNs cannot make online connections completely anonymous, but they can usually increase privacy and security. To prevent disclosure of private information, VPNs typically allow only authenticated remote access using tunneling protocols and [[Encryption software|encryption]] techniques.\n\nThe VPN security model provides:\n* [[Information security#Confidentiality|confidentiality]] such that even if the network traffic is sniffed at the packet level (see [[Packet analyzer|network sniffer]] and [[deep packet inspection]]), an attacker would see only [[Encryption|encrypted data]]\n* sender [[authentication]] to prevent unauthorized users from accessing the VPN\n* message [[Data integrity|integrity]] to detect any instances of tampering with transmitted messages.\n[[File:IPSec VPN-en.svg|300px|thumb|The life cycle phases of an IPSec Tunnel in a virtual private network.]]\nSecure VPN protocols include the following:\n* [[Internet Protocol Security]] ([[Internet Protocol Security|IPsec]]) was initially developed by the [[Internet Engineering Task Force]] (IETF) for [[IPv6]], which was required in all standards-compliant implementations of [[IPv6]] before {{IETF RFC|6434}} made it only a recommendation.<ref name=rfc6434>{{IETF RFC|6434}}, \"IPv6 Node Requirements\", E. Jankiewicz, J. Loughney, T. Narten (December 2011)</ref> This standards-based security protocol is also widely used with [[IPv4]] and the [[Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol]]. Its design meets most security goals: [[Information security#Key concepts|availability, integrity, and confidentiality]]. IPsec uses encryption, encapsulating an IP packet inside an IPsec packet. De-encapsulation happens at the end of the tunnel, where the original IP packet is decrypted and forwarded to its intended destination.\n* [[Transport Layer Security]] ([[Transport Layer Security|SSL/TLS]]) can tunnel an entire network's traffic (as it does in the [[OpenVPN]] project and [[SoftEther VPN]] project<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.softether.org/1-features/1._Ultimate_Powerful_VPN_Connectivity#SoftEther_VPN's_Solution:_Using_HTTPS_Protocol_to_Establish_VPN_Tunnels|title=1. Ultimate Powerful VPN Connectivity |publisher=SoftEther VPN Project|website=www.softether.org}}</ref>) or secure an individual connection. A number of vendors provide remote-access VPN capabilities through SSL. An SSL VPN can connect from locations where IPsec runs into trouble with [[Network Address Translation]] and firewall rules.\n* [[Datagram Transport Layer Security]] ([[Datagram Transport Layer Security|DTLS]]) \u2013 used in Cisco [[AnyConnect]] VPN and in [[OpenConnect]] VPN<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infradead.org/openconnect/index.html |title = OpenConnect |accessdate =2013-04-08 |quote =<nowiki>OpenConnect is a client for Cisco's AnyConnect SSL VPN [...] OpenConnect is not officially supported by, or associated in any way with, Cisco Systems. It just happens to interoperate with their equipment.</nowiki>\n}}</ref> to solve the issues [[Transport Layer Security|SSL/TLS]] has with tunneling over [[Transmission Control Protocol|TCP]]  (tunneling TCP over TCP can lead to big delays and connection aborts<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sites.inka.de/~W1011/devel/tcp-tcp.html|title=Why TCP Over TCP Is A Bad Idea|website=sites.inka.de|access-date=2018-10-24}}</ref>).\n* [[Microsoft Point-to-Point Encryption]] ([[Microsoft Point-to-Point Encryption|MPPE]]) works with the [[Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol]] and in several compatible implementations on other platforms.\n* Microsoft [[Secure Socket Tunneling Protocol]] ([[Secure Socket Tunneling Protocol|SSTP]]) tunnels [[Point-to-Point Protocol]] (PPP) or Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol traffic through an [[Transport Layer Security|SSL]] 3.0 channel (SSTP was introduced in [[Windows Server 2008]] and in [[Windows Vista]] Service Pack 1).\n* Multi Path Virtual Private Network (MPVPN). Ragula Systems Development Company owns the registered [[trademark]] \"MPVPN\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tarr.uspto.gov/servlet/tarr?regser=serial&entry=78063238&action=Request+Status|title=Trademark Status & Document Retrieval|website=tarr.uspto.gov}}</ref>\n* Secure Shell (SSH) VPN \u2013 [[OpenSSH]] offers VPN tunneling (distinct from [[port forwarding]]) to secure remote connections to a network or to inter-network links. OpenSSH server provides a limited number of concurrent tunnels. The VPN feature itself does not support personal authentication.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://man.openbsd.org/ssh.1#SSH-BASED_VIRTUAL_PRIVATE_NETWORKS|title=ssh(1) \u2013 OpenBSD manual pages|website=man.openbsd.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cb.vu/unixtoolbox.xhtml#vpn|title=Unix Toolbox|first=Colin Barschel|last=c@cb.vu|website=cb.vu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://help.ubuntu.com/community/SSH_VPN|title=SSH_VPN \u2013 Community Help Wiki|website=help.ubuntu.com}}</ref>\n* [[WireGuard]]\n===Authentication===\nTunnel endpoints must be authenticated before secure VPN tunnels can be established. User-created remote-access VPNs may use [[passwords]], [[biometrics]], [[two-factor authentication]] or other [[cryptographic]] methods. Network-to-network tunnels often use passwords or [[digital certificates]]. They permanently store the key to allow the tunnel to establish automatically, without intervention from the administrator.\n\n==Routing==\nTunneling protocols can operate in a [[Point-to-point (telecommunications)|point-to-point]] [[network topology]] that would theoretically not be considered a VPN because a VPN by definition is expected to support arbitrary and changing sets of network nodes. But since most [[Router (computing)|router]] implementations support a software-defined tunnel interface, customer-provisioned VPNs often are simply defined tunnels running conventional routing protocols.\n\n===Provider-provisioned VPN building-blocks===\n[[File:Site-to-Site VPN terminology-en.svg|thumb|300px|Site-to-Site VPN terminology.]]\nDepending on whether a provider-provisioned VPN (PPVPN) operates in layer 2 or layer 3, the building blocks described below may be L2 only, L3 only, or a combination of both. [[Multiprotocol label switching|Multi-protocol label switching]] (MPLS) functionality blurs the L2-L3 identity.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}{{original research inline|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{IETF RFC|4026}} generalized the following terms to cover L2 and L3 VPNs, but they were introduced in {{IETF RFC|2547}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2547.txt |rfc=2547 |title=BGP/MPLS VPNs |author=E. Rosen & Y. Rekhter |date=March 1999 |publisher=Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) }}</ref> More information on the devices below can also be found in Lewis, Cisco Press.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Mark|title=Comparing, designing, and deploying VPNs|year=2006|publisher=Cisco Press|location=Indianapolis, Ind.|isbn=1587051796|pages=5\u20136|edition=1st print.}}</ref>\n\n; Customer (C) devices\nA device that is within a customer's network and not directly connected to the service provider's network. C devices are not aware of the VPN.\n\n; Customer Edge device (CE)\nA device at the edge of the customer's network which provides access to the PPVPN. Sometimes it is just a demarcation point between provider and customer responsibility. Other providers allow customers to configure it.\n\n; Provider edge device (PE)\nA device, or set of devices, at the edge of the provider network which connects to customer networks through CE devices and presents the provider's view of the customer site. PEs are aware of the VPNs that connect through them, and maintain VPN state.\n\n; Provider device (P)\nA device that operates inside the provider's core network and does not directly interface to any customer endpoint. It might, for example, provide routing for many provider-operated tunnels that belong to different customers' PPVPNs. While the P device is a key part of implementing PPVPNs, it is not itself VPN-aware and does not maintain VPN state. Its principal role is allowing the service provider to scale its PPVPN offerings, for example, by acting as an aggregation point for multiple PEs. P-to-P connections, in such a role, often are high-capacity optical links between major locations of providers.\n\n==User-visible PPVPN services==\n===OSI Layer 2 services===\n{{more citations needed section|date=August 2016}}\n;Virtual LAN\n[[Virtual LAN]] (VLAN) is a Layer 2 technique that allow for the coexistence of multiple [[local area network]] (LAN) broadcast domains interconnected via trunks using the [[IEEE 802.1Q]] trunking protocol. Other trunking protocols have been used but have become obsolete, including Inter-Switch Link (ISL), IEEE 802.10 (originally a security protocol but a subset was introduced for trunking), and ATM LAN Emulation (LANE).\n\n;Virtual private LAN service (VPLS)\nDeveloped by [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]], [[Virtual LAN]]s (VLANs) allow multiple tagged LANs to share common trunking. VLANs frequently comprise only customer-owned facilities. Whereas VPLS as described in the above section (OSI Layer 1 services) supports emulation of both point-to-point and point-to-multipoint topologies, the method discussed here extends Layer 2 technologies such as [[802.1d]] and [[802.1q]] LAN trunking to run over transports such as [[Metro Ethernet]].\n\nAs used in this context, a [[VPLS]] is a Layer 2 PPVPN, emulating the full functionality of a traditional LAN. From a user standpoint, a VPLS makes it possible to interconnect several LAN segments over a packet-switched, or optical, provider core, a core transparent to the user, making the remote LAN segments behave as one single LAN.<ref>{{citation |url=http://openvpn.net/index.php/access-server/howto-openvpn-as/214-how-to-setup-layer-2-ethernet-bridging.html |title=Ethernet Bridging (OpenVPN)}}</ref>\n\nIn a VPLS, the provider network emulates a learning bridge, which optionally may include VLAN service.\n\n;Pseudo wire (PW)\nPW is similar to VPLS, but it can provide different L2 protocols at both ends. Typically, its interface is a WAN protocol such as [[Asynchronous Transfer Mode]] or [[Frame Relay]]. In contrast, when aiming to provide the appearance of a LAN contiguous between two or more locations, the Virtual Private LAN service or IPLS would be appropriate.\n\n; Ethernet over IP tunneling\nEtherIP ({{IETF RFC|3378}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tools.ietf.org/search/rfc3378|title=EtherIP: Tunneling Ethernet Frames in IP Datagrams|first1=Scott|last1=Hollenbeck|first2=Russell|last2=Housley|publisher=}}</ref> is an Ethernet over IP tunneling protocol specification. EtherIP has only packet encapsulation mechanism. It has no confidentiality nor message integrity protection. EtherIP was introduced in the [[FreeBSD]] network stack<ref>Glyn M Burton: [https://securethoughts.com/9-rfc-3378-etherip-with-freebsd/ RFC 3378  EtherIP with FreeBSD], 03 February 2011</ref> and the [[SoftEther VPN]]<ref name=\"net-security.org\">net-security.org news: [http://www.net-security.org/secworld.php?id=16171 Multi-protocol SoftEther VPN becomes open source], January 2014</ref> server program.\n\n;IP-only LAN-like service (IPLS)\nA subset of VPLS, the CE devices must have Layer 3 capabilities; the IPLS presents packets rather than frames. It may support IPv4 or IPv6.\n\n===OSI Layer 3 PPVPN architectures===\nThis section discusses the main architectures for PPVPNs, one where the PE disambiguates duplicate addresses in a single routing instance, and the other, virtual router, in which the PE contains a virtual router instance per VPN. The former approach, and its variants, have gained the most attention.\n\nOne of the challenges of PPVPNs involves different customers using the same address space, especially the IPv4 private address space.<ref>[http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc1918.txt Address Allocation for Private Internets], {{IETF RFC|1918}}, Y. Rekhter ''et al.'', February 1996</ref> The provider must be able to disambiguate overlapping addresses in the multiple customers' PPVPNs.\n\n;BGP/MPLS PPVPN\nIn the method defined by {{IETF RFC|2547}}, BGP extensions advertise routes in the IPv4 VPN address family, which are of the form of 12-byte strings, beginning with an 8-byte [[route distinguisher]] (RD) and ending with a 4-byte IPv4 address. RDs disambiguate otherwise duplicate addresses in the same PE.\n\nPEs understand the topology of each VPN, which are interconnected with MPLS tunnels either directly or via P routers. In MPLS terminology, the P routers are [[Label Switch Router]]s without awareness of VPNs.\n\n;Virtual router PPVPN\nThe virtual router architecture,<ref>{{IETF RFC|2917}}, ''A Core MPLS IP VPN Architecture''</ref><ref>{{IETF RFC|2918}}, E. Chen (September 2000)</ref> as opposed to BGP/MPLS techniques, requires no modification to existing routing protocols such as BGP. By the provisioning of logically independent routing domains, the customer operating a VPN is completely responsible for the address space. In the various MPLS tunnels, the different PPVPNs are disambiguated by their label but do not need routing distinguishers.\n\n===Unencrypted tunnels===\nSome virtual networks use tunneling protocols without encryption for protecting the privacy of data. While VPNs often do provide security, an unencrypted [[overlay network]] does not neatly fit within the secure or trusted categorization.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Yanyan|date=2006|title=IPsec/VPN security policy correctness and assurance|journal=Journal of High Speed Networks|volume=15|pages=275\u2013289|citeseerx=10.1.1.94.8561}}</ref> For example, a tunnel set up between two hosts with [[Generic Routing Encapsulation]] (GRE) is a virtual private network but is neither secure nor trusted.<ref>{{cite web |title=Overview of Provider Provisioned Virtual Private Networks (PPVPN) |url=https://securethoughts.com/overview-provider-provisioned-virtual-private-networks-ppvpn/ |publisher=Secure Thoughts |accessdate = 29 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{IETF RFC|1702}}: Generic Routing Encapsulation over IPv4 networks. October 1994.</ref>\n\nNative [[plaintext]] tunneling protocols include Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) when it is set up without [[IPsec]] and [[Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol]] (PPTP) or [[Microsoft Point-to-Point Encryption]] (MPPE).<ref>IETF (1999), {{IETF RFC|2661}}, Layer Two Tunneling Protocol \"L2TP\"</ref>\n\n==Trusted delivery networks==\nTrusted VPNs do not use cryptographic tunneling; instead they rely on the security of a single provider's network to protect the traffic.<ref>{{cite book\n| author                =Cisco Systems, Inc.\n| title                 =Internetworking Technologies Handbook\n| url                   =https://books.google.com/books?id=3Dn9KlIVM_EC\n| accessdate            =2013-02-15\n| edition               =4\n| series                =Networking Technology Series\n| year                  =2004\n| publisher             =Cisco Press\n| isbn                  =9781587051197\n| page                  =233\n| quote                 =<nowiki>[...] VPNs using dedicated circuits, such as Frame Relay [...] are sometimes called </nowiki>''trusted VPN''s, because customers trust that the network facilities operated by the service providers will not be compromised.\n}}\n</ref>\n* [[Multi-Protocol Label Switching]] (MPLS) often overlays VPNs, often with quality-of-service control over a trusted delivery network.\n* L2TP<ref>[http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2661.txt Layer Two Tunneling Protocol \"L2TP\"], {{IETF RFC|2661}}, W. Townsley ''et al.'', August 1999</ref> which is a standards-based replacement, and a compromise taking the good features from each, for two proprietary VPN protocols: Cisco's [[L2F|Layer 2 Forwarding (L2F)]]<ref>[http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2341.txt IP Based Virtual Private Networks], {{IETF RFC|2341}}, A. Valencia ''et al.'', May 1998</ref> (obsolete {{As of | 2009 | alt =as of 2009}}) and Microsoft's [[Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol|Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol (PPTP)]].<ref>[http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2637.txt Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol (PPTP)], {{IETF RFC|2637}}, K. Hamzeh ''et al.'', July 1999</ref>\n\nFrom the security standpoint, VPNs either trust the underlying delivery network or must enforce security with mechanisms in the VPN itself. Unless the trusted delivery network runs among physically secure sites only, both trusted and secure models need an authentication mechanism for users to gain access to the VPN.\n\n== Types of deployment ==\n\n===VPNs in mobile environments===\nUsers utilize [[mobile virtual private network]]s in settings where an endpoint of the VPN is not fixed to a single [[IP address spoofing|IP address]], but instead roams across various networks such as data networks from cellular carriers or between multiple [[Wi-Fi]] access points without dropping the secure VPN session or losing application sessions.<ref name=\"Phifer\">Phifer, Lisa. [http://searchmobilecomputing.techtarget.com/tip/0,289483,sid40_gci1210989_mem1,00.html \"Mobile VPN: Closing the Gap\"], ''SearchMobileComputing.com'', July 16, 2006. <!--accessed November 10, 2009--></ref> Mobile VPNs are widely used in [[public safety]] where they give law-enforcement officers access to applications such as [[computer-assisted dispatch]] and criminal databases,<ref>Willett, Andy. [http://www.officer.com/print/Law-Enforcement-Technology/Solving-the-Computing-Challenges-of-Mobile-Officers/1$30992 \"Solving the Computing Challenges of Mobile Officers\"], ''www.officer.com'', May, 2006. <!--accessed November 10, 2009--></ref> and in other organizations with similar requirements such as [[Field service management]] and healthcare<ref name=\"Cheng\">Cheng, Roger. [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119717610996418467 \"Lost Connections\"], ''The Wall Street Journal'', December 11, 2007. <!--accessed November 10, 2009--></ref>{{qn|date=June 2018}}. Commercial mobile VPNs are frequently used for public Wi-Fi network safety.\n\n===VPN on routers===\nWith the increasing use of VPNs, many have started deploying VPN connectivity on routers for additional security and encryption of data transmission by using various cryptographic techniques.<ref>{{cite web|title = Encryption and Security Protocols in a VPN|url = http://computer.howstuffworks.com/vpn7.htm|accessdate = 2015-09-23}}</ref> Home users usually deploy VPNs on their routers to protect devices such as [[smart TV]]<nowiki/>s or [[Video game console|gaming consoles]], which are not supported by native VPN clients. Supported devices are not restricted to those capable of running a VPN client.<ref name=draytek>{{cite web |title=VPN |website=Draytek |date= |url=http://www.draytek.co.uk/information/our-technology/vpn-overview |author= |accessdate= 19 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany router manufacturers supply routers with built-in VPN clients. Some use open-source firmware such as [[DD-WRT]], [[OpenWRT]] and [[Tomato (firmware)|Tomato]] in order to support additional protocols such as [[OpenVPN]].\n\nSetting up VPN services on a router requires a deep knowledge of network security and careful installation. Minor misconfiguration of VPN connections can leave the network vulnerable. Performance will vary depending on the [[Internet service provider]] (ISP).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://searchenterprisewan.techtarget.com/answer/How-can-incorrectly-configuring-VPN-clients-lead-to-a-security-breach|title=How can incorrectly configuring VPN clients lead to a security breach?|work=SearchEnterpriseWAN|access-date=2018-08-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Networking limitations==\nA limitation of traditional VPNs is that they are point-to-point connections and do not tend to support [[broadcast domain]]s; therefore, communication, software, and networking, which are based on [[OSI layer|layer 2]] and broadcast [[Network packet|packets]], such as [[NetBIOS]] used in [[My Network Places|Windows networking]], may not be fully supported as on a [[local area network]]. Variants on VPN such as [[Virtual Private LAN Service]] (VPLS) and layer 2 tunneling protocols are designed to overcome this limitation.<ref>{{cite web |title= Virtual Private Networking: An Overview |url= https://hackercombat.com/virtual-private-network/ |date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial VPNs==\n{{see also|Comparison of virtual private network services}}\nA wide variety of commercial entities also sell \"VPNs\" for all kinds of purposes, but depending on the provider and the application, they may not create a true \"private network\" with anything meaningful on the local network. For example, a commercial VPN marketed for Internet access (censorship circumvention, anonymization, geo-unblocking) only needs to tunnel the user's internet traffic somewhere else securely and there is typically no way for a user's devices connected to the same \"VPN\" to see each other. These VPNs can be based on typical VPN protocols or more camouflaged VPN implementations like [[SoftEther VPN]], but proxy protocols like [[Shadowsocks]] are used as well.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hodge |first1=Rae |title=Proxy vs. VPN: If it's built into your browser, it might not be a true VPN |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/proxy-vs-vpn-if-its-built-into-your-browser-its-actually-not-a-true-vpn/ |website=CNET |accessdate=21 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Commercial VPNs are usually marketed as privacy protection software that offers additional encryption services.\n\nOn the client side, a commercial VPN setup, even those not using a conventional VPN protocol, typically use the operating system's VPN interfaces to capture a user's data to send through. This include virtual network adapters on computer OSes and specialized \"VPN\" interfaces on mobile operating systems. A less common alternative is to provide a [[SOCKS]] proxy interface.\n\n{{anchor|Public or private VPNs}}\nUsers must consider that when the transmitted content is not encrypted ''before'' entering a VPN, that data is visible at the receiving endpoint (usually the public VPN provider's site) regardless of whether the VPN tunnel ''wrapper'' itself is encrypted for the inter-node transport. The ''only'' secure VPN is where the participants have oversight at ''both'' ends of the entire data path, or the content is encrypted before it enters the tunnel provider.\n\n==Legality==\n{{see|VPN blocking}}\nUnapproved VPNs are reportedly illegal in China, as they can be used to circumvent the [[Great Firewall]]. (VPN refers to any protocol that tunnels traffic out elsewhere, as above.)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-vpns/businesses-consumers-uncertain-ahead-of-china-vpn-ban-idUSKBN1H612F|title=Businesses, consumers uncertain ahead of China VPN ban|work=Reuters|access-date=2018-04-03|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nBut vpns are seem to be legal because the apps that are used to make them are available on play Store and even on the phone it's shown and Vpns are used to monitor the network\nAnd some VPN are used to share,connect and do all other stuffs \nAnd many people are using Vpns\nAnd some use vpns because they are struggling to buy data bundles because they are money less\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anonymizer]]\n* [[Dynamic Multipoint Virtual Private Network]]\n* [[Internet privacy]]\n* [[Mediated VPN]]\n* [[Opportunistic encryption]]\n* [[Split tunneling]]\n* [[Virtual private server]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |date=August 2001 |title=Necessity is the mother of VPN invention |journal=Communication News |pages=26\u201328 |issn=0010-3632 |url=http://www.comnews.com/cgi-bin/arttop.asp?Page=c0801necessity.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20011217153420/http://www.comnews.com/cgi-bin/arttop.asp?Page=c0801necessity.htm |archivedate=2001-12-17 |last=Kelly |first=Sean}}\n\n{{VPN}}\n{{Cryptographic software}}\n{{Internet censorship circumvention technologies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Virtual Private Network}}\n[[Category:Network architecture]]\n[[Category:Computer network security]]\n[[Category:Internet privacy]]\n[[Category:Crypto-anarchism]]\n[[Category:Virtual private networks| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|VPN}}\n{{short description|Allows a private network to go through a public network}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n\n[[File:VPN overview-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|VPN connectivity overview]]\n\nA '''virtual private network''' ('''VPN''') extends a [[private network]] across a public network and enables users to send and receive data across shared or public networks as if their computing devices were directly connected to the private network. Applications running on an [[end system]] (PC, smartphone etc.) across a VPN may therefore benefit from the functionality, security, and management of the private network. [[Encryption]] is a common, though not an inherent, part of a VPN connection.<ref>{{cite book |author= Mason, Andrew G. |title=Cisco Secure Virtual Private Network |url= https://archive.org/details/ciscosecurevirtu00andr |url-access= registration |publisher= Cisco Press |date= 2002 |page= [https://archive.org/details/ciscosecurevirtu00andr/page/7 7]}}</ref>\n\nVPN technology was developed to allow remote users and branch offices to access corporate applications and resources. To ensure security, the private network connection is established using an encrypted layered [[tunneling protocol]], and VPN users use authentication methods, including passwords or certificates, to gain access to the VPN. In other applications, Internet users may secure their connections with a VPN to circumvent [[Geo-blocking|geo-restrictions]] and [[censorship]] or to connect to [[proxy server]]s to protect personal identity and location to stay anonymous on the Internet. Some websites, however, block access to known VPN technology to prevent the circumvention of their geo-restrictions, and many VPN providers have been developing strategies to get around these roadblocks.\n\nA VPN is created by establishing a virtual [[point-to-point (network topology)|point-to-point]] connection through the use of dedicated circuits or with tunneling protocols over existing networks. A VPN available from the public Internet can provide some of the benefits of a [[wide area network]] (WAN). From a user perspective, the resources available within the private network can be accessed remotely.<ref>{{cite web |publisher= [[Microsoft Technet]] |title= Virtual Private Networking: An Overview |url= https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb742566.aspx |date=September 4, 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Types==\n[[File:VPN classification-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|VPN classification based on the topology first, then on the technology used.]]\n[[File:Site-to-site VPN-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|A typical site-to-site VPN.]]\nEarly data networks allowed VPN-style connections to remote sites through [[dial-up modem]] or through [[leased line]] connections utilizing [[X.25]], [[Frame Relay]] and [[Asynchronous Transfer Mode]] (ATM) virtual circuits provided through networks owned and operated by [[Telephone company|telecommunication carriers]]. These networks are not considered true VPNs because they passively secure the data being transmitted by the creation of logical data streams.<ref>Cisco Systems, et al. ''Internet working Technologies Handbook, Third Edition''. Cisco Press, 2000, p. 232.</ref> They have been replaced by VPNs based on IP and IP/[[Multiprotocol Label Switching|Multi-protocol Label Switching]] (MPLS) Networks, due to significant cost-reductions and increased bandwidth<ref>Lewis, Mark. ''Comparing, Designing. And Deploying VPNs''. Cisco Press, 2006, p. 5</ref> provided by new technologies such as digital subscriber line (DSL)<ref>International Engineering Consortium. ''Digital Subscriber Line 2001''. Intl. Engineering Consortium, 2001, p. 40.</ref> and fiber-optic networks.\n\nVPNs can be characterized as ''host-to-network'' or ''remote access'' by connecting a single computer to a network or as ''site-to-site'' for connecting two networks. In a corporate setting, remote-access VPNs allow employees to access the company's [[intranet]] from outside the office. Site-to-site VPNs allow collaborators in geographically disparate offices to share the same virtual network. A VPN can also be used to interconnect two similar networks over a dissimilar intermediate network, such as two [[IPv6]] networks connected over an [[IPv4]] network.<ref>{{cite web|last=Technet Lab |title=IPv6 traffic over VPN connections |url=http://lab.technet.microsoft.com/en-us/magazine/cc138002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615203602/http://lab.technet.microsoft.com/en-us/magazine/cc138002 |archivedate=15 June 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nVPN systems may be classified by:\n* the tunneling protocol used to [[IP tunnel|tunnel]] the traffic\n* the tunnel's termination point location, e.g., on the customer [[Edge device|edge]] or network-provider edge\n* the type of topology of connections, such as site-to-site or network-to-network\n* the levels of security provided\n* the [[OSI model|OSI layer]] they present to the connecting network, such as Layer 2 circuits or Layer 3 network connectivity\n* the number of simultaneous connections\n\n==Security mechanisms==\nVPNs cannot make online connections completely anonymous, but they can usually increase privacy and security. To prevent disclosure of private information, VPNs typically allow only authenticated remote access using tunneling protocols and [[Encryption software|encryption]] techniques.\n\nThe VPN security model provides:\n* [[Information security#Confidentiality|confidentiality]] such that even if the network traffic is sniffed at the packet level (see [[Packet analyzer|network sniffer]] and [[deep packet inspection]]), an attacker would see only [[Encryption|encrypted data]]\n* sender [[authentication]] to prevent unauthorized users from accessing the VPN\n* message [[Data integrity|integrity]] to detect any instances of tampering with transmitted messages.\n[[File:IPSec VPN-en.svg|300px|thumb|The life cycle phases of an IPSec Tunnel in a virtual private network.]]\nSecure VPN protocols include the following:\n* [[Internet Protocol Security]] ([[Internet Protocol Security|IPsec]]) was initially developed by the [[Internet Engineering Task Force]] (IETF) for [[IPv6]], which was required in all standards-compliant implementations of [[IPv6]] before {{IETF RFC|6434}} made it only a recommendation.<ref name=rfc6434>{{IETF RFC|6434}}, \"IPv6 Node Requirements\", E. Jankiewicz, J. Loughney, T. Narten (December 2011)</ref> This standards-based security protocol is also widely used with [[IPv4]] and the [[Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol]]. Its design meets most security goals: [[Information security#Key concepts|availability, integrity, and confidentiality]]. IPsec uses encryption, encapsulating an IP packet inside an IPsec packet. De-encapsulation happens at the end of the tunnel, where the original IP packet is decrypted and forwarded to its intended destination.\n* [[Transport Layer Security]] ([[Transport Layer Security|SSL/TLS]]) can tunnel an entire network's traffic (as it does in the [[OpenVPN]] project and [[SoftEther VPN]] project<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.softether.org/1-features/1._Ultimate_Powerful_VPN_Connectivity#SoftEther_VPN's_Solution:_Using_HTTPS_Protocol_to_Establish_VPN_Tunnels|title=1. Ultimate Powerful VPN Connectivity |publisher=SoftEther VPN Project|website=www.softether.org}}</ref>) or secure an individual connection. A number of vendors provide remote-access VPN capabilities through SSL. An SSL VPN can connect from locations where IPsec runs into trouble with [[Network Address Translation]] and firewall rules.\n* [[Datagram Transport Layer Security]] ([[Datagram Transport Layer Security|DTLS]]) \u2013 used in Cisco [[AnyConnect]] VPN and in [[OpenConnect]] VPN<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infradead.org/openconnect/index.html |title = OpenConnect |accessdate =2013-04-08 |quote =<nowiki>OpenConnect is a client for Cisco's AnyConnect SSL VPN [...] OpenConnect is not officially supported by, or associated in any way with, Cisco Systems. It just happens to interoperate with their equipment.</nowiki>\n}}</ref> to solve the issues [[Transport Layer Security|SSL/TLS]] has with tunneling over [[Transmission Control Protocol|TCP]]  (tunneling TCP over TCP can lead to big delays and connection aborts<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sites.inka.de/~W1011/devel/tcp-tcp.html|title=Why TCP Over TCP Is A Bad Idea|website=sites.inka.de|access-date=2018-10-24}}</ref>).\n* [[Microsoft Point-to-Point Encryption]] ([[Microsoft Point-to-Point Encryption|MPPE]]) works with the [[Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol]] and in several compatible implementations on other platforms.\n* Microsoft [[Secure Socket Tunneling Protocol]] ([[Secure Socket Tunneling Protocol|SSTP]]) tunnels [[Point-to-Point Protocol]] (PPP) or Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol traffic through an [[Transport Layer Security|SSL]] 3.0 channel (SSTP was introduced in [[Windows Server 2008]] and in [[Windows Vista]] Service Pack 1).\n* Multi Path Virtual Private Network (MPVPN). Ragula Systems Development Company owns the registered [[trademark]] \"MPVPN\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tarr.uspto.gov/servlet/tarr?regser=serial&entry=78063238&action=Request+Status|title=Trademark Status & Document Retrieval|website=tarr.uspto.gov}}</ref>\n* Secure Shell (SSH) VPN \u2013 [[OpenSSH]] offers VPN tunneling (distinct from [[port forwarding]]) to secure remote connections to a network or to inter-network links. OpenSSH server provides a limited number of concurrent tunnels. The VPN feature itself does not support personal authentication.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://man.openbsd.org/ssh.1#SSH-BASED_VIRTUAL_PRIVATE_NETWORKS|title=ssh(1) \u2013 OpenBSD manual pages|website=man.openbsd.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cb.vu/unixtoolbox.xhtml#vpn|title=Unix Toolbox|first=Colin Barschel|last=c@cb.vu|website=cb.vu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://help.ubuntu.com/community/SSH_VPN|title=SSH_VPN \u2013 Community Help Wiki|website=help.ubuntu.com}}</ref>\n* [[WireGuard]]\n===Authentication===\nTunnel endpoints must be authenticated before secure VPN tunnels can be established. User-created remote-access VPNs may use [[passwords]], [[biometrics]], [[two-factor authentication]] or other [[cryptographic]] methods. Network-to-network tunnels often use passwords or [[digital certificates]]. They permanently store the key to allow the tunnel to establish automatically, without intervention from the administrator.\n\n==Routing==\nTunneling protocols can operate in a [[Point-to-point (telecommunications)|point-to-point]] [[network topology]] that would theoretically not be considered a VPN because a VPN by definition is expected to support arbitrary and changing sets of network nodes. But since most [[Router (computing)|router]] implementations support a software-defined tunnel interface, customer-provisioned VPNs often are simply defined tunnels running conventional routing protocols.\n\n===Provider-provisioned VPN building-blocks===\n[[File:Site-to-Site VPN terminology-en.svg|thumb|300px|Site-to-Site VPN terminology.]]\nDepending on whether a provider-provisioned VPN (PPVPN) operates in layer 2 or layer 3, the building blocks described below may be L2 only, L3 only, or a combination of both. [[Multiprotocol label switching|Multi-protocol label switching]] (MPLS) functionality blurs the L2-L3 identity.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}{{original research inline|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{IETF RFC|4026}} generalized the following terms to cover L2 and L3 VPNs, but they were introduced in {{IETF RFC|2547}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2547.txt |rfc=2547 |title=BGP/MPLS VPNs |author=E. Rosen & Y. Rekhter |date=March 1999 |publisher=Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) }}</ref> More information on the devices below can also be found in Lewis, Cisco Press.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Mark|title=Comparing, designing, and deploying VPNs|year=2006|publisher=Cisco Press|location=Indianapolis, Ind.|isbn=1587051796|pages=5\u20136|edition=1st print.}}</ref>\n\n; Customer (C) devices\nA device that is within a customer's network and not directly connected to the service provider's network. C devices are not aware of the VPN.\n\n; Customer Edge device (CE)\nA device at the edge of the customer's network which provides access to the PPVPN. Sometimes it is just a demarcation point between provider and customer responsibility. Other providers allow customers to configure it.\n\n; Provider edge device (PE)\nA device, or set of devices, at the edge of the provider network which connects to customer networks through CE devices and presents the provider's view of the customer site. PEs are aware of the VPNs that connect through them, and maintain VPN state.\n\n; Provider device (P)\nA device that operates inside the provider's core network and does not directly interface to any customer endpoint. It might, for example, provide routing for many provider-operated tunnels that belong to different customers' PPVPNs. While the P device is a key part of implementing PPVPNs, it is not itself VPN-aware and does not maintain VPN state. Its principal role is allowing the service provider to scale its PPVPN offerings, for example, by acting as an aggregation point for multiple PEs. P-to-P connections, in such a role, often are high-capacity optical links between major locations of providers.\n\n==User-visible PPVPN services==\n===OSI Layer 2 services===\n{{more citations needed section|date=August 2016}}\n;Virtual LAN\n[[Virtual LAN]] (VLAN) is a Layer 2 technique that allow for the coexistence of multiple [[local area network]] (LAN) broadcast domains interconnected via trunks using the [[IEEE 802.1Q]] trunking protocol. Other trunking protocols have been used but have become obsolete, including Inter-Switch Link (ISL), IEEE 802.10 (originally a security protocol but a subset was introduced for trunking), and ATM LAN Emulation (LANE).\n\n;Virtual private LAN service (VPLS)\nDeveloped by [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]], [[Virtual LAN]]s (VLANs) allow multiple tagged LANs to share common trunking. VLANs frequently comprise only customer-owned facilities. Whereas VPLS as described in the above section (OSI Layer 1 services) supports emulation of both point-to-point and point-to-multipoint topologies, the method discussed here extends Layer 2 technologies such as [[802.1d]] and [[802.1q]] LAN trunking to run over transports such as [[Metro Ethernet]].\n\nAs used in this context, a [[VPLS]] is a Layer 2 PPVPN, emulating the full functionality of a traditional LAN. From a user standpoint, a VPLS makes it possible to interconnect several LAN segments over a packet-switched, or optical, provider core, a core transparent to the user, making the remote LAN segments behave as one single LAN.<ref>{{citation |url=http://openvpn.net/index.php/access-server/howto-openvpn-as/214-how-to-setup-layer-2-ethernet-bridging.html |title=Ethernet Bridging (OpenVPN)}}</ref>\n\nIn a VPLS, the provider network emulates a learning bridge, which optionally may include VLAN service.\n\n;Pseudo wire (PW)\nPW is similar to VPLS, but it can provide different L2 protocols at both ends. Typically, its interface is a WAN protocol such as [[Asynchronous Transfer Mode]] or [[Frame Relay]]. In contrast, when aiming to provide the appearance of a LAN contiguous between two or more locations, the Virtual Private LAN service or IPLS would be appropriate.\n\n; Ethernet over IP tunneling\nEtherIP ({{IETF RFC|3378}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tools.ietf.org/search/rfc3378|title=EtherIP: Tunneling Ethernet Frames in IP Datagrams|first1=Scott|last1=Hollenbeck|first2=Russell|last2=Housley|publisher=}}</ref> is an Ethernet over IP tunneling protocol specification. EtherIP has only packet encapsulation mechanism. It has no confidentiality nor message integrity protection. EtherIP was introduced in the [[FreeBSD]] network stack<ref>Glyn M Burton: [https://securethoughts.com/9-rfc-3378-etherip-with-freebsd/ RFC 3378  EtherIP with FreeBSD], 03 February 2011</ref> and the [[SoftEther VPN]]<ref name=\"net-security.org\">net-security.org news: [http://www.net-security.org/secworld.php?id=16171 Multi-protocol SoftEther VPN becomes open source], January 2014</ref> server program.\n\n;IP-only LAN-like service (IPLS)\nA subset of VPLS, the CE devices must have Layer 3 capabilities; the IPLS presents packets rather than frames. It may support IPv4 or IPv6.\n\n===OSI Layer 3 PPVPN architectures===\nThis section discusses the main architectures for PPVPNs, one where the PE disambiguates duplicate addresses in a single routing instance, and the other, virtual router, in which the PE contains a virtual router instance per VPN. The former approach, and its variants, have gained the most attention.\n\nOne of the challenges of PPVPNs involves different customers using the same address space, especially the IPv4 private address space.<ref>[http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc1918.txt Address Allocation for Private Internets], {{IETF RFC|1918}}, Y. Rekhter ''et al.'', February 1996</ref> The provider must be able to disambiguate overlapping addresses in the multiple customers' PPVPNs.\n\n;BGP/MPLS PPVPN\nIn the method defined by {{IETF RFC|2547}}, BGP extensions advertise routes in the IPv4 VPN address family, which are of the form of 12-byte strings, beginning with an 8-byte [[route distinguisher]] (RD) and ending with a 4-byte IPv4 address. RDs disambiguate otherwise duplicate addresses in the same PE.\n\nPEs understand the topology of each VPN, which are interconnected with MPLS tunnels either directly or via P routers. In MPLS terminology, the P routers are [[Label Switch Router]]s without awareness of VPNs.\n\n;Virtual router PPVPN\nThe virtual router architecture,<ref>{{IETF RFC|2917}}, ''A Core MPLS IP VPN Architecture''</ref><ref>{{IETF RFC|2918}}, E. Chen (September 2000)</ref> as opposed to BGP/MPLS techniques, requires no modification to existing routing protocols such as BGP. By the provisioning of logically independent routing domains, the customer operating a VPN is completely responsible for the address space. In the various MPLS tunnels, the different PPVPNs are disambiguated by their label but do not need routing distinguishers.\n\n===Unencrypted tunnels===\nSome virtual networks use tunneling protocols without encryption for protecting the privacy of data. While VPNs often do provide security, an unencrypted [[overlay network]] does not neatly fit within the secure or trusted categorization.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Yanyan|date=2006|title=IPsec/VPN security policy correctness and assurance|journal=Journal of High Speed Networks|volume=15|pages=275\u2013289|citeseerx=10.1.1.94.8561}}</ref> For example, a tunnel set up between two hosts with [[Generic Routing Encapsulation]] (GRE) is a virtual private network but is neither secure nor trusted.<ref>{{cite web |title=Overview of Provider Provisioned Virtual Private Networks (PPVPN) |url=https://securethoughts.com/overview-provider-provisioned-virtual-private-networks-ppvpn/ |publisher=Secure Thoughts |accessdate = 29 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{IETF RFC|1702}}: Generic Routing Encapsulation over IPv4 networks. October 1994.</ref>\n\nNative [[plaintext]] tunneling protocols include Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) when it is set up without [[IPsec]] and [[Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol]] (PPTP) or [[Microsoft Point-to-Point Encryption]] (MPPE).<ref>IETF (1999), {{IETF RFC|2661}}, Layer Two Tunneling Protocol \"L2TP\"</ref>\n\n==Trusted delivery networks==\nTrusted VPNs do not use cryptographic tunneling; instead they rely on the security of a single provider's network to protect the traffic.<ref>{{cite book\n| author                =Cisco Systems, Inc.\n| title                 =Internetworking Technologies Handbook\n| url                   =https://books.google.com/books?id=3Dn9KlIVM_EC\n| accessdate            =2013-02-15\n| edition               =4\n| series                =Networking Technology Series\n| year                  =2004\n| publisher             =Cisco Press\n| isbn                  =9781587051197\n| page                  =233\n| quote                 =<nowiki>[...] VPNs using dedicated circuits, such as Frame Relay [...] are sometimes called </nowiki>''trusted VPN''s, because customers trust that the network facilities operated by the service providers will not be compromised.\n}}\n</ref>\n* [[Multi-Protocol Label Switching]] (MPLS) often overlays VPNs, often with quality-of-service control over a trusted delivery network.\n* L2TP<ref>[http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2661.txt Layer Two Tunneling Protocol \"L2TP\"], {{IETF RFC|2661}}, W. Townsley ''et al.'', August 1999</ref> which is a standards-based replacement, and a compromise taking the good features from each, for two proprietary VPN protocols: Cisco's [[L2F|Layer 2 Forwarding (L2F)]]<ref>[http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2341.txt IP Based Virtual Private Networks], {{IETF RFC|2341}}, A. Valencia ''et al.'', May 1998</ref> (obsolete {{As of | 2009 | alt =as of 2009}}) and Microsoft's [[Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol|Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol (PPTP)]].<ref>[http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2637.txt Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol (PPTP)], {{IETF RFC|2637}}, K. Hamzeh ''et al.'', July 1999</ref>\n\nFrom the security standpoint, VPNs either trust the underlying delivery network or must enforce security with mechanisms in the VPN itself. Unless the trusted delivery network runs among physically secure sites only, both trusted and secure models need an authentication mechanism for users to gain access to the VPN.\n\n== Types of deployment ==\n\n===VPNs in mobile environments===\nUsers utilize [[mobile virtual private network]]s in settings where an endpoint of the VPN is not fixed to a single [[IP address spoofing|IP address]], but instead roams across various networks such as data networks from cellular carriers or between multiple [[Wi-Fi]] access points without dropping the secure VPN session or losing application sessions.<ref name=\"Phifer\">Phifer, Lisa. [http://searchmobilecomputing.techtarget.com/tip/0,289483,sid40_gci1210989_mem1,00.html \"Mobile VPN: Closing the Gap\"], ''SearchMobileComputing.com'', July 16, 2006. <!--accessed November 10, 2009--></ref> Mobile VPNs are widely used in [[public safety]] where they give law-enforcement officers access to applications such as [[computer-assisted dispatch]] and criminal databases,<ref>Willett, Andy. [http://www.officer.com/print/Law-Enforcement-Technology/Solving-the-Computing-Challenges-of-Mobile-Officers/1$30992 \"Solving the Computing Challenges of Mobile Officers\"], ''www.officer.com'', May, 2006. <!--accessed November 10, 2009--></ref> and in other organizations with similar requirements such as [[Field service management]] and healthcare<ref name=\"Cheng\">Cheng, Roger. [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119717610996418467 \"Lost Connections\"], ''The Wall Street Journal'', December 11, 2007. <!--accessed November 10, 2009--></ref>{{qn|date=June 2018}}. Commercial mobile VPNs are frequently used for public Wi-Fi network safety.\n\n===VPN on routers===\nWith the increasing use of VPNs, many have started deploying VPN connectivity on routers for additional security and encryption of data transmission by using various cryptographic techniques.<ref>{{cite web|title = Encryption and Security Protocols in a VPN|url = http://computer.howstuffworks.com/vpn7.htm|accessdate = 2015-09-23}}</ref> Home users usually deploy VPNs on their routers to protect devices such as [[smart TV]]<nowiki/>s or [[Video game console|gaming consoles]], which are not supported by native VPN clients. Supported devices are not restricted to those capable of running a VPN client.<ref name=draytek>{{cite web |title=VPN |website=Draytek |date= |url=http://www.draytek.co.uk/information/our-technology/vpn-overview |author= |accessdate= 19 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany router manufacturers supply routers with built-in VPN clients. Some use open-source firmware such as [[DD-WRT]], [[OpenWRT]] and [[Tomato (firmware)|Tomato]] in order to support additional protocols such as [[OpenVPN]].\n\nSetting up VPN services on a router requires a deep knowledge of network security and careful installation. Minor misconfiguration of VPN connections can leave the network vulnerable. Performance will vary depending on the [[Internet service provider]] (ISP).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://searchenterprisewan.techtarget.com/answer/How-can-incorrectly-configuring-VPN-clients-lead-to-a-security-breach|title=How can incorrectly configuring VPN clients lead to a security breach?|work=SearchEnterpriseWAN|access-date=2018-08-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Networking limitations==\nA limitation of traditional VPNs is that they are point-to-point connections and do not tend to support [[broadcast domain]]s; therefore, communication, software, and networking, which are based on [[OSI layer|layer 2]] and broadcast [[Network packet|packets]], such as [[NetBIOS]] used in [[My Network Places|Windows networking]], may not be fully supported as on a [[local area network]]. Variants on VPN such as [[Virtual Private LAN Service]] (VPLS) and layer 2 tunneling protocols are designed to overcome this limitation.<ref>{{cite web |title= Virtual Private Networking: An Overview |url= https://hackercombat.com/virtual-private-network/ |date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial VPNs==\n{{see also|Comparison of virtual private network services}}\nA wide variety of commercial entities also sell \"VPNs\" for all kinds of purposes, but depending on the provider and the application, they may not create a true \"private network\" with anything meaningful on the local network. For example, a commercial VPN marketed for Internet access (censorship circumvention, anonymization, geo-unblocking) only needs to tunnel the user's internet traffic somewhere else securely and there is typically no way for a user's devices connected to the same \"VPN\" to see each other. These VPNs can be based on typical VPN protocols or more camouflaged VPN implementations like [[SoftEther VPN]], but proxy protocols like [[Shadowsocks]] are used as well.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hodge |first1=Rae |title=Proxy vs. VPN: If it's built into your browser, it might not be a true VPN |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/proxy-vs-vpn-if-its-built-into-your-browser-its-actually-not-a-true-vpn/ |website=CNET |accessdate=21 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Commercial VPNs are usually marketed as privacy protection software that offers additional encryption services.\n\nOn the client side, a commercial VPN setup, even those not using a conventional VPN protocol, typically use the operating system's VPN interfaces to capture a user's data to send through. This include virtual network adapters on computer OSes and specialized \"VPN\" interfaces on mobile operating systems. A less common alternative is to provide a [[SOCKS]] proxy interface.\n\n{{anchor|Public or private VPNs}}\nUsers must consider that when the transmitted content is not encrypted ''before'' entering a VPN, that data is visible at the receiving endpoint (usually the public VPN provider's site) regardless of whether the VPN tunnel ''wrapper'' itself is encrypted for the inter-node transport. The ''only'' secure VPN is where the participants have oversight at ''both'' ends of the entire data path, or the content is encrypted before it enters the tunnel provider.\n\n==Legality==\n{{see|VPN blocking}}\nUnapproved VPNs are reportedly illegal in China, as they can be used to circumvent the [[Great Firewall]]. (VPN refers to any protocol that tunnels traffic out elsewhere, as above.)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-vpns/businesses-consumers-uncertain-ahead-of-china-vpn-ban-idUSKBN1H612F|title=Businesses, consumers uncertain ahead of China VPN ban|work=Reuters|access-date=2018-04-03|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anonymizer]]\n* [[Dynamic Multipoint Virtual Private Network]]\n* [[Internet privacy]]\n* [[Mediated VPN]]\n* [[Opportunistic encryption]]\n* [[Split tunneling]]\n* [[Virtual private server]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |date=August 2001 |title=Necessity is the mother of VPN invention |journal=Communication News |pages=26\u201328 |issn=0010-3632 |url=http://www.comnews.com/cgi-bin/arttop.asp?Page=c0801necessity.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20011217153420/http://www.comnews.com/cgi-bin/arttop.asp?Page=c0801necessity.htm |archivedate=2001-12-17 |last=Kelly |first=Sean}}\n\n{{VPN}}\n{{Cryptographic software}}\n{{Internet censorship circumvention technologies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Virtual Private Network}}\n[[Category:Network architecture]]\n[[Category:Computer network security]]\n[[Category:Internet privacy]]\n[[Category:Crypto-anarchism]]\n[[Category:Virtual private networks| ]]\n", "name_user": "41.115.63.179", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLegality)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_private_network"}
{"title_page": "William Howard Melish", "text_new": "{{short description|American Christian socialist leader (1873\u20131966)}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Episcopalian\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name             = Wiliam Howard Melish\n| honorific_suffix = \n| title            = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = Holy Trinity Church, Brooklyn (renamed [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]])\n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| elected          = <!-- or | appointed = -->\n| term             = <!-- or term_start / term_end -->\n| quashed          = <!-- or | retired = -->\n| predecessor      =\n| successor        = \n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = \n---------- Personal details ----------\n| birth_name       = Wiliam Howard Melish\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1910|5|11}}\n| baptised         = <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1986|6|15|1910|5|11}}\n| death_place      = [[Boerum Hill]], [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| buried           = <!-- or | tomb = -->\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality      = American\n| religion         = [[Episcopalianism]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = John Howard Melish\n| spouse           = Mary Jane Dietz\n| children         = 3 sons\n| occupation       = Episcopalian assistant rector, civil rights activist\n| profession       = <!-- or | previous_post = -->\n| education        =  [[Harvard University]], [[Cambridge University]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Episcopal Theological School]]\n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n}}\nReverend '''Wiliam Howard Melish''' (1874-1969) was an 20th-century American Episcopalian and social leader.<ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite news\n| first = Wolfgang\n| last = Saxon\n| title = Rev. W. Howard Melish, 76, Dies; Ousted at Parish in McCarthy Era\n| newspaper = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1986/06/16/obituaries/rev-w-howard-melish-76-dies-ousted-at-parish-in-mccarthy-era.html\n| page = B12\n| date = 16 June 1986\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=CRDL>\n{{cite web\n| title = Melish, William Howard, 1910-\n| newspaper = Civil Rights Digital Library\n| url = http://crdl.usg.edu/people/m/melish_william_howard_1910/?Welcome\n| date = 2013\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=BHS>\n{{cite web\n| title = Guide to the John Howard Melish, William Howard Melish and Protestant Episcopal Church of the Holy Trinity collection ARC.050\n| publisher = Brooklyn Historical Society\n| url = http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html\n| date = 15 February 2012\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=SNAC>\n{{cite web\n| title = Church of the Holy Trinity (Brooklyn, New York, N.Y.)\n| publisher = Social Networks and Archival Context\n| url = http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html\n| date =\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nWilliam Howard Melish was born on May 11, 1910, in [[Brooklyn, New York]].  His parents were was Dr. [http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,794688,00.html John Howard Melish] and Marguerite McComas.<ref name=JADE>\n{{cite web\n| title = Melish, John Howard (1874-1969)\n| publisher = Jane Addams Digital Edition\n| url = https://digital.janeaddams.ramapo.edu/items/show/3723\n| date = 2010\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>  He studied at [[Harvard University]] and then studied for the priesthood at [[Jesus College]], [[Cambridge University]], and at the [[Episcopal Theological School]].<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=BHS/>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Ann n Holy Trinity CoE Montague St jeh.jpg|thumb|right|Melish led Holy Trinity Episcopal Church, depicted here as [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]] in [[Brooklyn Heights, New York]].]]\nIn 1935, Melish began his ministry at Christ Church in Cincinnati, Ohio.  In 1938, he joined his father as assistant rector at the Holy Trinity Church in Brooklyn.  Melish served as assistant rector from 1938 to 1958; his father was rector there from 1904 until his ouster in 1949.<ref name=BHS/><ref name=SNAC/>\n\n===Political and civil activism===\n[[File:Joseph McCarthy adjusted.jpg|thumb|right|US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] expressed concern with Melish over his chairmanship of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]].]]\nIn the 1940s, Melish joined the [[American Labor Party]] (then, affiliated with the [[Communist Party USA]]).  Melish was also a founding member of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]]<ref name=CRDL/>  Melish was also editor for the council's biweekly publication, ''Reporter (CPUSA)'' (an [[English-language press of the Communist Party USA]] publication).\n\nIn the same period, Melish supported the civil rights movement in the South; he served as a regional representative for ''Southern Patriot''  monthly periodical of the Southern Conference Educational Fund (successor to the [[Southern Conference for Human Welfare]]).<ref name=CRDL/>\n\n===Ouster===\n[[File:James_P._deWolfe.jpg|thumb|right|Bishop [[James P. DeWolfe]] of Long Island opposed Melish's chairmanship of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]].]]\nMr. Melish's chairmanship (1947\u20131951) of the National Council of American-Soviet Friendship led both him and his father into a \"bitter struggle\" in the 1940s and 1950s that divided their parish as the council wound up on the [[Attorney General's List of Subversive Organizations]] (AGLOSO) in December 1947.  US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] investigated Melish as chairman of the council.  In 1957, Bishop [[James P. DeWolfe]] of the Episcopal Diocese of Long Island closed the Holy Trinity Church in Brooklyn in 1957 and ousted Melish, who had taken over from his father in 1949.  The bishop closed the church until a new congregation claimed it as \"[[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]].\"<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=BHS/>\n\n===''Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish''===\n\nThe rector, church wardens, and vestrymen of the Church of the Holy Trinity in Brooklyn sued Melish and his father to leave; they refused.  On June 24, 1957, the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of New York, Second Department, found in favor of the church.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish\n| publisher = CaseText\n| url = https://casetext.com/case/rector-church-of-holy-trinity-v-melish-1\n| date = 24 June 1957\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>    On March 26, 1958, the Supreme Court of [[Kings County, New York]], heard ''Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish''.  Hubbell and Davies represented the plaintiffs; Raphael H. Weissman and Hubert T. Delaney represented Melish.  The supreme court found in favor of the plaintiffs.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish\n| publisher = Leagle\n| url = https://www.leagle.com/decision/195833312misc2d3211224\n| date = 1958\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>  The case received press coverage, including ''Life'' magazine.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = 'Mr. Melish, You Are Out of Order'\n| magazine = Life\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=gT8EAAAAMBAJ\n| pages = 57-58\n| date = 30 January 1956\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Later life===\n\nAfter his ouster, Melish and his wife both visited the Soviet Union six times.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn 1963, Melish delivered an address at the memorial for [[W.E.B. DuBois]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Address delivered by the Rev. William Howard Melish at the memorial service of the late Dr. W. E. B. Du Bois at the Affrey Memorial Church, Achimota College, Accra, Ghana, ca. September 23, 1963\n| publisher = University of Massachusetts Amherst\n| url = https://credo.library.umass.edu/view/full/mums312-b287-i012\n| date = 23 September 1963\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, Melish became rector of [[Grace Episcopal Church Complex (Queens)]] for a decade until he retired in 1979.  He then returned to his Brooklyn church as an assisting priest until he died.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn 1971, Melish again became chairman of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]] until 1978.\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nMelish married Mary Jane Dietz; they had three sons.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish advocated civil rights.  He also advocated peaceful co-existence with the [[USSR]], which in July 1948 formed part of the foreign plank of the platform of the [[1948 Progressive Party of the United States].<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish lived in the [[Boerum Hill]] section of Brooklyn, New York.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish died age 76 on June 15, 1986, in Brooklyn.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Awards==\n\n* 1956:  [[World Peace Prize|International Peace Prize]] of the [[World Peace Council]]|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/04/28/archives/melish-is-honored-reddominated-world-peace-council-awards-prize.html|title=Melish is Honored; Red-Dominated World Peace Council Awards Prize|date=28 April 1956|page=6|accessdate=19 July 2010|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]] \n* [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.digitalcommonwealth.org/search?f%5Bname_facet_ssim%5D%5B%5D=Melish%2C+William+Howard%2C+1910- Digital Commonweath]\n* [http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html Brooklyn Historical Society]: Guide to the John Howard Melish, William Howard Melish and Protestant Episcopal Church of the Holy Trinity collection ARC.050\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/bud1929/6823486340 William Howard Melish (undated)]\n\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Episcopalian ministers]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York]]\n[[Category:American Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:American ethicists]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalian clergy]]\n[[Category:Christian clergy from New York]]\n[[Category:Christian ethicists]]\n[[Category:Christians from New York]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Episcopalian socialists]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from New York]]\n[[Category:Episcopal Theological School alumni]]\n\n {{US-Christian-clergy-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American Christian socialist leader (1873\u20131966)}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Episcopalian\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name             = Wiliam Howard Melish\n| honorific_suffix = \n| title            = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| church           = Holy Trinity Church, Brooklyn (renamed [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]])\n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| elected          = <!-- or | appointed = -->\n| term             = <!-- or term_start / term_end -->\n| quashed          = <!-- or | retired = -->\n| predecessor      =\n| successor        = \n| opposed          = \n| other_post       = \n---------- Personal details ----------\n| birth_name       = Wiliam Howard Melish\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1910|5|11}}\n| baptised         = <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1986|6|15|1910|5|11}}\n| death_place      = [[Boerum Hill]], [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| buried           = <!-- or | tomb = -->\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality      = American\n| religion         = [[Episcopalianism]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = John Howard Melish\n| spouse           = Mary Jane Dietz\n| children         = 3 sons\n| occupation       = Episcopalian assistant rector, civil rights activist\n| profession       = <!-- or | previous_post = -->\n| education        =  [[Harvard University]], [[Cambridge University]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Episcopal Theological School]]\n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n}}\nReverend '''Wiliam Howard Melish''' (1874-1969) was an 20th-century American Episcopalian and social leader.<ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite news\n| first = Wolfgang\n| last = Saxon\n| title = Rev. W. Howard Melish, 76, Dies; Ousted at Parish in McCarthy Era\n| newspaper = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1986/06/16/obituaries/rev-w-howard-melish-76-dies-ousted-at-parish-in-mccarthy-era.html\n| page = B12\n| date = 16 June 1986\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=CRDL>\n{{cite web\n| title = Melish, William Howard, 1910-\n| newspaper = Civil Rights Digital Library\n| url = http://crdl.usg.edu/people/m/melish_william_howard_1910/?Welcome\n| date = 2013\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=BHS>\n{{cite web\n| title = Guide to the John Howard Melish, William Howard Melish and Protestant Episcopal Church of the Holy Trinity collection ARC.050\n| publisher = Brooklyn Historical Society\n| url = http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html\n| date = 15 February 2012\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=SNAC>\n{{cite web\n| title = Church of the Holy Trinity (Brooklyn, New York, N.Y.)\n| publisher = Social Networks and Archival Context\n| url = http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html\n| date =\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nWilliam Howard Melish was born on May 11, 1910, in [[Brooklyn, New York]].  His parents were was Dr. [[John Howard Melish]] and Marguerite McComas.<ref name=JADE>\n{{cite web\n| title = Melish, John Howard (1874-1969)\n| publisher = Jane Addams Digital Edition\n| url = https://digital.janeaddams.ramapo.edu/items/show/3723\n| date = 2010\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>  He studied at [[Harvard University]] and then studied for the priesthood at [[Jesus College]], [[Cambridge University]], and at the [[Episcopal Theological School]].<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=BHS/>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Ann n Holy Trinity CoE Montague St jeh.jpg|thumb|right|Melish led Holy Trinity Episcopal Church, depicted here as [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]] in [[Brooklyn Heights, New York]].]]\nIn 1935, Melish began his ministry at Christ Church in Cincinnati, Ohio.  In 1938, he joined his father as assistant rector at the Holy Trinity Church in Brooklyn.  Melish served as assistant rector from 1938 to 1958; his father was rector there from 1904 until his ouster in 1949.<ref name=BHS/><ref name=SNAC/>\n\n===Political and civil activism===\n[[File:Joseph McCarthy adjusted.jpg|thumb|right|US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] expressed concern with Melish over his chairmanship of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]].]]\nIn the 1940s, Melish joined the [[American Labor Party]] (then, affiliated with the [[Communist Party USA]]).  Melish was also a founding member of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]]<ref name=CRDL/>  Melish was also editor for the council's biweekly publication, ''Reporter (CPUSA)'' (an [[English-language press of the Communist Party USA]] publication).\n\nIn the same period, Melish supported the civil rights movement in the South; he served as a regional representative for ''Southern Patriot''  monthly periodical of the Southern Conference Educational Fund (successor to the [[Southern Conference for Human Welfare]]).<ref name=CRDL/>\n\n===Ouster===\n[[File:James_P._deWolfe.jpg|thumb|right|Bishop [[James P. DeWolfe]] of Long Island opposed Melish's chairmanship of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]].]]\nMr. Melish's chairmanship (1947\u20131951) of the National Council of American-Soviet Friendship led both him and his father into a \"bitter struggle\" in the 1940s and 1950s that divided their parish as the council wound up on the [[Attorney General's List of Subversive Organizations]] (AGLOSO) in December 1947.  US Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] investigated Melish as chairman of the council.  In 1957, Bishop [[James P. DeWolfe]] of the Episcopal Diocese of Long Island closed the Holy Trinity Church in Brooklyn in 1957 and ousted Melish, who had taken over from his father in 1949.  The bishop closed the church until a new congregation claimed it as \"[[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]].\"<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=BHS/>\n\n===''Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish''===\n\nThe rector, church wardens, and vestrymen of the Church of the Holy Trinity in Brooklyn sued Melish and his father to leave; they refused.  On June 24, 1957, the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of New York, Second Department, found in favor of the church.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish\n| publisher = CaseText\n| url = https://casetext.com/case/rector-church-of-holy-trinity-v-melish-1\n| date = 24 June 1957\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>    On March 26, 1958, the Supreme Court of [[Kings County, New York]], heard ''Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish''.  Hubbell and Davies represented the plaintiffs; Raphael H. Weissman and Hubert T. Delaney represented Melish.  The supreme court found in favor of the plaintiffs.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Rector, Holy Trinity v. Melish\n| publisher = Leagle\n| url = https://www.leagle.com/decision/195833312misc2d3211224\n| date = 1958\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>  The case received press coverage, including ''Life'' magazine.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = 'Mr. Melish, You Are Out of Order'\n| magazine = Life\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=gT8EAAAAMBAJ\n| pages = 57-58\n| date = 30 January 1956\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Later life===\n\nAfter his ouster, Melish and his wife both visited the Soviet Union six times.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn 1963, Melish delivered an address at the memorial for [[W.E.B. DuBois]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Address delivered by the Rev. William Howard Melish at the memorial service of the late Dr. W. E. B. Du Bois at the Affrey Memorial Church, Achimota College, Accra, Ghana, ca. September 23, 1963\n| publisher = University of Massachusetts Amherst\n| url = https://credo.library.umass.edu/view/full/mums312-b287-i012\n| date = 23 September 1963\n| accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, Melish became rector of [[Grace Episcopal Church Complex (Queens)]] for a decade until he retired in 1979.  He then returned to his Brooklyn church as an assisting priest until he died.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn 1971, Melish again became chairman of the [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]] until 1978.\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nMelish married Mary Jane Dietz; they had three sons.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish advocated civil rights.  He also advocated peaceful co-existence with the [[USSR]], which in July 1948 formed part of the foreign plank of the platform of the [[1948 Progressive Party of the United States].<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish lived in the [[Boerum Hill]] section of Brooklyn, New York.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nMelish died age 76 on June 15, 1986, in Brooklyn.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Awards==\n\n* 1956:  [[World Peace Prize|International Peace Prize]] of the [[World Peace Council]]|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/04/28/archives/melish-is-honored-reddominated-world-peace-council-awards-prize.html|title=Melish is Honored; Red-Dominated World Peace Council Awards Prize|date=28 April 1956|page=6|accessdate=19 July 2010|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[National Council of American-Soviet Friendship]] \n* [[St. Ann & the Holy Trinity Church]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.digitalcommonwealth.org/search?f%5Bname_facet_ssim%5D%5B%5D=Melish%2C+William+Howard%2C+1910- Digital Commonweath]\n* [http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/bhs/arc_050_melish/bioghist.html Brooklyn Historical Society]: Guide to the John Howard Melish, William Howard Melish and Protestant Episcopal Church of the Holy Trinity collection ARC.050\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/bud1929/6823486340 William Howard Melish (undated)]\n\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Episcopalian ministers]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York]]\n[[Category:American Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:American ethicists]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalian clergy]]\n[[Category:Christian clergy from New York]]\n[[Category:Christian ethicists]]\n[[Category:Christians from New York]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Episcopalian socialists]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from New York]]\n[[Category:Episcopal Theological School alumni]]\n\n {{US-Christian-clergy-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Aboudaqn", "label": "safe", "comment": "added URL", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Howard_Melish"}
{"title_page": "Joel Baxley", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman and government official}}\n{{Orphan|date=February 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Joel Baxley\n| image = \n| office = Acting [[Assistant to the Secretary for Rural Development]]\n| term_start = February 7, 2019\n| term_end = \n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| predecessor = Anne Hazlett\n| successor = \n| party = Republican\n| birth_name = Joel Clinton Baxley \n| birth_date = \n| education = [[University of Alabama]] {{small|([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])}}, [[University of Oxford]] {{small|([[Postgraduate diploma|PgD]])}},\n}}\n\n'''Joel C. Baxley''' is an American businessman and government official who currently serves as the Acting [[Assistant to the Secretary for Rural Development]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBaxley was born and raised in [[Bay County, Florida]] and received a [[Master of Business Administration]] from the [[University of Alabama]]. He later went on to earn a postgraduate diploma in financial strategy from the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=\"who\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rd.usda.gov/about-rd/leadership/administrators/joel-c-baxley|title=Joel C. Baxley|website=[[USDA]]|publisher=[[U.S. Government]]|archivedate=January 11, 2019|url-status=dead|accessdate=February 13, 2019|df=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111043326/https://www.rd.usda.gov/about-rd/leadership/administrators/joel-c-baxley}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBaxley served as the managing partner of Baxley Property Advisors, LLC before holding the titles of Consulting Services Director and the senior real estate technical consultant with RSM US LLP's Financial Advisory Services consulting practice. He eventually rose to become Administrator of USDA Rural Development's Rural Housing Service.<ref name=\"who\"/> In 2019, he was  by Sec. [[Sonny Perdue]] to replace Assistant to the Secretary for Rural Development Anne Hazlett, who was named the Senior Adviser at the White House Office of National Drug Control Policy.<ref name=\"wh\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2019/02/07/hazlett-named-senior-adviser-white-house-office-national-drug|title=Hazlett Named Senior Adviser at the White House Office of National Drug Control Policy|website=[[USDA]]|publisher=[[U.S. Government]]|archivedate=February 15, 2019|url-status=dead|accessdate=February 13, 2019|df=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215102814/https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2019/02/07/hazlett-named-senior-adviser-white-house-office-national-drug}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBaxley is married and has three children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off\n}}{{s-bef|before=Anne Hazlett}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Acting [[Assistant to the Secretary for Rural Development]]\n| years = 2019\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baxley, Joel}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama alumni]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Agriculture officials]]\n[[Category:People from Bay County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman and government official}}\n{{Orphan|date=February 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Joel Baxley\n| image = \n| office = Acting [[Assistant to the Secretary for Rural Development]]\n| term_start = February 7, 2019\n| term_end = \n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| predecessor = Anne Hazlett\n| successor = \n| party = Republican\n| birth_name = Joel Clinton Baxley \n| birth_date = \n| education = [[University of Alabama]] {{small|([[Masters of Business Administration|MBA]])}}, [[University of Oxford]] {{small|([[Postgraduate diploma|PgD]])}},\n}}\n\n'''Joel C. Baxley''' is an American businessman and government official who currently serves as the Acting [[Assistant to the Secretary for Rural Development]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBaxley was born and raised in [[Bay County, Florida]] and received a [[Master of Business Administration]] from the [[University of Alabama]]. He later went on to earn a postgraduate diploma in financial strategy from the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=\"who\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rd.usda.gov/about-rd/leadership/administrators/joel-c-baxley|title=Joel C. Baxley|website=[[USDA]]|publisher=[[U.S. Government]]|archivedate=January 11, 2019|url-status=dead|accessdate=February 13, 2019|df=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111043326/https://www.rd.usda.gov/about-rd/leadership/administrators/joel-c-baxley}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBaxley served as the managing partner of Baxley Property Advisors, LLC before holding the titles of Consulting Services Director and the senior real estate technical consultant with RSM US LLP's Financial Advisory Services consulting practice. He eventually rose to become Administrator of USDA Rural Development's Rural Housing Service.<ref name=\"who\"/> In 2019, he was  by Sec. [[Sonny Perdue]] to replace Assistant to the Secretary for Rural Development Anne Hazlett, who was named the Senior Adviser at the White House Office of National Drug Control Policy.<ref name=\"wh\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2019/02/07/hazlett-named-senior-adviser-white-house-office-national-drug|title=Hazlett Named Senior Adviser at the White House Office of National Drug Control Policy|website=[[USDA]]|publisher=[[U.S. Government]]|archivedate=February 15, 2019|url-status=dead|accessdate=February 13, 2019|df=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215102814/https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2019/02/07/hazlett-named-senior-adviser-white-house-office-national-drug}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBaxley is married and has three children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off\n}}{{s-bef|before=Anne Hazlett}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Acting [[Assistant to the Secretary for Rural Development]]\n| years = 2019\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baxley, Joel}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama alumni]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Agriculture officials]]\n[[Category:People from Bay County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joel_Baxley"}
{"title_page": "John Wayne Gacy", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Gacy}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{pp-semi-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American serial killer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name = John Wayne Gacy\n| alias = \n| image = File:John Wayne Gacy.jpg\n| caption = John Wayne Gacy in May 1978\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1942|03|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], US\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1994|05|10|1942|03|17}}\n| death_place = [[Stateville Correctional Center]], [[Crest Hill, Illinois]], US\n| cause = [[Lethal injection|Execution by lethal injection]]\n| victims = 33+\n| parents = \n| party =\n| spouse = \n| children = 2\n| height = 5 ft 9 in{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=5}}\n| country = United States\n| states = Illinois\n| beginyear = 1972\n| endyear =  1978\n| apprehended = December 21, 1978\n| conviction = {{unbulleted list|1 count of [[sodomy]]|33 counts of [[murder]]|1 count of [[sexual assault]]|1 count of [[Child abuse|indecent liberties with a child]]}} | sentence = [[Capital punishment|Death]] (12 counts)<br />\n| imprisoned =\n[[Menard Correctional Center]]\n}}\n'''John Wayne Gacy''' (March 17, 1942&nbsp;\u2013 May 10, 1994) was an American [[serial killer]] and [[sex offender]] known as the '''Killer Clown''' who assaulted and murdered at least 33 young men and boys. Gacy regularly performed at children's hospitals and charitable events as \"Pogo the Clown\" or \"Patches the Clown\", clowning persona he devised. He was also active in his local community as a precinct captain and building contractor.\n\nIt is believed all of Gacy's known murders were committed inside his [[Ranch-style house|ranch house]] in [[Norwood Park Township, Cook County, Illinois|Norwood Park]], a part of [[Chicago metropolitan area|metropolitan Chicago]]. Gacy would typically lure a victim to his home, dupe him into donning [[handcuffs]] on the pretext of demonstrating a [[Magic (illusion)|magic trick]], then rape and torture his captive before killing him by either [[asphyxiation]] or [[strangulation]] with a [[garrote]]. Twenty-six victims were buried in the [[crawl space]] of his home, three others were buried elsewhere on his property, and the last four were discarded in the [[Des Plaines River]].\n\nGacy was convicted of the [[sodomy]] of a teenage boy in Iowa in 1968. He was sentenced to 10 years' imprisonment, but was released after 18 months. He first murdered in 1972, and at least 29 subsequent victims were killed after his divorce from his second wife in 1976. Investigation into the disappearance of [[Des Plaines, Illinois|Des Plaines]] teenager Robert Piest led to Gacy's arrest on December 21, 1978.\n\nThe conviction for 33 murders was the largest number of murders charged to one individual in United States until that time. Gacy was sentenced to death on March 13, 1980. On death row at [[Menard Correctional Center]] he spent much of his time painting. He was executed by [[lethal injection]] at [[Stateville Correctional Center]] on May 10, 1994.\n\n==Early life==\nJohn Wayne Gacy was born in Chicago, [[Illinois]] on March 17, 1942, the second child and only son of John Stanley Gacy (June 20, 1900 \u2013 December 25, 1969) and Marion Elaine Robinson (May 4, 1908 \u2013 December 6, 1989).<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 63.</ref> His father was an auto repair machinist and [[World War I]] veteran,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=24}} and his mother was a homemaker.<ref>Cook County marriage records provide his mother's name as Marion E. Robertson; {{cite web | title=Cook County, Illinois Marriage Index, 1930\u20131960. Cook County Clerk Genealogy Records. Cook County Clerk's Office, Chicago, IL |url=http://www.ancestry.com/search/db.aspx?dbid=1500&enc=1 |year=2008}}</ref>{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=67}} Gacy was of [[Poles|Polish]] and [[Danes|Danish]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/john-wayne-gacy-10367544|title=John Wayne Gacy Biography|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=February 11, 2019|website=The Biography.com website|publisher=A&amp;E Television Networks|orig-year=April 2, 2014|access-date=April 5, 2019}}</ref> His paternal grandparents (who spelled the family name as \"Gatza\" or \"Gaca\") had immigrated to the United States from [[Poland]] (then part of [[Prussia]] in [[German Empire|Germany]]).<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 51.</ref>{{sfn|Ressler|Schactman|1992|pp=207\u2013218}}\n \n===Childhood===\nAs a child, Gacy was overweight and not athletic. He was close to his two sisters and mother but endured a difficult relationship with his father, an [[alcoholic]] who was [[physical abuse|physically abusive]] to his wife and children.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=256\u2013257}} Gacy seldom received his father's approval, later recollecting that, no matter what he achieved, he was \"never good enough\" in his father's eyes.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=31}}  His father regularly belittled him, calling him \"dumb and stupid\" and comparing him unfavorably with his sisters.<ref>''Serial Killers.'' pp. 54\u201355.</ref> Despite this, Gacy always denied ever hating his father.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=21}} \n\nOne of Gacy's earliest childhood memories was of being beaten with a leather belt at the age of four for accidentally disarranging car engine components his father had assembled.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=18\u201319}} On another occasion, he was struck across the head with a broomstick and rendered [[Unconsciousness|unconscious]].<ref>{{cite book | first1=Jason| last1=Moss| first2=Jeffrey| last2=Kottler| title=The Last Victim: A True-life Journey into the Mind of the Serial Killer| publisher=Grand Central Publishing| location=New York City| date=2000|isbn=0-7535-0398-0| p=103}}</ref> When he was six years old, Gacy stole a toy truck from a neighborhood store. His mother made him walk back to the store, return the toy and apologize to the owners. His mother informed his father, who beat Gacy with a belt as punishment. After this incident, Gacy's mother attempted to shield her son from his father's verbal and physical abuse,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=26}} yet this only succeeded in Gacy earning accusations that he was a \"[[sissy]]\" and a \"Mama's boy\"{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=257}} who would \"probably grow up [[queer]]\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=40}}\n\nIn 1949, Gacy's father was informed that his son and another boy had been caught sexually fondling a young girl.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=218}} Gacy's father whipped him with a [[razor strop]] as punishment. The same year,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=17}} Gacy was [[child molestation|molested]] by a family friend,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=257}} a contractor who would take Gacy for rides in his truck and then fondle him. Gacy never told his father about these incidents, afraid that his father would blame him.<ref name=\"Serial Killers. p. 54\">''Serial Killers''. p. 54.</ref>\n\nBecause of a heart condition, Gacy was ordered to avoid all sports at school.<ref name=\"Serial Killers. p. 54\" /> During the fourth grade, Gacy began to experience [[Syncope (medicine)|blackout]]s. He was occasionally hospitalized because of these seizures, and also in 1957 for a [[appendicitis|burst appendix]].{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=18}} Gacy later estimated that between the ages of 14 and 18, he had spent almost a year in the hospital for these episodes, and attributed the decline of his grades to his missing school. His father suspected the episodes were an effort to gain sympathy and attention, and openly accused his son of faking the condition as the boy lay in a hospital bed.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Murder In Mind |issue=11 |issn=1364-5803 |page=5}}</ref> Although his mother, sisters, and few close friends never doubted his illness, Gacy's medical condition was never conclusively diagnosed.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=32}}\n\nOne of Gacy's friends at high school recalled several instances in which his father ridiculed or beat his son without provocation. On one occasion in 1957, the same friend witnessed an incident at the Gacy household in which Gacy's father began shouting at his son for no reason, then began hitting him.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=33}} Gacy's mother attempted to intervene. The friend recalled that Gacy simply \"put up his hands to defend himself\", adding that he never struck his father back during these physical altercations.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=32\u201333}}\n\n===Career origins===\nIn 1960, at the age of 18, Gacy became involved in politics, working as an assistant [[precinct captain]] for a [[U.S. Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] candidate in his neighborhood. This decision earned more criticism from his father, who accused his son of being a \"[[wikt:Special:Search/dupe|patsy]]\". Gacy later speculated the decision may have been an attempt to seek the acceptance from others that he never received from his father.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=36}}\n\nThe same year Gacy became a Democratic candidate, his father bought him a car, with the title of the vehicle being in his father's name until Gacy had completed the monthly repayments.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=42}} These repayments took several years to complete, and his father would confiscate the keys to the vehicle if Gacy did not do as his father said. On one occasion in 1962, Gacy bought an extra set of keys after his father confiscated the original set. In response, his father removed the [[distributor cap]] from the vehicle, withholding the component for three days. Gacy recalled that as a result of this incident, he felt \"totally sick; drained\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=44}} When his father replaced the distributor cap, Gacy left the family home and drove to [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], where he found work within the ambulance service before he was transferred to work as an attendant at Palm Mortuary.\n\nIn his role as a mortuary attendant, Gacy slept on a cot behind the [[embalming]] room.<ref>{{cite book|first=Tim|last=Cahill|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OF6itYw0HT0C&pg=PT30&lpg=PT30#v=onepage&q/ |title=Buried Dreams: Inside the Mind of a Serial Killer|publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |location=New York City|date=1986|access-date=March 14, 2013|isbn=978-0553051155}}</ref> He worked in this role for three months.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=258}} In this role, he observed morticians embalming dead bodies and later confessed that, on one evening while alone, he had clambered into the coffin of a deceased teenage male, embracing and caressing the body before experiencing a sense of shock.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=46}}{{efn|Gacy later claimed to have engaged in acts of [[necrophilia]] on approximately two occasions while he worked at Palm Mortuary. He justified his actions by claiming the bodies he had defiled were \"just dead things\" who \"couldn't tell anybody\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=346}}}} This prompted Gacy to call his mother the next day and ask whether his father would allow him to return home.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=46}} His father agreed and the same day, Gacy drove back to live with his family in Chicago.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=347}}\n\nUpon his return, despite the fact he had failed to graduate from high school, Gacy successfully enrolled in the [[Northwestern College (Illinois)|Northwestern Business College]],{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=47}} from which he graduated in 1963. Gacy subsequently took a management trainee position within the Nunn-Bush Shoe Company.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=18\u201319}} In 1964, the shoe company transferred Gacy to [[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]] to work as a salesman.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=258}} He was eventually promoted to manager of his department. In March of that year, he became engaged to Marlynn Myers, a co-worker in the department he managed.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=21}}\n\nDuring his courtship with Marlynn, Gacy joined the local [[Jaycees]] and became a tireless worker for the organization, being named Key Man for the organization in April 1964.<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 58.</ref> The same year, Gacy had his second homosexual experience. According to Gacy, he acquiesced to this incident after one of his colleagues in the Springfield Jaycees plied him with drinks and invited him to spend the evening upon his sofa; the colleague then performed [[oral sex]] upon him while he was drunk.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite journal |title=Murder In Mind |issue=11 |publisher=Marshall Cavendish Printworks|location=London, England|issn=1364-5803 |page=7}}</ref> By 1965, Gacy had risen to the position of vice-president of the Springfield Jaycees.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=20\u201322}} The same year, he was named as the third most outstanding Jaycee within the state of Illinois.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=48}}\n\n==Waterloo, Iowa==\nAfter a nine-month courtship, Gacy and Myers married in September 1964. Marlynn's father subsequently purchased three [[Kentucky Fried Chicken]] restaurants in [[Waterloo, Iowa|Waterloo]], [[Iowa]], and the couple moved to Waterloo so he could manage the restaurants, with the understanding that they would move into Marlynn's parents' home (which was vacated for the couple).{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=21}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=261\u2013262}} The offer was lucrative: Gacy would receive $15,000 per year (the equivalent of $115,513 {{as of|2020|lc=y|df=US}}), plus a share of profits earned via the restaurants.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=50}} Following his obligatory completion of a managerial course, Gacy relocated to Waterloo with his wife later that year.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=23\u201325}}\n\n=== Waterloo Jaycees ===\nIn Waterloo, Gacy joined the local chapter of the Jaycees, regularly offering extended hours to the organization in addition to the 12- and 14-hour days he worked managing three restaurants. Although considered ambitious and something of a braggart by other Jaycees, he was highly regarded for his fund-raising work. In 1967 he was named \"outstanding vice-president\" of the Waterloo Jaycees.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=28}} At Jaycee meetings Gacy often provided fried chicken and insisted on being called \"Colonel\" (for [[Colonel Sanders]]).{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=51}} The same year, Gacy served on the Board of Directors for the Waterloo Jaycees.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=51}}\n\nGacy's wife gave birth to a son in February 1966 and a daughter in March 1967. Gacy himself later described this period of his life as \"perfect\"{{snd}}he had earned his father's approval, which he had long sought. When Gacy's parents visited in July 1966, his father apologized for the abuse he had inflicted during Gacy's childhood, and said: \"Son, I was wrong about you.\"{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=53}}\n\nMany Jaycees in Waterloo were involved in [[wife swapping]],<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> [[prostitution]], [[pornography]], and drug use; Gacy was deeply involved in many of these activities and regularly had sex with local prostitutes.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=263}} He opened a \"club\" in his basement where his employees to drank and played pool. Although Gacy employed teenagers of both sexes at his restaurants, he socialized only with his young male employees. Many were given alcohol before Gacy made sexual advances; if rebuffed, Gacy would claim these advances were jokes or a test of morals.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=265}}\n\n===Assault of Donald Voorhees===\nIn August 1967, Gacy committed his first known [[sexual assault]] upon a teenage boy. The victim was 15-year-old Donald Voorhees, the son of a fellow Jaycee. Gacy lured Voorhees to his house with the promise of showing him pornographic films.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=55}} Gacy plied Voorhees with alcohol and persuaded Voorhees to perform oral sex upon him. Over the following months, several other youths were sexually abused in a similar manner, including one whom Gacy encouraged to have sex with his own wife before [[blackmail]]ing him into performing oral sex upon him.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=265}} Gacy tricked several teenagers into believing he was commissioned with conducting homosexual experiments in the interests of \"scientific research\", for which each was paid up to $50.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=266}}\n\nIn March 1968, Voorhees reported to his father that Gacy had sexually assaulted him. Voorhees Sr. immediately informed the police and Gacy was arrested and subsequently charged with oral [[Sodomy law|sodomy]] in relation to Voorhees and the attempted assault of 16-year-old Edward Lynch.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=267}} Gacy vehemently denied the charges and demanded to take a [[polygraph test]]. This request was granted, although the results indicated Gacy was nervous when he denied any wrongdoing in relation to either Voorhees or Lynch.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=65}}\n\nGacy publicly denied any wrongdoing and insisted the charges against him were politically motivated \u2013 Voorhees Sr. had opposed Gacy's nomination for appointment as president of the Iowa Jaycees.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=66}} Several fellow Jaycees found Gacy's story credible and rallied to his support. However, on May 10, 1968, Gacy was indicted on the sodomy charge.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=65}}\n{{quote box\n| quote = ''\"The most striking aspect of the test results is the patient's total denial of responsibility for everything that has happened to him. He can produce an 'alibi' for everything. He presents himself as a victim of circumstances and blames other people who are out to get him ... the patient attempts to assure a sympathetic response by depicting himself as being at the mercy of a hostile environment.\"''\n| source = Section of report detailing Gacy's 1968 psychiatric evaluation.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=270}}\n| width = 30em\n}}\nOn August 30, 1968, Gacy persuaded one of his employees, 18-year-old Russell Schroeder, to physically assault Voorhees in an effort to discourage the boy from testifying against him. Gacy promised to pay Schroeder $300 to lure Voorhees to a secluded spot, spray [[Mace (spray)|Mace]] in his face, and beat him. Schroeder agreed, and in early September, he lured Voorhees to an isolated county park, sprayed Mace into the youth's eyes, then beat him.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=72}}<ref name=\"Michael H. Stone 2019 pp. 196-203\">Michael H. Stone & Gary Brucato. The New Evil: Understanding the Emergence of Modern Violent Crime (Amherst, New York: Prometheus Books, 2019), pp. 196-203.</ref>\n\nVoorhees managed to escape, and immediately reported the assault to the police, identifying Schroeder as his attacker. Schroeder was arrested the following day. Despite initially denying any involvement, he soon confessed to having assaulted Voorhees, indicating that he had done so at Gacy's request. Gacy was arrested and additionally charged in relation to hiring Schroeder to assault and [[Witness tampering|intimidate]] Voorhees.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=268\u2013270}}\n\nOn September 12, Gacy was ordered to undergo a [[Psychological evaluation|psychiatric evaluation]] at the Psychiatric Hospital of the State University of Iowa.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=270}} Two doctors had examined Gacy over a period of 17 days before concluding he had an [[antisocial personality disorder]] (a disorder which incorporates constructs such as [[sociopathy]] and [[psychopathy]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/conditions/antisocial-personality-disorder |title=Antisocial Personality Disorder |magazine=[[Psychology Today]]|publisher=Sussex Publishers|location=New York City |date=April 19, 2017 |accessdate=January 13, 2018 }}</ref> was unlikely to benefit from any therapy or medical treatment, and that his behavior pattern was likely to bring him into repeated conflict with society.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=272}} The doctors also concluded he was mentally competent to stand trial.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=272}}\n\n===Conviction and imprisonment===\n[[File:John Wayne Gacy (mugshot).jpg|thumb|[[Mug shot]]s of Gacy, following his December 1968 sodomy conviction.]]\nOn November 7, 1968 Gacy pled guilty to one count of sodomy in relation to Voorhees, but not guilty to the charges related to other youths. Gacy said that Voorhees had offered his sexual services to him and that he had acted out of curiosity.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=272}} His story was not believed. Gacy was convicted of sodomy on December 3{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=272}} and sentenced to 10 years imprisonment, to be served at the [[Anamosa State Penitentiary]].{{sfn|Peck|Dolch|2001|p=260}} That same day, his wife petitioned for divorce,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=85}} requesting award of the couple's home and property, sole custody of their two children, and [[alimony]].{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=40}} The Court ruled in her favor and the divorce was finalized on September 18, 1969. Gacy never saw his first wife or children again.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=274}}\n\nDuring his incarceration in the Anamosa State Penitentiary, Gacy rapidly acquired a reputation as a model prisoner.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=273}} Within months of his arrival, he had risen to the position of head cook. He also joined the inmate Jaycee chapter and increased their membership figure from 50 to 650 in the span of less than 18 months. He is also known to have both secured an increase in the inmates' daily pay in the prison mess hall{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=88}} and to have supervised several projects to improve conditions for inmates at the prison.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=89}} On one occasion, Gacy oversaw the installation of a [[miniature golf]] course in the prison's recreation yard.<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 62.</ref>\n\nIn June 1969, Gacy first applied to the State of Iowa Board of Parole for early release: this application was denied. In preparation for a second scheduled parole hearing in May 1970, Gacy completed 16 high school courses, for which he obtained his diploma in November 1969.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=275}}\n\nOn [[Christmas Day]] 1969, Gacy's father died from [[cirrhosis]] of the [[liver]].{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=275}} When told the news, Gacy collapsed to the floor sobbing.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=275}} His request for supervised compassionate leave to attend the funeral was denied.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|page=92}}\n\n==Return to Chicago==\nGacy was granted parole with 12 months' probation on June 18, 1970, after serving 18 months of his 10-year sentence.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=277}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=276}}{{sfn|Foreman|1992|p=63}}{{sfn|Linedecker|1986|p=47}} Two of the conditions of his probation were for Gacy to relocate to Chicago to live with his mother and to observe a 10:00&nbsp;p.m. [[curfew]],{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=276}} with the Iowa Board of Parole receiving regular updates as to his progress.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=96}}\n\nUpon his release, Gacy told friend and fellow Jaycee Clarence Lane\u2014who picked him up from the prison upon release and had remained steadfast in his belief of Gacy's innocence\u2014that he would \"never go back to jail\" and that he intended to re-establish himself in Waterloo. However, within 24 hours of his release, Gacy relocated to Chicago to live with his mother.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=276}} He arrived in Chicago on June 19 and shortly thereafter obtained a job as a [[short-order cook]] in a restaurant.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=49}}\n\nOn February 12, 1971, Gacy was charged with sexually assaulting a teenage boy{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=95}} who claimed that Gacy had lured him into his car at Chicago's [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound bus]] terminal and driven him to his home, where he had attempted to force the boy into sex. This complaint was dismissed when the boy failed to appear in court. The Iowa Board of Parole did not learn of this incident (which violated the conditions of his parole) and eight months later, in October 1971, Gacy's parole ended.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=96}} The following month, records of Gacy's previous criminal convictions in Iowa were later [[Record sealing|sealed]].{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=53}}{{efn|Gacy successfully hid his [[criminal record]] from friends, business associates and political acquaintances; they only learned the truth of his past after police had begun investigating him for his later murders.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=72}}{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=73}}}}\n\n===8213 West Summerdale Avenue===\nWith financial assistance from his mother, Gacy bought a house in Norwood Park Township, an [[unincorporated area]] of [[Cook County, Illinois|Cook County]], a part of metropolitan Chicago. The address, 8213 West Summerdale Avenue, is where he resided until his arrest in December 1978 and where all his known murders were committed.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=175}} He became active in his local community, and his neighbors considered him helpful; willing to loan his construction tools and plowing snow from neighborhood walks free of charge.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=86\u201387}} Between 1974 and 1978, he hosted annual summer parties attended by hundreds of people, including politicians.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=150}} \n\nIn August 1971, shortly after Gacy and his mother moved into the house, he became engaged to Carole Hoff, a [[divorcee]] with two young daughters. Hoff, whom he had briefly dated in high school, had been a friend of his younger sister. His fianc\u00e9e and stepdaughters moved into his home soon after the couple announced their engagement.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=55\u201359}} Gacy's mother subsequently moved out of the house shortly before his wedding, which was held on July 1, 1972.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=278}}\n\nOne week before Gacy's wedding, on June 22, he was arrested and charged with aggravated [[Sexual battery|battery]] and reckless conduct. The arrest was in response to a complaint filed by a youth who claimed that Gacy had flashed a sheriff's badge, lured him into his car, and forced him to perform oral sex.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=112}} These charges were dropped after the complainant attempted to blackmail Gacy.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=61\u201362}}\n\n===PDM Contractors===\nIn 1971, Gacy established a part-time construction business, PDM Contractors (PDM being the initials for 'Painting, Decorating, and Maintenance').{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=65}} With the approval of his probation officer, he was allowed to work evenings to commit to his employment contracts while working as a cook during the day. The business initially undertook minor repair work, such as sign-writing, pouring concrete, and redecorating, but later expanded to include projects such as interior design, [[remodeling]], installation, assembly, and [[landscaping]]. In mid-1973, Gacy quit his job as a cook in order that he could fully commit to his construction business.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=115}} \n\nBy 1975, PDM was expanding rapidly and Gacy was working up to 16 hours per day. In March 1977, he became a supervisor for PE Systems, a firm specializing in the remodeling of drugstores. Between PE Systems and PDM, Gacy worked on up to four projects at once and frequently traveled to other states.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=180}} By 1978, PDM's annual revenue was over $200,000.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=221}}\n====Employees====\nMuch of the labor workforce consisted of high school students and young men.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=1}} In 1973, Gacy and a teenage employee of PDM traveled to [[Florida]] to view property Gacy had purchased. On the first night in Florida, Gacy raped the employee in their hotel room.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=118}} After returning to Chicago, he drove to Gacy's house and beat him in his yard. Gacy told his wife he had been attacked for refusing to pay the employee for poor-quality work.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=117\u2013118}}\n\nAnother employee of Gacy's was 15-year-old Anthony Antonucci, whom he had hired in May 1975. In July 1975, Gacy went to Antonucci's home. The two drank a bottle of wine, then watched a heterosexual [[stag film]] before Gacy wrestled Antonucci to the floor and cuffed his hands behind his back.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=122-123}} One cuff was loose and Antonucci freed his arm while Gacy was out of the room. When Gacy returned, Antonucci\u2014a high school wrestler\u2014pounced upon him. He wrestled Gacy to the floor, obtained possession of the handcuff key and cuffed Gacy's hands behind his back. Gacy at first threatened Antonucci, then calmed down and promised to leave if Antonucci would remove the handcuffs. Antonucci agreed and Gacy left.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=122-123}} Antonucci later recalled that Gacy told him: \"Not only are you the only one who got out of the cuffs, you got them on me\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=123}}\n=====Cram and Rossi=====\nOn July 26, 1976, Gacy employed 18-year-old David Cram. On August 21,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=168}} Cram moved into his house. The following day, Gacy conned Cram into donning handcuffs while Cram was drunk. Gacy swung Cram around while holding the chain linking the cuffs, then said he intended to rape him. Cram kicked Gacy in the face and freed himself from the handcuffs. One month later, Gacy appeared at Cram's bedroom door and again attempted to rape Cram, saying: \"Dave, you really don't know who I am. Maybe it would be good if you give me what I want.\"{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=172}} Cram resisted Gacy and Gacy left the bedroom. Cram moved out and left PDM, although he did periodically work for Gacy over the following two years.<ref name=\"The Montreal Gazette Feb. 13, 1980\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19800213&id=slsxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=laQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1116,946568|title=Man Helped Dig Trenches at Gacy Home|date=February 13, 1980|publisher=The Montreal Gazette}}</ref>\n\nShortly after Cram moved out of Gacy's house another employee, 18-year-old Michael Rossi, moved in.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=177}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=184}}{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=67}} Rossi had worked for PDM Contractors since May 1976.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=58\u201360}} He lived with Gacy until April 1977.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=179}}\n\n===Politics===\n[[File:Johnwaynegacyrosalynncarter.jpg|upright=1|thumb|Gacy with First Lady [[Rosalynn Carter]] on May 6, 1978, six years after his first murder and seven months before his final arrest.|alt=]]\nGacy became active in local Democratic Party politics, initially offering the labor services of his employees to clean party headquarters for free.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=70}} He was rewarded for his community service by being appointed to serve upon the Norwood Park Township street lighting committee,{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=72}} subsequently earning the title of precinct captain.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=73}}{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=222}}\n\nIn 1975, Gacy was appointed director of Chicago's annual [[Polish Constitution Day Parade]]\u2014he supervised the annual event from 1975 until 1978. Through his work with the parade, Gacy met and was photographed with [[First Lady]] [[Rosalynn Carter]] on May 6, 1978.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=212-213}} She signed one photo: \"To John Gacy. Best wishes. Rosalynn Carter\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=214}} The event later became an embarrassment to the [[United States Secret Service]], as in the pictures taken, Gacy can be seen wearing an \"S\" pin, indicating a person who has been given special clearance by the Secret Service.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=142\u2013143}}\n\n===Divorce===\nBy 1975, Gacy had told his wife that he was [[Bisexuality|bisexual]].{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=102}} After the couple had sex on [[Mother's Day (United States)|Mother's Day]] that year, he informed her this would be \"the last time\" they would ever have sex.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=118}} He began spending most evenings away from home only to return in the early hours of the morning with the excuse he had been working late.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=66}} His wife observed Gacy bringing teenage boys into his garage and also found [[gay pornography]] and men's wallets and identification cards inside the house.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=68}} When she once confronted Gacy about who these items belonged to, he angrily informed her the property was none of her business.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=68}} \n\nFollowing a heated argument regarding her failing to balance a checkbook correctly in October 1975,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=140}} Carole Gacy asked her husband for a divorce. Gacy agreed to his wife's request although, by mutual consent, Carole continued to live at 8213 West Summerdale until February 1976, when she and her daughters moved into their own apartment. One month later, on March 2, the Gacys' divorce\u2014decreed upon the false grounds of Gacy's [[infidelity]] with women<ref name=\"autogenerated28\">''Murder In Mind'' issue 11 {{ISSN|1364-5803}} p. 28/ Murder In Mind p. 28</ref>\u2014was finalized.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19820501&id=o64yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=he4FAAAAIBAJ&pg=2634,556459|title=John Gacy: Businessman, Clown, Mass Killer|date=May 1, 1982|publisher=The Ottawa Citizen}}</ref>{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=87}}{{efn|In the hope of a reconciliation, Gacy and Hoff began dating again in late 1977, but Hoff became engaged to another man the following year.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=205, 220}}}}\n\n===Pogo the Clown===\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Johnwaynegacypogo.jpg\n| width1 = 145\n| height1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = Gacy as Pogo the Clown.\n| image2 = John Wayne Gacy's clown suit (17104376201).jpg\n| width2 = 145\n| height2 = \n| caption2 = Gacy's clown costume and one of his paintings.\n| direction = \n| total_width = \n}}\nThrough his membership in a local [[Moose International|Moose Club]], Gacy became aware of a \"Jolly Joker\" clown club, whose members regularly performed at fund-raising events and parades in addition to voluntarily entertaining hospitalized children.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=143}} In late 1975, Gacy joined the Jolly Jokers and created his own performance characters: \"Pogo the Clown\" and \"Patches the Clown.\"<ref>''Serial Killers''. p 68.</ref>{{efn|Gacy later stated acting as a clown allowed him to \"regress into childhood\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=145}} His clown costumes are on display at the [[National Museum of Crime & Punishment]].}} He performed as Pogo or Patches at numerous local parties, political functions, charitable events, and children's hospitals.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=145\u2013147}} He designed his own costumes and taught himself how to apply clown makeup.{{efn|Some professional clowns noted the sharp corners Gacy painted at the edges of his mouth are contrary to the rounded borders that professional clowns normally employ, so as not to scare children.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=70}}}} Gacy was also known to occasionally remain in his clowning garb after a performance. On several occasions, he is known to have arrived, dressed in his clowning garb, at a favorite drinking venue, \"The Good Luck Lounge\", with the explanation he had performed at a charitable event and was stopping for a social drink before heading home.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=111}}<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:W4fr6GQWh-0J:graphics.chicagotribune.com|accessdate=March 4, 2010|title=John Wayne Gacy was Arrested 40 Years Ago in a Killing Spree that Claimed 33 Victims and Shattered the Illusion of the Ssafe Suburban Community|date=December 16, 2018}}</ref> For these reasons, Gacy is known as the \"Killer Clown.\"\n\n==Murders==\nGacy typically abducted his victims from Chicago's Greyhound Bus station, from [[Washington Square Park (Chicago)|Bughouse Square]], or simply off the streets. The victims were often grabbed by force or conned into believing Gacy\u2014often carrying a sheriff's badge and placing spotlights on his black [[Oldsmobile]]\u2014was a policeman.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=178}} Others were lured to his house with either the promise of a job with his construction company, or an offer of drink, drugs, or money for sex.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=173}}\n\nInside Gacy's home, his usual ''[[modus operandi]]'' was to ply a youth with drink, drugs or generally gain his trust. Gacy would then produce a pair of handcuffs, occasionally as part of a clowning routine. He typically cuffed his own hands behind his back, then surreptitiously released himself with the key, which he hid between his fingers, before offering to show his intended victim how to release himself from the handcuffs.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=18}}{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=169\u2013170}} With his victim manacled and unable to free himself, Gacy then made a statement to the effect of: \"The trick is, you have to have the key\", before proceeding to rape and torture his captive.<ref name=\"Kozenczak\">Kozenczak (2012), pp. 200\u2013201</ref> Gacy referred to this act of restraining his victim as his \"handcuff trick\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=166}}\n\nSome victims were partly drowned in his bathtub before Gacy revived them, enabling him to continue his prolonged assault.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=331}} The victims were usually lured alone to his house, although on approximately three occasions, Gacy had what he called \"[[Double murder|doubles]]\"\u2014occasions wherein he killed two victims on the same evening.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=174}} With the exceptions of his first and last victims, all were murdered between 3:00&nbsp;a.m. and 6:00&nbsp;a.m.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=179}}\n\nGacy typically killed by placing a rope around a victim's neck, then progressively tightening the rope with a hammer handle;<ref>Kozenczak (2012), pp. 201-203</ref>{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=21}} he referred to this act as the \"rope trick.\" Occasionally, the victim [[convulse]]d for an \"hour or two\" before dying. Several victims died by asphyxiation from cloth gags stuffed into the mouth.<ref name=\"Kozenczak\" />\n\nAfter death, the victims' bodies were typically stored beneath his bed for up to 24 hours before Gacy buried his victim in the crawl space, where he periodically poured [[Calcium oxide|quicklime]] to hasten the decomposition of the bodies.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=177}} The bodies of some victims would be taken to his garage and [[embalming|embalmed]] prior to their burial.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=345}}\n\n=== Murder of Timothy McCoy ===\n[[File:TimothyJackMcCoyJohnGacyOmahaIllinoisJanuary31972a.jpg|upright=0.65|right|thumb|Timothy McCoy.]]\nGacy's first known murder occurred on January 2, 1972. According to Gacy's later account, following a family party, he decided to drive to the Civic Center to view a display of [[Ice sculpture|ice sculptures]] before luring a 16-year-old named Timothy Jack McCoy from Chicago's Greyhound bus terminal into his car. McCoy was traveling from [[Michigan]] to [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]]. Gacy took McCoy on a sightseeing tour of Chicago, and then drove him to his home with the promise that he could spend the night and be driven back to the station in time to catch his bus.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CSTB&p_theme=cstb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB36D062F6AA91B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D | date=May 20, 1986 |title=Gacy Victim's Remains Going Home to Iowa |first=Andrew |last=Herrmann |newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times}}</ref> Prior to McCoy's identification, he was known simply as the \"Greyhound Bus Boy\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Berry-Dee|2009|page=193}}</ref>\n\nGacy claimed he woke early the following morning to find McCoy standing in his bedroom doorway with a kitchen knife in his hand.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=348}} He then jumped from his bed and McCoy raised both arms in a gesture of surrender, tilting the knife upwards and accidentally cutting Gacy's forearm.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=110}}{{efn|Gacy had a scar on his arm to support this account.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=110-111}}}} He then twisted the knife from McCoy's wrist, banged his head against his bedroom wall, kicked him against his wardrobe and walked towards him. McCoy then kicked Gacy in the stomach, doubling him over. Gacy then grabbed McCoy, wrestled him to the floor, then stabbed him repeatedly in the chest as he straddled him.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=102}}\n\nAs McCoy lay dying, Gacy claimed he washed the knife in his bathroom, then went to his kitchen and saw an opened carton of eggs and a slab of unsliced bacon on his kitchen table. McCoy had also set the table for two; he had walked into Gacy's room to wake him while absentmindedly carrying the kitchen knife in his hand.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=349}} Gacy buried McCoy in his crawl space and later covered his grave with a layer of concrete.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=101}} In an interview several years after his arrest, Gacy stated that immediately after killing McCoy, he felt \"totally drained\", yet noted as he listened to the \"[[Gurgling|gurgulations]]\" as McCoy lay gasping for air that he had experienced a mind-numbing [[orgasm]] as he had stabbed him.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=348}} He added: \"That's when I realized that death was the ultimate thrill.\"{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=349}}\n\n===Second murder===\nGacy later stated that the second time he committed murder was around January 1974. The victim is believed to have been an unidentified teenager with medium brown hair and estimated to be aged between 14 and 18 whom Gacy strangled before stowing his body in his closet prior to burial.<ref name=\"Case File 954UMIL\">{{cite web|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/954umil.html|title=Case File 954UMIL|publisher=The Doe Network|access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> The victim was found wrapped within several plastic bags and wore a silver ring on the [[Ring finger|fourth finger]] of his left hand, indicating the possibility he had been married.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=249\u2013250}} Gacy later stated that fluid leaked out of the mouth and nose of this body while stored in his closet, staining his carpet.<ref>Whoever Fights Monsters {{ISBN|0-671-71561-5}} p. 336</ref> As a result of this experience, Gacy later stated he regularly stuffed cloth rags or the victims' own underwear in their mouths to prevent a recurrence of this incident. This particular unidentified victim was buried about {{convert|15|ft}} from the barbecue pit in Gacy's backyard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_IgxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9qEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6913,2124365&dq/|work=The Montreal Gazette|title=Another Skeleton Found at Gacy Home|date=March 10, 1979|access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Murder of John Butkovich===\n[[File:Butkovich.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|John Butkovich]]\nOne week after the attempted assault of Anthony Antonucci, on July 31, 1975, another of Gacy's employees, 18-year-old John Butkovich, disappeared.<ref>{{cite news|title=Search at Gacy Home to Resume |date=January 1, 1979 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19790101&id=PEEsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=v80EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2963,232748 |publisher=Herald-Journal |accessdate=April 11, 2019}}</ref> The day before his disappearance, Butkovich had threatened Gacy over two weeks' outstanding back pay. Butkovich's car was found abandoned in a parking lot with his jacket and wallet inside and the keys still in the ignition.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=132\u2013133}}  \n\nButkovich's father, a [[Yugoslavs|Yugoslav]] immigrant, called Gacy, who claimed he was happy to help search for his son but was sorry Butkovich had \"run away\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=133}} When questioned, Gacy said Butkovich and two friends had arrived at his house demanding the overdue pay, but that they left after a compromise was reached. Over the following three years, Butkovich's parents called police more than 100 times, urging them to investigate Gacy further.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=133}}{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=83\u201385}}\n\nGacy later admitted to luring Butkovich to his home, ostensibly to settle the issue of his overdue wages, on a date his wife and stepchildren were visiting his sister in [[Arkansas]]. He offered Butkovich a drink, then conned him into allowing his wrists to be cuffed behind his back. Gacy said he \"sat on the kid's chest for a while\" before he strangled him. He initially stowed Butkovich's body in his garage, with view to later burying the body in his crawl space.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=131}} When his wife and stepdaughters returned to Illinois earlier than expected, Gacy buried the body of Butkovich under the concrete floor of the garage.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=126, 129}}\n\n===Cruising years===\nIn addition to 1975 being the year of his business expanding, Gacy freely admitted that 1975 was also the year in which he began to increase the frequency of his excursions for sex with young males.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=121}} He often referred to these jaunts as his \"[[Cruising for sex|cruising]]\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=153}} The majority of Gacy's murders were committed between 1976 and 1978, which he later referred to as his \"cruising years\" as he largely lived alone following his divorce.\n\nAlthough Gacy remained gregarious and civic-minded, several neighbors became aware of erratic changes in his behavior after his 1976 divorce and subsequent arrest in December 1978. This behavior included hearing his car arrive and depart in the early hours of the morning; noting lights switching on and off in his home at odd hours and his keeping company with young males.<ref name=\"autogenerated28\" /> One neighbor later recollected that, for several years, she and her son had repeatedly been awoken by the repeated sounds of muffled screaming, shouting, and crying in the early morning hours, which she and her son identified as emanating from a house adjacent to theirs on Summerdale Avenue.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=274}}\n\n====1976====\nOne month after his divorce was finalized, Gacy abducted and murdered 18-year-old Darrell Samson. Samson was last seen alive in Chicago on April 6, 1976.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=158}} Five weeks later, on the afternoon of May 14, 15-year-old Randall Reffett disappeared while walking home from [[Senn High School]]; he was gagged with a cloth,{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=326}} causing him to die of asphyxiation.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), pp. 200\u2013201</ref> Hours after Reffett had been abducted, 14-year-old Samuel Stapleton vanished as he walked to his home from his sister's apartment.<ref name=\"autogenerated28\" /> Both victims were buried in the same grave in the crawl space.<ref>''Serial Killers''. p 70.</ref>\n\nOn June 3, 1976, Gacy killed a 17-year-old [[Lake View, Chicago|Lakeview]] teenager named Michael Bonnin. He disappeared while traveling from Chicago to [[Waukegan, Illinois|Waukegan]],{{sfn|Linedecker|1986|p=123}} and was strangled with a [[Ligature strangulation|ligature]] and buried in the crawl space.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=326}} Ten days later, a 16-year-old [[Uptown, Chicago|Uptown]] youth named William Carroll was murdered and buried directly beneath Gacy's kitchen. Carroll may have been the first of four males known to have been murdered between June 13 and August 6, 1976, and who were buried in a [[common grave]] located beneath Gacy's kitchen and laundry room.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=217}}{{efn|This common grave also held the body of a fifth male estimated to have been killed after this date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cookcountysheriff.org/sheriffs_police/gacy/gacy.html|title=Unidentified Victims of John Wayne Gacy|publisher=cookcountysheriff.org|date=October 11, 2011|access-date=January 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202030834/http://cookcountysheriff.org/sheriffs_police/gacy/gacy.html|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n\nThe three identified youths killed between June 13 and August 6 were aged between 16 and 17 years old, whereas the only unidentified male known to have been murdered between these dates is a man with medium dark brown hair estimated to have been aged between 23 and 30 years old and between {{nowrap|5 ft 1 in}} and {{nowrap|5 ft 6 in}} ({{convert|61|and|66|in|cm|disp=out}}) tall. This man had two missing upper front teeth at the time of his disappearance,<ref name=\"doenetwork1\">{{cite web|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/956umil.html |title=Case File 956UMIL |publisher=The Doe Network |access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> leading investigators to believe this particular victim most likely wore a [[denture]]. He was buried directly beneath the body of a 16-year-old [[Minnesota]] youth named James Haakenson, who is last known to have phoned his family on August 5, and whose body was itself buried directly beneath that of a 17-year-old [[Bensenville, Illinois|Bensenville]] youth named Rick Johnston, who was last seen alive on August 6.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2017/07/19/john-wayne-gacy-victim/|title=Minnesota Teen ID'd as John Wayne Gacy Victim|access-date=July 19, 2017|newspaper=CBS Local|date=July 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/sheriff-update-investigation-unnamed-gacy-victims-48724804 |title=Illinois Sheriff IDs Another Victim of John Wayne Gacy |access-date=July 19, 2017 |publisher=abcnews.go.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720051638/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/sheriff-update-investigation-unnamed-gacy-victims-48724804 |archivedate=July 20, 2017  }}</ref>{{efn|Because Haakenson and Johnston disappeared just 24 hours apart and their bones were commingled,{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=217\u2013218}} they may have been murdered on the same day or even at the same time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/19/us/john-wayne-gacy-victim-identified.html|title=John Wayne Gacy Victim is Identified After Four Decades|access-date=August 8, 2017|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 19, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nTwo further unidentified males are estimated to have been killed between August and October 1976. One of these victims was buried directly above the body of William Carroll, who had been murdered on June 13, yet higher than the body of Rick Johnston, who was last seen on August 6. This particular unidentified male is estimated to have been aged between 15 and 24 years old and had light brown hair. Sequential burial patterns of victims within the crawl space, plus the [[circumstantial evidence|circumstantial]] fact that Cram had not lived with Gacy until August 21, leave a possible date of between August 6 and 20, 1976 as the time this particular man was murdered.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=311}} The second unidentified male likely to have been murdered between August and October 1976 is a youth with dark brown, wavy hair, between 18 and 22 years old, and with an [[tooth abscess|abscessed tooth]]. This victim may have been killed somewhat before early October 1976, when Gacy had an employee to dig a trench in northeast corner of the crawlspace, where this victim's body was found.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=311}} \n\nOn October 24, 1976, Gacy abducted and killed teenage friends Kenneth Parker and Michael Marino:<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Apparent Gacy Victims Identified |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UO9eAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K1QNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5070,3504589&dq/ |publisher=St. Joseph Gazette |accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> the two were last seen outside a restaurant on [[Clark Street (Chicago)|Clark Street]]. Both were strangled and buried in the same grave in the crawl space. Two days later, a 19-year-old employee of PDM, William Bundy, disappeared after informing his family he was to attend a party. Bundy was also strangled and buried in the crawl space, directly beneath Gacy's master bedroom.<ref name=\"Serial Killers. p 83\">''Serial Killers''. p 83.</ref>\n\nIn December 1976, another PDM employee, 17-year-old Gregory Godzik, disappeared: he was last seen by his girlfriend outside her house after he had driven her home following a date.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=104}} Godzik had worked for PDM for only three weeks before he disappeared. In the time he had worked for Gacy, he had informed his family Gacy had had him \"dig trenches for some kind of (drain) tiles\" in his crawl space.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=184}} Godzik's car was later found abandoned in [[Niles, Illinois|Niles]]. His parents and older sister, Eugenia, contacted Gacy about Greg's disappearance. Gacy claimed to the family that Greg had run away from home, having indicated to Gacy before his disappearance that he wished to do so. Gacy also claimed to have received an [[answering machine]] message from Godzik shortly after he had disappeared. When asked if he could play back the message to Godzik's parents, Gacy stated that he had erased it.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=184}}{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=92\u201393}}\n\n====1977====\nOn January 20, 1977, John Szyc, a 19-year-old acquaintance of Butkovich, Godzik, and Gacy, disappeared. Szyc was lured to Gacy's house on the pretext of selling his [[Plymouth Satellite#Third Generation (1971-1974)|Plymouth Satellite]] to Gacy. He was buried in Gacy's crawl space directly above the body of Godzik.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=207}}\n\nBetween December 1976 and March 1977, Gacy is known to have killed an unidentified man estimated to be around 25 years old.<ref name=\"Case File 958UMIL\">{{cite web|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/958umil.html |title=Case File 958UMIL |publisher=The Doe Network |access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> An inscription upon a [[key fob]] found among the personal artifacts buried with this unknown victim suggests his first name may have been Greg or Gregory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/10994|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System|publisher=}}</ref> His body was buried in the crawl space beneath the body of 20-year-old Jon Prestidge, a Michigan man visiting friends in Chicago whom Gacy killed on March 15.\n\nAfter the murder of Prestidge, Gacy is believed to have murdered one further unidentified youth exhumed from his crawl space, although the timing of this particular youth's murder is inconclusive. He was buried parallel to the wall of Gacy's crawl space directly beneath the entrance to his home. The two victims murdered on the same day in May 1976 were buried alongside him, yet sequential burial patterns of three victims murdered in 1977 leave an equal possibility this particular victim may have been murdered in the spring or summer of 1977. All that is known about this youth is that he was aged between 17 and 21 years old and that he had suffered a fractured left [[clavicle|collarbone]] before his disappearance.<ref name=\"NamUs Case File 1282Dec78\">{{cite web|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/full_report/10998|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 10998|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1977,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=179}} Michael Rossi moved out of Gacy's home; the same month, Gacy became temporarily engaged to a woman he had been dating for three months, and his fianc\u00e9e moved into his house. By mutual agreement, the engagement was called off in June of that year and his fianc\u00e9e moved out of his home.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=180}} The following month, Gacy killed a 19-year-old [[Crystal Lake, Illinois|Crystal Lake]] youth named Matthew Bowman. He was buried in the crawl space with the tourniquet used to strangle him still knotted around his neck.<ref>{{cite news|title=Youthful Victims May Have Been Buried Alive, Expert Speculates |date=February 9, 1980 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rgtKAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HiINAAAAIBAJ&pg=5006,4386127&dq/Press |publisher=Press-Courier |accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1977, Rossi, who had bought Szyc's car from Gacy, was arrested for stealing gasoline from a service station while driving the car. The attendant noted the license plate number and police traced the car to Gacy's house. When questioned, Gacy told officers that Szyc had sold the car to him in February with the explanation that he needed money to leave town. A check of the [[Vehicle Identification Number|VIN]] number confirmed the car had belonged to Szyc.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 78</ref> The police did not pursue the matter further,{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=95\u201397}} although they did inform Szyc's mother that her son had sold his car to Gacy in February.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=184}}\n\nBy the end of 1977, Gacy is also known to have murdered an additional six young men between the ages of 16 and 21. The first of these six victims, 18-year-old Robert Gilroy, was last seen alive on September 15. Gilroy\u2014the son of a Chicago police sergeant{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=140}}\u2014was [[suffocation|suffocated]] and buried in the crawl space. On September 12, Gacy had flown to [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]] to supervise a remodeling project and did not return to Chicago until September 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/02/10/10374067-serial-killer-john-wayne-gacy-had-accomplices-lawyers-say |title=Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy Had Accomplices, lawyers Say \u2013 U.S. News |publisher=Usnews.nbcnews.com |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> As Gacy is known to have been in another state at the time Gilroy was last seen, this is cited to support Gacy's claim of being assisted by one or more accomplices. Ten days after Gilroy was last seen, 19-year-old former [[U.S. Marine]] John Mowery disappeared after leaving his mother's house to walk to his own apartment. Mowery was strangled and buried in the northwest corner of the crawl space perpendicular to the body of William Bundy.<ref name=\"Serial Killers. p 83\" />\n\nOn October 17, 21-year-old Minnesota Russell Nelson disappeared: he was last seen outside a Chicago bar. Nelson died of suffocation and was also buried in the crawl space. Less than four weeks later, 16-year-old [[Kalamazoo, Michigan|Kalamazoo]] teenager Robert Winch was murdered and buried in the crawl space, and on November 18, 20-year-old father-of-one Tommy Boling disappeared after leaving a Chicago bar. Both Winch and Boling were strangled<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 202</ref> and buried in the crawl space directly beneath the hallway.<ref>''Serial Killers''. pp 80\u201383.</ref>\n\nThree weeks after the murder of Tommy Boling, on December 9, a 19-year-old U.S. Marine named David Talsma disappeared after informing his mother he was to attend a rock concert in [[Hammond, Illinois|Hammond]].{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=183}} Talsma was strangled with a ligature and buried in the crawl space.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 203</ref>\n\nOn December 30, 1977, Gacy abducted 19-year-old student Robert Donnelly from a Chicago bus stop at gunpoint.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=241}} Gacy drove Donnelly home with him, where Donnelly was raped, tortured, and repeatedly had his head dunked into a bathtub until he passed out. Donnelly later testified at Gacy's trial that he was in such pain that he asked Gacy to kill him;{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=244\u2013245}} Gacy replied, \"I'm getting round to it.\" After several hours Gacy drove Donnelly to his workplace and released him, first warning him that if he complained to police they would not believe him.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=334}}\n\n====1978====\nDonnelly reported the assault and Gacy was questioned by police on January 6, 1978. Gacy admitted to having had \"[[BDSM|slave-sex]]\" with Donnelly, but insisted everything was consensual. The police believed him and no charges were filed.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=150}} The following month, Gacy killed 19-year-old William Kindred, who disappeared on February 16, after telling his fianc\u00e9e he was to spend the evening in a bar.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=217}} Kindred was the final victim to be buried in Gacy's crawl space.<ref>''Serial Killers''. p 73.</ref>{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=219}}\n\nIn March, Gacy lured 26-year-old [[Jeffrey Rignall]] into his car. Upon entering the car, the young man was [[chloroform]]ed and driven to the house on Summerdale, where he was raped, tortured with various instruments including lit candles and whips, and repeatedly chloroformed into unconsciousness.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=208}} Rignall was then driven to [[Lincoln Park, Chicago|Lincoln Park]], where he was dumped, unconscious but alive. He was later informed the chloroform had permanently damaged his liver.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=208}}\n\n[[File:Des Plaines River.png|thumb|upright=1.2|In June 1978 Gacy began discarding his victims' bodies of his victims in the [[Des Plaines River]], as his crawl space was full.|alt=]]Rignall managed to stagger to his girlfriend's apartment. Police were again informed of the assault but did not investigate Gacy. Rignall was able to recall, through the haze of that night, the Oldsmobile, the [[Kennedy Expressway]] and particular side streets. He staked out the exit on the Expressway when in April he saw the Oldsmobile, which Rignall and his friends followed to 8213 West Summerdale.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=208\u2013209}} Police issued an [[arrest warrant]], and Gacy was arrested on July 15.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=146\u2013150}} He was facing an impending trial for battery against Rignall when he was arrested.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=153}}\n\nBy 1978, the crawl space could store no further bodies.<ref name=\"Michael H. Stone 2019 pp. 196-203\" />{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=273}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=171\u2013175}} Gacy later confessed to police that he initially considered stowing bodies in his attic, but had been worried of complications arising from \"excessive leakage\".<ref name=\"Kozenczak, 2012 p. 177\">Kozenczak, (2012) p. 177</ref> Therefore, he chose to dispose of his victims off the [[Interstate 55|I-55]] bridge into the [[Des Plaines River]].{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=152}} Gacy stated he had thrown five bodies off the I-55 bridge into the Des Plaines River in 1978, one of which he believed had landed upon a passing [[barge]].{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=175}} Only four of these five bodies were ever found.<ref>{{cite news |title=Timeline: Suburban Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy and the Efforts to Recover, Name His 33 Victims |date=December 17, 2018 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/history/ct-john-wayne-gacy-timeline-htmlstory.html}}</ref>\n\nThe first known victim thrown from the I-55 bridge into the Des Plaines River, 20-year-old Timothy O'Rourke, was killed in mid-June after leaving his Dover Street apartment, having informed his roommate of his intention to purchase cigarettes; his body was found {{convert|6|mi|km|0}} downstream on June 30.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=273}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=220}}  \n[[File:Piest1.jpg|upright=0.7|thumb|Robert Piest, whose disappearance led to Gacy's arrest|alt=|left]]\nOn November 4, Gacy killed 19-year-old Frank Landingin. His body was found in the Des Plaines River on November 12. Less than three weeks later, on November 24, a 20-year-old [[Elmwood Park, Illinois|Elmwood Park]] resident, James Mazzara, disappeared after sharing Thanksgiving dinner with his family; his body was found on December 28. The cause of death in the case of Landingin was certified as suffocation through his own underwear being lodged down his throat, plugging his airway and effectively causing him to drown in his own vomit.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=276}} Mazzara had been strangled with a ligature.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=275}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=225}}\n\n=====Murder of Robert Piest=====\nOn the afternoon of December 11, 1978, Gacy visited the Nisson Pharmacy in [[Des Plaines, Illinois|Des Plaines]] to discuss a potential remodeling deal with store owner Phil Torf. While Gacy was within earshot of 15-year-old, part-time employee Robert Piest, he mentioned that his firm hired teenage boys at a starting wage of $5 per hour\u2014almost double the pay Piest earned at the pharmacy.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=5\u20136}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=4}}\n\nShortly after Gacy left the pharmacy, Piest informed his mother\u2014who had arrived at the pharmacy to drive her son home\u2014that \"some contractor wants to talk to me about a job\". Piest left the store, promising to return shortly.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=7}}  He was murdered shortly after 10:00&nbsp;p.m. at Gacy's home. Gacy later stated that as he placed the tourniquet around Piest's neck, Piest was \"crying, scared\".<ref>Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 140</ref> He also admitted to having received a phone call from a business acquaintance as Piest lay dying on his bedroom floor.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=231}}\n\n==Investigation==\nWhen Piest failed to return, his family filed a [[missing person]] report on their son with the Des Plaines police. Torf named Gacy as the contractor Piest had most likely left the store to talk with about a job.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), pp. 25-26</ref> Convinced Piest had not run away from home, Lieutenant [[Joseph R. Kozenczak|Joseph Kozenczak]] chose to investigate Gacy further.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), pp. 26-27</ref>\n\nKozenczak and two other Des Plaines police officers visited Gacy at his home the following evening. Gacy indicated he had seen two youths working at the pharmacy and that he had asked one of them\u2014whom he believed to be Piest\u2014whether any remodeling materials were present in the rear of the store.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=19\u201321}} He was adamant, however, that he had not offered Piest a job and promised to come to the station later that evening to make a statement confirming this, indicating he was unable to do so at that moment as his uncle had just died. When questioned as to how soon he could come to the police station, he responded: \"You guys are very rude. Don't you have any respect for the dead?\"{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=240}}\n\nAt 3:20&nbsp;a.m., Gacy, covered in mud, arrived at the police station, claiming he had been involved in a car accident.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=23}} Upon returning to the police station later that day, Gacy denied any involvement in the disappearance of Piest and repeated that he had not offered him a job. When asked why he had returned to the pharmacy at 8:00&nbsp;p.m. Gacy claimed he had done so in response to a phone call from Torf informing him he had left his appointment book at the store. Detectives had already spoken with Torf, who had stated he had placed no such call to Gacy.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=27}} At the request of detectives, Gacy prepared a written statement detailing his movements on December 11.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=28}}\n\n===Revelations===\nDes Plaines police were convinced Gacy was behind Piest's disappearance and checked Gacy's record, discovering that he had an outstanding battery charge against him in Chicago and had served a prison sentence in Iowa for the sodomy of a 15-year-old boy.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=17}} A search of Gacy's house on December 13 was ordered by a judge at the request of detectives and revealed several suspicious items. These included a [[syringe]], several police badges, and a 6mm Brevettata [[starter pistol]]. They also found handcuffs, books on homosexuality and [[pederasty]], a 39 inch long [[Dimensional lumber#Dimensional lumber|two-by-four]] with two holes drilled into each end,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=33}} several driver's licenses, a blue hooded parka and underwear too small to fit Gacy.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 61</ref>\n\nIn the northwest bedroom, investigators found a [[Maine West High School]] ring. This item initially interested investigators as Piest had attended Maine West, but the ring was not his. It was a class of 1975 ring engraved with the initials J.A.S.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=243}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=87}} A photo receipt from Nisson Pharmacy was also recovered from a trash can.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 61</ref>\n\nGacy's Oldsmobile and other PDM work vehicles were confiscated by the Des Plaines police, who assigned two two-man [[surveillance]] teams to monitor Gacy on a rotational twelve-hour basis as they continued their investigation into his background and potential involvement in Piest's disappearance.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Murder casebook number 84 {{ISBN|0-7485-1454-6}}, p. 1915</ref> These surveillance teams consisted of officers Mike Albrecht and David Hachmeister, and Ronald Robinson and Robert Schultz.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=41}} The following day, investigators received a phone call from Michael Rossi, who informed the investigators both of Gregory Godzik's disappearance and the fact that another PDM employee, Charles Hattula, had been found drowned in an Illinois river the previous year.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=53}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=123}}\n\nOn December 15, Des Plaines investigators obtained further details upon Gacy's battery charge, learning the complainant, Jeffrey Rignall, had reported that Gacy had lured him into his car, chloroformed him, raped him and dumped him, with severe chest and facial burns and rectal bleeding, in Lincoln Park the following morning. In an interview with Gacy's former wife the same day, they learned of the disappearance of John Butkovich.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=84}} The same day, the Maine West High School ring was traced to a John Alan Szyc.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=53\u201355}} In an interview with Szyc's mother the same day, she informed officers of the January 1977 disappearance of her son and that several items from his apartment were also missing, including a Motorola TV set.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 117</ref>\n\nBy December 16, Gacy was becoming affable with the surveillance detectives, regularly inviting them to join him for meals in restaurants and occasionally for drinks in bars or within his home. He repeatedly denied that he had anything to do with Piest's disappearance and accused the officers of harassing him because of his political connections or because of his recreational drug use. Knowing these officers were unlikely to arrest him on anything trivial, he openly taunted them by flouting traffic laws and succeeded in losing his pursuers on more than one occasion.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=89}}\n\nOn December 17, investigators conducted a formal interview of Michael Rossi, who informed them Gacy had sold Szyc's vehicle to him with the explanation that he had bought the car from Szyc because Szyc needed money to move to California. A further examination of Gacy's Oldsmobile was conducted on this date. In the course of examining the trunk of the car, the investigators discovered a small cluster of fibers which may have been human hair. These fibers were sent for further analysis. That evening, officers conducted a test using three trained [[German shepherd]] [[Search and rescue dog|search dogs]] to determine whether Piest had been present in any of Gacy's vehicles.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=93}} The dogs were allowed to examine each of Gacy's vehicles, whereupon one dog approached Gacy's Oldsmobile and lay upon the passenger seat in what the dog's handler informed investigators was a \"death reaction\", indicating the body of Robert Piest had been present in this vehicle.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=93}}\n\nThat evening, Gacy invited two of the surveillance detectives to a restaurant for a meal. In the early hours of December 18, he invited the same officers into another restaurant where, over breakfast, he talked of his business, his marriages and his activities as a registered clown. At one point during this conversation, Gacy remarked to one of the two surveillance detectives: \"You know\u2026 clowns can get away with murder.\"{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=226}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=90}}\n\n===Civil suit===\nBy December 18, Gacy was beginning to show visible signs of strain as a result of the constant surveillance: he was unshaven, looked tired, appeared anxious and was drinking heavily. That afternoon, he drove to his lawyers' office to prepare a $750,000 [[civil suit]] against the Des Plaines police,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=102}} demanding that they cease their surveillance. The same day, the serial number of the Nisson Pharmacy photo receipt found in Gacy's kitchen was traced to 17-year-old Kim Byers, a colleague of Piest at Nisson Pharmacy, who admitted when contacted in person the following day that she had worn the jacket and had placed the receipt in the [[Anorak|parka]] pocket just before she gave the parka to Piest as he left the store to talk with a contractor.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=110}} This revelation contradicted Gacy's previous statements that he had had no contact with Robert Piest on the evening of December 11.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|pp=116\u2013117}}\n\nThe same evening, Michael Rossi was interviewed a second time: on this occasion, Rossi was more cooperative, informing detectives that in the summer of 1977, Gacy had had him spread ten bags of [[Lime (material)|lime]] in the crawl space of the house.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=143}}\n\nOn December 19, investigators began compiling evidence for a second search warrant of Gacy's house. The same day, Gacy's lawyers filed the civil suit against the Des Plaines police. The hearing of the suit was scheduled for December 22. That afternoon, Gacy invited two of the surveillance detectives inside his house. On this occasion, as one officer distracted Gacy with conversation, another officer walked into Gacy's bedroom in an unsuccessful attempt to write down the serial number of the Motorola TV set they suspected belonged to John Szyc. While flushing Gacy's toilet, this officer noticed a smell he suspected could be that of rotting corpses emanating from a [[heating duct]]; the officers who previously searched Gacy's house had failed to notice this, as on that occasion the house had been cold.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nBoth David Cram and Michael Rossi were interviewed by investigators on December 20. Rossi had agreed to be interviewed in relation to his possible links with John Szyc as well as the disappearance of Robert Piest. When questioned by Kozenczak as to where he believed Gacy had placed Piest's body, Rossi replied: \"In the crawl space; he could have put him in the crawl space.\"<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 147</ref> A polygraph test showed his responses to questions to be inconclusive; however, upon his agreeing to a subsequent visual test in which a map of Cook County was divided into 12 [[Grid plan|grid sections]] numbered 1 to 12, with Gacy's home marked in the fourth grid section, Kozenczak noted an extreme response in Rossi's [[blood pressure]] when asked: \"Is the body of Robert Piest buried in grid number 4?\"<ref>Kozenczak, Joseph R.; Kozenczak, Karen M. (February 6, 2012) ''The Chicago Killer: The Hunt For Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy''. CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform. {{ISBN|978-1401095314}} p. 148</ref> Upon hearing this question, Rossi refused to continue the polygraph questioning, although he did discuss further his digging trenches in the crawl space and remarked upon Gacy's insistence that he not deviate from where he was instructed to dig.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=181}}\n\nCram himself informed investigators of Gacy's attempts to rape him in 1976 and stated that after he and Gacy had returned to his home after the December 13 search of his property, Gacy had turned pale upon noting a clot of mud on his carpet which he suspected had come from his crawl space. Cram then stated Gacy had grabbed a flashlight and immediately entered the crawl space to look for evidence of digging. When asked whether he had been to the crawl space, Cram replied he had been asked by Gacy to spread lime down there and also dug trenches upon Gacy's behest with the explanation they were for plumbing.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=143}} Cram stated these trenches were {{convert|2|ft|m|sp=us}} wide, {{convert|6|ft|m|sp=us}} long and {{convert|2|ft|m|sp=us}} deep\u2014the size of graves.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=143\u2013145}}\n\n===Verbal confession===\nOn the evening of December 20, Gacy drove to his lawyers' office in [[Park Ridge, Illinois|Park Ridge]] to attend a pre-scheduled meeting he had arranged with them, ostensibly to discuss the progress of his civil suit. Upon his arrival, Gacy appeared disheveled and immediately asked for an alcoholic drink, whereupon Sam Amirante fetched a bottle of whiskey from his car. Upon his return, Amirante asked Gacy what he had to discuss with them. Gacy picked up a copy of the ''[[Chicago Daily Herald|Daily Herald]]'' from Amirante's desk; he pointed to a front-page article covering the disappearance of Robert Piest and informed his lawyers: \"This boy is dead. He's in a river.\"{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=136}}\n\nOver the following hours, Gacy gave a rambling confession that ran into the early hours of the following morning. He began by informing Amirante and Stevens he had \"been the judge ... jury and executioner of many, many people\", and that he now wanted to be the same for himself.<ref>Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 127</ref> He stated most of his victims were buried in his crawl space, and others in the Des Plaines River. Gacy dismissed his victims as \"[[Male prostitution|male prostitutes]]\", \"hustlers\" and \"liars\" to whom he gave \"the rope trick\", adding that he occasionally awoke to find \"dead, strangled kids\" on his floor, with their hands cuffed behind their back.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=171}}\n\nAs a result of the alcohol he had consumed, Gacy fell asleep midway through his confession and Amirante immediately arranged a psychiatric appointment for Gacy at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. that morning. Upon awakening several hours later, Gacy simply shook his head when informed by Amirante he had earlier confessed to killing approximately 30 people, stating: \"Well, I can't think about this right now. I've got things to do.\"<ref name=\"Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 150\">Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 150</ref> Ignoring his lawyers' advice regarding his scheduled appointment, Gacy left their office to attend to the needs of his business.<ref name=\"Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 150\" />\n\nGacy later recollected his memories of his final day of freedom as being \"hazy\", adding that he knew his arrest was inevitable and that, in his final hours of freedom, he intended to visit his friends and say his final farewells.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=255\u2013258}} Upon leaving his lawyers' office, Gacy drove to a Shell gas station where, in the course of filling his rental car, he handed a small bag of [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] to the attendant, Lance Jacobson. Jacobson immediately handed the bag to the surveillance officers, adding that Gacy had told him: \"The end is coming (for me). These guys are going to kill me.\" Gacy then drove to the home of a fellow contractor, Ronald Rhode. Inside Rhode's living room, Gacy hugged Rhode before bursting into tears and saying: \"I killed thirty people, give or take a few.\" Gacy then left Rhode's home to meet with Michael Rossi and David Cram. As he drove along the expressway, the surveillance officers noted he was holding a [[Catholic rosary|rosary]] to his chin as he prayed while driving.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=152}}\n\nAfter talking with Cram and Rossi at Cram's home, Gacy had Cram drive him to a scheduled meeting with Leroy Stevens. As he spoke with his lawyer, Cram informed the officers that Gacy had earlier divulged to both himself and Rossi that the previous evening, he had confessed to his lawyers his guilt in over thirty murders. Upon concluding his meeting with his lawyer, Gacy had Cram drive him to Maryhill Cemetery, where his father was buried.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=259}}\n\nAs Gacy drove to various locations that morning, police outlined their formal draft of their second search warrant. The purpose of the warrant was specifically to search for the body of Robert Piest in the crawl space. Upon hearing radioed reports from the surveillance detectives that, in light of his erratic behavior, Gacy might be about to commit suicide, police decided to arrest him upon a charge of possession and distribution of marijuana{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=157}} in order to hold him in custody as the formal request for a second search warrant was presented. At 4:30 on the afternoon of December 21, the eve of the hearing of Gacy's civil suit, the request for a second search warrant was granted by Judge Marvin J. Peters.<ref>Kozenczak, (2012) p. 158</ref>\n\nArmed with the signed search warrant, police and evidence technicians quickly drove to Gacy's home. Upon their arrival, officers found that Gacy had unplugged his [[sump pump]] and that the crawl space was flooded with water; to clear the water they simply replaced the plug and waited for the water to drain. After it had done so, evidence technician Daniel Genty entered the {{convert|28|x|38|ft|adj=on}} crawl space,<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 50.</ref> crawled to the southwest area, and began digging. Within minutes, he had uncovered [[putrefaction|putrefied]] flesh and a human arm bone. Genty immediately shouted to the investigators that they could charge Gacy with murder.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=167}} Genty added the remark: \"I think this place is full of kids.\"{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=167}}\n\n==Arrest and confession==\n[[File:Gacysmilemugshot.png|thumb|upright=0.7|Gacy's [[mug shot]], taken December 22.]]\nAfter being informed that the police had found human remains in his crawl space and that he would now face murder charges, Gacy told officers he wanted to \"clear the air\",{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=171}} adding that he had known his arrest was inevitable since the previous evening, which he had spent on the couch in his lawyers' office.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=170}}\n\nIn the early hours of December 22, 1978, Gacy confessed to police that since 1972, he had committed 25 to 30 murders, all of whom he falsely claimed were of teenage male [[Runaway (dependent)|runaway]]s or male prostitutes, the majority of whom he had buried in his crawl space.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=174}} Some victims he referred to by name, but most names he claimed not to know or remember. He confessed he had buried the body of John Butkovich in his garage.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=188}} When asked where he drew the inspiration for the two-by-four attached with manacles at either end found at his house, Gacy stated he had been inspired to construct the device from reading about the [[Dean Corll|Houston Mass Murders]].{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=197}}{{efn|The Houston Mass Murders were a series of killings uncovered in 1973 in which Dean Corll, with two teenaged accomplices, had also used a wooden device (in their case a board fitted with handcuffs at each corner) to restrain their male victims throughout their sexual abuse and torture.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Man with the Candy: The Story of the Houston Mass Murders|last = Olsen|first = Jack|publisher = Simon and Schuster|year = 2008|isbn = 978-1-439-12870-1 |page = 146}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = How to Make a Serial Killer: The Twisted Development of Innocent Children Into the World's Most Sadistic Murderers|last = Berry-Dee|first = Christopher|publisher = Ulysses Press|year = 2008|isbn = 978-1-569-75943-1|location = |page = 202}}</ref> Gacy was likely inspired to construct this device, and to initially restrain his victims by tricking them into handcuffs, by press coverage relating to the Houston Mass Murders.{{sfn|Berry-Dee|2009|p=138}}}} In January 1979, he had planned to further conceal the corpses by covering the entire crawl space with concrete.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=222}} \n\nWhen specifically questioned about Piest, Gacy confessed to strangling him at his house on the evening of December 11 after luring him there. He also admitted to having slept alongside Piest's body that evening, before disposing of the corpse in the Des Plaines River in the early hours of December 13.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19800210&id=aE80AAAAIBAJ&sjid=zWcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6517,3813660|title=Alleged Victim of Gacy Never Returned to Store|date=February 10, 1980|newspaper=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref> The reason he had arrived at the police station in a dirty and disheveled manner in the early hours of December 13 was that he had been in a minor traffic accident after disposing of Piest's body, en route to his appointment with Des Plaines officers. In this accident, his vehicle had slid off an ice-covered road, and he had unsuccessfully attempted to free the vehicle himself before the vehicle had to be towed from its location.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=176\u2013177}} \n[[File:Gacycrawlspace.png|thumb|upright=1.45|Gacy's sketch of burial locations in his basement, and investigators' later diagram]]\nTo assist officers in their search for the victims buried beneath his house, Gacy drew a rough diagram of his basement upon a phone message sheet to indicate where their bodies were buried.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=193}}\n\n===Search for victims===\nOn December 22 police took Gacy to his house, where he marked his garage floor with paint to show where he had buried Butkovich's body. They then drove to the spot on the I-55 bridge from which he had thrown the bodies of Piest and four others. Four of the five victims Gacy claimed to have disposed of there were recovered.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=219}}{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=320}}\n\nBy December 29, twenty-six bodies had been found in the crawl space, and one beneath the garage.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=213}} Operations were suspended due to the [[Chicago Blizzard of 1979]], but resumed in March despite Gacy's insistence that all the buried victims had been found.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19790105&id=Yk8xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yaEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5965,3354691|work=The Montreal Gazette|via=Google News Archive Search|title=Search to Continue at 'House of Horrors'|date=January 5, 1979|page=70}}</ref><ref name=\"Michael H. Stone 2019 pp. 196-203\"/>\n\nOn March 9, a body was found buried close to a barbecue in the backyard, and on March 16 another was found beneath the dining room floor.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=250}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=250}} In April 1979, Gacy's vacant house was demolished.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19790412&id=FH4xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4aEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7078,918268|work=The Montreal Gazette|via=Google News Archive Search|publisher=|title=Neighbors Relieved as Gacy Home Demolished|date=April 12, 1979|page=95}}</ref>\n\nThree additional bodies, which had been found in the nearby Des Plaines River between June and December 1978, were also confirmed to have been victims of Gacy.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=219\u2013221}}\n[[File:Crawlspace29.jpg|upright=1|thumb|Twenty-six bodies were found buried in Gacy's crawl space.]]\nSeveral bodies unearthed at Gacy's property were found with plastic bags over their heads or upper torsos.{{efn|Gacy had stated in a January 1979 interview that he would cover the victim's head or upper torso with a plastic bag if he noted bleeding from the nose or mouth.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=223}}}} In addition, several of the bodies were found with the ligature used to strangle them still knotted around their necks. In other instances, cloth gags were found lodged deep down the victims' throats, leading the medical examiner to conclude that 12 victims died not of strangulation, but of asphyxiation.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=221}} In some cases, bodies were found with foreign objects such as prescription bottles lodged into their pelvic region, the position of which indicated the items had been thrust into the victims' anus.<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 80.</ref> All the victims discovered at 8213 Summerdale were in an advanced state of decomposition, and the medical examiner chiefly relied upon [[Forensic dentistry|dental records]] to facilitate the identification of the remains.<ref>''The Casebook of Forensic Detection'' {{ISBN|0-471-07650-3}} p. 134</ref>\n\nTwo victims were identified because of their known connection to Gacy through PDM.<ref name=\"SHJ-3morebodies\" /> Most identifications were facilitated with the assistance of [[X-ray]] charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1891&dat=19791118&id=mZ8fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DNYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4650,2607923|title=Gacy Victim Identified|date=November 18, 1979|publisher=The Gadsden Times}}</ref> Identifications were supported via personal [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifact]]s being found at 8213 Summerdale: one victim, 19-year-old David Talsma, was identified via comparison of [[radiology]] records of a healed fracture of the left [[scapula]] matching distress evident upon the 17th skeleton recovered from Gacy's property.<ref>''The Casebook of Forensic Detection'' {{ISBN|0-471-07650-3}} p. 135</ref> Timothy O'Rourke was last heard mentioning that a contractor had offered him a job.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=219}} Of Gacy's identified victims, the youngest were Samuel Stapleton and Michael Marino, both 14; the oldest was Russell Nelson, who was 21. Six victims have never been identified.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cookcountysheriff.org/sheriffs_police/gacy/gacy.html|title=Cook County Sheriff \u2013 Unidentified Victims of John Wayne Gacy|publisher=|access-date=November 22, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223144708/http://cookcountysheriff.org/sheriffs_police/gacy/gacy.html|archive-date=December 23, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 1979, a decomposed body was discovered entangled in exposed roots on the edge of the Des Plaines River in [[Grundy County, Illinois|Grundy County]].<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 190</ref> The body was identified via dental records as being that of Robert Piest. A subsequent [[autopsy]] revealed that three wads of \"paper-like material\" had been shoved down his throat while he was alive,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=362}} causing him to die of suffocation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Authorities Level John Gacy Home |date=April 12, 1979 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1916&dat=19790412&id=QyVJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VAYNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1285,2633468 |publisher=The Hour |accessdate=September 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nGacy was brought to trial on February 6, 1980, charged with 33 murders.<ref name=\"SHT-Speedup\" /> He was tried in Cook County, Illinois, before [[Louis B. Garippo|Judge Louis Garippo]]; the [[voir dire|jury was selected]] from [[Rockford, Illinois|Rockford]] because of significant press coverage in Cook County.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|pp=241\u2013242}}\n\nAt the request of his defense counsel, Gacy spent over three hundred hours in the year before his trial with the doctors at the [[Menard Correctional Center]]. He underwent a variety of psychological tests{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=261}} before a panel of psychiatrists to determine whether he was mentally competent to stand trial.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=261\u2013262}}\n\nGacy had attempted to convince the doctors that he suffered from a [[Dissociative identity disorder|multiple personality disorder]].{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=312}} His lawyers opted to have Gacy plead [[insanity plea|not guilty by reason of insanity]] to the charges against him, and produced several psychiatric experts who had examined Gacy the previous year to testify to their findings.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=315\u2013323}} Three psychiatric experts appearing for the defense at Gacy's trial testified they found Gacy to be a [[paranoid schizophrenic]] with a multiple personality disorder.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|pp=301}}<ref name=\"Michael H. Stone 2019 pp. 196-203\"/>\n\nThe prosecutors presented a case that indicated Gacy was sane and fully in control of his actions.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=250}} To support this contention, they produced several witnesses to testify to the [[premeditation]] of Gacy's actions and the efforts he went to in order to escape detection. Those doctors refuted the defense doctors' claims of multiple personality and insanity. Cram and Rossi both confessed that Gacy had made them dig trenches in his crawl space. Cram testified that in August 1977, Gacy had marked a location in the crawl space with sticks and told him to dig a [[Drainage#Drainage in construction|drainage]] trench.<ref name=\"The Montreal Gazette Feb. 13, 1980\" />{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=181}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=311}}\n\nImmediately after Cram had completed his testimony, Rossi testified for the state. When asked where he had dug in the crawl space, Rossi turned to a diagram of Gacy's home on display in the courtroom. This diagram showed where the bodies were found in the crawl space and elsewhere on the property. Rossi pointed to the location of the remains of an unidentified victim known as \"Body 13\".{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=311}} Rossi stated he had not dug any other trenches, but\u2014at Gacy's request\u2014had supervised other PDM employees digging trenches in the crawl space.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=181}}\n\nBoth Rossi and Cram also testified that Gacy periodically looked into the crawl space to ensure they and other employees ordered to dig trenches in the crawl space did not deviate from the precise locations he had marked.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=312}} Gacy had testified after his arrest that he had only dug five of the victims' graves in his crawl space{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=142}} and had his employees (including Gregory Godzik) dig the remaining trenches so that he would \"have graves available\".{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=360}}\n\nOn February 18 Robert Stein,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=321}} the Cook County medical examiner who supervised the exhumations, testified that all the bodies were \"markedly decomposed<!--,--> [and] putrefied<!--, skeletalized remains-->\",<ref>{{cite news|title=Mother Cries at Description of Son's Grave|date=February 19, 1980 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VHVkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Mn4NAAAAIBAJ&pg=2366,5212913 |newspaper=The Calgary Herald |accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref> and that of all the autopsies he performed, thirteen victims had died of asphyxiation, six of ligature strangulation, one of multiple stab wounds to the chest,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=102}} and ten in undetermined ways.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=322}}{{efn|Stein performed autopsies on each victim recovered at Gacy's property and upon the body of Robert Piest. He did not perform autopsies upon the three other victims recovered from the Des Plaines River.}}\nWhen Gacy's defense team suggested that all 33 deaths were accidental (by [[erotic asphyxia]]), Stein called this highly improbable.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=322\u2013323}}{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=233}}\n\nJeffrey Rignall testified on behalf of the defense on February 21.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=325}} Recounting his ordeal, Rignall wept repeatedly while describing Gacy's torture of him in March 1978. Asked whether Gacy appreciated the criminality of his actions, Rignall said he believed that Gacy was unable to conform his actions to the law's expectations because of the \"beastly and animalistic ways he attacked me\".<ref>Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 290</ref> During specific cross-examination relating to the torture, Rignall vomited and was excused from further testimony.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=300}}\n\nOn February 29, Donald Voorhees, whom Gacy had sexually assaulted in 1967, testified to his ordeal at Gacy's hands, and that Gacy had subsequently paid another youth to beat him and spray Mace in his face so he would not testify against him.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=340}} Voorhees felt unable to testify, but did briefly attempt to do so, before being asked to step down.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=340}}\n\nRobert Donnelly testified the week after Voorhees, recounting his ordeal at Gacy's hands in December 1977. Donnelly was visibly distressed as he recollected the abuse he endured at Gacy's hands and came close to breaking down on several occasions. As Donnelly testified, Gacy repeatedly laughed at him,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=333}} but Donnelly finished his testimony. One of Gacy's defense attorneys, Robert Motta, during Donnelly's cross-examination, attempted to discredit his testimony, but Donnelly did not waver from his testimony of what had occurred.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=345}}\n\nDuring the fifth week of the trial, Gacy wrote a personal letter to Judge Garippo requesting a [[mistrial]]{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=342}} on a number of bases, including that he did not approve his lawyers' insanity plea approach; that his lawyers had not allowed him to take the witness stand (as he had desired to do); that his defense had not called enough witnesses, and that the police were lying about statements he had purportedly made to detectives after his arrest and that, in any event, the statements were \"self-serving\" for use by the prosecution.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=350\u2013351}} Judge Garippo addressed Gacy's letter by informing him that under the law he had the choice as to whether he wished to testify, and he was free to indicate as much to the judge if he wished to do so.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=312}}\n\n===Closing arguments===\nOn March 11, final arguments from both prosecution and defense attorneys began, with the arguments concluding on the following day. Prosecuting attorney Terry Sullivan argued first, outlining Gacy's history of abusing youths, the testimony of his efforts to avoid detection and describing Gacy's surviving victims\u2014Voorhees and Donnelly\u2014as \"living dead\".{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=361}} Referring to Gacy as the \"worst of all murderers\",<ref>Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 324</ref> Sullivan stated: \"John Gacy has accounted for more human devastation than many earthly catastrophes, but one must tremble. I tremble when thinking about just how close he came to getting away with it all.\"{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=361}}\n\nAfter the state's four-hour closing, counsel Sam Amirante argued for the defense. Amirante argued against the testimony delivered by the doctors who had testified for the prosecution, repeatedly citing the testimony of the four psychiatrists and psychologists who had testified on behalf of the defense.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=360}} Amirante also accused Sullivan of scarcely referring to the evidence presented throughout the trial in his own closing argument, and of arousing hatred against his client. The defense lawyer attempted to portray Gacy as a \"man driven by compulsions he was unable to control\".{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=363}}\n\nIn support of these arguments, the defense counsel repeatedly referred to the testimony of the doctors who had appeared for the defense, in addition to the testimony of defense witnesses such as Jeffrey Rignall and Gacy's former business associate Mickel Reed\u2014both of whom had testified to their belief that Gacy had been unable to control his actions.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=359}} Amirante then urged the jury to put aside any prejudice they held against his client, and requested they deliver a verdict of not guilty by reason of insanity, adding that the psychology of Gacy's behavior would be of benefit to scientific research and that the psychology of his mind should be studied.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=361}}\n\n[[File:Kunkletrial.jpg|upright=1|thumb|William Kunkle, prosecutor at Gacy's trial, standing before a board depicting the 22 victims identified by February 1980.]]\nOn the morning of March 12,{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=364}} William Kunkle continued to argue for the prosecution. Kunkle referred to the defense's contention of insanity as \"a [[falsity|sham]]\", arguing that the facts of the case demonstrated Gacy's ability to think logically and control his actions. Kunkle also referred to the testimony of a doctor who had examined Gacy in 1968. This doctor had diagnosed Gacy as an [[antisocial personality]], capable of committing crimes without remorse. Kunkle indicated that had the recommendations of this doctor been heeded, Gacy would have not been freed.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=368}}\n\nAt the close of his argument, Kunkle pulled each of the 22 photos of Gacy's identified victims off a board displaying the images and asked the jury not to show sympathy but to \"show justice\". Kunkle then asked the jury to \"show the same sympathy this man showed when he took these lives and put them ''there!''{{-\"}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=368}} before throwing the stack of photos into the opening of the trap door of Gacy's crawl space, which had been introduced as evidence and was on display in the courtroom. After Kunkle had finished his testimony, the jury retired to consider their verdict.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=369}}\n\nThe jury deliberated for less than two hours<ref>{{cite news|title=Gacy Sentenced to Die; Readies Appeals |date=March 14, 1980 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2209&dat=19800314&id=pp8rAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PPwFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2750,2719769 |newspaper=The Telegraph |access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> and found Gacy guilty of the thirty-three charges of murder for which he had been brought to trial; he was also found guilty of sexual assault and taking indecent liberties with a child; both convictions in reference to Robert Piest.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=369}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Court Refuses to Hear Mass Murderer Case |date=March 1, 1985 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=IbZBAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sKkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6852,3893550&dq/ |publisher=The Harlan Daily Enterprise |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> The conviction for 33 murders was then the largest number of murders charged to one individual in United States history.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the [[Sentence (law)|sentencing phase]] of the trial, the jury deliberated for more than two hours before sentencing Gacy to death.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=374}}<ref name=\"Rossi1980b\" /> Execution was initially set for June 2, 1980.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=387}}\n\n==Death row==\nUpon being sentenced, Gacy was transferred to the [[Menard Correctional Center]] in [[Chester, Illinois]], where he remained [[incarceration|incarcerated]] on death row for 14 years.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=388}}\n\nIsolated in his prison cell, Gacy began to paint. The subjects Gacy painted varied, although many were of clowns, some of which depicted himself as \"Pogo\". Many of his paintings have been displayed at exhibitions;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/north-america/usa/illinois/articles/the-controversy-of-killer-john-wayne-gacys-artwork/ |title=Controversy of Killer John Wayne Gacy's Artwork |publisher=theculturetrip.com |date=November 25, 2016 |access-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=CNN>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/US/05/13/serial.killer.art/|title=Controversial Serial Killer's Paintings go on Display in Las Vegas|work=CNN|access-date=May 15, 2011|date=May 13, 2011}}</ref> others have been sold at various auctions, with individual prices ranging between $200 and $20,000.<ref name=autogenerated1>Murder casebook number 11 {{ISSN|1364-5803}}, p. 36</ref> Although Gacy was permitted to earn money from the sale of his paintings until 1985, he claimed his artwork was intended \"to bring joy into people's lives\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=351}}\n\nOn February 15, 1983, Gacy was stabbed in the arm by Henry Brisbon, a fellow death row inmate known as the I-57 killer. At the time of this attack, Gacy had been participating in a voluntary work program when Brisbon ran towards him and stabbed him once in the upper arm with a sharpened wire. A second death row inmate injured in the attack, William Jones, received a [[surface anatomy|superficial]] stab wound to the head. Both received treatment in the prison hospital for their wounds.<ref>Koziol, Ronald (February 16, 1983). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1291&dat=19830216&id=Suo0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=T40DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6608,4021186 \"Gacy Stabbed in Prison\"]. ''[[Boca Raton News]]''. p 11A. Archived at Google News.</ref>\n\n===Appeals===\nAfter his incarceration, Gacy read numerous law books and filed voluminous motions and appeals, although he did not prevail in any. Gacy's appeals related to issues such as the validity of the first search warrant granted to Des Plaines police on December 13, 1978, and his objection to his lawyers' insanity plea defense at his trial.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=344}} Gacy also contended that, although he held \"some knowledge\" of five of the murders (those of McCoy, Butkovich, Godzik, Szyc and Piest),{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=347}} the other 28 murders had been committed by employees who were in possession of keys to his house while he was away on business trips.\n\nIn mid-1984, the [[Supreme Court of Illinois]] upheld Gacy's conviction and ordered that he be executed by lethal injection on November 14.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=351}} Gacy filed an appeal against this decision, which was denied by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] on March 4, 1985. The following year, Gacy filed a further post-conviction petition, seeking a new trial. His then-defense lawyer, [[Richard Kling]], argued that Gacy had been provided with ineffective legal counsel at his 1980 trial. This post-conviction petition was dismissed on September 11, 1986.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-09-12/news/8603080188_1_gacy-new-trial-illinois-supreme-court \"Mass Killer Gacy Denied New Trial\"]. ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. September 12, 1986.</ref>\n\nThe 1985 decision that he be executed was again appealed by Gacy, although his conviction was again upheld on September 29, 1988, with the Illinois Supreme Court setting a renewed execution date of January 11, 1989.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19880930&id=FKgeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=V84EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5611,6110201 \"Death Sentence Upheld for John Wayne Gacy\"]. ''[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]''. September 30, 1988 p A2. Archived at Google News.</ref>\n\nAfter Gacy's final appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court was denied in October 1993, the Illinois Supreme Court formally set an execution date for May 10, 1994.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1993-12-18/news/9312180642_1_gacy-john-wayne-supreme-court |title=Long-delayed Execution Set For John Wayne Gacy |newspaper=Orlando Sentinel |date=December 18, 1993 |access-date=December 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Execution===\n[[File:John Wayne Gacy certificate of death.jpg|upright=1|thumb|Gacy's certificate of death.]]\nOn the morning of May 9, 1994, Gacy was transferred from the Menard Correctional Center to [[Stateville Correctional Center]] in [[Crest Hill, Illinois|Crest Hill]] to be executed. That afternoon, he was allowed a private picnic on the prison grounds with his family. For his [[last meal]], Gacy ordered a bucket of Kentucky Fried Chicken, a dozen [[fried shrimp]], french fries, fresh strawberries, and a Diet Coke.<ref name=\"tw\">{{cite web|title=Last Meals|work=[[Tucson Weekly]]|first=John|last=Peck|date=January 5, 2006|url=http://www.tucsonweekly.com/tucson/last-meals/Content?oid=1082921|access-date=November 11, 2015}}</ref> That evening, he observed prayer with a [[Catholic priest]] before being escorted to the Stateville execution chamber to receive a lethal injection.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Susan|last1=Kuczka|first2=Rob|last2=Karwath|url=http://www.soci.niu.edu/~critcrim/dp/dpill/dpgacy1.txt|title=All Appeals Fail: Gacy is Executed. Serial Killer Dies of Lethal Injection|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=May 10, 1994|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612215340/http://www.soci.niu.edu/~critcrim/dp/dpill/dpgacy1.txt |archive-date=June 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\nBefore the execution began, the chemicals used to perform the execution unexpectedly solidified, clogging the [[IV tube]] administering the chemicals into Gacy's arm and complicating the execution procedure. Blinds covering the window through which witnesses observed the execution were drawn, and the execution team replaced the clogged tube to complete the procedure. After ten minutes, the blinds were reopened and the execution resumed. The entire procedure took 18 minutes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,980752,00.html |magazine=Time |date=May 23, 1994 |ref=seideman |title=A Twist Before Dying |last=Seideman |first=David |access-date=January 14, 2010}}</ref> [[Anesthesia|Anesthesiologists]] blamed the problem on the inexperience of prison officials who were conducting the execution, stating that had correct execution procedures been followed, the complications would never have occurred. This error apparently led to Illinois' subsequent adoption of an alternative method of lethal injection. On this subject, one of the prosecutors at Gacy's trial, William Kunkle, said: \"He got a much easier death than any of his victims.\"<ref name=\"Deseret\">{{cite news| title=Serial Killer Executed by Injection in Illinois| url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/352327/SERIAL-KILLER-EXECUTED-BY-INJECTION-IN-ILLINOIS.html/| newspaper=[[Deseret News]]| date=May 10, 1994| access-date=February 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to published reports, Gacy was a diagnosed [[psychopath]]<ref name=\"hare\">{{cite book|first=Robert D.|last=Hare|authorlink=Robert D. Hare|title=Without Conscience: The Disturbing World of the Psychopaths Among Us|publisher=[[Guilford Press]]|location=New York City|date=1999|page=[https://archive.org/details/withoutconscienc00hare/page/23 23]|isbn=978-1-57230-451-2|url=https://archive.org/details/withoutconscienc00hare/page/23}}</ref> who did not express any remorse for his crimes. His [[final statement]] to his lawyer before his execution was that killing him would not compensate for the loss of others, and that the state was murdering him.<ref name=\"Deseret\" /> His [[Last words|final spoken words]] were \"Kiss my ass.\"<ref name=\"CBSChicago\" />\n\nIn the hours leading up to Gacy's execution, a crowd estimated to number over 1,000<ref>{{cite journal |title=Murder In Mind |issue=11 |issn=1364-5803 |pages=36\u201337}}</ref> gathered outside the correctional center; the majority of whom were vocally in favor of the execution, although a number of [[Opposition to capital punishment in the United States|anti-death penalty]] protesters were also present. Some of those in favor of the execution wore T-shirts hearkening to Gacy's previous community services as a clown and bearing satirical slogans such as \"No tears for the clown\".<ref name=\"poster\">{{cite journal |journal=[[The Economist]] |title=Poster Child |date=May 14, 1994 |volume=331 |issue=7863}}</ref> The anti-death penalty protesters present observed a silent [[candlelight vigil]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/uncategorized/in-joliet-little-sympathy-for-convicted-killer/article_f7d646be-9c16-5bf1-853f-c845a302ef5b.html|title=In Joliet, Little Sympathy for Convicted Killer|access-date=July 22, 2017|newspaper=NWI Times|date=May 10, 1994}}</ref>\n\nAfter Gacy's death was confirmed at 12:58&nbsp;a.m. on May 10, 1994, his brain was removed. It is in the possession of [[Helen Morrison]], a witness for the defense at Gacy's trial,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=354}} who has interviewed Gacy and other serial killers in an attempt to isolate common personality traits of violent [[antisocial personality disorder|sociopaths]]. His body was cremated after the execution.\n\nIn the months following Gacy's execution, many of his paintings were auctioned.<ref name=paintings /> Some were bought so that they could be destroyed in a June 1994 communal bonfire held in [[Naperville, Illinois]] and attended by approximately 300 people, including family members of nine of Gacy's victims.<ref name=paintings>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2004/06/06/State/Sale_of_Chicago_seria.shtml |title=Sale of Chicago Serial Killer's Art Draws Protests |newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]] |publisher=[[Times Publishing Company]]|location=St. Petersburg, Florida|date=June 6, 2004 |access-date=January 14, 2010 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\n\n===Identified victims===\nOnly 27 of Gacy's victims were ever conclusively identified. By the time of Gacy's trial, 22 victims had been identified. In March 1980, two further bodies unearthed from Gacy's crawl space were identified via dental and radiology records{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=248}} as those of Kenneth Parker and Michael Marino; both reported missing on October 25, 1976,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=L3cLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bVMDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5938,2528900&dq/|title=Gacy Victims Identified|date=March 31, 1980|publisher=Kingsman Daily Miner}}</ref> the day after they had disappeared.<ref name=\"StJoseph\" />\n\nIn May 1986, the ninth victim exhumed from Gacy's crawl space was identified as Timothy Jack McCoy, Gacy's first victim.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gacy Victim is Identified|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3iZTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sIIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2450,753399&dq/ |publisher=Mohave Daily Miner |date=May 8, 1986|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/identified7.html |title=\"Closed Cases\", Doe Network |publisher=Doenetwork.org |access-date=July 7, 2010}}</ref> Dental records and a belt buckle assisted the identification.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gacy's 1st Victim Finally Identified|date=May 10, 1986 |url=http://chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1986-05-10-8602020800-story.html |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=October 12, 2018}}</ref> One further victim was identified in November 2011 through [[DNA testing]] as William George Bundy, a 19-year-old construction worker who was last seen by his family on his way to a party on October 26, 1976.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-sheriff-gacy-victim-identified-through-dna-20111129,0,3315365.story \"Sheriff: Gacy victim identified through DNA\"], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', November 29, 2011</ref> Bundy had apparently worked for Gacy.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\" /> Shortly after Gacy's arrest, his family had contacted Bundy's dentist in the hope of submitting his dental records for comparison with the unidentified bodies. However, the records had been destroyed after the dentist had retired.<ref>[http://www.torontosun.com/2011/11/29/gacys-victim-19-identified-illinois-cops/ Toronto Sun] November 29, 2011</ref> A second victim was identified through DNA testing in July 2017 as a 16-year-old from [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]] named James Haakenson, who was last known to have contacted his family on August 5, 1976.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-john-wayne-gacy-victim-haakenson-20170719-story.html|title=Second Long-unknown Gacy Victim Identified as Boy from Minnesota|last=Crepeau|first=Megan|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=July 20, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Timothy Jack McCoy (16)<br />January 3, 1972<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/24901028.html?dids=24901028:24901028&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=May+10%2C+1986&author=Mitchell+Locin&pub=Chicago+Tribune|title=Chicago Tribune |publisher=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com |date=May 10, 1986 |access-date=July 7, 2010 | first=Mitchell | last=Locin}}</ref> Body 9. Crawl space.\n* John Butkovich (18)<br />July 31, 1975{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=126}} Body 2. Garage.\n* Darrell Julius Samson (18)<br />April 6, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=361\u2013362}} Body 29. Dining room.\n* Randall Wayne Reffett (15)<br />May 14, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=301}} Body 7. Crawl space.\n* Samuel G. Dodd Stapleton (14)<br />May 14, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=215}} Body 6. Crawl space.\n* Michael Bonnin (17)<br />June 3, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=301}} Body 18. Crawl space.\n* William Huey Carroll, Jr. (16)<br />June 13, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=303}} Body 22. Crawl space.\n* James Byron Haakenson (16)<br />August 5, 1976<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/timeline-john-wayne-gacys-case-48729716|title=Timeline of John Wayne Gacy Case|access-date=July 19, 2017|newspaper=ABC News|date=July 19, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720011748/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/timeline-john-wayne-gacys-case-48729716|archivedate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> Body 24. Crawl space.\n* Rick Louis Johnston (17)<br />August 6, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=215}} Body 23. Crawl space.\n{{col-break}}\n* Kenneth Ray Parker (16)<br />October 24, 1976{{sfn|Linedecker|1986|p=248}} Body 15. Crawl space.\n* Michael Marino (14)<br />October 24, 1976{{sfn|Linedecker|1986|p=248}} Body 14. Crawl space.\n* William George Bundy (19)<br />October 26, 1976<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cookcountysheriff.org/press_page/press_GacyVictimIdentified_11_29_2011.html|title=Cook County Sheriff Press \u2013 Unknown Victim of John Wayne Gacy is Identified|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223030827/http://www.cookcountysheriff.org/press_page/press_GacyVictimIdentified_11_29_2011.html|archivedate=February 23, 2015}}</ref> Body 19. Crawl space.\n* Gregory John Godzik (17)<br />December 12, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=54}} Body 4. Crawl space.\n* John Alan Szyc (19)<br />January 20, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=55}} Body 3. Crawl space.\n* Jon Steven Prestidge (20)<br />March 15, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=303}} Body 1. Crawl space.\n* Matthew Bowman (19)<br />July 5, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 8. Crawl space.\n* Robert Edward Gilroy, Jr. (18)<br />September 15, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 25. Crawl space.\n* John Antheney Mowery (19)<br />September 25, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 20. Crawl space.\n{{col-break}}\n* Russell Lloyd Nelson (21)<br />October 17, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 16. Crawl space.\n* Robert Winch (16)<br />November 10, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 11. Crawl space.\n* Tommy Joe Boling (20)<br />November 18, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 12. Crawl space.\n* David Paul Talsma (19)<br />December 9, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=305}} Body 17. Crawl space.\n* William Wayne Kindred (19)<br />February 16, 1978{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=141}} Body 27. Crawl space.\n* Timothy D. O'Rourke (20)<br />June 16\u201323, 1978{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=219\u2013220}} Body 31. Des Plaines river.\n* Frank William Landingin (19)<br />November 4, 1978{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=220}} Body 32. Des Plaines river.\n* James Mazzara (20)<br />November 24, 1978{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=153}} Body 33. Des Plaines river.\n* Robert Jerome Piest (15)<br />December 11, 1978{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=7}} Body 30. Des Plaines river.\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Unidentified victims===\n[[File:Gacy victims.jpg|thumb|upright=1.85|Facial reconstructions of the unidentified victims, released to the [[News media|media]] in 1980. Depicted left to right are Body 5, Body 9 (later identified as Timothy McCoy), Body 24 (later identified as James Haakenson), Body 19 (later identified as William Bundy), Body 21, Body 28, Body 13, Body 26, and Body 10.]]\nSix victims remain unidentified, five of whom had been buried beneath Gacy's crawl space, with one additional youth buried approximately {{convert|15|ft}} from the barbecue pit in his backyard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_IgxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9qEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6913,2124365&dq/ |title=Another Skeleton Found at Home |access-date=February 14, 2017}}</ref> Experts used the skulls of the unidentified victims to create [[forensic facial reconstruction|facial reconstruction]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aboutforensics.co.uk/john-wayne-gacy/ |title=The Forensics Library: John Wayne Gacy |publisher=aboutforensics.co.uk |date=June 30, 2012 |access-date=February 14, 2017}}</ref> Based upon Gacy's confession, information relative to where the victims were buried in his crawl space relative to Gacy's identified victims, and forensic analysis, police were able to determine the most likely dates when his unidentified victims were killed.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1980/07/15/page/41/article/parents-is-your-missing-son-pictured-here | date=July 15, 1980 |title=Parents: Is Your Missing Son Pictured Here? |first=Jerry |last=Crimmins |newspaper=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n# [[circa|c]]. January 1974. Body 28. Backyard. Male aged 14\u201318.<ref name=\"Case File 954UMIL\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/11006|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 11006|publisher=}}</ref>\n# June 13 \u2013 August 5, 1976. Body 26. Crawl space. Male aged 23\u201330.<ref name=\"doenetwork1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/11004|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 11004|publisher=}}</ref>\n# August 6 \u2013 October 5, 1976. Body 13. Crawl space. Male aged 18\u201322.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/955umil.html |title=Case File 955UMIL |publisher=The Doe Network |access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/10999|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 10999|publisher=}}</ref>\n# August 6 \u2013 October 24, 1976. Body 21. Crawl space. Male aged 15\u201324.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/962umil.html |title=Case File 962UMIL |publisher=The Doe Network |access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/11000|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 11000|publisher=}}</ref>\n# December 1976 \u2013 March 15, 1977. Body 5. Crawl space. Male aged 22\u201332.<ref name=\"Case File 958UMIL\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/10994|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 10994|publisher=}}</ref>\n# March 15 \u2013 July 5, 1977. Body 10. Crawl space. Male aged 17\u201321.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/957umil.html |title=Case File 954UMIL |publisher=The Doe Network |access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/10998|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 10998|publisher=}}</ref>\n[[File:Body 10 and Body 13.jpg|thumb|2018 [[Forensic facial reconstruction|facial reconstructions]] of Body 10 (left) and Body 13.]]\nAn unidentified body found in the crawl space may also have been the first unidentified victim; Gacy's second victim. Gacy stated to investigators he had also been buried in the crawl space close to first victim (later identifed as McCoy). However, at his 1980 trial, prosecutor William Kunkle reasoned Gacy's second murder victim must have been the unidentified victim buried beneath his barbecue pit.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=274}} Statements made by Gacy following his arrest also leave a possibility the sixth unidentified victim may have been murdered as early as 1974.{{efn|His [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System|NamUs]] case report can be found [https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/10998 ''here''], and a [[facial composite]] can be seen [https://tribwgntv.files.wordpress.com/2018/07/john-doe-10.jpeg ''here'']}}\n\nIn October 2011, Cook County Sheriff [[Tom Dart|Thomas Dart]] announced that investigators, having obtained full DNA profiles from each of the unidentified victims, were to renew their efforts to identify all of them. At a press conference held to announce this intention, Sheriff Dart stated investigators are actively seeking DNA samples from individuals across the United States related to any male missing between 1970 and 1979.<ref name=\"CookCS\" /> Test results thus far conducted have confirmed the identification of two victims, ruled out the possibility of numerous other missing youths as being victims of Gacy,<ref>{{cite news |title=Sheriff: Solid Leads in Effort to ID Gacy Victims |first=Don |last=Babwin |date=October 17, 2011 |url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2011/10/17/sheriff_solid_leads_in_effort_to_id_gacy_victims |access-date=October 26, 2011 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2012/05/07/more-dna-being-analyzed-to-determine-ids-of-gacy-victims/ |title=More DNA Being Analyzed To Determine IDs Of Gacy Victims \u00ab CBS Chicago |publisher=Chicago.cbslocal.com |date=May 7, 2012 |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> and solved four unrelated [[cold case]]s dating between 1972 and 1979.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/21/john-wayne-gacy-investigation_n_1904401.html/ |title=John Wayne Gacy Investigation Helps Solve Missing Daniel Noe Case |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=September 21, 2012 |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cookcountysheriff.org/press_page/press_%20ColdCaseSolved_09_23_2015.html|title=Cook County Sheriff Press \u2013 Sherifs's Gacy Investigation Solves 1979 Cold Case|publisher=|access-date=September 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927025637/http://www.cookcountysheriff.org/press_page/press_%20ColdCaseSolved_09_23_2015.html|archive-date=September 27, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865562848/Remains-found-in-Utah-identified-through-John-Wayne-Gacy-investigation.html |title=Remains Found in Utah Identified Through John Wayne Gacy Investigation |newspaper=deseretnews.com |date=September 20, 2012 |access-date=February 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Tribune\" />\n\n====Identification dispute of Michael Marino====\nDisputed [[DNA]] and dental tests conducted between 2012 and 2016 indicates that neither body found in the common grave in Gacy's crawl space and identified as those of Kenneth Parker and Michael Marino in 1980 was actually Marino.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/07/03/dna-test-gacy-victim-mother-marino/2486561/|title=DNA Test Revives Mystery of Killer Gacy's Victim No. 14 |access-date=October 9, 2018|newspaper=USA Today|date=July 5, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"alison1\">{{cite web|url=https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2016/03/31/new-dna-test-confirms-second-false-id-in-gacy-case/|title=BREAKING: New DNA Test Confirms Second False ID in Gacy Case|last=Alison|date=March 31, 2016|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211200055/https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2016/03/31/new-dna-test-confirms-second-false-id-in-gacy-case/|archivedate=December 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"cbslocal1\">{{cite web|url=http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2012/10/25/dna-backs-up-moms-doubt-gacy-victim-misidentified/ |title=DNA Backs Up Mom's Doubt: Gacy Victim Misidentified \u00ab CBS Chicago |publisher=Chicago.cbslocal.com |access-date=March 14, 2013|date=October 25, 2012 }}</ref> Marino's mother had always doubted the identification of her son because clothing found upon the body was inconsistent with what her son had worn when she last saw him. In addition, the [[dental radiography|dental X-ray]] conducted upon the victim identified as Michael Marino had revealed the victim had all of his [[second molar]]s, whereas a dental X-ray conducted upon Marino in March 1976 revealed one molar had not [[tooth eruption|erupted]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-10-07/news/ct-met-john-wayne-gacy-victim-20111007_1_dna-testing-exhumed-grave-site/ |title=Alleged Victim of John Wayne Gacy to be Exhumed|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=October 7, 2011 |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> The original identification of the body identified as Michael Marino has been disputed because neither an upper nor a lower jaw bone was present upon the exhumed body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/10/25/14705528-lawyers-dna-proves-john-wayne-gacy-victim-was-misidentified |title=Lawyers: DNA Proves John Wayne Gacy Victim was Misidentified \u2013 U.S. News |publisher=Usnews.nbcnews.com |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> Nonetheless, the [[orthodontist]] who had identified Marino's remains has stated his conviction in the accuracy of his findings, adding he had \"compared 32 teeth, probably half a dozen of them had very distinct [[tooth filling|fillings]] and every one of them was consistent with Michael Marino.\"{{efn| DNA testing conducted upon the exhumed body of Kenneth Parker has also proven that Marino's body had not been mistaken for Parker, and that they had not both been misidentified (Kenneth Parker's relatives refused to submit to DNA testing.)<ref name=\"alison1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-gacy-victim-20141130-story.html|title=Mother of Supposed John Wayne Gacy Victim Still Seeks Answers|first=Patrick M.|last=O'Connell|publisher=|date=November 30, 2014}}</ref>}}\n\n====Possible additional victims====\nAt the time of Gacy's arrest, he had claimed to both Des Plaines and Chicago investigators that the total number of victims he had killed could be as high as 45.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=196}} However, only 33 bodies were ever found which were linked to Gacy. Investigators did excavate the grounds of his property until they had exposed the [[Subsoil|substratum]] of clay beneath the foundations, yet only 29 bodies were found buried upon his property.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1982&dat=19790318&id=oHdGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RioNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2520,2232357|title=29 Murder Victims Found as Gacy Waits in Prison|access-date=February 15, 2017|newspaper=The Evening News|date=March 18, 1979}}</ref> When asked as to whether there were more victims, Gacy simply stated, \"That's for you guys to find out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagobreakingnews.com/2011-03-18/news/29143715_1_john-wayne-gacy-detective-probe |title=Retired Detective Wants Gacy Probe Reopened |publisher=chicagobreakingnews.com |date=March 18, 2011 |access-date=February 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 8, 1977, 24-year-old Charles Hattula was found drowned in a river near [[Freeport, Illinois]].<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 116</ref> Hattula, an employee of PDM, had been linked to the initial investigation of Gacy after Robert Piest's disappearance; this was after the same employee who had informed the investigators of Gregory Godzik's disappearance informed them of Hattula's death. Moreover, this employee had stated that Hattula was known to have conflicts with Gacy.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=99}} Gacy had himself informed several of his employees Hattula had drowned after Hattula's body was recovered from the [[Pecatonica River]]. Des Plaines authorities had contacted colleagues in Freeport during their investigation into Gacy, but were told Hattula had fallen to his death from a bridge.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=124}} At the time of Hattula's death, Gacy had become engaged, and his fianc\u00e9e had moved into his home, which leaves a possibility that Gacy had disposed of Hattula's body in the Pecatonica River as opposed to burying the man in his crawl space. However, Hattula's death has been officially ruled as [[accidental death|accidental]].{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=124}}\n\nGacy stated that after he had assaulted and then released Jeffrey Rignall in March 1978, he had begun to throw his murder victims into the Des Plaines River. He confessed to having disposed of five bodies in this manner. However, only four bodies were recovered from the river. Given the gap of over four months between the dates of the murders of the first and second victims known to have been disposed in the river, it is possible that this unknown victim may have been killed between June and November 1978.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=220}}\n\nRetired Chicago police officer Bill Dorsch<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-03-30/news/chi-sheriff-wants-new-dig-for-gacy-victims-20120329_1_bill-dorsch-gacy-victims-west-miami-avenue/|title=Sheriff Barred from Digging for More Gacy Victims|publisher=}}</ref> has stated he has reason to believe there may be more victims buried within the grounds of the apartment building located at the 6100 block of West Miami Avenue in Chicago; a property which Gacy is known to have been the caretaker of for several years prior to his 1978 arrest. In 1975, Dorsch\u2014then a Chicago police officer\u2014observed Gacy (whom he knew on a casual basis), holding a shovel in the early hours of the morning. When confronted by Dorsch as to his actions, Gacy stated he was performing work that he was too busy to do during the day. Dorsch has also related that several other residents of West Miami Avenue have stated that, in the early- to mid-1970s, they had observed Gacy digging trenches in the grounds of the property;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/5/10/4315390/the-controversial-high-tech-search-for-john-wayne-gacy-lost-victims|title=Grave Mistake: The Controversial, High-tech Search for John Wayne Gacy's Lost Victims|first=Matt|last=Stroud|date=May 10, 2013|publisher=}}</ref> one of these residents has also stated that Gacy later placed plants in the elongated trenches he had dug. At the time these actions had been observed, Gacy had still been married to Carole Hoff.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police May Look for More Gacy Victims |date=November 12, 1998 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1893&dat=19981112&id=zJEkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w9wFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1375,1891358 |newspaper=The Southeast Missourian |access-date=November 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Cook County Sheriff's officials submitted a request to excavate the grounds of this property. The [[Cook County State's Attorney]] denied this request, stating a lack of [[probable cause]] as the reason the submission was denied (including the previous 1998 search).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-03-30/news/ct-met-gacy-dig-20120330_1_west-miami-avenue-john-wayne-gacy-gacy-investigation/ |title=Criminal Justice: Sheriff's Officials Seeking More Victims of Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy Want to Excavate Chicago Backyard. Chicago Tribune |publisher=Articles.chicagotribune.com |date=March 30, 2012 |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> However, the sheriff's office had noted that in 1998, a radar survey conducted had noted 14 areas of interest within the property grounds, yet only two of these 14 anomalies had been excavated. Of the 12 remaining anomalies which police had not examined in greater detail on that occasion, four were described as being \"staggeringly suggestive\" as human skeletons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tracy-ullman-felshman/john-wayne-gacy-search_b_2569172.html/ |title=Tracy Ullman Felshman: To Parents of the Missing in Chicago: A Note About John Wayne Gacy |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |access-date=March 14, 2013 |date=February 1, 2013}}</ref> Moreover, Bill Dorsch had provided police with a letter from the radar company which confirmed the 1998 search of the grounds was incomplete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-03-30/news/chi-sheriff-wants-new-dig-for-gacy-victims-20120329_1_bill-dorsch-gacy-victims-west-miami-avenue|title=Sheriff Barred from Digging for More Gacy Victims|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nA second request to excavate the grounds of West Miami Avenue was submitted to the Cook County State's Attorney by Sheriff Tom Dart in October 2012. This request was granted in January 2013, and a search of the property was conducted in the spring. Both FBI [[Detection dog|sniffer dogs]] and ground-penetrating radar equipment were used in the second search of West Miami Avenue; however, the search yielded no human remains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timescolonist.com/opinion/search-of-killer-john-wayne-gacy-s-mother-s-home-fruitless-county-sheriff-to-keep-hunting-1.109486|title=Search of Killer John Wayne Gacy's Mother's Home Fruitless; County Sheriff to Keep Hunting|first=The Associated|last=Press|publisher=}}</ref>{{efn|Some parties have questioned the [[integrity]] and thoroughness of the second search conducted of West Miami Avenue;<ref name=\"alison2\">{{cite web|url=https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2013/04/15/something-stinks/|title=Something Stinks|last=Alison|date=April 15, 2013|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211202539/https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2013/04/15/something-stinks/|archivedate=December 11, 2016}}</ref> citing the fact the ground of the property was still frozen on the date of the search (March 20), that the press had not been informed that the property had been searched until 6 days after the search had been conducted, and that the sniffer dogs used had solely been provided [[core sample]]s of soil to test.}}\n\n==Inspiration for the Missing Child Recovery Act of 1984==\nIn 1984, Sam Amirante, one of Gacy's two defense attorneys at his 1980 trial, authored procedures that were incorporated by the [[Illinois General Assembly]] into the Missing Child Recovery Act of 1984. Amirante has since stated that the primary inspiration for this legislation was the fact that at the time of the Gacy murders, there had been a 72-hour period which police in Illinois had to allow to elapse before initiating a search for a missing child or adolescent.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|page= 395}}\n\nThe Illinois Missing Child Recovery Act of 1984 removed this 72-hour waiting period. Other states across America subsequently adopted similar procedures and sensibilities, as a result of which a national network aimed at locating missing children was gradually formed. This national network has since developed into the Child Abduction Emergency\u2014commonly known today as an [[Amber Alert]].{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|page= 395}}\n\n==Potential accomplices and connections==\nOne of the first things Gacy told investigators after his arrest was that he had not acted alone in several of the murders: he asked whether \"my associates\" had also been arrested.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=171}} When questioned as to whether these associates had participated directly or indirectly in the killings, Gacy replied, \"Directly.\"{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=171}}\n\nGacy specifically named Cram and Rossi as being involved in several of the murders.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=171}} In the 1980s, he also informed [[Robert Ressler]] that \"two or three\" PDM employees had assisted him in several murders.<ref>Whoever Fights Monsters {{ISBN|0-671-71561-5}} pp 341\u2013342</ref> Ressler replied that he believed there were unexplained avenues to the case and stated his belief that Gacy had killed more than 33 victims. Gacy neither confirmed nor denied Ressler's suspicions.<ref>Whoever Fights Monsters {{ISBN|0-671-71561-5}} p 342</ref>{{efn|Gacy is known to have given Ressler a painting with a written inscription reading: \"Dear Bob Ressler, You cannot hope to enjoy the harvest, without first laboring in the fields\".<ref>Whoever Fights Monsters {{ISBN|0-671-71561-5}} p 343</ref>}}\n\nJeffrey Rignall, who had been assaulted and tortured by Gacy in March 1978, was adamant that at one point during his abuse and torture, a young man with brown hair, kneeling before him, watched his abuse.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=209}} Rignall also said that as Gacy was assaulting him he saw a light switch on in another part of the house.<ref name=\"google2963\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19790101&id=PEEsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=v80EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2963,232748|title=Search of Gacy Home to Resume|date=January 2, 1979|publisher=Spartanburg Herald-Journal}}</ref>\n\nMoreover, on one occasion during the surveillance of Gacy prior to his arrest, two officers followed him to a bar to which Gacy had driven to meet two of his employees. At the bar, the officers overheard a hushed conversation between Gacy and one of his employees in which the employee asked Gacy, \"And what? Buried like the other five?\"{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=102}}\n\nIn interviews following his arrest and conviction, Gacy repeatedly claimed that he was not present in Chicago when 16 of the identified victims had disappeared. In one interview, he stated that at the time of his arrest, four PDM employees were also considered suspects in the disappearances of the missing boys investigators had linked to Gacy\u2014all of whom he stated were in possession of keys to his house.<ref>Whoever Fights Monsters {{ISBN|0-671-71561-5}} pp=341\u2013342</ref> One of these employees was Philip Paske, a young man who is known to have been a close associate of John Norman. At the time, Norman operated a nationwide [[sex trafficking]] ring based in Chicago.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago is Center of National Child Pornography Ring|date=May 16, 1977 |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1977/05/16/page/1/article/chicago-is-center-of-national-child-porno-ring |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref> At least two victims believed to have been murdered by Gacy, Kenneth Parker and Michael Marino, are known to have last been seen alive close to where Norman resided at the time of their disappearance, and Gacy is known to have been aware of Paske's connections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2016/06/20/child-sex-trafficking-in-chicago-the-missing-link-in-the-gacy-mystery/|title=Child Sex Trafficking in Chicago: The Missing Link in the Gacy Mystery|last=Alison|date=June 20, 2016|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827120623/https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2016/06/20/child-sex-trafficking-in-chicago-the-missing-link-in-the-gacy-mystery/|archivedate=August 27, 2016}}</ref> This led to the theory Gacy may have been connected to this trafficking ring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wgntv.com/2016/06/21/what-really-happened-to-michael-marino-investigation-begins/|title=What Really Happened to Michael Marino? Investigation Begins|date=June 22, 2016|website=WGN-TV|access-date=June 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Later investigations===\nIn 2012, two Chicago lawyers<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beckerstephenson.com |title=Beckerstephenson.com |publisher=Beckerstephenson.com |date=January 1, 2009 |access-date=March 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508182752/http://www.beckerstephenson.com/ |archivedate=May 8, 2013 |df= }}</ref> claimed that travel records show that Gacy had been in another state at the time of three of the murders, implying he was assisted by one or more accomplices.<ref name=\"gacyaccomplices\">{{cite news |first=Frank|last=Main|url=http://southtownstar.suntimes.com/news/10545326-418/lawyers-suggest-gacy-had-accomplices.html |title=Lawyers Contend Gacy Had Help in Some Killings|publisher=Southtown Star |date=February 9, 2012|accessdate=March 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824085509/http://southtownstar.suntimes.com/news/10545326-418/lawyers-suggest-gacy-had-accomplices.html |archivedate=August 24, 2013 |df= }}</ref> For example, Gacy had flown to Pittsburgh three days before the disappearance of Robert Gilroy, and only returned to Chicago the day after the youth disappeared.<ref name=\"gacyaccomplices\" />\n\nInvestigators also note that Robert Young, the traveling companion with whom victim Russell Nelson was visiting Chicago at the time of his disappearance in October 1977, gave differing accounts of Nelson disappearance to both Nelson's family and investigators. To Nelson's family, Young had stated Nelson failed to arrive at a bar at a prearranged time; to investigators, Young claimed he had last seen Nelson standing among a crowd who had gathered outside a Chicago bar and when his attention was diverted for a few moments, Nelson simply disappeared. Investigators contend this could not have happened without his traveling companion noticing.<ref name=\"twincities1\">{{cite news|title=Another of John Wayne Gacy's Victims: A 22-year-old UMN Student |date=July 19, 2017 |url=https://www.twincities.com/2017/07/19/another-of-john-wayne-gacys-victims-a-22-year-old-umn-student/ |accessdate=February 3, 2019|publisher=Pioneer Press}}</ref>\n\nYoung is known to have filed a missing person's report with Chicago police, before unsuccessfully requesting money from Nelson's parents to finance a search for their son. When Nelson's two brothers arrived in Chicago to search for him, Young had offered both brothers a job with Gacy's construction company.<ref name=\"gacyaccomplices\" /> Young was never summoned to testify at Gacy's trial as to the circumstances surrounding Nelson's disappearance.<ref name=\"twincities1\"/>\n\nIn a third case, travel records indicate Gacy was at a scheduled job site in Michigan at 6:00&nbsp;a.m. on September 26, 1977\u2014the day following the disappearance of 19-year-old John Mowery, who was last seen leaving his mother's house at 10:00&nbsp;p.m. on September 25.<ref name=\"gacyaccomplices\" /> Mowery's roommate was a PDM employee who had formerly lived with Gacy and had moved into Mowery's apartment less than one week before Mowery's disappearance. Two witnesses have stated that this roommate had recommended to Mowery that he meet \"a man who is going out of town\" two days before Mowery disappeared.<ref name=\"google2963\" />\n\nCriminal defense attorneys and investigators researching the possibility Gacy had not acted alone in several of the murders have stated there is \"overwhelming evidence Gacy worked with an accomplice\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1N1-13CF85F3996A5130.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213164552/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1N1-13CF85F3996A5130.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 13, 2017 |title=Did Gacy Have Help? |publisher=highbeam.com |date=February 17, 2012 |access-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE SOUTH PARK OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n===Film===\n* The made-for-TV film ''[[To Catch a Killer]]'', starring [[Brian Dennehy]] as Gacy, was released in 1992. The film is largely based on the investigation of Gacy, following the disappearance of Robert Piest, by Des Plaines Police and their efforts to arrest him before the scheduled civil suit hearing on December 22.\n* A feature film, ''[[Gacy (film)|Gacy]]'', was released in 2003. This film cast [[Mark Holton]] in the role of Gacy and depicts Gacy's life after he moved to Norwood Park in 1971 up until his arrest in 1978.\n* The made-for-TV film ''[[Dear Mr. Gacy]]'', released in 2010, stars [[William Forsythe (actor)|William Forsythe]] as Gacy. The film is based upon the book ''[[The Last Victim]]'', written by [[Jason Moss (writer)|Jason Moss]].{{sfn|Moss|Kottler|1999}} The film focuses upon the correspondence between Moss and Gacy before Gacy invited Moss to visit him on death row in 1994.\n* The horror film ''[[8213: Gacy House]]'' was released in 2010 and is based upon paranormal investigators spending a night in the house built on the former site of 8213 Summerdale Terrace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1667418/|title=8213: Gacy House|date=September 28, 2010|publisher=|via=IMDb}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n* ''29 Below'', by Jeffrey Rignall and Ron Wilder (ISBN B0006XG56Y).\n* ''A Question of Doubt: The John Wayne Gacy Story'', by John Wayne Gacy ({{ISBN|1-87886-503-X}}).\n* ''Buried Dreams: Inside the Mind of Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy'', by [[Tim Cahill (writer)|Tim Cahill]] ({{ISBN|1-85702-084-7}}).\n* ''John Wayne Gacy: Defending a Monster'', by Sam L. Amirante and Danny Broderick ({{ISBN|1-616-08248-8}}).\n* ''Johnny and Me: The True Story of John Wayne Gacy'', by Barry Boschelli ({{ISBN|1-4343-2184-3}}).<ref>{{cite web|last=Creepy |first=Uncle |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/41399/barry-boschelli-talks-growing-evil-john-wayne-gacy |title=Barry Boschelli Talks Growing Up with Evil \u2013 John Wayne Gacy |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date=December 10, 2010 |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref>\n* ''Killer Clown: The John Wayne Gacy Murders'', by Terry Sullivan and Peter T. Maiken ({{ISBN|0-7860-1422-9}}).\n* ''Killer Clown: The True Story of John Wayne Gacy'', by Aimee Baxter ({{ISBN|978-1-973-75535-7}}).\n* ''The Chicago Killer'', by Joseph R. Kozenczak and Karen M. Kozenczak ({{ISBN|978-1401095314}}).\n* ''The Last Victim: A True-Life Journey into the Mind of the Serial Killer'', by Jason Moss and Jeffrey Kottler, Ph.D ({{ISBN|0-7535-0398-0}}).\n* ''The Man Who Killed Boys'', by Clifford L. Linedecker ({{ISBN|0-312-95228-7}}).\n* ''Unfinished Nightmare: The Search for More Victims of Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy'', by Chris Maloney ({{ISBN|978-1466080317}}).\n* ''Destination Gacy: A Cross-Country Journey to Shake the Devil's Hand'', by [[Nancy Rommelmann]] ({{ISBN|978-1940838380}}).\n\n===Television===\n* The [[Discovery Channel]] has broadcast an episode relating to Gacy's crimes within the true crime series ''[[The New Detectives|The New Detectives: Case Studies in Forensic Science]]''. This documentary features an interview between Gacy and FBI profiler Robert Ressler, whom Gacy claimed to have known when both he and Ressler were children. (As a child, Ressler had lived just four blocks from Gacy in Chicago and Gacy had delivered groceries to Ressler's family.)\n* The [[Investigation Discovery]] channel has broadcast two documentaries about the Gacy murders. The first documentary focusing upon Gacy's crimes was commissioned for the ''[[Most Evil]]'' series, a forensics program in which [[forensic psychiatrist]] Michael Stone analyzes various murderers and psychopaths. The second Investigation Discovery program on Gacy is featured in the ''Evil Lives Here'' series. This program explores how Gacy's actions affected his family. Gacy's sister and niece are among those interviewed.\n* The [[Biography Channel]] has broadcast a 45-minute documentary on the crimes of John Wayne Gacy.\n* The television program, ''Psychic Investigators'', has broadcast an episode entitled \"What Lies Below\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/z2hr/psychic-investigators--s3-e3-what-lies-below |title=Psychic Investigators S3-E3: What Lies Below |publisher=radiotimes.com |date=July 25, 2009 |access-date=February 14, 2017}}</ref> This program focuses upon the consultation between Detective Joseph Kozenczak and [[psychic]] Carol Broman, whom Kozenczak had met on December 17, 1978 to discuss the whereabouts of the body of Robert Piest.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), pp. 104\u2013105</ref>\n* The [[Lifetime Movies]] network series ''[[Monster in My Family]]'' has broadcast a 42-minute episode focusing on the murders committed by Gacy. This episode, titled \"Killer Clown: John Wayne Gacy\", was initially broadcast in August 2015. The episode features Karen Kuzma, the sister of John Wayne Gacy, and her daughter, and focuses upon formative events in Gacy's life that may have initiated his later crimes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch Killer Clown: John Wayne Gacy Full Episode \u2013 Monster in My Family {{!}} Lifetime|url=http://www.mylifetime.com/shows/monster-in-my-family/season-1/episode-6|website=mylifetime.com|publisher=Lifetime Movies|accessdate=November 9, 2017|language=en|date=August 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Monster in My Family {{!}} Season 1, Episode 6 Killer Clown: John Wayne Gacy|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/monster-in-my-family/episode-6-season-1/killer-clown-john-wayne-gacy/816193/|website=TVGuide.com|publisher=CBS Interactive Inc.|accessdate=November 9, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE THE SIMPSONS OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of people executed in Illinois]]\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n* [[List of unidentified murder victims in the United States]]\n* [[Most prolific murderers by number of victims]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|20em\n| refs =\n\n{{cite news\n| title = Gacy Victim Is Identified\n| date = May 8, 1986\n| newspaper = Mohave Daily Miner\n| agency = UPI\n| page = 5\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QggPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sIIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2452,753401\n| access-date = July 20, 2010\n}}\n\n<ref name=\"SHJ-3morebodies\">\n{{cite news\n| title = 3 More Bodies Are Found At Home\n| date = December 24, 1978\n| newspaper = Spartanburg Herald-Journal\n| agency = AP\n| page = 1\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lYUsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0M0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3744,5182626\n| access-date = July 20, 2010\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<!-- <ref name=\"Rossi1980a\">\n{{cite news\n| last = Rossi\n| first = Rosalind\n| title = Mothers Tell Gacy Jury Of Last Time They Saw Sons\n| date = February 8, 1980\n| newspaper = Sarasota Herald-Tribune\n| agency = UPI\n| page = 6\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Zk80AAAAIBAJ&sjid=zWcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6679,3103134&\n| access-date = July 20, 2010\n}}\n</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=\"Rossi1980b\">\n{{cite news\n| last = Rossi\n| first = Rosalind\n| title = Gacy Sentenced To Die For 33 Deaths\n| date = March 14, 1980\n| newspaper = Sarasota Herald-Tribune\n| agency = UPI\n| page = 7\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZLYcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zmcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5140,7396894\n| access-date = July 20, 2010\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SHT-Speedup\">\n{{cite news\n| title = Speedup Sought In Gacy Trial\n| date = November 23, 1979\n| newspaper = Sarasota Herald-Tribune\n| agency = AP\n| page = 6\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4zogAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s2cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6515,4117798\n| access-date = July 20, 2010\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"StJoseph\">\n{{cite news\n| title = 2 apparent victims of Gacy identified\n| date = March 31, 1980\n| newspaper = St. Joseph Gazette\n| agency = AP\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UO9eAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K1QNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5070,3504589&dq/\n| access-date = June 12, 2011\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CookCS\">{{cite web\n |title        = Unidentified Victims of John Wayne Gacy\n |publisher    = Cook County Sheriff's Office\n |url          = http://cookcountysheriff.com/sheriffs_police/gacy/gacy.html#MissingForm/\n |access-date  = October 27, 2011\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20111015180420/http://www.cookcountysheriff.com/sheriffs_police/gacy/gacy.html#MissingForm/\n |archive-date = October 15, 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CBSChicago\">\n{{cite web\n| title = Movie, Documentary Could Be Adapted From Book By Gacy's Lawyer\n| date = December 21, 2011\n| publisher = CBS\n| url = http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2011/12/21/movie-documentary-could-be-adapted-from-book-by-gacys-lawyer/\n| access-date = December 21, 2011\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tribune\">\n{{cite news\n| last = Mills\n| first = Steve\n| title = Long-lost relation, thought slain by John Wayne Gacy, alive and well and living in South Florida\n| date= October 26, 2011\n| newspaper = Chicago Tribune\n| url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-10-26/news/ct-met-gacy-victims-20111026_1_gacy-case-john-wayne-gacy-serial-killer\n| access-date = October 26, 2011\n}}\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Cited works and further reading==\n* {{cite book\n| last = Amirante\n| first = Sam L.\n| last2 = Broderick\n| first2 = Danny\n| title = John Wayne Gacy: Defending a Monster\n| publisher = Skyhorse Publishing\n| year = 2011\n| isbn = 978-1-61608-248-2\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Berry-Dee\n| first = Christopher\n| title = Talking With Serial Killers 2: The World's Most Evil Killers Tell Their Stories\n| publisher = John Blake Publishing\n| year = 2005\n| isbn = 978-1-85782-630-2\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Berry-Dee\n| first = Christopher\n| title=Born Killers\n|year=2009\n| isbn=978-1-85782-648-7\n\n|ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Cahill\n| first = Tim\n| title = Buried Dreams: Inside the Mind of a Serial Killer\n| publisher = Bantam Books\n| year = 1986\n| isbn = 0-553-05115-6\n| oclc = 12421532\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/burieddreamsinsi00cahi\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = Foreman\n| first1 = Laura\n| author2= The editors of Time-Life Books\n| title = Serial Killers: True Crime\n| url = https://archive.org/details/serialkillerspro00edit\n| url-access = registration\n| year = 1992\n| publisher = Time-Life Books\n| edition = Hardcover\n| isbn = 978-0-7835-0001-0\n| ref = {{SfnRef|Foreman|1992}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = Kozenczak\n| first1 = Joseph R.\n| first2 = Karen\n| last2 = Henrikson\n| title = The Chicago Killer: The Hunt for Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy\n| publisher = Xlibris\n| location = Philadelphia\n| date = November 3, 2003\n| isbn = 1-4010-9532-1\n| oclc = 54782106\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Linedecker\n| first = Clifford L.\n| title = The Man Who Killed Boys: A True Story of Mass Murder in a Chicago Suburb\n| url = https://archive.org/details/manwhokilledboys0000line\n| url-access = registration\n| publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]]\n| year = 1980\n| edition = First\n| isbn = 0-312-51157-4\n| oclc = 5564916\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Linedecker\n| first = Clifford L.\n| title = The Man Who Killed Boys: A True Story of Mass Murder in a Chicago Suburb\n| publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]]\n| year = 1986\n| edition = Paperback\n| isbn = 0-312-95228-7\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Moss\n| first = Jason\n| last2 = Kottler\n| first2 = Jeffrey, Ph.D\n| title = The Last Victim: A True-Life Journey into the Mind of the Serial Killer\n| year = 1999\n| isbn = 0-7535-0398-0\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = Peck\n| first1 = Dennis L.\n| author-link2= Dennis L. Peck\n| last2 = Dolch\n| first2 = Norman Allan\n| title = Extraordinary Behavior: A Case Study Approach to Understanding Social Problems\n| chapter = Behavior Beyond the Boundaries\n| publisher = [[Greenwood Publishing Group|Greenwood]]\n| year = 2001\n| isbn = 0-275-97057-4\n| oclc = 43694355\n| ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Ressler\n| first = Robert\n| first2 = Tom\n| last2 = Schactman\n| title = Whoever Fights Monsters: My Twenty Years Hunting Serial Killers for the FBI\n| publisher = St Martin's Press\n| year = 1992\n| isbn = 0-312-95044-6\n| oclc = 27658115\n| location = New York\n| ref = harv\n| url = https://archive.org/details/whoeverfightsmo00ress\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Sullivan\n| first = Terry\n| last2 = Maiken\n| first2 = Peter T.\n| title = Killer Clown: The John Wayne Gacy Murders\n| publisher = [[Kensington Books#Imprints|Pinnacle]]\n| year = 2000\n| edition = Paperback\n| isbn = 0-7860-1422-9\n| oclc = 156783287\n| ref = harv\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|John Wayne Gacy}}\n*[http://vault.fbi.gov/John%20Wayne%20Gacy Archived FBI files] relating to John Gacy\n*[http://www.museumsyndicate.com/artist.php?artist=475 Examples of artwork] produced by Gacy\n*People v. John Wayne Gacy [http://www.cookcountyclerkofcourt.org/?section=RecArchivePage&RecArchivePage=john_w_gacy \"Cook County Clerk of Court\" records and archives]\n*[http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/994/305/271650/ 1993 Decision] of Gacy's case by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit]], rejecting his federal appeal\n*''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' article exploring the possibility [http://newsfeed.time.com/2012/02/13/serial-killer-john-wayne-gacy-may-have-had-accomplices/ Gacy had a minimum of one accomplice]\n*[http://johnwaynegacynews.com/ ''John Wayne Gacy's Other Victims'':] A website detailing the ongoing investigation by Detective Bill Dorsch into the possibility Gacy had committed other murders\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gacy, John Wayne}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:1972 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by Illinois]]\n[[Category:American clowns]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:American murderers of children]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of sodomy]]\n[[Category:American people of Danish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:American rapists]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:American sex offenders]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Iowa]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Criminals of Chicago]]\n[[Category:Executed American serial killers]]\n[[Category:Executed people from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against boys]]\n[[Category:Iowa Democrats]]\n[[Category:John Wayne Gacy]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Illinois]]\n[[Category:People executed by Illinois by lethal injection]]\n[[Category:People from Waterloo, Iowa]]\n[[Category:People with antisocial personality disorder]]\n[[Category:Torture in the United States]]\n[[Category:Violence against men in North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Gacy}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{pp-semi-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American serial killer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name = John Wayne Gacy\n| alias = \n| image = File:John Wayne Gacy.jpg\n| caption = John Wayne Gacy in May 1978\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1942|03|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], US\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1994|05|10|1942|03|17}}\n| death_place = [[Stateville Correctional Center]], [[Crest Hill, Illinois]], US\n| cause = [[Lethal injection|Execution by lethal injection]]\n| victims = 33+\n| parents = \n| party =\n| spouse = \n| children = 2\n| height = 5 ft 9 in{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=5}}\n| country = United States\n| states = Illinois\n| beginyear = 1972\n| endyear =  1978\n| apprehended = December 21, 1978\n| conviction = {{unbulleted list|1 count of [[sodomy]]|33 counts of [[murder]]|1 count of [[sexual assault]]|1 count of [[Child abuse|indecent liberties with a child]]}} | sentence = [[Capital punishment|Death]] (12 counts)<br />\n| imprisoned =\n[[Menard Correctional Center]]\n}}\n'''John Wayne Gacy''' (March 17, 1942&nbsp;\u2013 May 10, 1994) was an American [[serial killer]] and [[sex offender]] known as the '''Killer Clown''' who assaulted and murdered at least 33 young men and boys. Gacy regularly performed at children's hospitals and charitable events as \"Pogo the Clown\" or \"Patches the Clown\", clowning persona he devised. He was also active in his local community as a precinct captain and building contractor.\n\nIt is believed all of Gacy's known murders were committed inside his [[Ranch-style house|ranch house]] in [[Norwood Park Township, Cook County, Illinois|Norwood Park]], a part of [[Chicago metropolitan area|metropolitan Chicago]]. Gacy would typically lure a victim to his home, dupe him into donning [[handcuffs]] on the pretext of demonstrating a [[Magic (illusion)|magic trick]], then rape and torture his captive before killing him by either [[asphyxiation]] or [[strangulation]] with a [[garrote]]. Twenty-six victims were buried in the [[crawl space]] of his home, three others were buried elsewhere on his property, and the last four were discarded in the [[Des Plaines River]].\n\nGacy was convicted of the [[sodomy]] of a teenage boy in Iowa in 1968. He was sentenced to 10 years' imprisonment, but was released after 18 months. He first murdered in 1972, and at least 29 subsequent victims were killed after his divorce from his second wife in 1976. Investigation into the disappearance of [[Des Plaines, Illinois|Des Plaines]] teenager Robert Piest led to Gacy's arrest on December 21, 1978.\n\nThe conviction for 33 murders was the largest number of murders charged to one individual in United States until that time. Gacy was sentenced to death on March 13, 1980. On death row at [[Menard Correctional Center]] he spent much of his time painting. He was executed by [[lethal injection]] at [[Stateville Correctional Center]] on May 10, 1994.\n\n==Early life==\nJohn Wayne Gacy was born in Chicago, [[Illinois]] on March 17, 1942, the second child and only son of John Stanley Gacy (June 20, 1900 \u2013 December 25, 1969) and Marion Elaine Robinson (May 4, 1908 \u2013 December 6, 1989).<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 63.</ref> His father was an auto repair machinist and [[World War I]] veteran,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=24}} and his mother was a homemaker.<ref>Cook County marriage records provide his mother's name as Marion E. Robertson; {{cite web | title=Cook County, Illinois Marriage Index, 1930\u20131960. Cook County Clerk Genealogy Records. Cook County Clerk's Office, Chicago, IL |url=http://www.ancestry.com/search/db.aspx?dbid=1500&enc=1 |year=2008}}</ref>{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=67}} Gacy was of [[Poles|Polish]] and [[Danes|Danish]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/john-wayne-gacy-10367544|title=John Wayne Gacy Biography|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=February 11, 2019|website=The Biography.com website|publisher=A&amp;E Television Networks|orig-year=April 2, 2014|access-date=April 5, 2019}}</ref> His paternal grandparents (who spelled the family name as \"Gatza\" or \"Gaca\") had immigrated to the United States from [[Poland]] (then part of [[Prussia]] in [[German Empire|Germany]]).<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 51.</ref>{{sfn|Ressler|Schactman|1992|pp=207\u2013218}}\n \n===Childhood===\nAs a child, Gacy was overweight and not athletic. He was close to his two sisters and mother but endured a difficult relationship with his father, an [[alcoholic]] who was [[physical abuse|physically abusive]] to his wife and children.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=256\u2013257}} Gacy seldom received his father's approval, later recollecting that, no matter what he achieved, he was \"never good enough\" in his father's eyes.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=31}}  His father regularly belittled him, calling him \"dumb and stupid\" and comparing him unfavorably with his sisters.<ref>''Serial Killers.'' pp. 54\u201355.</ref> Despite this, Gacy always denied ever hating his father.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=21}} \n\nOne of Gacy's earliest childhood memories was of being beaten with a leather belt at the age of four for accidentally disarranging car engine components his father had assembled.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=18\u201319}} On another occasion, he was struck across the head with a broomstick and rendered [[Unconsciousness|unconscious]].<ref>{{cite book | first1=Jason| last1=Moss| first2=Jeffrey| last2=Kottler| title=The Last Victim: A True-life Journey into the Mind of the Serial Killer| publisher=Grand Central Publishing| location=New York City| date=2000|isbn=0-7535-0398-0| p=103}}</ref> When he was six years old, Gacy stole a toy truck from a neighborhood store. His mother made him walk back to the store, return the toy and apologize to the owners. His mother informed his father, who beat Gacy with a belt as punishment. After this incident, Gacy's mother attempted to shield her son from his father's verbal and physical abuse,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=26}} yet this only succeeded in Gacy earning accusations that he was a \"[[sissy]]\" and a \"Mama's boy\"{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=257}} who would \"probably grow up [[queer]]\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=40}}\n\nIn 1949, Gacy's father was informed that his son and another boy had been caught sexually fondling a young girl.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=218}} Gacy's father whipped him with a [[razor strop]] as punishment. The same year,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=17}} Gacy was [[child molestation|molested]] by a family friend,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=257}} a contractor who would take Gacy for rides in his truck and then fondle him. Gacy never told his father about these incidents, afraid that his father would blame him.<ref name=\"Serial Killers. p. 54\">''Serial Killers''. p. 54.</ref>\n\nBecause of a heart condition, Gacy was ordered to avoid all sports at school.<ref name=\"Serial Killers. p. 54\" /> During the fourth grade, Gacy began to experience [[Syncope (medicine)|blackout]]s. He was occasionally hospitalized because of these seizures, and also in 1957 for a [[appendicitis|burst appendix]].{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=18}} Gacy later estimated that between the ages of 14 and 18, he had spent almost a year in the hospital for these episodes, and attributed the decline of his grades to his missing school. His father suspected the episodes were an effort to gain sympathy and attention, and openly accused his son of faking the condition as the boy lay in a hospital bed.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Murder In Mind |issue=11 |issn=1364-5803 |page=5}}</ref> Although his mother, sisters, and few close friends never doubted his illness, Gacy's medical condition was never conclusively diagnosed.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=32}}\n\nOne of Gacy's friends at high school recalled several instances in which his father ridiculed or beat his son without provocation. On one occasion in 1957, the same friend witnessed an incident at the Gacy household in which Gacy's father began shouting at his son for no reason, then began hitting him.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=33}} Gacy's mother attempted to intervene. The friend recalled that Gacy simply \"put up his hands to defend himself\", adding that he never struck his father back during these physical altercations.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=32\u201333}}\n\n===Career origins===\nIn 1960, at the age of 18, Gacy became involved in politics, working as an assistant [[precinct captain]] for a [[U.S. Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] candidate in his neighborhood. This decision earned more criticism from his father, who accused his son of being a \"[[wikt:Special:Search/dupe|patsy]]\". Gacy later speculated the decision may have been an attempt to seek the acceptance from others that he never received from his father.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=36}}\n\nThe same year Gacy became a Democratic candidate, his father bought him a car, with the title of the vehicle being in his father's name until Gacy had completed the monthly repayments.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=42}} These repayments took several years to complete, and his father would confiscate the keys to the vehicle if Gacy did not do as his father said. On one occasion in 1962, Gacy bought an extra set of keys after his father confiscated the original set. In response, his father removed the [[distributor cap]] from the vehicle, withholding the component for three days. Gacy recalled that as a result of this incident, he felt \"totally sick; drained\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=44}} When his father replaced the distributor cap, Gacy left the family home and drove to [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], where he found work within the ambulance service before he was transferred to work as an attendant at Palm Mortuary.\n\nIn his role as a mortuary attendant, Gacy slept on a cot behind the [[embalming]] room.<ref>{{cite book|first=Tim|last=Cahill|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OF6itYw0HT0C&pg=PT30&lpg=PT30#v=onepage&q/ |title=Buried Dreams: Inside the Mind of a Serial Killer|publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |location=New York City|date=1986|access-date=March 14, 2013|isbn=978-0553051155}}</ref> He worked in this role for three months.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=258}} In this role, he observed morticians embalming dead bodies and later confessed that, on one evening while alone, he had clambered into the coffin of a deceased teenage male, embracing and caressing the body before experiencing a sense of shock.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=46}}{{efn|Gacy later claimed to have engaged in acts of [[necrophilia]] on approximately two occasions while he worked at Palm Mortuary. He justified his actions by claiming the bodies he had defiled were \"just dead things\" who \"couldn't tell anybody\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=346}}}} This prompted Gacy to call his mother the next day and ask whether his father would allow him to return home.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=46}} His father agreed and the same day, Gacy drove back to live with his family in Chicago.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=347}}\n\nUpon his return, despite the fact he had failed to graduate from high school, Gacy successfully enrolled in the [[Northwestern College (Illinois)|Northwestern Business College]],{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=47}} from which he graduated in 1963. Gacy subsequently took a management trainee position within the Nunn-Bush Shoe Company.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=18\u201319}} In 1964, the shoe company transferred Gacy to [[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]] to work as a salesman.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=258}} He was eventually promoted to manager of his department. In March of that year, he became engaged to Marlynn Myers, a co-worker in the department he managed.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=21}}\n\nDuring his courtship with Marlynn, Gacy joined the local [[Jaycees]] and became a tireless worker for the organization, being named Key Man for the organization in April 1964.<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 58.</ref> The same year, Gacy had his second homosexual experience. According to Gacy, he acquiesced to this incident after one of his colleagues in the Springfield Jaycees plied him with drinks and invited him to spend the evening upon his sofa; the colleague then performed [[oral sex]] upon him while he was drunk.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite journal |title=Murder In Mind |issue=11 |publisher=Marshall Cavendish Printworks|location=London, England|issn=1364-5803 |page=7}}</ref> By 1965, Gacy had risen to the position of vice-president of the Springfield Jaycees.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=20\u201322}} The same year, he was named as the third most outstanding Jaycee within the state of Illinois.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=48}}\n\n==Waterloo, Iowa==\nAfter a nine-month courtship, Gacy and Myers married in September 1964. Marlynn's father subsequently purchased three [[Kentucky Fried Chicken]] restaurants in [[Waterloo, Iowa|Waterloo]], [[Iowa]], and the couple moved to Waterloo so he could manage the restaurants, with the understanding that they would move into Marlynn's parents' home (which was vacated for the couple).{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=21}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=261\u2013262}} The offer was lucrative: Gacy would receive $15,000 per year (the equivalent of $115,513 {{as of|2020|lc=y|df=US}}), plus a share of profits earned via the restaurants.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=50}} Following his obligatory completion of a managerial course, Gacy relocated to Waterloo with his wife later that year.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=23\u201325}}\n\n=== Waterloo Jaycees ===\nIn Waterloo, Gacy joined the local chapter of the Jaycees, regularly offering extended hours to the organization in addition to the 12- and 14-hour days he worked managing three restaurants. Although considered ambitious and something of a braggart by other Jaycees, he was highly regarded for his fund-raising work. In 1967 he was named \"outstanding vice-president\" of the Waterloo Jaycees.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=28}} At Jaycee meetings Gacy often provided fried chicken and insisted on being called \"Colonel\" (for [[Colonel Sanders]]).{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=51}} The same year, Gacy served on the Board of Directors for the Waterloo Jaycees.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=51}}\n\nGacy's wife gave birth to a son in February 1966 and a daughter in March 1967. Gacy himself later described this period of his life as \"perfect\"{{snd}}he had earned his father's approval, which he had long sought. When Gacy's parents visited in July 1966, his father apologized for the abuse he had inflicted during Gacy's childhood, and said: \"Son, I was wrong about you.\"{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=53}}\n\nMany Jaycees in Waterloo were involved in [[wife swapping]],<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" /> [[prostitution]], [[pornography]], and drug use; Gacy was deeply involved in many of these activities and regularly had sex with local prostitutes.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=263}} He opened a \"club\" in his basement where his employees to drank and played pool. Although Gacy employed teenagers of both sexes at his restaurants, he socialized only with his young male employees. Many were given alcohol before Gacy made sexual advances; if rebuffed, Gacy would claim these advances were jokes or a test of morals.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=265}}\n\n===Assault of Donald Voorhees===\nIn August 1967, Gacy committed his first known [[sexual assault]] upon a teenage boy. The victim was 15-year-old Donald Voorhees, the son of a fellow Jaycee. Gacy lured Voorhees to his house with the promise of showing him pornographic films.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=55}} Gacy plied Voorhees with alcohol and persuaded Voorhees to perform oral sex upon him. Over the following months, several other youths were sexually abused in a similar manner, including one whom Gacy encouraged to have sex with his own wife before [[blackmail]]ing him into performing oral sex upon him.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=265}} Gacy tricked several teenagers into believing he was commissioned with conducting homosexual experiments in the interests of \"scientific research\", for which each was paid up to $50.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=266}}\n\nIn March 1968, Voorhees reported to his father that Gacy had sexually assaulted him. Voorhees Sr. immediately informed the police and Gacy was arrested and subsequently charged with oral [[Sodomy law|sodomy]] in relation to Voorhees and the attempted assault of 16-year-old Edward Lynch.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=267}} Gacy vehemently denied the charges and demanded to take a [[polygraph test]]. This request was granted, although the results indicated Gacy was nervous when he denied any wrongdoing in relation to either Voorhees or Lynch.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=65}}\n\nGacy publicly denied any wrongdoing and insisted the charges against him were politically motivated \u2013 Voorhees Sr. had opposed Gacy's nomination for appointment as president of the Iowa Jaycees.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=66}} Several fellow Jaycees found Gacy's story credible and rallied to his support. However, on May 10, 1968, Gacy was indicted on the sodomy charge.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=65}}\n{{quote box\n| quote = ''\"The most striking aspect of the test results is the patient's total denial of responsibility for everything that has happened to him. He can produce an 'alibi' for everything. He presents himself as a victim of circumstances and blames other people who are out to get him ... the patient attempts to assure a sympathetic response by depicting himself as being at the mercy of a hostile environment.\"''\n| source = Section of report detailing Gacy's 1968 psychiatric evaluation.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=270}}\n| width = 30em\n}}\nOn August 30, 1968, Gacy persuaded one of his employees, 18-year-old Russell Schroeder, to physically assault Voorhees in an effort to discourage the boy from testifying against him. Gacy promised to pay Schroeder $300 to lure Voorhees to a secluded spot, spray [[Mace (spray)|Mace]] in his face, and beat him. Schroeder agreed, and in early September, he lured Voorhees to an isolated county park, sprayed Mace into the youth's eyes, then beat him.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=72}}<ref name=\"Michael H. Stone 2019 pp. 196-203\">Michael H. Stone & Gary Brucato. The New Evil: Understanding the Emergence of Modern Violent Crime (Amherst, New York: Prometheus Books, 2019), pp. 196-203.</ref>\n\nVoorhees managed to escape, and immediately reported the assault to the police, identifying Schroeder as his attacker. Schroeder was arrested the following day. Despite initially denying any involvement, he soon confessed to having assaulted Voorhees, indicating that he had done so at Gacy's request. Gacy was arrested and additionally charged in relation to hiring Schroeder to assault and [[Witness tampering|intimidate]] Voorhees.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=268\u2013270}}\n\nOn September 12, Gacy was ordered to undergo a [[Psychological evaluation|psychiatric evaluation]] at the Psychiatric Hospital of the State University of Iowa.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=270}} Two doctors had examined Gacy over a period of 17 days before concluding he had an [[antisocial personality disorder]] (a disorder which incorporates constructs such as [[sociopathy]] and [[psychopathy]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/conditions/antisocial-personality-disorder |title=Antisocial Personality Disorder |magazine=[[Psychology Today]]|publisher=Sussex Publishers|location=New York City |date=April 19, 2017 |accessdate=January 13, 2018 }}</ref> was unlikely to benefit from any therapy or medical treatment, and that his behavior pattern was likely to bring him into repeated conflict with society.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=272}} The doctors also concluded he was mentally competent to stand trial.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=272}}\n\n===Conviction and imprisonment===\n[[File:John Wayne Gacy (mugshot).jpg|thumb|[[Mug shot]]s of Gacy, following his December 1968 sodomy conviction.]]\nOn November 7, 1968 Gacy pled guilty to one count of sodomy in relation to Voorhees, but not guilty to the charges related to other youths. Gacy said that Voorhees had offered his sexual services to him and that he had acted out of curiosity.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=272}} His story was not believed. Gacy was convicted of sodomy on December 3{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=272}} and sentenced to 10 years imprisonment, to be served at the [[Anamosa State Penitentiary]].{{sfn|Peck|Dolch|2001|p=260}} That same day, his wife petitioned for divorce,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=85}} requesting award of the couple's home and property, sole custody of their two children, and [[alimony]].{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=40}} The Court ruled in her favor and the divorce was finalized on September 18, 1969. Gacy never saw his first wife or children again.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=274}}\n\nDuring his incarceration in the Anamosa State Penitentiary, Gacy rapidly acquired a reputation as a model prisoner.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=273}} Within months of his arrival, he had risen to the position of head cook. He also joined the inmate Jaycee chapter and increased their membership figure from 50 to 650 in the span of less than 18 months. He is also known to have both secured an increase in the inmates' daily pay in the prison mess hall{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=88}} and to have supervised several projects to improve conditions for inmates at the prison.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=89}} On one occasion, Gacy oversaw the installation of a [[miniature golf]] course in the prison's recreation yard.<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 62.</ref>\n\nIn June 1969, Gacy first applied to the State of Iowa Board of Parole for early release: this application was denied. In preparation for a second scheduled parole hearing in May 1970, Gacy completed 16 high school courses, for which he obtained his diploma in November 1969.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=275}}\n\nOn [[Christmas Day]] 1969, Gacy's father died from [[cirrhosis]] of the [[liver]].{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=275}} When told the news, Gacy collapsed to the floor sobbing.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=275}} His request for supervised compassionate leave to attend the funeral was denied.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|page=92}}\n\n==Return to Chicago==\nGacy was granted parole with 12 months' probation on June 18, 1970, after serving 18 months of his 10-year sentence.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=277}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=276}}{{sfn|Foreman|1992|p=63}}{{sfn|Linedecker|1986|p=47}} Two of the conditions of his probation were for Gacy to relocate to Chicago to live with his mother and to observe a 10:00&nbsp;p.m. [[curfew]],{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=276}} with the Iowa Board of Parole receiving regular updates as to his progress.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=96}}\n\nUpon his release, Gacy told friend and fellow Jaycee Clarence Lane\u2014who picked him up from the prison upon release and had remained steadfast in his belief of Gacy's innocence\u2014that he would \"never go back to jail\" and that he intended to re-establish himself in Waterloo. However, within 24 hours of his release, Gacy relocated to Chicago to live with his mother.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=276}} He arrived in Chicago on June 19 and shortly thereafter obtained a job as a [[short-order cook]] in a restaurant.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=49}}\n\nOn February 12, 1971, Gacy was charged with sexually assaulting a teenage boy{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=95}} who claimed that Gacy had lured him into his car at Chicago's [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound bus]] terminal and driven him to his home, where he had attempted to force the boy into sex. This complaint was dismissed when the boy failed to appear in court. The Iowa Board of Parole did not learn of this incident (which violated the conditions of his parole) and eight months later, in October 1971, Gacy's parole ended.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=96}} The following month, records of Gacy's previous criminal convictions in Iowa were later [[Record sealing|sealed]].{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=53}}{{efn|Gacy successfully hid his [[criminal record]] from friends, business associates and political acquaintances; they only learned the truth of his past after police had begun investigating him for his later murders.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=72}}{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=73}}}}\n\n===8213 West Summerdale Avenue===\nWith financial assistance from his mother, Gacy bought a house in Norwood Park Township, an [[unincorporated area]] of [[Cook County, Illinois|Cook County]], a part of metropolitan Chicago. The address, 8213 West Summerdale Avenue, is where he resided until his arrest in December 1978 and where all his known murders were committed.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=175}} He became active in his local community, and his neighbors considered him helpful; willing to loan his construction tools and plowing snow from neighborhood walks free of charge.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=86\u201387}} Between 1974 and 1978, he hosted annual summer parties attended by hundreds of people, including politicians.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=150}} \n\nIn August 1971, shortly after Gacy and his mother moved into the house, he became engaged to Carole Hoff, a [[divorcee]] with two young daughters. Hoff, whom he had briefly dated in high school, had been a friend of his younger sister. His fianc\u00e9e and stepdaughters moved into his home soon after the couple announced their engagement.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=55\u201359}} Gacy's mother subsequently moved out of the house shortly before his wedding, which was held on July 1, 1972.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=278}}\n\nOne week before Gacy's wedding, on June 22, he was arrested and charged with aggravated [[Sexual battery|battery]] and reckless conduct. The arrest was in response to a complaint filed by a youth who claimed that Gacy had flashed a sheriff's badge, lured him into his car, and forced him to perform oral sex.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=112}} These charges were dropped after the complainant attempted to blackmail Gacy.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=61\u201362}}\n\n===PDM Contractors===\nIn 1971, Gacy established a part-time construction business, PDM Contractors (PDM being the initials for 'Painting, Decorating, and Maintenance').{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=65}} With the approval of his probation officer, he was allowed to work evenings to commit to his employment contracts while working as a cook during the day. The business initially undertook minor repair work, such as sign-writing, pouring concrete, and redecorating, but later expanded to include projects such as interior design, [[remodeling]], installation, assembly, and [[landscaping]]. In mid-1973, Gacy quit his job as a cook in order that he could fully commit to his construction business.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=115}} \n\nBy 1975, PDM was expanding rapidly and Gacy was working up to 16 hours per day. In March 1977, he became a supervisor for PE Systems, a firm specializing in the remodeling of drugstores. Between PE Systems and PDM, Gacy worked on up to four projects at once and frequently traveled to other states.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=180}} By 1978, PDM's annual revenue was over $200,000.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=221}}\n====Employees====\nMuch of the labor workforce consisted of high school students and young men.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=1}} In 1973, Gacy and a teenage employee of PDM traveled to [[Florida]] to view property Gacy had purchased. On the first night in Florida, Gacy raped the employee in their hotel room.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=118}} After returning to Chicago, he drove to Gacy's house and beat him in his yard. Gacy told his wife he had been attacked for refusing to pay the employee for poor-quality work.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=117\u2013118}}\n\nAnother employee of Gacy's was 15-year-old Anthony Antonucci, whom he had hired in May 1975. In July 1975, Gacy went to Antonucci's home. The two drank a bottle of wine, then watched a heterosexual [[stag film]] before Gacy wrestled Antonucci to the floor and cuffed his hands behind his back.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=122-123}} One cuff was loose and Antonucci freed his arm while Gacy was out of the room. When Gacy returned, Antonucci\u2014a high school wrestler\u2014pounced upon him. He wrestled Gacy to the floor, obtained possession of the handcuff key and cuffed Gacy's hands behind his back. Gacy at first threatened Antonucci, then calmed down and promised to leave if Antonucci would remove the handcuffs. Antonucci agreed and Gacy left.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=122-123}} Antonucci later recalled that Gacy told him: \"Not only are you the only one who got out of the cuffs, you got them on me\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=123}}\n=====Cram and Rossi=====\nOn July 26, 1976, Gacy employed 18-year-old David Cram. On August 21,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=168}} Cram moved into his house. The following day, Gacy conned Cram into donning handcuffs while Cram was drunk. Gacy swung Cram around while holding the chain linking the cuffs, then said he intended to rape him. Cram kicked Gacy in the face and freed himself from the handcuffs. One month later, Gacy appeared at Cram's bedroom door and again attempted to rape Cram, saying: \"Dave, you really don't know who I am. Maybe it would be good if you give me what I want.\"{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=172}} Cram resisted Gacy and Gacy left the bedroom. Cram moved out and left PDM, although he did periodically work for Gacy over the following two years.<ref name=\"The Montreal Gazette Feb. 13, 1980\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19800213&id=slsxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=laQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1116,946568|title=Man Helped Dig Trenches at Gacy Home|date=February 13, 1980|publisher=The Montreal Gazette}}</ref> \n\nShortly after Cram moved out of Gacy's house another employee, 18-year-old Michael Rossi, moved in.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=177}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=184}}{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=67}} Rossi had worked for PDM Contractors since May 1976.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=58\u201360}} He lived with Gacy until April 1977.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=179}}\n\n===Politics===\n[[File:Johnwaynegacyrosalynncarter.jpg|upright=1|thumb|Gacy with First Lady [[Rosalynn Carter]] on May 6, 1978, six years after his first murder and seven months before his final arrest.|alt=]]\nGacy became active in local Democratic Party politics, initially offering the labor services of his employees to clean party headquarters for free.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=70}} He was rewarded for his community service by being appointed to serve upon the Norwood Park Township street lighting committee,{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=72}} subsequently earning the title of precinct captain.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=73}}{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=222}}\n\nIn 1975, Gacy was appointed director of Chicago's annual [[Polish Constitution Day Parade]]\u2014he supervised the annual event from 1975 until 1978. Through his work with the parade, Gacy met and was photographed with [[First Lady]] [[Rosalynn Carter]] on May 6, 1978.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=212-213}} She signed one photo: \"To John Gacy. Best wishes. Rosalynn Carter\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=214}} The event later became an embarrassment to the [[United States Secret Service]], as in the pictures taken, Gacy can be seen wearing an \"S\" pin, indicating a person who has been given special clearance by the Secret Service.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=142\u2013143}}\n\n===Divorce===\nBy 1975, Gacy had told his wife that he was [[Bisexuality|bisexual]].{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=102}} After the couple had sex on [[Mother's Day (United States)|Mother's Day]] that year, he informed her this would be \"the last time\" they would ever have sex.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=118}} He began spending most evenings away from home only to return in the early hours of the morning with the excuse he had been working late.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=66}} His wife observed Gacy bringing teenage boys into his garage and also found [[gay pornography]] and men's wallets and identification cards inside the house.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=68}} When she once confronted Gacy about who these items belonged to, he angrily informed her the property was none of her business.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=68}} \n\nFollowing a heated argument regarding her failing to balance a checkbook correctly in October 1975,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=140}} Carole Gacy asked her husband for a divorce. Gacy agreed to his wife's request although, by mutual consent, Carole continued to live at 8213 West Summerdale until February 1976, when she and her daughters moved into their own apartment. One month later, on March 2, the Gacys' divorce\u2014decreed upon the false grounds of Gacy's [[infidelity]] with women<ref name=\"autogenerated28\">''Murder In Mind'' issue 11 {{ISSN|1364-5803}} p. 28/ Murder In Mind p. 28</ref>\u2014was finalized.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19820501&id=o64yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=he4FAAAAIBAJ&pg=2634,556459|title=John Gacy: Businessman, Clown, Mass Killer|date=May 1, 1982|publisher=The Ottawa Citizen}}</ref>{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=87}}{{efn|In the hope of a reconciliation, Gacy and Hoff began dating again in late 1977, but Hoff became engaged to another man the following year.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=205, 220}}}}\n\n===Pogo the Clown===\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Johnwaynegacypogo.jpg\n| width1 = 145\n| height1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = Gacy as Pogo the Clown.\n| image2 = John Wayne Gacy's clown suit (17104376201).jpg\n| width2 = 145\n| height2 = \n| caption2 = Gacy's clown costume and one of his paintings.\n| direction = \n| total_width = \n}}\nThrough his membership in a local [[Moose International|Moose Club]], Gacy became aware of a \"Jolly Joker\" clown club, whose members regularly performed at fund-raising events and parades in addition to voluntarily entertaining hospitalized children.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=143}} In late 1975, Gacy joined the Jolly Jokers and created his own performance characters: \"Pogo the Clown\" and \"Patches the Clown.\"<ref>''Serial Killers''. p 68.</ref>{{efn|Gacy later stated acting as a clown allowed him to \"regress into childhood\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=145}} His clown costumes are on display at the [[National Museum of Crime & Punishment]].}} He performed as Pogo or Patches at numerous local parties, political functions, charitable events, and children's hospitals.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=145\u2013147}} He designed his own costumes and taught himself how to apply clown makeup.{{efn|Some professional clowns noted the sharp corners Gacy painted at the edges of his mouth are contrary to the rounded borders that professional clowns normally employ, so as not to scare children.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=70}}}} Gacy was also known to occasionally remain in his clowning garb after a performance. On several occasions, he is known to have arrived, dressed in his clowning garb, at a favorite drinking venue, \"The Good Luck Lounge\", with the explanation he had performed at a charitable event and was stopping for a social drink before heading home.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=111}}<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:W4fr6GQWh-0J:graphics.chicagotribune.com|accessdate=March 4, 2010|title=John Wayne Gacy was Arrested 40 Years Ago in a Killing Spree that Claimed 33 Victims and Shattered the Illusion of the Ssafe Suburban Community|date=December 16, 2018}}</ref> For these reasons, Gacy is known as the \"Killer Clown.\"\n\n==Murders==\nGacy typically abducted his victims from Chicago's Greyhound Bus station, from [[Washington Square Park (Chicago)|Bughouse Square]], or simply off the streets. The victims were often grabbed by force or conned into believing Gacy\u2014often carrying a sheriff's badge and placing spotlights on his black [[Oldsmobile]]\u2014was a policeman.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=178}} Others were lured to his house with either the promise of a job with his construction company, or an offer of drink, drugs, or money for sex.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=173}}\n\nInside Gacy's home, his usual ''[[modus operandi]]'' was to ply a youth with drink, drugs or generally gain his trust. Gacy would then produce a pair of handcuffs, occasionally as part of a clowning routine. He typically cuffed his own hands behind his back, then surreptitiously released himself with the key, which he hid between his fingers, before offering to show his intended victim how to release himself from the handcuffs.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=18}}{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=169\u2013170}} With his victim manacled and unable to free himself, Gacy then made a statement to the effect of: \"The trick is, you have to have the key\", before proceeding to rape and torture his captive.<ref name=\"Kozenczak\">Kozenczak (2012), pp. 200\u2013201</ref> Gacy referred to this act of restraining his victim as his \"handcuff trick\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=166}}\n\nSome victims were partly drowned in his bathtub before Gacy revived them, enabling him to continue his prolonged assault.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=331}} The victims were usually lured alone to his house, although on approximately three occasions, Gacy had what he called \"[[Double murder|doubles]]\"\u2014occasions wherein he killed two victims on the same evening.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=174}} With the exceptions of his first and last victims, all were murdered between 3:00&nbsp;a.m. and 6:00&nbsp;a.m.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=179}}\n\nGacy typically killed by placing a rope around a victim's neck, then progressively tightening the rope with a hammer handle;<ref>Kozenczak (2012), pp. 201-203</ref>{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=21}} he referred to this act as the \"rope trick.\" Occasionally, the victim [[convulse]]d for an \"hour or two\" before dying. Several victims died by asphyxiation from cloth gags stuffed into the mouth.<ref name=\"Kozenczak\" />\n\nAfter death, the victims' bodies were typically stored beneath his bed for up to 24 hours before Gacy buried his victim in the crawl space, where he periodically poured [[Calcium oxide|quicklime]] to hasten the decomposition of the bodies.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=177}} The bodies of some victims would be taken to his garage and [[embalming|embalmed]] prior to their burial.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=345}}\n\n=== Murder of Timothy McCoy ===\n[[File:TimothyJackMcCoyJohnGacyOmahaIllinoisJanuary31972a.jpg|upright=0.65|right|thumb|Timothy McCoy.]]\nGacy's first known murder occurred on January 2, 1972. According to Gacy's later account, following a family party, he decided to drive to the Civic Center to view a display of [[Ice sculpture|ice sculptures]] before luring a 16-year-old named Timothy Jack McCoy from Chicago's Greyhound bus terminal into his car. McCoy was traveling from [[Michigan]] to [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]]. Gacy took McCoy on a sightseeing tour of Chicago, and then drove him to his home with the promise that he could spend the night and be driven back to the station in time to catch his bus.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CSTB&p_theme=cstb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB36D062F6AA91B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D | date=May 20, 1986 |title=Gacy Victim's Remains Going Home to Iowa |first=Andrew |last=Herrmann |newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times}}</ref> Prior to McCoy's identification, he was known simply as the \"Greyhound Bus Boy\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Berry-Dee|2009|page=193}}</ref>\n\nGacy claimed he woke early the following morning to find McCoy standing in his bedroom doorway with a kitchen knife in his hand.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=348}} He then jumped from his bed and McCoy raised both arms in a gesture of surrender, tilting the knife upwards and accidentally cutting Gacy's forearm.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=110}}{{efn|Gacy had a scar on his arm to support this account.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=110-111}}}} He then twisted the knife from McCoy's wrist, banged his head against his bedroom wall, kicked him against his wardrobe and walked towards him. McCoy then kicked Gacy in the stomach, doubling him over. Gacy then grabbed McCoy, wrestled him to the floor, then stabbed him repeatedly in the chest as he straddled him.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=102}}\n\nAs McCoy lay dying, Gacy claimed he washed the knife in his bathroom, then went to his kitchen and saw an opened carton of eggs and a slab of unsliced bacon on his kitchen table. McCoy had also set the table for two; he had walked into Gacy's room to wake him while absentmindedly carrying the kitchen knife in his hand.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=349}} Gacy buried McCoy in his crawl space and later covered his grave with a layer of concrete.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=101}} In an interview several years after his arrest, Gacy stated that immediately after killing McCoy, he felt \"totally drained\", yet noted as he listened to the \"[[Gurgling|gurgulations]]\" as McCoy lay gasping for air that he had experienced a mind-numbing [[orgasm]] as he had stabbed him.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=348}} He added: \"That's when I realized that death was the ultimate thrill.\"{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=349}}\n\n===Second murder===\nGacy later stated that the second time he committed murder was around January 1974. The victim is believed to have been an unidentified teenager with medium brown hair and estimated to be aged between 14 and 18 whom Gacy strangled before stowing his body in his closet prior to burial.<ref name=\"Case File 954UMIL\">{{cite web|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/954umil.html|title=Case File 954UMIL|publisher=The Doe Network|access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> The victim was found wrapped within several plastic bags and wore a silver ring on the [[Ring finger|fourth finger]] of his left hand, indicating the possibility he had been married.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=249\u2013250}} Gacy later stated that fluid leaked out of the mouth and nose of this body while stored in his closet, staining his carpet.<ref>Whoever Fights Monsters {{ISBN|0-671-71561-5}} p. 336</ref> As a result of this experience, Gacy later stated he regularly stuffed cloth rags or the victims' own underwear in their mouths to prevent a recurrence of this incident. This particular unidentified victim was buried about {{convert|15|ft}} from the barbecue pit in Gacy's backyard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_IgxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9qEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6913,2124365&dq/|work=The Montreal Gazette|title=Another Skeleton Found at Gacy Home|date=March 10, 1979|access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Murder of John Butkovich===\n[[File:Butkovich.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|John Butkovich]]\nOne week after the attempted assault of Anthony Antonucci, on July 31, 1975, another of Gacy's employees, 18-year-old John Butkovich, disappeared.<ref>{{cite news|title=Search at Gacy Home to Resume |date=January 1, 1979 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19790101&id=PEEsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=v80EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2963,232748 |publisher=Herald-Journal |accessdate=April 11, 2019}}</ref> The day before his disappearance, Butkovich had threatened Gacy over two weeks' outstanding back pay. Butkovich's car was found abandoned in a parking lot with his jacket and wallet inside and the keys still in the ignition.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=132\u2013133}}  \n\nButkovich's father, a [[Yugoslavs|Yugoslav]] immigrant, called Gacy, who claimed he was happy to help search for his son but was sorry Butkovich had \"run away\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=133}} When questioned, Gacy said Butkovich and two friends had arrived at his house demanding the overdue pay, but that they left after a compromise was reached. Over the following three years, Butkovich's parents called police more than 100 times, urging them to investigate Gacy further.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=133}}{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=83\u201385}}\n\nGacy later admitted to luring Butkovich to his home, ostensibly to settle the issue of his overdue wages, on a date his wife and stepchildren were visiting his sister in [[Arkansas]]. He offered Butkovich a drink, then conned him into allowing his wrists to be cuffed behind his back. Gacy said he \"sat on the kid's chest for a while\" before he strangled him. He initially stowed Butkovich's body in his garage, with view to later burying the body in his crawl space.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=131}} When his wife and stepdaughters returned to Illinois earlier than expected, Gacy buried the body of Butkovich under the concrete floor of the garage.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=126, 129}}\n\n===Cruising years===\nIn addition to 1975 being the year of his business expanding, Gacy freely admitted that 1975 was also the year in which he began to increase the frequency of his excursions for sex with young males.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=121}} He often referred to these jaunts as his \"[[Cruising for sex|cruising]]\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=153}} The majority of Gacy's murders were committed between 1976 and 1978, which he later referred to as his \"cruising years\" as he largely lived alone following his divorce.\n\nAlthough Gacy remained gregarious and civic-minded, several neighbors became aware of erratic changes in his behavior after his 1976 divorce and subsequent arrest in December 1978. This behavior included hearing his car arrive and depart in the early hours of the morning; noting lights switching on and off in his home at odd hours and his keeping company with young males.<ref name=\"autogenerated28\" /> One neighbor later recollected that, for several years, she and her son had repeatedly been awoken by the repeated sounds of muffled screaming, shouting, and crying in the early morning hours, which she and her son identified as emanating from a house adjacent to theirs on Summerdale Avenue.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=274}}\n\n====1976====\nOne month after his divorce was finalized, Gacy abducted and murdered 18-year-old Darrell Samson. Samson was last seen alive in Chicago on April 6, 1976.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=158}} Five weeks later, on the afternoon of May 14, 15-year-old Randall Reffett disappeared while walking home from [[Senn High School]]; he was gagged with a cloth,{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=326}} causing him to die of asphyxiation.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), pp. 200\u2013201</ref> Hours after Reffett had been abducted, 14-year-old Samuel Stapleton vanished as he walked to his home from his sister's apartment.<ref name=\"autogenerated28\" /> Both victims were buried in the same grave in the crawl space.<ref>''Serial Killers''. p 70.</ref>\n\nOn June 3, 1976, Gacy killed a 17-year-old [[Lake View, Chicago|Lakeview]] teenager named Michael Bonnin. He disappeared while traveling from Chicago to [[Waukegan, Illinois|Waukegan]],{{sfn|Linedecker|1986|p=123}} and was strangled with a [[Ligature strangulation|ligature]] and buried in the crawl space.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=326}} Ten days later, a 16-year-old [[Uptown, Chicago|Uptown]] youth named William Carroll was murdered and buried directly beneath Gacy's kitchen. Carroll may have been the first of four males known to have been murdered between June 13 and August 6, 1976, and who were buried in a [[common grave]] located beneath Gacy's kitchen and laundry room.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=217}}{{efn|This common grave also held the body of a fifth male estimated to have been killed after this date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cookcountysheriff.org/sheriffs_police/gacy/gacy.html|title=Unidentified Victims of John Wayne Gacy|publisher=cookcountysheriff.org|date=October 11, 2011|access-date=January 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202030834/http://cookcountysheriff.org/sheriffs_police/gacy/gacy.html|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n\nThe three identified youths killed between June 13 and August 6 were aged between 16 and 17 years old, whereas the only unidentified male known to have been murdered between these dates is a man with medium dark brown hair estimated to have been aged between 23 and 30 years old and between {{nowrap|5 ft 1 in}} and {{nowrap|5 ft 6 in}} ({{convert|61|and|66|in|cm|disp=out}}) tall. This man had two missing upper front teeth at the time of his disappearance,<ref name=\"doenetwork1\">{{cite web|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/956umil.html |title=Case File 956UMIL |publisher=The Doe Network |access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> leading investigators to believe this particular victim most likely wore a [[denture]]. He was buried directly beneath the body of a 16-year-old [[Minnesota]] youth named James Haakenson, who is last known to have phoned his family on August 5, and whose body was itself buried directly beneath that of a 17-year-old [[Bensenville, Illinois|Bensenville]] youth named Rick Johnston, who was last seen alive on August 6.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2017/07/19/john-wayne-gacy-victim/|title=Minnesota Teen ID'd as John Wayne Gacy Victim|access-date=July 19, 2017|newspaper=CBS Local|date=July 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/sheriff-update-investigation-unnamed-gacy-victims-48724804 |title=Illinois Sheriff IDs Another Victim of John Wayne Gacy |access-date=July 19, 2017 |publisher=abcnews.go.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720051638/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/sheriff-update-investigation-unnamed-gacy-victims-48724804 |archivedate=July 20, 2017  }}</ref>{{efn|Because Haakenson and Johnston disappeared just 24 hours apart and their bones were commingled,{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=217\u2013218}} they may have been murdered on the same day or even at the same time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/19/us/john-wayne-gacy-victim-identified.html|title=John Wayne Gacy Victim is Identified After Four Decades|access-date=August 8, 2017|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 19, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nTwo further unidentified males are estimated to have been killed between August and October 1976. One of these victims was buried directly above the body of William Carroll, who had been murdered on June 13, yet higher than the body of Rick Johnston, who was last seen on August 6. This particular unidentified male is estimated to have been aged between 15 and 24 years old and had light brown hair. Sequential burial patterns of victims within the crawl space, plus the [[circumstantial evidence|circumstantial]] fact that Cram had not lived with Gacy until August 21, leave a possible date of between August 6 and 20, 1976 as the time this particular man was murdered.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=311}} The second unidentified male likely to have been murdered between August and October 1976 is a youth with dark brown, wavy hair, between 18 and 22 years old, and with an [[tooth abscess|abscessed tooth]]. This victim may have been killed somewhat before early October 1976, when Gacy had an employee to dig a trench in northeast corner of the crawlspace, where this victim's body was found.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=311}} \n\nOn October 24, 1976, Gacy abducted and killed teenage friends Kenneth Parker and Michael Marino:<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Apparent Gacy Victims Identified |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UO9eAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K1QNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5070,3504589&dq/ |publisher=St. Joseph Gazette |accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> the two were last seen outside a restaurant on [[Clark Street (Chicago)|Clark Street]]. Both were strangled and buried in the same grave in the crawl space. Two days later, a 19-year-old employee of PDM, William Bundy, disappeared after informing his family he was to attend a party. Bundy was also strangled and buried in the crawl space, directly beneath Gacy's master bedroom.<ref name=\"Serial Killers. p 83\">''Serial Killers''. p 83.</ref>\n\nIn December 1976, another PDM employee, 17-year-old Gregory Godzik, disappeared: he was last seen by his girlfriend outside her house after he had driven her home following a date.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=104}} Godzik had worked for PDM for only three weeks before he disappeared. In the time he had worked for Gacy, he had informed his family Gacy had had him \"dig trenches for some kind of (drain) tiles\" in his crawl space.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=184}} Godzik's car was later found abandoned in [[Niles, Illinois|Niles]]. His parents and older sister, Eugenia, contacted Gacy about Greg's disappearance. Gacy claimed to the family that Greg had run away from home, having indicated to Gacy before his disappearance that he wished to do so. Gacy also claimed to have received an [[answering machine]] message from Godzik shortly after he had disappeared. When asked if he could play back the message to Godzik's parents, Gacy stated that he had erased it.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=184}}{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=92\u201393}}\n\n====1977====\nOn January 20, 1977, John Szyc, a 19-year-old acquaintance of Butkovich, Godzik, and Gacy, disappeared. Szyc was lured to Gacy's house on the pretext of selling his [[Plymouth Satellite#Third Generation (1971-1974)|Plymouth Satellite]] to Gacy. He was buried in Gacy's crawl space directly above the body of Godzik.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=207}}\n\nBetween December 1976 and March 1977, Gacy is known to have killed an unidentified man estimated to be around 25 years old.<ref name=\"Case File 958UMIL\">{{cite web|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/958umil.html |title=Case File 958UMIL |publisher=The Doe Network |access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> An inscription upon a [[key fob]] found among the personal artifacts buried with this unknown victim suggests his first name may have been Greg or Gregory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/10994|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System|publisher=}}</ref> His body was buried in the crawl space beneath the body of 20-year-old Jon Prestidge, a Michigan man visiting friends in Chicago whom Gacy killed on March 15.\n\nAfter the murder of Prestidge, Gacy is believed to have murdered one further unidentified youth exhumed from his crawl space, although the timing of this particular youth's murder is inconclusive. He was buried parallel to the wall of Gacy's crawl space directly beneath the entrance to his home. The two victims murdered on the same day in May 1976 were buried alongside him, yet sequential burial patterns of three victims murdered in 1977 leave an equal possibility this particular victim may have been murdered in the spring or summer of 1977. All that is known about this youth is that he was aged between 17 and 21 years old and that he had suffered a fractured left [[clavicle|collarbone]] before his disappearance.<ref name=\"NamUs Case File 1282Dec78\">{{cite web|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/full_report/10998|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 10998|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1977,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=179}} Michael Rossi moved out of Gacy's home; the same month, Gacy became temporarily engaged to a woman he had been dating for three months, and his fianc\u00e9e moved into his house. By mutual agreement, the engagement was called off in June of that year and his fianc\u00e9e moved out of his home.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=180}} The following month, Gacy killed a 19-year-old [[Crystal Lake, Illinois|Crystal Lake]] youth named Matthew Bowman. He was buried in the crawl space with the tourniquet used to strangle him still knotted around his neck.<ref>{{cite news|title=Youthful Victims May Have Been Buried Alive, Expert Speculates |date=February 9, 1980 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rgtKAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HiINAAAAIBAJ&pg=5006,4386127&dq/Press |publisher=Press-Courier |accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1977, Rossi, who had bought Szyc's car from Gacy, was arrested for stealing gasoline from a service station while driving the car. The attendant noted the license plate number and police traced the car to Gacy's house. When questioned, Gacy told officers that Szyc had sold the car to him in February with the explanation that he needed money to leave town. A check of the [[Vehicle Identification Number|VIN]] number confirmed the car had belonged to Szyc.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 78</ref> The police did not pursue the matter further,{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=95\u201397}} although they did inform Szyc's mother that her son had sold his car to Gacy in February.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=184}}\n\nBy the end of 1977, Gacy is also known to have murdered an additional six young men between the ages of 16 and 21. The first of these six victims, 18-year-old Robert Gilroy, was last seen alive on September 15. Gilroy\u2014the son of a Chicago police sergeant{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=140}}\u2014was [[suffocation|suffocated]] and buried in the crawl space. On September 12, Gacy had flown to [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]] to supervise a remodeling project and did not return to Chicago until September 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/02/10/10374067-serial-killer-john-wayne-gacy-had-accomplices-lawyers-say |title=Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy Had Accomplices, lawyers Say \u2013 U.S. News |publisher=Usnews.nbcnews.com |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> As Gacy is known to have been in another state at the time Gilroy was last seen, this is cited to support Gacy's claim of being assisted by one or more accomplices. Ten days after Gilroy was last seen, 19-year-old former [[U.S. Marine]] John Mowery disappeared after leaving his mother's house to walk to his own apartment. Mowery was strangled and buried in the northwest corner of the crawl space perpendicular to the body of William Bundy.<ref name=\"Serial Killers. p 83\" />\n\nOn October 17, 21-year-old Minnesota Russell Nelson disappeared: he was last seen outside a Chicago bar. Nelson died of suffocation and was also buried in the crawl space. Less than four weeks later, 16-year-old [[Kalamazoo, Michigan|Kalamazoo]] teenager Robert Winch was murdered and buried in the crawl space, and on November 18, 20-year-old father-of-one Tommy Boling disappeared after leaving a Chicago bar. Both Winch and Boling were strangled<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 202</ref> and buried in the crawl space directly beneath the hallway.<ref>''Serial Killers''. pp 80\u201383.</ref>\n\nThree weeks after the murder of Tommy Boling, on December 9, a 19-year-old U.S. Marine named David Talsma disappeared after informing his mother he was to attend a rock concert in [[Hammond, Illinois|Hammond]].{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=183}} Talsma was strangled with a ligature and buried in the crawl space.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 203</ref>\n\nOn December 30, 1977, Gacy abducted 19-year-old student Robert Donnelly from a Chicago bus stop at gunpoint.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=241}} Gacy drove Donnelly home with him, where Donnelly was raped, tortured, and repeatedly had his head dunked into a bathtub until he passed out. Donnelly later testified at Gacy's trial that he was in such pain that he asked Gacy to kill him;{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=244\u2013245}} Gacy replied, \"I'm getting round to it.\" After several hours Gacy drove Donnelly to his workplace and released him, first warning him that if he complained to police they would not believe him.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=334}}\n\n====1978====\nDonnelly reported the assault and Gacy was questioned by police on January 6, 1978. Gacy admitted to having had \"[[BDSM|slave-sex]]\" with Donnelly, but insisted everything was consensual. The police believed him and no charges were filed.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=150}} The following month, Gacy killed 19-year-old William Kindred, who disappeared on February 16, after telling his fianc\u00e9e he was to spend the evening in a bar.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=217}} Kindred was the final victim to be buried in Gacy's crawl space.<ref>''Serial Killers''. p 73.</ref>{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=219}}\n\nIn March, Gacy lured 26-year-old [[Jeffrey Rignall]] into his car. Upon entering the car, the young man was [[chloroform]]ed and driven to the house on Summerdale, where he was raped, tortured with various instruments including lit candles and whips, and repeatedly chloroformed into unconsciousness.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=208}} Rignall was then driven to [[Lincoln Park, Chicago|Lincoln Park]], where he was dumped, unconscious but alive. He was later informed the chloroform had permanently damaged his liver.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=208}}\n\n[[File:Des Plaines River.png|thumb|upright=1.2|In June 1978 Gacy began discarding his victims' bodies of his victims in the [[Des Plaines River]], as his crawl space was full.|alt=]]Rignall managed to stagger to his girlfriend's apartment. Police were again informed of the assault but did not investigate Gacy. Rignall was able to recall, through the haze of that night, the Oldsmobile, the [[Kennedy Expressway]] and particular side streets. He staked out the exit on the Expressway when in April he saw the Oldsmobile, which Rignall and his friends followed to 8213 West Summerdale.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=208\u2013209}} Police issued an [[arrest warrant]], and Gacy was arrested on July 15.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|pp=146\u2013150}} He was facing an impending trial for battery against Rignall when he was arrested.{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=153}}\n\nBy 1978, the crawl space could store no further bodies.<ref name=\"Michael H. Stone 2019 pp. 196-203\" />{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=273}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=171\u2013175}} Gacy later confessed to police that he initially considered stowing bodies in his attic, but had been worried of complications arising from \"excessive leakage\".<ref name=\"Kozenczak, 2012 p. 177\">Kozenczak, (2012) p. 177</ref> Therefore, he chose to dispose of his victims off the [[Interstate 55|I-55]] bridge into the [[Des Plaines River]].{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=152}} Gacy stated he had thrown five bodies off the I-55 bridge into the Des Plaines River in 1978, one of which he believed had landed upon a passing [[barge]].{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=175}} Only four of these five bodies were ever found.<ref>{{cite news |title=Timeline: Suburban Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy and the Efforts to Recover, Name His 33 Victims |date=December 17, 2018 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/history/ct-john-wayne-gacy-timeline-htmlstory.html}}</ref>\n\nThe first known victim thrown from the I-55 bridge into the Des Plaines River, 20-year-old Timothy O'Rourke, was killed in mid-June after leaving his Dover Street apartment, having informed his roommate of his intention to purchase cigarettes; his body was found {{convert|6|mi|km|0}} downstream on June 30.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=273}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=220}}  \n[[File:Piest1.jpg|upright=0.7|thumb|Robert Piest, whose disappearance led to Gacy's arrest|alt=|left]]\nOn November 4, Gacy killed 19-year-old Frank Landingin. His body was found in the Des Plaines River on November 12. Less than three weeks later, on November 24, a 20-year-old [[Elmwood Park, Illinois|Elmwood Park]] resident, James Mazzara, disappeared after sharing Thanksgiving dinner with his family; his body was found on December 28. The cause of death in the case of Landingin was certified as suffocation through his own underwear being lodged down his throat, plugging his airway and effectively causing him to drown in his own vomit.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=276}} Mazzara had been strangled with a ligature.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=275}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=225}}\n\n=====Murder of Robert Piest=====\nOn the afternoon of December 11, 1978, Gacy visited the Nisson Pharmacy in [[Des Plaines, Illinois|Des Plaines]] to discuss a potential remodeling deal with store owner Phil Torf. While Gacy was within earshot of 15-year-old, part-time employee Robert Piest, he mentioned that his firm hired teenage boys at a starting wage of $5 per hour\u2014almost double the pay Piest earned at the pharmacy.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=5\u20136}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=4}}\n\nShortly after Gacy left the pharmacy, Piest informed his mother\u2014who had arrived at the pharmacy to drive her son home\u2014that \"some contractor wants to talk to me about a job\". Piest left the store, promising to return shortly.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=7}}  He was murdered shortly after 10:00&nbsp;p.m. at Gacy's home. Gacy later stated that as he placed the tourniquet around Piest's neck, Piest was \"crying, scared\".<ref>Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 140</ref> He also admitted to having received a phone call from a business acquaintance as Piest lay dying on his bedroom floor.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=231}}\n\n==Investigation==\nWhen Piest failed to return, his family filed a [[missing person]] report on their son with the Des Plaines police. Torf named Gacy as the contractor Piest had most likely left the store to talk with about a job.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), pp. 25-26</ref> Convinced Piest had not run away from home, Lieutenant [[Joseph R. Kozenczak|Joseph Kozenczak]] chose to investigate Gacy further.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), pp. 26-27</ref>\n\nKozenczak and two other Des Plaines police officers visited Gacy at his home the following evening. Gacy indicated he had seen two youths working at the pharmacy and that he had asked one of them\u2014whom he believed to be Piest\u2014whether any remodeling materials were present in the rear of the store.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=19\u201321}} He was adamant, however, that he had not offered Piest a job and promised to come to the station later that evening to make a statement confirming this, indicating he was unable to do so at that moment as his uncle had just died. When questioned as to how soon he could come to the police station, he responded: \"You guys are very rude. Don't you have any respect for the dead?\"{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=240}}\n\nAt 3:20&nbsp;a.m., Gacy, covered in mud, arrived at the police station, claiming he had been involved in a car accident.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=23}} Upon returning to the police station later that day, Gacy denied any involvement in the disappearance of Piest and repeated that he had not offered him a job. When asked why he had returned to the pharmacy at 8:00&nbsp;p.m. Gacy claimed he had done so in response to a phone call from Torf informing him he had left his appointment book at the store. Detectives had already spoken with Torf, who had stated he had placed no such call to Gacy.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=27}} At the request of detectives, Gacy prepared a written statement detailing his movements on December 11.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=28}}\n\n===Revelations===\nDes Plaines police were convinced Gacy was behind Piest's disappearance and checked Gacy's record, discovering that he had an outstanding battery charge against him in Chicago and had served a prison sentence in Iowa for the sodomy of a 15-year-old boy.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=17}} A search of Gacy's house on December 13 was ordered by a judge at the request of detectives and revealed several suspicious items. These included a [[syringe]], several police badges, and a 6mm Brevettata [[starter pistol]]. They also found handcuffs, books on homosexuality and [[pederasty]], a 39 inch long [[Dimensional lumber#Dimensional lumber|two-by-four]] with two holes drilled into each end,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=33}} several driver's licenses, a blue hooded parka and underwear too small to fit Gacy.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 61</ref>\n\nIn the northwest bedroom, investigators found a [[Maine West High School]] ring. This item initially interested investigators as Piest had attended Maine West, but the ring was not his. It was a class of 1975 ring engraved with the initials J.A.S.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=243}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=87}} A photo receipt from Nisson Pharmacy was also recovered from a trash can.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 61</ref>\n\nGacy's Oldsmobile and other PDM work vehicles were confiscated by the Des Plaines police, who assigned two two-man [[surveillance]] teams to monitor Gacy on a rotational twelve-hour basis as they continued their investigation into his background and potential involvement in Piest's disappearance.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Murder casebook number 84 {{ISBN|0-7485-1454-6}}, p. 1915</ref> These surveillance teams consisted of officers Mike Albrecht and David Hachmeister, and Ronald Robinson and Robert Schultz.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=41}} The following day, investigators received a phone call from Michael Rossi, who informed the investigators both of Gregory Godzik's disappearance and the fact that another PDM employee, Charles Hattula, had been found drowned in an Illinois river the previous year.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=53}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=123}}\n\nOn December 15, Des Plaines investigators obtained further details upon Gacy's battery charge, learning the complainant, Jeffrey Rignall, had reported that Gacy had lured him into his car, chloroformed him, raped him and dumped him, with severe chest and facial burns and rectal bleeding, in Lincoln Park the following morning. In an interview with Gacy's former wife the same day, they learned of the disappearance of John Butkovich.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=84}} The same day, the Maine West High School ring was traced to a John Alan Szyc.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=53\u201355}} In an interview with Szyc's mother the same day, she informed officers of the January 1977 disappearance of her son and that several items from his apartment were also missing, including a Motorola TV set.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 117</ref>\n\nBy December 16, Gacy was becoming affable with the surveillance detectives, regularly inviting them to join him for meals in restaurants and occasionally for drinks in bars or within his home. He repeatedly denied that he had anything to do with Piest's disappearance and accused the officers of harassing him because of his political connections or because of his recreational drug use. Knowing these officers were unlikely to arrest him on anything trivial, he openly taunted them by flouting traffic laws and succeeded in losing his pursuers on more than one occasion.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=89}}\n\nOn December 17, investigators conducted a formal interview of Michael Rossi, who informed them Gacy had sold Szyc's vehicle to him with the explanation that he had bought the car from Szyc because Szyc needed money to move to California. A further examination of Gacy's Oldsmobile was conducted on this date. In the course of examining the trunk of the car, the investigators discovered a small cluster of fibers which may have been human hair. These fibers were sent for further analysis. That evening, officers conducted a test using three trained [[German shepherd]] [[Search and rescue dog|search dogs]] to determine whether Piest had been present in any of Gacy's vehicles.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=93}} The dogs were allowed to examine each of Gacy's vehicles, whereupon one dog approached Gacy's Oldsmobile and lay upon the passenger seat in what the dog's handler informed investigators was a \"death reaction\", indicating the body of Robert Piest had been present in this vehicle.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=93}}\n\nThat evening, Gacy invited two of the surveillance detectives to a restaurant for a meal. In the early hours of December 18, he invited the same officers into another restaurant where, over breakfast, he talked of his business, his marriages and his activities as a registered clown. At one point during this conversation, Gacy remarked to one of the two surveillance detectives: \"You know\u2026 clowns can get away with murder.\"{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=226}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=90}}\n\n===Civil suit===\nBy December 18, Gacy was beginning to show visible signs of strain as a result of the constant surveillance: he was unshaven, looked tired, appeared anxious and was drinking heavily. That afternoon, he drove to his lawyers' office to prepare a $750,000 [[civil suit]] against the Des Plaines police,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=102}} demanding that they cease their surveillance. The same day, the serial number of the Nisson Pharmacy photo receipt found in Gacy's kitchen was traced to 17-year-old Kim Byers, a colleague of Piest at Nisson Pharmacy, who admitted when contacted in person the following day that she had worn the jacket and had placed the receipt in the [[Anorak|parka]] pocket just before she gave the parka to Piest as he left the store to talk with a contractor.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=110}} This revelation contradicted Gacy's previous statements that he had had no contact with Robert Piest on the evening of December 11.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|pp=116\u2013117}}\n\nThe same evening, Michael Rossi was interviewed a second time: on this occasion, Rossi was more cooperative, informing detectives that in the summer of 1977, Gacy had had him spread ten bags of [[Lime (material)|lime]] in the crawl space of the house.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=143}}\n\nOn December 19, investigators began compiling evidence for a second search warrant of Gacy's house. The same day, Gacy's lawyers filed the civil suit against the Des Plaines police. The hearing of the suit was scheduled for December 22. That afternoon, Gacy invited two of the surveillance detectives inside his house. On this occasion, as one officer distracted Gacy with conversation, another officer walked into Gacy's bedroom in an unsuccessful attempt to write down the serial number of the Motorola TV set they suspected belonged to John Szyc. While flushing Gacy's toilet, this officer noticed a smell he suspected could be that of rotting corpses emanating from a [[heating duct]]; the officers who previously searched Gacy's house had failed to notice this, as on that occasion the house had been cold.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nBoth David Cram and Michael Rossi were interviewed by investigators on December 20. Rossi had agreed to be interviewed in relation to his possible links with John Szyc as well as the disappearance of Robert Piest. When questioned by Kozenczak as to where he believed Gacy had placed Piest's body, Rossi replied: \"In the crawl space; he could have put him in the crawl space.\"<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 147</ref> A polygraph test showed his responses to questions to be inconclusive; however, upon his agreeing to a subsequent visual test in which a map of Cook County was divided into 12 [[Grid plan|grid sections]] numbered 1 to 12, with Gacy's home marked in the fourth grid section, Kozenczak noted an extreme response in Rossi's [[blood pressure]] when asked: \"Is the body of Robert Piest buried in grid number 4?\"<ref>Kozenczak, Joseph R.; Kozenczak, Karen M. (February 6, 2012) ''The Chicago Killer: The Hunt For Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy''. CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform. {{ISBN|978-1401095314}} p. 148</ref> Upon hearing this question, Rossi refused to continue the polygraph questioning, although he did discuss further his digging trenches in the crawl space and remarked upon Gacy's insistence that he not deviate from where he was instructed to dig.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=181}}\n\nCram himself informed investigators of Gacy's attempts to rape him in 1976 and stated that after he and Gacy had returned to his home after the December 13 search of his property, Gacy had turned pale upon noting a clot of mud on his carpet which he suspected had come from his crawl space. Cram then stated Gacy had grabbed a flashlight and immediately entered the crawl space to look for evidence of digging. When asked whether he had been to the crawl space, Cram replied he had been asked by Gacy to spread lime down there and also dug trenches upon Gacy's behest with the explanation they were for plumbing.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=143}} Cram stated these trenches were {{convert|2|ft|m|sp=us}} wide, {{convert|6|ft|m|sp=us}} long and {{convert|2|ft|m|sp=us}} deep\u2014the size of graves.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=143\u2013145}}\n\n===Verbal confession===\nOn the evening of December 20, Gacy drove to his lawyers' office in [[Park Ridge, Illinois|Park Ridge]] to attend a pre-scheduled meeting he had arranged with them, ostensibly to discuss the progress of his civil suit. Upon his arrival, Gacy appeared disheveled and immediately asked for an alcoholic drink, whereupon Sam Amirante fetched a bottle of whiskey from his car. Upon his return, Amirante asked Gacy what he had to discuss with them. Gacy picked up a copy of the ''[[Chicago Daily Herald|Daily Herald]]'' from Amirante's desk; he pointed to a front-page article covering the disappearance of Robert Piest and informed his lawyers: \"This boy is dead. He's in a river.\"{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=136}}\n\nOver the following hours, Gacy gave a rambling confession that ran into the early hours of the following morning. He began by informing Amirante and Stevens he had \"been the judge ... jury and executioner of many, many people\", and that he now wanted to be the same for himself.<ref>Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 127</ref> He stated most of his victims were buried in his crawl space, and others in the Des Plaines River. Gacy dismissed his victims as \"[[Male prostitution|male prostitutes]]\", \"hustlers\" and \"liars\" to whom he gave \"the rope trick\", adding that he occasionally awoke to find \"dead, strangled kids\" on his floor, with their hands cuffed behind their back.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=171}}\n\nAs a result of the alcohol he had consumed, Gacy fell asleep midway through his confession and Amirante immediately arranged a psychiatric appointment for Gacy at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. that morning. Upon awakening several hours later, Gacy simply shook his head when informed by Amirante he had earlier confessed to killing approximately 30 people, stating: \"Well, I can't think about this right now. I've got things to do.\"<ref name=\"Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 150\">Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 150</ref> Ignoring his lawyers' advice regarding his scheduled appointment, Gacy left their office to attend to the needs of his business.<ref name=\"Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 150\" />\n\nGacy later recollected his memories of his final day of freedom as being \"hazy\", adding that he knew his arrest was inevitable and that, in his final hours of freedom, he intended to visit his friends and say his final farewells.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=255\u2013258}} Upon leaving his lawyers' office, Gacy drove to a Shell gas station where, in the course of filling his rental car, he handed a small bag of [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] to the attendant, Lance Jacobson. Jacobson immediately handed the bag to the surveillance officers, adding that Gacy had told him: \"The end is coming (for me). These guys are going to kill me.\" Gacy then drove to the home of a fellow contractor, Ronald Rhode. Inside Rhode's living room, Gacy hugged Rhode before bursting into tears and saying: \"I killed thirty people, give or take a few.\" Gacy then left Rhode's home to meet with Michael Rossi and David Cram. As he drove along the expressway, the surveillance officers noted he was holding a [[Catholic rosary|rosary]] to his chin as he prayed while driving.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=152}}\n\nAfter talking with Cram and Rossi at Cram's home, Gacy had Cram drive him to a scheduled meeting with Leroy Stevens. As he spoke with his lawyer, Cram informed the officers that Gacy had earlier divulged to both himself and Rossi that the previous evening, he had confessed to his lawyers his guilt in over thirty murders. Upon concluding his meeting with his lawyer, Gacy had Cram drive him to Maryhill Cemetery, where his father was buried.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=259}}\n\nAs Gacy drove to various locations that morning, police outlined their formal draft of their second search warrant. The purpose of the warrant was specifically to search for the body of Robert Piest in the crawl space. Upon hearing radioed reports from the surveillance detectives that, in light of his erratic behavior, Gacy might be about to commit suicide, police decided to arrest him upon a charge of possession and distribution of marijuana{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=157}} in order to hold him in custody as the formal request for a second search warrant was presented. At 4:30 on the afternoon of December 21, the eve of the hearing of Gacy's civil suit, the request for a second search warrant was granted by Judge Marvin J. Peters.<ref>Kozenczak, (2012) p. 158</ref>\n\nArmed with the signed search warrant, police and evidence technicians quickly drove to Gacy's home. Upon their arrival, officers found that Gacy had unplugged his [[sump pump]] and that the crawl space was flooded with water; to clear the water they simply replaced the plug and waited for the water to drain. After it had done so, evidence technician Daniel Genty entered the {{convert|28|x|38|ft|adj=on}} crawl space,<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 50.</ref> crawled to the southwest area, and began digging. Within minutes, he had uncovered [[putrefaction|putrefied]] flesh and a human arm bone. Genty immediately shouted to the investigators that they could charge Gacy with murder.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=167}} Genty added the remark: \"I think this place is full of kids.\"{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=167}}\n\n==Arrest and confession==\n[[File:Gacysmilemugshot.png|thumb|upright=0.7|Gacy's [[mug shot]], taken December 22.]]\nAfter being informed that the police had found human remains in his crawl space and that he would now face murder charges, Gacy told officers he wanted to \"clear the air\",{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=171}} adding that he had known his arrest was inevitable since the previous evening, which he had spent on the couch in his lawyers' office.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=170}}\n\nIn the early hours of December 22, 1978, Gacy confessed to police that since 1972, he had committed 25 to 30 murders, all of whom he falsely claimed were of teenage male [[Runaway (dependent)|runaway]]s or male prostitutes, the majority of whom he had buried in his crawl space.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=174}} Some victims he referred to by name, but most names he claimed not to know or remember.  He confessed he had buried the body of John Butkovich in his garage.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=188}} When asked where he drew the inspiration for the two-by-four attached with manacles at either end found at his house, Gacy stated he had been inspired to construct the device from reading about the [[Dean Corll|Houston Mass Murders]].{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=197}}{{efn|The Houston Mass Murders were a series of killings uncovered in 1973 in which Dean Corll, with two teenaged accomplices, had also used a wooden device (in their case a board fitted with handcuffs at each corner) to restrain their male victims throughout their sexual abuse and torture.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Man with the Candy: The Story of the Houston Mass Murders|last = Olsen|first = Jack|publisher = Simon and Schuster|year = 2008|isbn = 978-1-439-12870-1 |page = 146}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = How to Make a Serial Killer: The Twisted Development of Innocent Children Into the World's Most Sadistic Murderers|last = Berry-Dee|first = Christopher|publisher = Ulysses Press|year = 2008|isbn = 978-1-569-75943-1|location = |page = 202}}</ref> Gacy was likely inspired to construct this device, and to initially restrain his victims by tricking them into handcuffs, by press coverage relating to the Houston Mass Murders.{{sfn|Berry-Dee|2009|p=138}}}} In January 1979, he had planned to further conceal the corpses by covering the entire crawl space with concrete.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=222}} \n\nWhen specifically questioned about Piest, Gacy confessed to strangling him at his house on the evening of December 11 after luring him there. He also admitted to having slept alongside Piest's body that evening, before disposing of the corpse in the Des Plaines River in the early hours of December 13.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19800210&id=aE80AAAAIBAJ&sjid=zWcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6517,3813660|title=Alleged Victim of Gacy Never Returned to Store|date=February 10, 1980|newspaper=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref> The reason he had arrived at the police station in a dirty and disheveled manner in the early hours of December 13 was that he had been in a minor traffic accident after disposing of Piest's body, en route to his appointment with Des Plaines officers. In this accident, his vehicle had slid off an ice-covered road, and he had unsuccessfully attempted to free the vehicle himself before the vehicle had to be towed from its location.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=176\u2013177}} \n[[File:Gacycrawlspace.png|thumb|upright=1.45|Gacy's sketch of burial locations in his basement, and investigators' later diagram]]\nTo assist officers in their search for the victims buried beneath his house, Gacy drew a rough diagram of his basement upon a phone message sheet to indicate where their bodies were buried.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=193}}\n\n===Search for victims===\nOn December 22 police took Gacy to his house, where he marked his garage floor with paint to show where he had buried Butkovich's body. They then drove to the spot on the I-55 bridge from which he had thrown the bodies of Piest and four others. Four of the five victims Gacy claimed to have disposed of there were recovered.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=219}}{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=320}}\n\nBy December 29, twenty-six bodies had been found in the crawl space, and one beneath the garage.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=213}} Operations were suspended due to the [[Chicago Blizzard of 1979]], but resumed in March despite Gacy's insistence that all the buried victims had been found.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19790105&id=Yk8xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yaEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5965,3354691|work=The Montreal Gazette|via=Google News Archive Search|title=Search to Continue at 'House of Horrors'|date=January 5, 1979|page=70}}</ref><ref name=\"Michael H. Stone 2019 pp. 196-203\"/>\n\nOn March 9, a body was found buried close to a barbecue in the backyard, and on March 16 another was found beneath the dining room floor.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=250}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=250}} In April 1979, Gacy's vacant house was demolished.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19790412&id=FH4xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4aEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7078,918268|work=The Montreal Gazette|via=Google News Archive Search|publisher=|title=Neighbors Relieved as Gacy Home Demolished|date=April 12, 1979|page=95}}</ref>\n\nThree additional bodies, which had been found in the nearby Des Plaines River between June and December 1978, were also confirmed to have been victims of Gacy.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=219\u2013221}}\n[[File:Crawlspace29.jpg|upright=1|thumb|Twenty-six bodies were found buried in Gacy's crawl space.]]\nSeveral bodies unearthed at Gacy's property were found with plastic bags over their heads or upper torsos.{{efn|Gacy had stated in a January 1979 interview that he would cover the victim's head or upper torso with a plastic bag if he noted bleeding from the nose or mouth.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=223}}}} In addition, several of the bodies were found with the ligature used to strangle them still knotted around their necks. In other instances, cloth gags were found lodged deep down the victims' throats, leading the medical examiner to conclude that 12 victims died not of strangulation, but of asphyxiation.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=221}} In some cases, bodies were found with foreign objects such as prescription bottles lodged into their pelvic region, the position of which indicated the items had been thrust into the victims' anus.<ref>''Serial Killers''. p. 80.</ref> All the victims discovered at 8213 Summerdale were in an advanced state of decomposition, and the medical examiner chiefly relied upon [[Forensic dentistry|dental records]] to facilitate the identification of the remains.<ref>''The Casebook of Forensic Detection'' {{ISBN|0-471-07650-3}} p. 134</ref>\n\nTwo victims were identified because of their known connection to Gacy through PDM.<ref name=\"SHJ-3morebodies\" /> Most identifications were facilitated with the assistance of [[X-ray]] charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1891&dat=19791118&id=mZ8fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DNYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4650,2607923|title=Gacy Victim Identified|date=November 18, 1979|publisher=The Gadsden Times}}</ref> Identifications were supported via personal [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifact]]s being found at 8213 Summerdale: one victim, 19-year-old David Talsma, was identified via comparison of [[radiology]] records of a healed fracture of the left [[scapula]] matching distress evident upon the 17th skeleton recovered from Gacy's property.<ref>''The Casebook of Forensic Detection'' {{ISBN|0-471-07650-3}} p. 135</ref> Timothy O'Rourke was last heard mentioning that a contractor had offered him a job.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=219}} Of Gacy's identified victims, the youngest were Samuel Stapleton and Michael Marino, both 14; the oldest was Russell Nelson, who was 21. Six victims have never been identified.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cookcountysheriff.org/sheriffs_police/gacy/gacy.html|title=Cook County Sheriff \u2013 Unidentified Victims of John Wayne Gacy|publisher=|access-date=November 22, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223144708/http://cookcountysheriff.org/sheriffs_police/gacy/gacy.html|archive-date=December 23, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 1979, a decomposed body was discovered entangled in exposed roots on the edge of the Des Plaines River in [[Grundy County, Illinois|Grundy County]].<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 190</ref> The body was identified via dental records as being that of Robert Piest. A subsequent [[autopsy]] revealed that three wads of \"paper-like material\" had been shoved down his throat while he was alive,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=362}} causing him to die of suffocation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Authorities Level John Gacy Home |date=April 12, 1979 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1916&dat=19790412&id=QyVJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VAYNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1285,2633468 |publisher=The Hour |accessdate=September 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nGacy was brought to trial on February 6, 1980, charged with 33 murders.<ref name=\"SHT-Speedup\" /> He was tried in Cook County, Illinois, before [[Louis B. Garippo|Judge Louis Garippo]]; the [[voir dire|jury was selected]] from [[Rockford, Illinois|Rockford]] because of significant press coverage in Cook County.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|pp=241\u2013242}}\n\nAt the request of his defense counsel, Gacy spent over three hundred hours in the year before his trial with the doctors at the [[Menard Correctional Center]]. He underwent a variety of psychological tests{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=261}} before a panel of psychiatrists to determine whether he was mentally competent to stand trial.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=261\u2013262}}\n\nGacy had attempted to convince the doctors that he suffered from a [[Dissociative identity disorder|multiple personality disorder]].{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=312}} His lawyers opted to have Gacy plead [[insanity plea|not guilty by reason of insanity]] to the charges against him, and produced several psychiatric experts who had examined Gacy the previous year to testify to their findings.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|pp=315\u2013323}} Three psychiatric experts appearing for the defense at Gacy's trial testified they found Gacy to be a [[paranoid schizophrenic]] with a multiple personality disorder.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|pp=301}}<ref name=\"Michael H. Stone 2019 pp. 196-203\"/>\n\nThe prosecutors presented a case that indicated Gacy was sane and fully in control of his actions.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=250}} To support this contention, they produced several witnesses to testify to the [[premeditation]] of Gacy's actions and the efforts he went to in order to escape detection. Those doctors refuted the defense doctors' claims of multiple personality and insanity. Cram and Rossi both confessed that Gacy had made them dig trenches in his crawl space. Cram testified that in August 1977, Gacy had marked a location in the crawl space with sticks and told him to dig a [[Drainage#Drainage in construction|drainage]] trench.<ref name=\"The Montreal Gazette Feb. 13, 1980\" />{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=181}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=311}}\n\nImmediately after Cram had completed his testimony, Rossi testified for the state. When asked where he had dug in the crawl space, Rossi turned to a diagram of Gacy's home on display in the courtroom. This diagram showed where the bodies were found in the crawl space and elsewhere on the property. Rossi pointed to the location of the remains of an unidentified victim known as \"Body 13\".{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=311}} Rossi stated he had not dug any other trenches, but\u2014at Gacy's request\u2014had supervised other PDM employees digging trenches in the crawl space.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=181}}\n\nBoth Rossi and Cram also testified that Gacy periodically looked into the crawl space to ensure they and other employees ordered to dig trenches in the crawl space did not deviate from the precise locations he had marked.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=312}} Gacy had testified after his arrest that he had only dug five of the victims' graves in his crawl space{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=142}} and had his employees (including Gregory Godzik) dig the remaining trenches so that he would \"have graves available\".{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=360}}\n\nOn February 18 Robert Stein,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=321}} the Cook County medical examiner who supervised the exhumations, testified that all the bodies were \"markedly decomposed<!--,--> [and] putrefied<!--, skeletalized remains-->\",<ref>{{cite news|title=Mother Cries at Description of Son's Grave|date=February 19, 1980 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VHVkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Mn4NAAAAIBAJ&pg=2366,5212913 |newspaper=The Calgary Herald |accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref> and that of all the autopsies he performed, thirteen victims had died of asphyxiation, six of ligature strangulation, one of multiple stab wounds to the chest,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=102}} and ten in undetermined ways.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=322}}{{efn|Stein performed autopsies on each victim recovered at Gacy's property and upon the body of Robert Piest. He did not perform autopsies upon the three other victims recovered from the Des Plaines River.}}\nWhen Gacy's defense team suggested that all 33 deaths were accidental (by [[erotic asphyxia]]), Stein called this highly improbable.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=322\u2013323}}{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=233}}\n\nJeffrey Rignall testified on behalf of the defense on February 21.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=325}} Recounting his ordeal, Rignall wept repeatedly while describing Gacy's torture of him in March 1978. Asked whether Gacy appreciated the criminality of his actions, Rignall said he believed that Gacy was unable to conform his actions to the law's expectations because of the \"beastly and animalistic ways he attacked me\".<ref>Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 290</ref> During specific cross-examination relating to the torture, Rignall vomited and was excused from further testimony.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=300}}\n\nOn February 29, Donald Voorhees, whom Gacy had sexually assaulted in 1967, testified to his ordeal at Gacy's hands, and that Gacy had subsequently paid another youth to beat him and spray Mace in his face so he would not testify against him.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=340}} Voorhees felt unable to testify, but did briefly attempt to do so, before being asked to step down.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=340}}\n\nRobert Donnelly testified the week after Voorhees, recounting his ordeal at Gacy's hands in December 1977. Donnelly was visibly distressed as he recollected the abuse he endured at Gacy's hands and came close to breaking down on several occasions. As Donnelly testified, Gacy repeatedly laughed at him,{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=333}} but Donnelly finished his testimony. One of Gacy's defense attorneys, Robert Motta, during Donnelly's cross-examination, attempted to discredit his testimony, but Donnelly did not waver from his testimony of what had occurred.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=345}}\n\nDuring the fifth week of the trial, Gacy wrote a personal letter to Judge Garippo requesting a [[mistrial]]{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=342}} on a number of bases, including that he did not approve his lawyers' insanity plea approach; that his lawyers had not allowed him to take the witness stand (as he had desired to do); that his defense had not called enough witnesses, and that the police were lying about statements he had purportedly made to detectives after his arrest and that, in any event, the statements were \"self-serving\" for use by the prosecution.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=350\u2013351}} Judge Garippo addressed Gacy's letter by informing him that under the law he had the choice as to whether he wished to testify, and he was free to indicate as much to the judge if he wished to do so.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=312}}\n\n===Closing arguments===\nOn March 11, final arguments from both prosecution and defense attorneys began, with the arguments concluding on the following day. Prosecuting attorney Terry Sullivan argued first, outlining Gacy's history of abusing youths, the testimony of his efforts to avoid detection and describing Gacy's surviving victims\u2014Voorhees and Donnelly\u2014as \"living dead\".{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=361}} Referring to Gacy as the \"worst of all murderers\",<ref>Amirante & Broderick 2011, p. 324</ref> Sullivan stated: \"John Gacy has accounted for more human devastation than many earthly catastrophes, but one must tremble. I tremble when thinking about just how close he came to getting away with it all.\"{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=361}}\n\nAfter the state's four-hour closing, counsel Sam Amirante argued for the defense. Amirante argued against the testimony delivered by the doctors who had testified for the prosecution, repeatedly citing the testimony of the four psychiatrists and psychologists who had testified on behalf of the defense.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=360}} Amirante also accused Sullivan of scarcely referring to the evidence presented throughout the trial in his own closing argument, and of arousing hatred against his client. The defense lawyer attempted to portray Gacy as a \"man driven by compulsions he was unable to control\".{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=363}}\n\nIn support of these arguments, the defense counsel repeatedly referred to the testimony of the doctors who had appeared for the defense, in addition to the testimony of defense witnesses such as Jeffrey Rignall and Gacy's former business associate Mickel Reed\u2014both of whom had testified to their belief that Gacy had been unable to control his actions.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=359}} Amirante then urged the jury to put aside any prejudice they held against his client, and requested they deliver a verdict of not guilty by reason of insanity, adding that the psychology of Gacy's behavior would be of benefit to scientific research and that the psychology of his mind should be studied.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=361}}\n\n[[File:Kunkletrial.jpg|upright=1|thumb|William Kunkle, prosecutor at Gacy's trial, standing before a board depicting the 22 victims identified by February 1980.]]\nOn the morning of March 12,{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=364}} William Kunkle continued to argue for the prosecution. Kunkle referred to the defense's contention of insanity as \"a [[falsity|sham]]\", arguing that the facts of the case demonstrated Gacy's ability to think logically and control his actions. Kunkle also referred to the testimony of a doctor who had examined Gacy in 1968. This doctor had diagnosed Gacy as an [[antisocial personality]], capable of committing crimes without remorse. Kunkle indicated that had the recommendations of this doctor been heeded, Gacy would have not been freed.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=368}}\n\nAt the close of his argument, Kunkle pulled each of the 22 photos of Gacy's identified victims off a board displaying the images and asked the jury not to show sympathy but to \"show justice\". Kunkle then asked the jury to \"show the same sympathy this man showed when he took these lives and put them ''there!''{{-\"}}{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=368}} before throwing the stack of photos into the opening of the trap door of Gacy's crawl space, which had been introduced as evidence and was on display in the courtroom. After Kunkle had finished his testimony, the jury retired to consider their verdict.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=369}}\n\nThe jury deliberated for less than two hours<ref>{{cite news|title=Gacy Sentenced to Die; Readies Appeals |date=March 14, 1980 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2209&dat=19800314&id=pp8rAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PPwFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2750,2719769 |newspaper=The Telegraph |access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> and found Gacy guilty of the thirty-three charges of murder for which he had been brought to trial; he was also found guilty of sexual assault and taking indecent liberties with a child; both convictions in reference to Robert Piest.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=369}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Court Refuses to Hear Mass Murderer Case |date=March 1, 1985 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=IbZBAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sKkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6852,3893550&dq/ |publisher=The Harlan Daily Enterprise |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> The conviction for 33 murders was then the largest number of murders charged to one individual in United States history.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the [[Sentence (law)|sentencing phase]] of the trial, the jury deliberated for more than two hours before sentencing Gacy to death.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=374}}<ref name=\"Rossi1980b\" /> Execution was initially set for June 2, 1980.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=387}}\n\n==Death row==\nUpon being sentenced, Gacy was transferred to the [[Menard Correctional Center]] in [[Chester, Illinois]], where he remained [[incarceration|incarcerated]] on death row for 14 years.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=388}}\n\nIsolated in his prison cell, Gacy began to paint. The subjects Gacy painted varied, although many were of clowns, some of which depicted himself as \"Pogo\". Many of his paintings have been displayed at exhibitions;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/north-america/usa/illinois/articles/the-controversy-of-killer-john-wayne-gacys-artwork/ |title=Controversy of Killer John Wayne Gacy's Artwork |publisher=theculturetrip.com |date=November 25, 2016 |access-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=CNN>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/US/05/13/serial.killer.art/|title=Controversial Serial Killer's Paintings go on Display in Las Vegas|work=CNN|access-date=May 15, 2011|date=May 13, 2011}}</ref> others have been sold at various auctions, with individual prices ranging between $200 and $20,000.<ref name=autogenerated1>Murder casebook number 11 {{ISSN|1364-5803}}, p. 36</ref> Although Gacy was permitted to earn money from the sale of his paintings until 1985, he claimed his artwork was intended \"to bring joy into people's lives\".{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=351}}\n\nOn February 15, 1983, Gacy was stabbed in the arm by Henry Brisbon, a fellow death row inmate known as the I-57 killer. At the time of this attack, Gacy had been participating in a voluntary work program when Brisbon ran towards him and stabbed him once in the upper arm with a sharpened wire. A second death row inmate injured in the attack, William Jones, received a [[surface anatomy|superficial]] stab wound to the head. Both received treatment in the prison hospital for their wounds.<ref>Koziol, Ronald (February 16, 1983). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1291&dat=19830216&id=Suo0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=T40DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6608,4021186 \"Gacy Stabbed in Prison\"]. ''[[Boca Raton News]]''. p 11A. Archived at Google News.</ref>\n\n===Appeals===\nAfter his incarceration, Gacy read numerous law books and filed voluminous motions and appeals, although he did not prevail in any. Gacy's appeals related to issues such as the validity of the first search warrant granted to Des Plaines police on December 13, 1978, and his objection to his lawyers' insanity plea defense at his trial.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=344}} Gacy also contended that, although he held \"some knowledge\" of five of the murders (those of McCoy, Butkovich, Godzik, Szyc and Piest),{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=347}} the other 28 murders had been committed by employees who were in possession of keys to his house while he was away on business trips.\n\nIn mid-1984, the [[Supreme Court of Illinois]] upheld Gacy's conviction and ordered that he be executed by lethal injection on November 14.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=351}} Gacy filed an appeal against this decision, which was denied by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] on March 4, 1985. The following year, Gacy filed a further post-conviction petition, seeking a new trial. His then-defense lawyer, [[Richard Kling]], argued that Gacy had been provided with ineffective legal counsel at his 1980 trial. This post-conviction petition was dismissed on September 11, 1986.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-09-12/news/8603080188_1_gacy-new-trial-illinois-supreme-court \"Mass Killer Gacy Denied New Trial\"]. ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. September 12, 1986.</ref>\n\nThe 1985 decision that he be executed was again appealed by Gacy, although his conviction was again upheld on September 29, 1988, with the Illinois Supreme Court setting a renewed execution date of January 11, 1989.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19880930&id=FKgeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=V84EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5611,6110201 \"Death Sentence Upheld for John Wayne Gacy\"]. ''[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]''. September 30, 1988 p A2. Archived at Google News.</ref>\n\nAfter Gacy's final appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court was denied in October 1993, the Illinois Supreme Court formally set an execution date for May 10, 1994.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1993-12-18/news/9312180642_1_gacy-john-wayne-supreme-court |title=Long-delayed Execution Set For John Wayne Gacy |newspaper=Orlando Sentinel |date=December 18, 1993 |access-date=December 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Execution===\n[[File:John Wayne Gacy certificate of death.jpg|upright=1|thumb|Gacy's certificate of death.]]\nOn the morning of May 9, 1994, Gacy was transferred from the Menard Correctional Center to [[Stateville Correctional Center]] in [[Crest Hill, Illinois|Crest Hill]] to be executed. That afternoon, he was allowed a private picnic on the prison grounds with his family. For his [[last meal]], Gacy ordered a bucket of Kentucky Fried Chicken, a dozen [[fried shrimp]], french fries, fresh strawberries, and a Diet Coke.<ref name=\"tw\">{{cite web|title=Last Meals|work=[[Tucson Weekly]]|first=John|last=Peck|date=January 5, 2006|url=http://www.tucsonweekly.com/tucson/last-meals/Content?oid=1082921|access-date=November 11, 2015}}</ref> That evening, he observed prayer with a [[Catholic priest]] before being escorted to the Stateville execution chamber to receive a lethal injection.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Susan|last1=Kuczka|first2=Rob|last2=Karwath|url=http://www.soci.niu.edu/~critcrim/dp/dpill/dpgacy1.txt|title=All Appeals Fail: Gacy is Executed. Serial Killer Dies of Lethal Injection|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=May 10, 1994|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612215340/http://www.soci.niu.edu/~critcrim/dp/dpill/dpgacy1.txt |archive-date=June 12, 2007}}</ref>\n\nBefore the execution began, the chemicals used to perform the execution unexpectedly solidified, clogging the [[IV tube]] administering the chemicals into Gacy's arm and complicating the execution procedure. Blinds covering the window through which witnesses observed the execution were drawn, and the execution team replaced the clogged tube to complete the procedure. After ten minutes, the blinds were reopened and the execution resumed. The entire procedure took 18 minutes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,980752,00.html |magazine=Time |date=May 23, 1994 |ref=seideman |title=A Twist Before Dying |last=Seideman |first=David |access-date=January 14, 2010}}</ref> [[Anesthesia|Anesthesiologists]] blamed the problem on the inexperience of prison officials who were conducting the execution, stating that had correct execution procedures been followed, the complications would never have occurred. This error apparently led to Illinois' subsequent adoption of an alternative method of lethal injection. On this subject, one of the prosecutors at Gacy's trial, William Kunkle, said: \"He got a much easier death than any of his victims.\"<ref name=\"Deseret\">{{cite news| title=Serial Killer Executed by Injection in Illinois| url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/352327/SERIAL-KILLER-EXECUTED-BY-INJECTION-IN-ILLINOIS.html/| newspaper=[[Deseret News]]| date=May 10, 1994| access-date=February 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to published reports, Gacy was a diagnosed [[psychopath]]<ref name=\"hare\">{{cite book|first=Robert D.|last=Hare|authorlink=Robert D. Hare|title=Without Conscience: The Disturbing World of the Psychopaths Among Us|publisher=[[Guilford Press]]|location=New York City|date=1999|page=[https://archive.org/details/withoutconscienc00hare/page/23 23]|isbn=978-1-57230-451-2|url=https://archive.org/details/withoutconscienc00hare/page/23}}</ref> who did not express any remorse for his crimes. His [[final statement]] to his lawyer before his execution was that killing him would not compensate for the loss of others, and that the state was murdering him.<ref name=\"Deseret\" /> His [[Last words|final spoken words]] were \"Kiss my ass.\"<ref name=\"CBSChicago\" />\n\nIn the hours leading up to Gacy's execution, a crowd estimated to number over 1,000<ref>{{cite journal |title=Murder In Mind |issue=11 |issn=1364-5803 |pages=36\u201337}}</ref> gathered outside the correctional center; the majority of whom were vocally in favor of the execution, although a number of [[Opposition to capital punishment in the United States|anti-death penalty]] protesters were also present. Some of those in favor of the execution wore T-shirts hearkening to Gacy's previous community services as a clown and bearing satirical slogans such as \"No tears for the clown\".<ref name=\"poster\">{{cite journal |journal=[[The Economist]] |title=Poster Child |date=May 14, 1994 |volume=331 |issue=7863}}</ref> The anti-death penalty protesters present observed a silent [[candlelight vigil]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/uncategorized/in-joliet-little-sympathy-for-convicted-killer/article_f7d646be-9c16-5bf1-853f-c845a302ef5b.html|title=In Joliet, Little Sympathy for Convicted Killer|access-date=July 22, 2017|newspaper=NWI Times|date=May 10, 1994}}</ref>\n\nAfter Gacy's death was confirmed at 12:58&nbsp;a.m. on May 10, 1994, his brain was removed. It is in the possession of [[Helen Morrison]], a witness for the defense at Gacy's trial,{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=354}} who has interviewed Gacy and other serial killers in an attempt to isolate common personality traits of violent [[antisocial personality disorder|sociopaths]]. His body was cremated after the execution.\n\nIn the months following Gacy's execution, many of his paintings were auctioned.<ref name=paintings /> Some were bought so that they could be destroyed in a June 1994 communal bonfire held in [[Naperville, Illinois]] and attended by approximately 300 people, including family members of nine of Gacy's victims.<ref name=paintings>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2004/06/06/State/Sale_of_Chicago_seria.shtml |title=Sale of Chicago Serial Killer's Art Draws Protests |newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]] |publisher=[[Times Publishing Company]]|location=St. Petersburg, Florida|date=June 6, 2004 |access-date=January 14, 2010 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\n\n===Identified victims===\nOnly 27 of Gacy's victims were ever conclusively identified. By the time of Gacy's trial, 22 victims had been identified. In March 1980, two further bodies unearthed from Gacy's crawl space were identified via dental and radiology records{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=248}} as those of Kenneth Parker and Michael Marino; both reported missing on October 25, 1976,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=L3cLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bVMDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5938,2528900&dq/|title=Gacy Victims Identified|date=March 31, 1980|publisher=Kingsman Daily Miner}}</ref> the day after they had disappeared.<ref name=\"StJoseph\" />\n\nIn May 1986, the ninth victim exhumed from Gacy's crawl space was identified as Timothy Jack McCoy, Gacy's first victim.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gacy Victim is Identified|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3iZTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sIIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2450,753399&dq/ |publisher=Mohave Daily Miner |date=May 8, 1986|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/identified7.html |title=\"Closed Cases\", Doe Network |publisher=Doenetwork.org |access-date=July 7, 2010}}</ref> Dental records and a belt buckle assisted the identification.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gacy's 1st Victim Finally Identified|date=May 10, 1986 |url=http://chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1986-05-10-8602020800-story.html |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=October 12, 2018}}</ref> One further victim was identified in November 2011 through [[DNA testing]] as William George Bundy, a 19-year-old construction worker who was last seen by his family on his way to a party on October 26, 1976.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-sheriff-gacy-victim-identified-through-dna-20111129,0,3315365.story \"Sheriff: Gacy victim identified through DNA\"], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', November 29, 2011</ref> Bundy had apparently worked for Gacy.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\" /> Shortly after Gacy's arrest, his family had contacted Bundy's dentist in the hope of submitting his dental records for comparison with the unidentified bodies. However, the records had been destroyed after the dentist had retired.<ref>[http://www.torontosun.com/2011/11/29/gacys-victim-19-identified-illinois-cops/ Toronto Sun] November 29, 2011</ref> A second victim was identified through DNA testing in July 2017 as a 16-year-old from [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]] named James Haakenson, who was last known to have contacted his family on August 5, 1976.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-john-wayne-gacy-victim-haakenson-20170719-story.html|title=Second Long-unknown Gacy Victim Identified as Boy from Minnesota|last=Crepeau|first=Megan|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=July 20, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Timothy Jack McCoy (16)<br />January 3, 1972<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/24901028.html?dids=24901028:24901028&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=May+10%2C+1986&author=Mitchell+Locin&pub=Chicago+Tribune|title=Chicago Tribune |publisher=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com |date=May 10, 1986 |access-date=July 7, 2010 | first=Mitchell | last=Locin}}</ref> Body 9. Crawl space.\n* John Butkovich (18)<br />July 31, 1975{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=126}} Body 2. Garage.\n* Darrell Julius Samson (18)<br />April 6, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=361\u2013362}} Body 29. Dining room.\n* Randall Wayne Reffett (15)<br />May 14, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=301}} Body 7. Crawl space.\n* Samuel G. Dodd Stapleton (14)<br />May 14, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=215}} Body 6. Crawl space.\n* Michael Bonnin (17)<br />June 3, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=301}} Body 18. Crawl space.\n* William Huey Carroll, Jr. (16)<br />June 13, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=303}} Body 22. Crawl space.\n* James Byron Haakenson (16)<br />August 5, 1976<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/timeline-john-wayne-gacys-case-48729716|title=Timeline of John Wayne Gacy Case|access-date=July 19, 2017|newspaper=ABC News|date=July 19, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720011748/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/timeline-john-wayne-gacys-case-48729716|archivedate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> Body 24. Crawl space.\n* Rick Louis Johnston (17)<br />August 6, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=215}} Body 23. Crawl space.\n{{col-break}}\n* Kenneth Ray Parker (16)<br />October 24, 1976{{sfn|Linedecker|1986|p=248}} Body 15. Crawl space.\n* Michael Marino (14)<br />October 24, 1976{{sfn|Linedecker|1986|p=248}} Body 14. Crawl space.\n* William George Bundy (19)<br />October 26, 1976<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cookcountysheriff.org/press_page/press_GacyVictimIdentified_11_29_2011.html|title=Cook County Sheriff Press \u2013 Unknown Victim of John Wayne Gacy is Identified|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223030827/http://www.cookcountysheriff.org/press_page/press_GacyVictimIdentified_11_29_2011.html|archivedate=February 23, 2015}}</ref> Body 19. Crawl space.\n* Gregory John Godzik (17)<br />December 12, 1976{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=54}} Body 4. Crawl space.\n* John Alan Szyc (19)<br />January 20, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=55}} Body 3. Crawl space.\n* Jon Steven Prestidge (20)<br />March 15, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=303}} Body 1. Crawl space.\n* Matthew Bowman (19)<br />July 5, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 8. Crawl space.\n* Robert Edward Gilroy, Jr. (18)<br />September 15, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 25. Crawl space.\n* John Antheney Mowery (19)<br />September 25, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 20. Crawl space.\n{{col-break}}\n* Russell Lloyd Nelson (21)<br />October 17, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 16. Crawl space.\n* Robert Winch (16)<br />November 10, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 11. Crawl space.\n* Tommy Joe Boling (20)<br />November 18, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=304}} Body 12. Crawl space.\n* David Paul Talsma (19)<br />December 9, 1977{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=305}} Body 17. Crawl space.\n* William Wayne Kindred (19)<br />February 16, 1978{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=141}} Body 27. Crawl space.\n* Timothy D. O'Rourke (20)<br />June 16\u201323, 1978{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|pp=219\u2013220}} Body 31. Des Plaines river.\n* Frank William Landingin (19)<br />November 4, 1978{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=220}} Body 32. Des Plaines river.\n* James Mazzara (20)<br />November 24, 1978{{sfn|Linedecker|1980|p=153}} Body 33. Des Plaines river.\n* Robert Jerome Piest (15)<br />December 11, 1978{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=7}} Body 30. Des Plaines river.\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Unidentified victims===\n[[File:Gacy victims.jpg|thumb|upright=1.85|Facial reconstructions of the unidentified victims, released to the [[News media|media]] in 1980. Depicted left to right are Body 5, Body 9 (later identified as Timothy McCoy), Body 24 (later identified as James Haakenson), Body 19 (later identified as William Bundy), Body 21, Body 28, Body 13, Body 26, and Body 10.]]\nSix victims remain unidentified, five of whom had been buried beneath Gacy's crawl space, with one additional youth buried approximately {{convert|15|ft}} from the barbecue pit in his backyard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_IgxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9qEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6913,2124365&dq/ |title=Another Skeleton Found at Home |access-date=February 14, 2017}}</ref> Experts used the skulls of the unidentified victims to create [[forensic facial reconstruction|facial reconstruction]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aboutforensics.co.uk/john-wayne-gacy/ |title=The Forensics Library: John Wayne Gacy |publisher=aboutforensics.co.uk |date=June 30, 2012 |access-date=February 14, 2017}}</ref> Based upon Gacy's confession, information relative to where the victims were buried in his crawl space relative to Gacy's identified victims, and forensic analysis, police were able to determine the most likely dates when his unidentified victims were killed.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1980/07/15/page/41/article/parents-is-your-missing-son-pictured-here | date=July 15, 1980 |title=Parents: Is Your Missing Son Pictured Here? |first=Jerry |last=Crimmins |newspaper=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n# [[circa|c]]. January 1974. Body 28. Backyard. Male aged 14\u201318.<ref name=\"Case File 954UMIL\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/11006|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 11006|publisher=}}</ref>\n# June 13 \u2013 August 5, 1976. Body 26. Crawl space. Male aged 23\u201330.<ref name=\"doenetwork1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/11004|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 11004|publisher=}}</ref>\n# August 6 \u2013 October 5, 1976. Body 13. Crawl space. Male aged 18\u201322.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/955umil.html |title=Case File 955UMIL |publisher=The Doe Network |access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/10999|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 10999|publisher=}}</ref>\n# August 6 \u2013 October 24, 1976. Body 21. Crawl space. Male aged 15\u201324.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/962umil.html |title=Case File 962UMIL |publisher=The Doe Network |access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/11000|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 11000|publisher=}}</ref>\n# December 1976 \u2013 March 15, 1977. Body 5. Crawl space. Male aged 22\u201332.<ref name=\"Case File 958UMIL\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/10994|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 10994|publisher=}}</ref>\n# March 15 \u2013 July 5, 1977. Body 10. Crawl space. Male aged 17\u201321.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/957umil.html |title=Case File 954UMIL |publisher=The Doe Network |access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/10998|title=NamUs \u2013 National Unidentified Persons Data System Case Report \u2013 10998|publisher=}}</ref>\n[[File:Body 10 and Body 13.jpg|thumb|2018 [[Forensic facial reconstruction|facial reconstructions]] of Body 10 (left) and Body 13.]]\nAn unidentified body found in the crawl space may also have been the first unidentified victim; Gacy's second victim. Gacy stated to investigators he had also been buried in the crawl space close to first victim (later identifed as McCoy). However, at his 1980 trial, prosecutor William Kunkle reasoned Gacy's second murder victim must have been the unidentified victim buried beneath his barbecue pit.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|p=274}} Statements made by Gacy following his arrest also leave a possibility the sixth unidentified victim may have been murdered as early as 1974.{{efn|His [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System|NamUs]] case report can be found [https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/10998 ''here''], and a [[facial composite]] can be seen [https://tribwgntv.files.wordpress.com/2018/07/john-doe-10.jpeg ''here'']}}\n\nIn October 2011, Cook County Sheriff [[Tom Dart|Thomas Dart]] announced that investigators, having obtained full DNA profiles from each of the unidentified victims, were to renew their efforts to identify all of them. At a press conference held to announce this intention, Sheriff Dart stated investigators are actively seeking DNA samples from individuals across the United States related to any male missing between 1970 and 1979.<ref name=\"CookCS\" /> Test results thus far conducted have confirmed the identification of two victims, ruled out the possibility of numerous other missing youths as being victims of Gacy,<ref>{{cite news |title=Sheriff: Solid Leads in Effort to ID Gacy Victims |first=Don |last=Babwin |date=October 17, 2011 |url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2011/10/17/sheriff_solid_leads_in_effort_to_id_gacy_victims |access-date=October 26, 2011 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2012/05/07/more-dna-being-analyzed-to-determine-ids-of-gacy-victims/ |title=More DNA Being Analyzed To Determine IDs Of Gacy Victims \u00ab CBS Chicago |publisher=Chicago.cbslocal.com |date=May 7, 2012 |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> and solved four unrelated [[cold case]]s dating between 1972 and 1979.<ref>{{cite news|author=|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/21/john-wayne-gacy-investigation_n_1904401.html/ |title=John Wayne Gacy Investigation Helps Solve Missing Daniel Noe Case |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=September 21, 2012 |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cookcountysheriff.org/press_page/press_%20ColdCaseSolved_09_23_2015.html|title=Cook County Sheriff Press \u2013 Sherifs's Gacy Investigation Solves 1979 Cold Case|publisher=|access-date=September 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927025637/http://www.cookcountysheriff.org/press_page/press_%20ColdCaseSolved_09_23_2015.html|archive-date=September 27, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865562848/Remains-found-in-Utah-identified-through-John-Wayne-Gacy-investigation.html |title=Remains Found in Utah Identified Through John Wayne Gacy Investigation |newspaper=deseretnews.com |date=September 20, 2012 |access-date=February 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Tribune\" />\n\n====Identification dispute of Michael Marino====\nDisputed [[DNA]] and dental tests conducted between 2012 and 2016 indicates that neither body found in the common grave in Gacy's crawl space and identified as those of Kenneth Parker and Michael Marino in 1980 was actually Marino.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/07/03/dna-test-gacy-victim-mother-marino/2486561/|title=DNA Test Revives Mystery of Killer Gacy's Victim No. 14 |access-date=October 9, 2018|newspaper=USA Today|date=July 5, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"alison1\">{{cite web|url=https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2016/03/31/new-dna-test-confirms-second-false-id-in-gacy-case/|title=BREAKING: New DNA Test Confirms Second False ID in Gacy Case|last=Alison|date=March 31, 2016|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211200055/https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2016/03/31/new-dna-test-confirms-second-false-id-in-gacy-case/|archivedate=December 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"cbslocal1\">{{cite web|url=http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2012/10/25/dna-backs-up-moms-doubt-gacy-victim-misidentified/ |title=DNA Backs Up Mom's Doubt: Gacy Victim Misidentified \u00ab CBS Chicago |publisher=Chicago.cbslocal.com |access-date=March 14, 2013|date=October 25, 2012 }}</ref> Marino's mother had always doubted the identification of her son because clothing found upon the body was inconsistent with what her son had worn when she last saw him. In addition, the [[dental radiography|dental X-ray]] conducted upon the victim identified as Michael Marino had revealed the victim had all of his [[second molar]]s, whereas a dental X-ray conducted upon Marino in March 1976 revealed one molar had not [[tooth eruption|erupted]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-10-07/news/ct-met-john-wayne-gacy-victim-20111007_1_dna-testing-exhumed-grave-site/ |title=Alleged Victim of John Wayne Gacy to be Exhumed|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=October 7, 2011 |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> The original identification of the body identified as Michael Marino has been disputed because neither an upper nor a lower jaw bone was present upon the exhumed body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/10/25/14705528-lawyers-dna-proves-john-wayne-gacy-victim-was-misidentified |title=Lawyers: DNA Proves John Wayne Gacy Victim was Misidentified \u2013 U.S. News |publisher=Usnews.nbcnews.com |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> Nonetheless, the [[orthodontist]] who had identified Marino's remains has stated his conviction in the accuracy of his findings, adding he had \"compared 32 teeth, probably half a dozen of them had very distinct [[tooth filling|fillings]] and every one of them was consistent with Michael Marino.\"{{efn| DNA testing conducted upon the exhumed body of Kenneth Parker has also proven that Marino's body had not been mistaken for Parker, and that they had not both been misidentified (Kenneth Parker's relatives refused to submit to DNA testing.)<ref name=\"alison1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-gacy-victim-20141130-story.html|title=Mother of Supposed John Wayne Gacy Victim Still Seeks Answers|first=Patrick M.|last=O'Connell|publisher=|date=November 30, 2014}}</ref>}}\n\n====Possible additional victims====\nAt the time of Gacy's arrest, he had claimed to both Des Plaines and Chicago investigators that the total number of victims he had killed could be as high as 45.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=196}} However, only 33 bodies were ever found which were linked to Gacy. Investigators did excavate the grounds of his property until they had exposed the [[Subsoil|substratum]] of clay beneath the foundations, yet only 29 bodies were found buried upon his property.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1982&dat=19790318&id=oHdGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RioNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2520,2232357|title=29 Murder Victims Found as Gacy Waits in Prison|access-date=February 15, 2017|newspaper=The Evening News|date=March 18, 1979}}</ref> When asked as to whether there were more victims, Gacy simply stated, \"That's for you guys to find out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagobreakingnews.com/2011-03-18/news/29143715_1_john-wayne-gacy-detective-probe |title=Retired Detective Wants Gacy Probe Reopened |publisher=chicagobreakingnews.com |date=March 18, 2011 |access-date=February 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 8, 1977, 24-year-old Charles Hattula was found drowned in a river near [[Freeport, Illinois]].<ref>Kozenczak (2012), p. 116</ref> Hattula, an employee of PDM, had been linked to the initial investigation of Gacy after Robert Piest's disappearance; this was after the same employee who had informed the investigators of Gregory Godzik's disappearance informed them of Hattula's death. Moreover, this employee had stated that Hattula was known to have conflicts with Gacy.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=99}} Gacy had himself informed several of his employees Hattula had drowned after Hattula's body was recovered from the [[Pecatonica River]]. Des Plaines authorities had contacted colleagues in Freeport during their investigation into Gacy, but were told Hattula  had fallen to his death from a bridge.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=124}} At the time of Hattula's death, Gacy had become engaged, and his fianc\u00e9e had moved into his home, which leaves a possibility that Gacy had disposed of Hattula's body in the Pecatonica River as opposed to burying the man in his crawl space. However, Hattula's death has been officially ruled as [[accidental death|accidental]].{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=124}}\n\nGacy stated that after he had assaulted and then released Jeffrey Rignall in March 1978, he had begun to throw his murder victims into the Des Plaines River. He confessed to having disposed of five bodies in this manner. However, only four bodies were recovered from the river. Given the gap of over four months between the dates of the murders of the first and second victims known to have been disposed in the river, it is possible that this unknown victim may have been killed between June and November 1978.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=220}}\n\nRetired Chicago police officer Bill Dorsch<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-03-30/news/chi-sheriff-wants-new-dig-for-gacy-victims-20120329_1_bill-dorsch-gacy-victims-west-miami-avenue/|title=Sheriff Barred from Digging for More Gacy Victims|publisher=}}</ref> has stated he has reason to believe there may be more victims buried within the grounds of the apartment building located at the 6100 block of West Miami Avenue in Chicago; a property which Gacy is known to have been the caretaker of for several years prior to his 1978 arrest. In 1975, Dorsch\u2014then a Chicago police officer\u2014observed Gacy (whom he knew on a casual basis), holding a shovel in the early hours of the morning. When confronted by Dorsch as to his actions, Gacy stated he was performing work that he was too busy to do during the day. Dorsch has also related that several other residents of West Miami Avenue have stated that, in the early- to mid-1970s, they had observed Gacy digging trenches in the grounds of the property;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/5/10/4315390/the-controversial-high-tech-search-for-john-wayne-gacy-lost-victims|title=Grave Mistake: The Controversial, High-tech Search for John Wayne Gacy's Lost Victims|first=Matt|last=Stroud|date=May 10, 2013|publisher=}}</ref> one of these residents has also stated that Gacy later placed plants in the elongated trenches he had dug. At the time these actions had been observed, Gacy had still been married to Carole Hoff.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police May Look for More Gacy Victims |date=November 12, 1998 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1893&dat=19981112&id=zJEkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w9wFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1375,1891358 |newspaper=The Southeast Missourian |access-date=November 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Cook County Sheriff's officials submitted a request to excavate the grounds of this property. The [[Cook County State's Attorney]] denied this request, stating a lack of [[probable cause]] as the reason the submission was denied (including the previous 1998 search).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-03-30/news/ct-met-gacy-dig-20120330_1_west-miami-avenue-john-wayne-gacy-gacy-investigation/ |title=Criminal Justice: Sheriff's Officials Seeking More Victims of Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy Want to Excavate Chicago Backyard. Chicago Tribune |publisher=Articles.chicagotribune.com |date=March 30, 2012 |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> However, the sheriff's office had noted that in 1998, a radar survey conducted had noted 14 areas of interest within the property grounds, yet only two of these 14 anomalies had been excavated. Of the 12 remaining anomalies which police had not examined in greater detail on that occasion, four were described as being \"staggeringly suggestive\" as human skeletons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tracy-ullman-felshman/john-wayne-gacy-search_b_2569172.html/ |title=Tracy Ullman Felshman: To Parents of the Missing in Chicago: A Note About John Wayne Gacy |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |access-date=March 14, 2013 |date=February 1, 2013}}</ref> Moreover, Bill Dorsch had provided police with a letter from the radar company which confirmed the 1998 search of the grounds was incomplete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-03-30/news/chi-sheriff-wants-new-dig-for-gacy-victims-20120329_1_bill-dorsch-gacy-victims-west-miami-avenue|title=Sheriff Barred from Digging for More Gacy Victims|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nA second request to excavate the grounds of West Miami Avenue was submitted to the Cook County State's Attorney by Sheriff Tom Dart in October 2012. This request was granted in January 2013, and a search of the property was conducted in the spring. Both FBI [[Detection dog|sniffer dogs]] and ground-penetrating radar equipment were used in the second search of West Miami Avenue; however, the search yielded no human remains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timescolonist.com/opinion/search-of-killer-john-wayne-gacy-s-mother-s-home-fruitless-county-sheriff-to-keep-hunting-1.109486|title=Search of Killer John Wayne Gacy's Mother's Home Fruitless; County Sheriff to Keep Hunting|first=The Associated|last=Press|publisher=}}</ref>{{efn|Some parties have questioned the [[integrity]] and thoroughness of the second search conducted of West Miami Avenue;<ref name=\"alison2\">{{cite web|url=https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2013/04/15/something-stinks/|title=Something Stinks|last=Alison|date=April 15, 2013|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211202539/https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2013/04/15/something-stinks/|archivedate=December 11, 2016}}</ref> citing the fact the ground of the property was still frozen on the date of the search (March 20), that the press had not been informed that the property had been searched until 6 days after the search had been conducted, and that the sniffer dogs used had solely been provided [[core sample]]s of soil to test.}}\n\n==Inspiration for the Missing Child Recovery Act of 1984==\nIn 1984, Sam Amirante, one of Gacy's two defense attorneys at his 1980 trial, authored procedures that were incorporated by the [[Illinois General Assembly]] into the Missing Child Recovery Act of 1984. Amirante has since stated that the primary inspiration for this legislation was the fact that at the time of the Gacy murders, there had been a 72-hour period which police in Illinois had to allow to elapse before initiating a search for a missing child or adolescent.{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|page= 395}}\n\nThe Illinois Missing Child Recovery Act of 1984 removed this 72-hour waiting period. Other states across America subsequently adopted similar procedures and sensibilities, as a result of which a national network aimed at locating missing children was gradually formed. This national network has since developed into the Child Abduction Emergency\u2014commonly known today as an [[Amber Alert]].{{sfn|Amirante|Broderick|2011|page= 395}}\n\n==Potential accomplices and connections==\nOne of the first things Gacy told investigators after his arrest was that he had not acted alone in several of the murders: he asked whether \"my associates\" had also been arrested.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=171}} When questioned as to whether these associates had participated directly or indirectly in the killings, Gacy replied, \"Directly.\"{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=171}}\n\nGacy specifically named Cram and Rossi as being involved in several of the murders.{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=171}} In the 1980s, he also informed [[Robert Ressler]] that \"two or three\" PDM employees had assisted him in several murders.<ref>Whoever Fights Monsters {{ISBN|0-671-71561-5}} pp 341\u2013342</ref> Ressler replied that he believed there were unexplained avenues to the case and stated his belief that Gacy had killed more than 33 victims. Gacy neither confirmed nor denied Ressler's suspicions.<ref>Whoever Fights Monsters {{ISBN|0-671-71561-5}} p 342</ref>{{efn|Gacy is known to have given Ressler a painting with a written inscription reading: \"Dear Bob Ressler, You cannot hope to enjoy the harvest, without first laboring in the fields\".<ref>Whoever Fights Monsters {{ISBN|0-671-71561-5}} p 343</ref>}}\n\nJeffrey Rignall, who had been assaulted and tortured by Gacy in March 1978, was adamant that at one point during his abuse and torture, a young man with brown hair, kneeling before him, watched his abuse.{{sfn|Cahill|1986|p=209}} Rignall also said that as Gacy was assaulting him he saw a light switch on in another part of the house.<ref name=\"google2963\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19790101&id=PEEsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=v80EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2963,232748|title=Search of Gacy Home to Resume|date=January 2, 1979|publisher=Spartanburg Herald-Journal}}</ref>\n\nMoreover, on one occasion during the surveillance of Gacy prior to his arrest, two officers followed him to a bar to which Gacy had driven to meet two of his employees. At the bar, the officers overheard a hushed conversation between Gacy and one of his employees in which the employee asked Gacy, \"And what? Buried like the other five?\"{{sfn|Sullivan|Maiken|2000|p=102}}\n\nIn interviews following his arrest and conviction, Gacy repeatedly claimed that he was not present in Chicago when 16 of the identified victims had disappeared. In one interview, he stated that at the time of his arrest, four PDM employees were also considered suspects in the disappearances of the missing boys investigators had linked to Gacy\u2014all of whom he stated were in possession of keys to his house.<ref>Whoever Fights Monsters {{ISBN|0-671-71561-5}} pp=341\u2013342</ref> One of these employees was Philip Paske, a young man who is known to have been a close associate of John Norman. At the time, Norman operated a nationwide [[sex trafficking]] ring based in Chicago.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago is Center of National Child Pornography Ring|date=May 16, 1977 |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1977/05/16/page/1/article/chicago-is-center-of-national-child-porno-ring |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref> At least two victims believed to have been murdered by Gacy, Kenneth Parker and Michael Marino, are known to have last been seen alive close to where Norman resided at the time of their disappearance, and Gacy is known to have been aware of Paske's connections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2016/06/20/child-sex-trafficking-in-chicago-the-missing-link-in-the-gacy-mystery/|title=Child Sex Trafficking in Chicago: The Missing Link in the Gacy Mystery|last=Alison|date=June 20, 2016|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827120623/https://johnwaynegacynews.com/2016/06/20/child-sex-trafficking-in-chicago-the-missing-link-in-the-gacy-mystery/|archivedate=August 27, 2016}}</ref> This led to the theory Gacy may have been connected to this trafficking ring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wgntv.com/2016/06/21/what-really-happened-to-michael-marino-investigation-begins/|title=What Really Happened to Michael Marino? Investigation Begins|date=June 22, 2016|website=WGN-TV|access-date=June 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Later investigations===\nIn 2012, two Chicago lawyers<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beckerstephenson.com |title=Beckerstephenson.com |publisher=Beckerstephenson.com |date=January 1, 2009 |access-date=March 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508182752/http://www.beckerstephenson.com/ |archivedate=May 8, 2013 |df= }}</ref> claimed that travel records show that Gacy had been in another state at the time of three of the murders, implying he was assisted by one or more accomplices.<ref name=\"gacyaccomplices\">{{cite news |first=Frank|last=Main|url=http://southtownstar.suntimes.com/news/10545326-418/lawyers-suggest-gacy-had-accomplices.html |title=Lawyers Contend Gacy Had Help in Some Killings|publisher=Southtown Star |date=February 9, 2012|accessdate=March 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824085509/http://southtownstar.suntimes.com/news/10545326-418/lawyers-suggest-gacy-had-accomplices.html |archivedate=August 24, 2013 |df= }}</ref> For example, Gacy had flown to Pittsburgh three days before the disappearance of Robert Gilroy, and only returned to Chicago the day after the youth disappeared.<ref name=\"gacyaccomplices\" />\n\nInvestigators also note that Robert Young, the traveling companion with whom victim Russell Nelson was visiting Chicago at the time of his disappearance in October 1977, gave differing accounts of Nelson disappearance to both Nelson's family and investigators. To Nelson's family, Young had stated Nelson failed to arrive at a bar at a prearranged time; to investigators, Young claimed he had last seen Nelson standing among a crowd who had gathered outside a Chicago bar and when his attention was diverted for a few moments, Nelson simply disappeared. Investigators contend this could not have happened without his traveling companion noticing.<ref name=\"twincities1\">{{cite news|title=Another of John Wayne Gacy's Victims: A 22-year-old UMN Student |date=July 19, 2017 |url=https://www.twincities.com/2017/07/19/another-of-john-wayne-gacys-victims-a-22-year-old-umn-student/ |accessdate=February 3, 2019|publisher=Pioneer Press}}</ref>\n\nYoung is known to have filed a missing person's report with Chicago police, before unsuccessfully requesting money from Nelson's parents to finance a search for their son. When Nelson's two brothers arrived in Chicago to search for him, Young had offered both brothers a job with Gacy's construction company.<ref name=\"gacyaccomplices\" /> Young was never summoned to testify at Gacy's trial as to the circumstances surrounding Nelson's disappearance.<ref name=\"twincities1\"/>\n\nIn a third case, travel records indicate Gacy was at a scheduled job site in Michigan at 6:00&nbsp;a.m. on September 26, 1977\u2014the day following the disappearance of 19-year-old John Mowery, who was last seen leaving his mother's house at 10:00&nbsp;p.m. on September 25.<ref name=\"gacyaccomplices\" /> Mowery's roommate was a PDM employee who had formerly lived with Gacy and had moved into Mowery's apartment less than one week before Mowery's disappearance. Two witnesses have stated that this roommate had recommended to Mowery that he meet \"a man who is going out of town\" two days before Mowery disappeared.<ref name=\"google2963\" />\n\nCriminal defense attorneys and investigators researching the possibility Gacy had not acted alone in several of the murders have stated there is \"overwhelming evidence Gacy worked with an accomplice\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1N1-13CF85F3996A5130.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213164552/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1N1-13CF85F3996A5130.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 13, 2017 |title=Did Gacy Have Help? |publisher=highbeam.com |date=February 17, 2012 |access-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE SOUTH PARK OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n===Film===\n* The made-for-TV film ''[[To Catch a Killer]]'', starring [[Brian Dennehy]] as Gacy, was released in 1992. The film is largely based on the investigation of Gacy, following the disappearance of Robert Piest, by Des Plaines Police and their efforts to arrest him before the scheduled civil suit hearing on December 22.\n* A feature film, ''[[Gacy (film)|Gacy]]'', was released in 2003. This film cast [[Mark Holton]] in the role of Gacy and depicts Gacy's life after he moved to Norwood Park in 1971 up until his arrest in 1978.\n* The made-for-TV film ''[[Dear Mr. Gacy]]'', released in 2010, stars [[William Forsythe (actor)|William Forsythe]] as Gacy. The film is based upon the book ''[[The Last Victim]]'', written by [[Jason Moss (writer)|Jason Moss]].{{sfn|Moss|Kottler|1999}} The film focuses upon the correspondence between Moss and Gacy before Gacy invited Moss to visit him on death row in 1994.\n* The horror film ''[[8213: Gacy House]]'' was released in 2010 and is based upon paranormal investigators spending a night in the house built on the former site of 8213 Summerdale Terrace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1667418/|title=8213: Gacy House|date=September 28, 2010|publisher=|via=IMDb}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n* ''29 Below'', by Jeffrey Rignall and Ron Wilder (ISBN B0006XG56Y).\n* ''A Question of Doubt: The John Wayne Gacy Story'', by John Wayne Gacy ({{ISBN|1-87886-503-X}}).\n* ''Buried Dreams: Inside the Mind of Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy'', by [[Tim Cahill (writer)|Tim Cahill]] ({{ISBN|1-85702-084-7}}).\n* ''John Wayne Gacy: Defending a Monster'', by Sam L. Amirante and Danny Broderick ({{ISBN|1-616-08248-8}}).\n* ''Johnny and Me: The True Story of John Wayne Gacy'', by Barry Boschelli ({{ISBN|1-4343-2184-3}}).<ref>{{cite web|last=Creepy |first=Uncle |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/41399/barry-boschelli-talks-growing-evil-john-wayne-gacy |title=Barry Boschelli Talks Growing Up with Evil \u2013 John Wayne Gacy |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date=December 10, 2010 |access-date=March 14, 2013}}</ref>\n* ''Killer Clown: The John Wayne Gacy Murders'', by Terry Sullivan and Peter T. Maiken ({{ISBN|0-7860-1422-9}}).\n* ''Killer Clown: The True Story of John Wayne Gacy'', by Aimee Baxter ({{ISBN|978-1-973-75535-7}}).\n* ''The Chicago Killer'', by Joseph R. Kozenczak and Karen M. Kozenczak ({{ISBN|978-1401095314}}).\n* ''The Last Victim: A True-Life Journey into the Mind of the Serial Killer'', by Jason Moss and Jeffrey Kottler, Ph.D ({{ISBN|0-7535-0398-0}}).\n* ''The Man Who Killed Boys'', by Clifford L. Linedecker ({{ISBN|0-312-95228-7}}).\n* ''Unfinished Nightmare: The Search for More Victims of Serial Killer John Wayne Gacy'', by Chris Maloney ({{ISBN|978-1466080317}}).\n* ''Destination Gacy: A Cross-Country Journey to Shake the Devil's Hand'', by [[Nancy Rommelmann]] ({{ISBN|978-1940838380}}).\n\n===Television===\n* The [[Discovery Channel]] has broadcast an episode relating to Gacy's crimes within the true crime series ''[[The New Detectives|The New Detectives: Case Studies in Forensic Science]]''. This documentary features an interview between Gacy and FBI profiler Robert Ressler, whom Gacy claimed to have known when both he and Ressler were children. (As a child, Ressler had lived just four blocks from Gacy in Chicago and Gacy had delivered groceries to Ressler's family.)\n* The [[Investigation Discovery]] channel has broadcast two documentaries about the Gacy murders. The first documentary focusing upon Gacy's crimes was commissioned for the ''[[Most Evil]]'' series, a forensics program in which [[forensic psychiatrist]] Michael Stone analyzes various murderers and psychopaths. The second Investigation Discovery program on Gacy is featured in the ''Evil Lives Here'' series. This program explores how Gacy's actions affected his family. Gacy's sister and niece are among those interviewed.\n* The [[Biography Channel]] has broadcast a 45-minute documentary on the crimes of John Wayne Gacy.\n* The television program, ''Psychic Investigators'', has broadcast an episode entitled \"What Lies Below\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/z2hr/psychic-investigators--s3-e3-what-lies-below |title=Psychic Investigators S3-E3: What Lies Below |publisher=radiotimes.com |date=July 25, 2009 |access-date=February 14, 2017}}</ref> This program focuses upon the consultation between Detective Joseph Kozenczak and [[psychic]] Carol Broman, whom Kozenczak had met on December 17, 1978 to discuss the whereabouts of the body of Robert Piest.<ref>Kozenczak (2012), pp. 104\u2013105</ref>\n* The [[Lifetime Movies]] network series ''[[Monster in My Family]]'' has broadcast a 42-minute episode focusing on the murders committed by Gacy. This episode, titled \"Killer Clown: John Wayne Gacy\", was initially broadcast in August 2015. The episode features Karen Kuzma, the sister of John Wayne Gacy, and her daughter, and focuses upon formative events in Gacy's life that may have initiated his later crimes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch Killer Clown: John Wayne Gacy Full Episode \u2013 Monster in My Family {{!}} Lifetime|url=http://www.mylifetime.com/shows/monster-in-my-family/season-1/episode-6|website=mylifetime.com|publisher=Lifetime Movies|accessdate=November 9, 2017|language=en|date=August 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Monster in My Family {{!}} Season 1, Episode 6 Killer Clown: John Wayne Gacy|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/monster-in-my-family/episode-6-season-1/killer-clown-john-wayne-gacy/816193/|website=TVGuide.com|publisher=CBS Interactive Inc.|accessdate=November 9, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE THE SIMPSONS OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of people executed in Illinois]]\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n* [[List of unidentified murder victims in the United States]]\n* [[Most prolific murderers by number of victims]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|20em\n| refs =\n\n{{cite news\n| title = Gacy Victim Is Identified\n| date = May 8, 1986\n| newspaper = Mohave Daily Miner\n| agency = UPI\n| page = 5\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QggPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sIIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2452,753401\n| access-date = July 20, 2010\n}}\n\n<ref name=\"SHJ-3morebodies\">\n{{cite news\n| title = 3 More Bodies Are Found At Home\n| date = December 24, 1978\n| newspaper = Spartanburg Herald-Journal\n| agency = AP\n| page = 1\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lYUsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0M0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3744,5182626\n| access-date = July 20, 2010\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<!-- <ref name=\"Rossi1980a\">\n{{cite news\n| last = Rossi\n| first = Rosalind\n| title = Mothers Tell Gacy Jury Of Last Time They Saw Sons\n| date = February 8, 1980\n| newspaper = Sarasota Herald-Tribune\n| agency = UPI\n| page = 6\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Zk80AAAAIBAJ&sjid=zWcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6679,3103134&\n| access-date = July 20, 2010\n}}\n</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=\"Rossi1980b\">\n{{cite news\n| last = Rossi\n| first = Rosalind\n| title = Gacy Sentenced To Die For 33 Deaths\n| date = March 14, 1980\n| newspaper = Sarasota Herald-Tribune\n| agency = UPI\n| page = 7\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZLYcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zmcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5140,7396894\n| access-date = July 20, 2010\n}}\