{"title_page": "2010 Commonwealth Games opening ceremony", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox news event\n| title         = 2010 Commonwealth Games<br />opening ceremony\n| image_name    = File:Commonwealth-Games-2010-Opening-Ceremony.jpg \n| caption       = Performance of \"[[Jiyo Utho Bado Jeeto]]\", official song of the games\n| date          = {{start date|2010|10|03|df=y}}\n| time          = 19:00 \u2013 22:00 [[Indian Standard Time|IST]] \n| place         = [[Delhi]], [[India]]\n| coordinates   =  {{coord|28|34|58|N|77|14|4|E|display=it}}\n| also known as = \n| filmed by     = [[Doordarshan|DD]]\n| participants  = \n| awards        = \n| url           =[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JuUR8lR50Yk&t=12146s Youtube]  \n}}\n{{2010 Commonwealth Games}}\n\nThe '''opening ceremony''' of the '''[[2010 Commonwealth Games]]''' was held at the [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Delhi|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium]], the main stadium of the event, in [[New Delhi]], India. It began at 7:00 PM ([[Indian Standard Time|IST]]) on 3 October 2010 ending at 10:00 PM (IST) displaying India's varied culture in a plethora of cultural showcases. Wizcraft was given the contract to produce the opening and closing ceremonies of the 2010 Commonwealth Games.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/special-report/wizcraft-puts-together-the-cwg-inaugural-event/articleshow/6674821.cms|title=Wizcraft puts together the CWG inaugural event|last=Molekhi|first=Pankaj|date=3 October 2010|work=The Economic Times|access-date=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Guests of Honour==\n[[File:Pratibha Devisingh Patil, the former President of India, Dr. A.P.J. Abdul Kalam, the Prince of Wales, Prince Charles, his wife Duchess of Cornwall Camilla Parker, the Prime Minister, Dr. Manmohan Singh.jpg|thumb|The Dignitaries at the opening ceremony]]\n\nThe following were the guests that attended the opening ceremony of the 2010 Commonwealth Games:{{div col}}\n* {{Flagicon|UK}} [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], representing [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/sports/prince-charles-arrives-in-india-for-xix-commonwealth-games-2010-delhi|title=Prince Charles arrives in India for XIX Commonwealth Games 2010 Delhi|date=2 October 2010|access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon|UK}} [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]]\n* {{Flagicon|India}} [[Pratibha Patil]] \u2013 President of [[India]]<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|author=ANTHONY HUBBARD \u2013 Sunday Star Times |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sunday-star-times/features/4189179/At-Her-Majestys-service |title=At Her Majesty's service |publisher=Stuff.co.nz |accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon|India}} [[Devisingh Shekhawat]] \u2013 First Gentleman of [[India]]\n* {{Flagicon|India}} [[Manmohan Singh]] \u2013 Prime Minister of India<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dilipkumar.in/articles/india/mind-blowing-opening-ceremony.html|title=2010 CommonWealth Games Opening Ceremony \u2013 What a Show \u2013 Mind Blasting I Say!!! \u00ab www.dilipkumar.in|website=dilipkumar.in|access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon|India}} [[Gursharan Kaur]] \u2013 Spouse of the Prime Minister of India\n* {{Flagicon|CGF}} Michael Fennell \u2013 President of the [[Commonwealth Games Federation]]\n* {{Flagicon|Maldives}} [[Mohamed Nasheed]] \u2013 President of the [[Maldives]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sports.rediff.com/report/2010/oct/04/ceg-2010-delhi-cwg-critics-failed-to-judge-new-india-nasheed.htm|title=CWG critics failed to judge new India: Nasheed \u2013 Rediff.com Sports|website=sports.rediff.com|access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon|Nauru}} [[Marcus Stephen]] \u2013 President of [[Nauru]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/story/games-all-set-for-a-gala-opening-on-sunday-83067-2010-10-02|title=Games all set for a gala opening on Sunday|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref> \n* {{Flagicon|Monaco}} [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco|Albert II]] \u2013 Prince of [[Monaco]]\n* {{Flagicon|New Zealand}} [[Anand Satyanand|Sir Anand Satyanand]] \u2013  Governor General of [[New Zealand]]<ref name=\":1\" />\n* {{Flagicon|India}} [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]] \u2013 Former President of India\n* {{Flagicon|India}} [[Sonia Gandhi]] \u2013  Chairperson of National Advisory Council\n* {{Flagicon|Commonwealth of Nations}} [[Kamalesh Sharma]] \u2013 Secretary General of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]]\n* {{Flagicon|IOC}} [[Jacques Rogge]] \u2013 President of the [[International Olympic Committee]]<ref name=\":2\" />\n* {{Flagicon|India}} [[Sheila Dikshit]] \u2013 Chief Minister of [[Delhi]]\n* {{Flagicon|India}} [[Arjan Singh]] \u2013 Marshal of [[Indian Air Force]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== The Royal Family ===\n[[Charles, Prince of Wales]] (representing [[Elizabeth II]] as [[Head of the Commonwealth]]) and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] attended the ceremony.\n\n=== International Guests ===\nA total of three [[heads of state]] from outside India attended the opening ceremony; two from [[List of members of the Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth nations]] and one from a non-Commonwealth nation. The three head of states are [[Mohamed Nasheed]], [[President of the Maldives]], [[Marcus Stephen]], [[President of Nauru]] and a multiple Commonwealth gold medallist, and [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco]], a former Olympian, whose country Monaco is not a member of the Commonwealth.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Four heads of state to attend CWG opener | url =http://www.ndtv.com/article/commonwealth%20games/four-heads-of-state-to-attend-cwg-opener-56334 |date = 1 October 2010 | publisher = [[NDTV]] | location = New Delhi | accessdate = 2 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101005015417/http://www.ndtv.com/article/commonwealth%20games/four-heads-of-state-to-attend-cwg-opener-56334| archivedate= 5 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[Anand Satyanand|Sir Anand Satyanand]], the [[Governor General of New Zealand]] (the first of Indian descent), attended the ceremony as well.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=Biography of The Right Honourable Sir Anand Satyanand |url=http://www.gov-gen.govt.nz/the-governor-general/biogg |publisher=[[Government of New Zealand]] |format=biography |accessdate=4 October 2010  |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100602152957/http://www.gov-gen.govt.nz/the-governor-general/biogg |archivedate=2 June 2010  }}</ref>\n\nAlongside the Commonwealth president, attendees included [[International Olympic Committee]] president, [[Jacques Rogge]]. He was quoted as saying, \"I think India has set a good foundation stone for the Olympics bid and a successful Commonwealth Games can help India mount a serious bid for the Olympics.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news | title = Games good foundation for Olympic bid by India: Rogge | url =http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/cwgarticleshow/6680736.cms |date = 4 October 2010 | work = [[Times of India]] | location = New Delhi | accessdate = 4 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Programme==\n[[File:A drummer performs at the opening ceremony of the 19th Commonwealth Games Delhi-2010, in New Delhi on October 03, 2010.jpg|left|thumb|A drummer performs at the opening ceremony]]\nThe opening ceremony featured aspects of India's heritage and culture in seven segments. It featured an [[aerostat]] costing U$8 million,<ref>{{cite news|last=Beckett |first=Paul |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2010/10/04/the-aerostat-tech-marvel-or-stage-prop/ |title=The Aerostat: Tech Marvel or Stage Prop? \u2013 India Real Time \u2013 WSJ |publisher=Blogs.wsj.com |date=4 October 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101006211900/https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2010/10/04/the-aerostat-tech-marvel-or-stage-prop/| archivedate= 6 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> measuring 40\u00d780x12 meters and manufactured in [[Oswestry]], [[England]].<ref name=\"hindustantimes1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Controversy-hit-aerostat-lights-up-Games-ceremony/Article1-607895.aspx |title=Controversy-hit aerostat lights up Games ceremony |work=Hindustan Times|date=4 October 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101006024138/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Controversy-hit-aerostat-lights-up-Games-ceremony/Article1-607895.aspx| archivedate= 6 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The original plan was to have drummers on the aerostat, but the plan was cancelled.<ref name=\"hindustantimes1\"/> The ceremony started with the [[Indian national anthem]] which was played live at the stadium. The roof of the stadium turned into orange colour and the ground was lit up with three colours of the Indian flag \u2013 orange in the center, white in the middle and green near the boundary.\n\n===Rhythm of India===\n[[File:Giant Puppets hang from the aerostat during the opening ceremony of the 19th Commonwealth Games Delhi-2010, in New Delhi on October 03, 2010 (2).jpg|thumb|Giant Puppets hang from the aerostat]]\nThe countdown for the opening of commonwealth games started as the drums were being played, and fireworks exploded from the roof of the stadium. The aerostat slowly raised from the ground to the center space of the roof while a traditional [[Rajasthani culture|Rajasthani]] hymn was being played by the musicians. Various Drummers from [[Kerala]], [[Manipur]], [[Karnataka]], [[Orissa, India|Orissa]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] and [[Meghalaya]] played a symphony that aimed to be \"uniquely Indian in character, yet global in appeal\". Seven year old [[tabla]] player Keshav from Puducherry played the tabla instrument in front of the audience live and he was given a big applause from the audience.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/Child-prodigy-delights-spectators/article15771941.ece|title=Child prodigy delights spectators|last=Sarkar|first=Urvashi|date=4 October 2010|work=The Hindu|access-date=18 October 2018|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n===Swagatham===\n[[File:Commonwealth games Delhi 2010 opening ceremony swagatham mehndi.png|thumb|School children from across delhi performed in this segment,intricate mehndi design was painted on large pieces of cloth in 30 seconds.|alt=|left]]\n[[Hariharan (singer)|Hariharan]] led this segment, which created an amalgamation of Hindustani classical, Carnatic and folk music. The song was composed by [[A. R. Rahman]], who also composed the [[Jiyo Utho Bado Jeeto|official theme song]] of the games, and was performed by various artists along with Hariharan. Children from various Delhi schools participated in a simultaneous performance forming hands of an Indian woman in a pose of [[Namaste]] \u2013 a popular Indian salutation. Later, they separated and rearranged themselves in another formation representing the Indian flag colors of saffron, white and green while another group of children entered the stadium and covered the flag formations with a large white cloth. In a widely appreciated act, the children then made a [[mehndi]] \u2013 a traditional Indian art \u2013 on this large white piece of cloth in under 30 seconds on the spot.[http://www.blog.shopedude.com Latest News Updates]\n\n===Tree of Knowledge===\n\nPt. [[Birju Maharaj]] ([[Kathak]]), Guru [[Rajkumar Singhajit Singh]]-Charu Sija Mathur ([[Manipuri dance|Manipuri]]), Dr. [[Saroja Vaidyanathan]] ([[Bharatnatyam]]), Dr. [[Sonal Mansingh]] ([[Odissi dance|Odissi]]), [[Bharati Shivaji]] ([[Mohiniattam]]) and Raja Reddy-Radha Reddy ([[Kuchipudi]]) choreographed 480 dancers bringing alive India's \"Guru-Shishya Parampara\" or the master-protege tradition on stage through classical dance recitals which also depicted four different [[Indian season|seasons of India]]. The aerostat (the largest ever helium balloon built for such an event) formed the leaves of the Bodhi tree, while large strips elevated from the ground, made of silk and bamboo fibre form the tree trunk.\n\n===The Great Indian Journey===\n[[File:A spectacular view of Jawahar Lal Nehru stadium during the opening ceremony of the 19th Commonwealth Games 2010-Delhi, in New Delhi on October 03, 2010 (1).jpg|thumb|Dancers from all the states of India performed at the ceremony]]\nThis segment will give a glimpse of the lives of the masses in India, as seen through a train window. Art director Omung Kumar created a 600-ft train of bamboo sticks for this. It portrayed a common man's life and every thing in it, such as the bangle shops, politicians campaigning, Bollywood, the cycle shop etc.\n\n===Finale===\n[[Academy Awards|Academy]] and [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] award winner [[A.R. Rahman]] ended the programme with his rendition of \"[[Jiyo Utho Bado Jeeto]]\", the theme song of the Delhi games, and \"[[Jai Ho (song)|Jai Ho]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C_dTKoii85I |title=commonwealth games 2010 opening ceremony A.R.Rahman |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=14 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101007114829/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C_dTKoii85I| archivedate= 7 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/A-R-Rahmans-grand-finale-with-Jeeyo-Utho/articleshow/6679650.cms|title=A R Rahman's grand finale with 'Jeeyo, Utho'|work=Times of India|accessdate=3 October 2010|date=3 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sify.com/news/rahman-brings-cwg-ceremony-to-electrifying-climax-news-national-kkdx4ccdbib.html|title=Rahman brings CWG ceremony to electrifying climax|publisher=[[Sify]]|accessdate=3 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101006052925/http://sify.com/news/rahman-brings-cwg-ceremony-to-electrifying-climax-news-national-kkdx4ccdbib.html| archivedate= 6 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:The Artistes performing cultural programme at the opening ceremony of the 19th Commonwealth Games 2010-Delhi, at Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, in New Delhi on October 03, 2010.jpg|Artistes showcasing [[Flag of India|Indian flag]] at the opening ceremony\nFile:Master Keshava a seven year old Prodigy from Puducherry plays the tabla at the opening ceremony of the 19th Commonwealth Games 2010-Delhi, at Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, in New Delhi on October 03, 2010.jpg|Master Keshava a seven-year old Prodigy from Puducherry plays the tabla at the opening ceremony\nFile:The Prime Minister Dr. Manmohan Singh addressing at the opening ceremony of the 19th Commonwealth Games 2010-Delhi, at Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, in New Delhi on October 03, 2010 (1).jpg|The Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh|Dr. Manmohan Singh]] addressing at the opening ceremony\nFile:The Prince of Wales, Prince Charles reads out the message of Queen Elizabeth on her behalf during the opening ceremony of the 19th Commonwealth Games 2010-Delhi, at Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, in New Delhi on October 03, 2010.jpg|[[Charles, Prince of Wales]] reads out the message of [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth]] on her behalf during the opening ceremony\nFile:Shri Sushil Kumar, Wrestler the gold medalist, Moscow World Wrestling Championship holding the Queen's Baton, 19th Commonwealth Games Delhi 2010.jpg|[[Sushil Kumar (wrestler)|Sushil Kumar]], Wrestler holding the [[Queen's Baton Relay|Queen's Baton]]\nFile:The President Pratibha Patil declares the Games open, during the opening ceremony of the 19th Commonwealth Games 2010-Delhi, at Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, in New Delhi on October 03, 2010.jpg|President [[Pratibha Patil]] declares the Games open\nFile:The Oscar winning music composer A.R. Rehman performs during the opening ceremony of the 19th Commonwealth Games 2010-Delhi, at Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, in New Delhi on October 03, 2010.jpg|Music composer [[A. R. Rahman|A.R. Rehman]] performs during the opening ceremony \n</gallery>\n\n== List of national flag bearers ==\nAustralia entered first as the host of [[2006 Commonwealth Games|the last games]], and India entered last as the host. Excluding these two nations, the flag bearers entered by alphabetical order of their nations; Anguilla was the first (after Australia) and Zambia was the last (before India). Each flag bearer was preceded by a woman in traditional Indian dress, each reflecting a different part of the country, carrying a placard with the country's name.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Order\n!Nation\n!Flag bearer\n!Sport\n!Total Athletes\n|-\n|align=center| 1 || {{flagCGFteam|AUS|2010}} || {{sortname|Sharelle|McMahon}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-sport/mcmahon-named-australian-team-flagbearer-20101001-161af.html |title=McMahon named Australian team flagbearer |publisher=News.smh.com.au |date=1 October 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref> || [[Netball at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Netball]] || 377\n|-\n|align=center| 2 || {{flagCGFteam|AIA|2010}} || {{sortname|Ronnie|Bryan|dab=cyclist}} || [[Cycling at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Cycling]]||12\n|-\n|align=center| 3 || {{flagCGFteam|ANT|2010}} ||{{sortname|James|Grayman}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antiguaobserver.com/?p=43543 |title=ABNOC announces 2010 Commonwealth Games team &#124; Antigua Observer Newspaper |publisher=Antiguaobserver.com |date=25 September 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref> || [[Athletics at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Athletics]]||17\n|-\n|align=center| 4 || {{flagCGFteam|BAH|2010}} ||{{sortname|Valentino|Knowles}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tribune242.com/10022010_KNOWLES-CARRYING-FLAG_sports_pg11 |title=The Tribune |publisher=Tribune242.com |date=2 October 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717101648/http://www.tribune242.com/10022010_KNOWLES-CARRYING-FLAG_sports_pg11 |archive-date=17 July 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> || [[Athletics at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Athletics]]||24\n|-\n|align=center| 5 || {{flagCGFteam|BAN|2010}} || {{sortname|Asif Hossain|Khan}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bdnews24.com/details.php?id=175050&cid=19 |title=CW GAMES OPENINGRatna to carry Bangladesh flag &#124; Sport |publisher=bdnews24.com |date=2 October 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722134652/http://bdnews24.com/details.php?id=175050&cid=19 |archivedate=22 July 2011  }}</ref> || [[Shooting at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Shooting]]||70\n|-\n|align=center| 6 || {{flagCGFteam|BAR|2010}} || {{sortname|Laurel|Browne}} || [[Netball at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Netball]]||39\n|-\n|align=center| 7 || {{flagCGFteam|BIZ|2010}} || {{sortname|Kaina|Martinez}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reporter.bz/index.php?mod=article&cat=Sports&article=4650 |title=The Reporter \u2013 Sports |publisher=Reporter.bz |date=24 February 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref> || [[Athletics at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Athletics]]||9\n|-\n|align=center| 8 || {{flagCGFteam|BER|2010}} || {{sortname|Kiera|Aitken}} || [[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Swimming]]||14\n|-\n|align=center| 9 || {{flagCGFteam|BOT|2010}} || {{sortname|Amantle|Montsho}} || [[Athletics at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Athletics]]||49\n|-\n|align=center| 10 || {{flagCGFteam|IVB|2010}} ||{{sortname|Joseph|Chapman|Joseph S. Chapman}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virginislandsnewsonline.com/news/tahesia-arrives-in-delhi-foresees-great-commonwealth-games |title=Tahesia arrives in Delhi, foresees great Commonwealth Games \u00ab Virgin Islands News Online |publisher=Virginislandsnewsonline.com |accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref> || [[Squash at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Squash]]||2\n|-\n|align=center| 11 || {{flagCGFteam|BRU|2010}} || {{sortname|Ampuan|Ahad}}|| [[Lawn bowls at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Lawn bowls]]||12\n|-\n|align=center| 12 || {{flagCGFteam|CMR|2010}} ||{{sortname|Hugo|Mamba}}<ref>[http://www.crtv.cm/cont/nouvelles/nouvelles_sola_fr.phpidField=8009&table=nouvelles&sub=sport]{{dead link|date=Oct